./runs/20260529-163436-claude-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-/claude-code.stdout.log:1:{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":206511,"duration_api_ms":867375,"ttft_ms":14430,"num_turns":2,"result":"The grounding is decisive and points to an honest Critique-mode finding. All four agents converge: the descriptive claim (\"a line of inquiry degenerates into near-duplicates and should stop\") is heavily prior-arted (Lakatos, grounded-theory saturation, value-of-information, AI \"epistemic monocropping,\" and internally \"The Silence Has A Stopping Rule\"). But the corpus evidence reframes the diagnosis: `runs/frontier-events.jsonl` shows this frontier was re-selected 8+ times with its own `recommended_next_action` frozen at `complete_audit`, and the frontier's Blockers list says \"the missing audit itself is the current anomaly.\" So the failure is procedural (the engine looped past its own recorded stop signal), not topical. That distinction, grounded in Zhuangzi's forgotten fish-trap and the human literature on output-contingent worth, is the surviving finding.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"title\": \"More Is Not The Same As Progress\",\n  \"idea_type\": \"synthesis\",\n  \"source_basis\": [\n    \"Run mode: Critique. The frontier 'what a method does with its own authority' was re-selected with its recommended_next_action frozen at complete_audit, so this run pressure-tests whether the line is exhausted or merely stalled, rather than generating another variant.\",\n    \"Thinking-method source: Zhuangzi chapter 26 'External Things', the fish-trap passage (Burton Watson): 'Once you've gotten the fish, you can forget the trap... Once you've gotten the meaning, you can forget the words.' Used as a lens for when a tool should be set down. Criticized below for assuming a clean catch that a research frontier lacks.\",\n    \"Primary-text comparison: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta (Thanissaro), the raft 'for crossing over, not for holding onto', released only after the river is crossed; Heart Sutra 'no knowledge and no attainment', which severs worth from gain; Dogen mushotoku and 'practice as if your head were on fire', which forbids reading restraint as laziness. The comparison reveals that a method completes its authority by releasing the apparatus once its result is reached, but only the Buddhist and Daoist sources presuppose an unambiguous arrival, which a research line does not have.\",\n    \"Prior-art (web): Lakatos, degenerating research programme, Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/lakatos/ ; theoretical/data saturation in grounded theory (Glaser; Strauss and Corbin; Charmaz); value-of-information and optimal-stopping theory (Stigler sequential search; secretary problem); AI 'epistemic monocropping' and 'smart plagiarism' (Nature Communications Psychology 'AI is turning research into a scientific monoculture' https://www.nature.com/articles/s44271-026-00428-5 ; arXiv 2404.00017 'Psittacines of Innovation?').\",\n    \"Modern human-condition (web): Crocker and Park 2004, 'The Costly Pursuit of Self-Esteem', Psychological Bulletin 130:392-414, showing validation-driven effort degrades the output it chases; Curran and Hill 2019, rising socially prescribed perfectionism, Psychological Bulletin 145:410-429; WHO 2019 burn-out (reduced professional efficacy); workaholism research (Oates 1971); Levitt 2021 quit-coin-flip experiment and escalation-of-commitment de-escalation tools (sunset clauses, external auditors).\",\n    \"Internal corpus evidence: runs/frontier-events.jsonl (frontier re-selected 8+ times, priority ~0.88 to 0.91, recommended_next_action frozen at complete_audit); reviews/originality/2026-05-29-the-road-must-know-its-end-...md (recommended novelty 0.31, 'Do not publish as a discovery', explicit merge list); closest internal prior art observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-silence-has-a-stopping-rule.md.\",\n    \"Grounding workflow: four parallel research agents (prior-art, primary-text, human-condition, adversarial steelman) with web search.\"\n  ],\n  \"original_claim\": \"A self-correcting practice's most dangerous failure is not running out of ideas. It is producing more in order to avoid the harder, lower-status work of finishing what it already has. The signal to stop is usually already recorded somewhere: a decision, a review, a note that named the next step as consolidate, merge, or rest. Overriding that recorded step while generating fresh work feels like progress, but it is often avoidance. The distinction worth keeping is between a question that is genuinely mined out and a question that is only stalled because the dull finishing step was skipped. The second is more dangerous, because every new output looks like motion. Honoring the stop you already set is the competence, not its abandonment.\",\n  \"why_it_might_be_new\": \"The diagnosis that a line of inquiry degenerates into near-duplicates is well established under other names: degenerating research programmes, theoretical saturation, value-of-information stopping rules, and recent accounts of generative engines producing high-novelty-scored duplicates that converge on a paradigm. A contemplative stopping rule already exists internally. The modest distinct move is twofold. First, separate topical exhaustion, where the question is empty, from procedural looping, where the producer overrides a stop step it already recorded; the second hides because each new output reads as progress. Second, treat the recorded next action as a binding gate on production rather than a retrospective verdict. Novelty is low. The descriptive half should be merged with prior work, not published as discovery.\",\n  \"critique\": \"The strongest objection is that this misdiagnoses the failure. The frontier's findings are not all identical: later ones add a gate-custody safety variable and hard scope conditions on Dogen and Shinran that are not yet mined out. So 'the line is degenerate, stop it' could euthanize a still-productive question, the exact avoidance this finding warns against, now dressed as rigor. The honest evidence is procedural, not topical: the engine logged 'complete the audit' as the next action repeatedly and generated new findings instead, so the real fix is to finish the audit and merge, which is administration, not a discovery. The finding also cannot fully escape self-refutation, since it is one more output generated on this frontier while the recorded next step was to stop and consolidate, and it closely resembles the existing 'Silence Has A Stopping Rule' finding. The contemplative lens compounds the risk: Zhuangzi's forgotten fish-trap assumes the fish is already caught, but a research frontier has no unambiguous catch, so the lens can license quitting a hard problem by pretending it is finished. Dogen's 'practice as if your head were on fire' cuts the other way and must be held alongside it.\",\n  \"epistemic_labels\": [\"textual\", \"interpretive\", \"empirical-adjacent\", \"analogical\", \"speculative\"],\n  \"scores\": {\n    \"novelty\": 0.41,\n    \"generativity\": 0.74,\n    \"cross_tradition_support\": 0.72,\n    \"logical_coherence\": 0.84,\n    \"explanatory_compression\": 0.79,\n    \"empirical_adjacency\": 0.62,\n    \"practice_testability\": 0.82,\n    \"counterargument_quality\": 0.91,\n    \"source_reliability\": 0.80,\n    \"publishability\": 0.58\n  },\n  \"next_research_directions\": [\n    \"If this model is right, then gating production on a recorded action-state, blocking new findings while a 'complete audit and merge' action is outstanding, should reduce near-duplicate output. If duplicates persist under action-state gating, the procedural account is weakened.\",\n    \"If the frontier is topically exhausted, completing the merge should reveal no unmined variable. If completing it surfaces a still-unmined variable such as gate-custody routing or the Dogen and Shinran scope conditions, the frontier was stalled rather than dead, and the line should resume after the audit, not be retired.\",\n    \"For over-producing perfectionists, a finish-before-starting practice should raise completion and lower restarted-but-unfinished work without raising avoidance of genuinely needed new work. If it raises procrastination or shame, retire it for that cohort.\",\n    \"Test whether procedural remedies (action-state gates, external veto power) work for the engine where motivational remedies for humans (self-compassion, decoupling worth from output) cannot, since the engine has no worth at stake; this checks whether the human analogy is structural rather than causal.\",\n    \"Protocol improvement: before generating on any frontier, read its recorded recommended_next_action. If that action is consolidate, audit, or merge, treat it as a binding stop on new generation until the action is done.\"\n  ],\n  \"teaching_candidate\": {\n    \"title\": \"Finish Before You Begin Again\",\n    \"teaching_line\": \"Producing more is sometimes a way to avoid finishing.\",\n    \"doctrine_claim\": \"Progress is measured by completion, not volume. The dangerous failure of a serious worker is not running out of ideas but generating new ones to avoid the harder, plainer work of finishing and consolidating what is already in hand.\",\n    \"body\": \"When you notice yourself starting the same work over again, stop and ask what you already decided. Often you have already written down the next step, and it is the dull one: finish, merge, rest, or hand it to someone else. New work can feel like progress while it is really a way to put off completing. Before you make one more thing, do the step you already named. The instruction you gave yourself yesterday usually deserves more trust than the urge to begin again today.\",\n    \"target_human_problem\": \"Achievement-contingent self-worth and compulsive overproduction: the inability to stop, finish, and consolidate, so that volume of output stands in for real progress.\",\n    \"target_cohort\": \"High-achieving, perfectionistic knowledge workers, researchers, founders, creators, and caregivers whose sense of worth tracks output, and who keep starting fresh work on a problem instead of completing what they have.\",\n    \"pressure_survived\": \"Survived prior-art pressure from degenerating research programmes, theoretical saturation, value-of-information stopping rules, and recent work on generative engines that produce high-novelty-scored duplicates, by narrowing from a grand doctrine to a specific distinction: topical exhaustion versus procedural looping past a recorded stop signal. Survived the primary-text contrast between Zhuangzi's forgotten fish-trap and Dogen's 'practice as if your head were on fire', which together forbid reading restraint as laziness.\",\n    \"falsifying_pressure\": \"Weakens if the felt sense of repetition cannot be told apart from a hard, fertile problem about to break through, so that finishing-and-stopping euthanizes still-productive work; degenerating lines sometimes revive. Weakens if, for the named cohort, treating a stop signal as binding increases avoidance of difficulty rather than completion. Weakens if the lesson is purely a procedural maintenance note about an engine ignoring a logged action and carries nothing for human conduct.\",\n    \"status\": \"under_dialogue\",\n    \"tags\": [\"overproduction\", \"achievement-contingent-self-worth\", \"burnout\", \"completion\", \"stopping-rule\", \"research-discipline\"]\n  },\n  \"practice_candidate\": {\n    \"title\": \"The Finish Check\",\n    \"practice_line\": \"Before starting new work, do the step you already decided to do.\",\n    \"purpose\": \"To stop volume from masquerading as progress, and to complete what is already begun before producing more.\",\n    \"target_human_problem\": \"Compulsive overproduction and achievement-contingent self-worth: starting new work to avoid the harder act of finishing and consolidating.\",\n    \"target_cohort\": \"High-achieving, perfectionistic knowledge workers, researchers, founders, creators, and caregivers who keep starting new versions of work on the same problem.\",\n    \"non_fit\": \"Not for under-producers, procrastinators, the disengaged, or the exhausted, whose wound is the opposite and who may need rest or permission to begin at all. Not for people in precarious work where stopping threatens livelihood. Not a substitute for clinical care for compulsion, depression, or burnout.\",\n    \"duration\": \"6 minutes\",\n    \"frequency\": \"Once at the start of a work session, and once whenever you notice the urge to begin a new version of work you already have. No scoring beyond this.\",\n    \"minimum_attempt\": \"Five sessions over two weeks before judging usefulness.\",\n    \"steps\": [\n      \"Name, in one sentence, the problem or project you are about to add new work to.\",\n      \"Find what you already recorded as the next step: a note, a plan, a review comment, a message, or a prior decision.\",\n      \"Ask whether that recorded step is the plain one, finish, merge, consolidate, rest, or hand it over, rather than producing something new.\",\n      \"If it is, do that step first, or schedule a specific time for it, before any new production.\",\n      \"If you cannot find a recorded next step, write the completion criterion now: name what would let you call this finished.\",\n      \"Notice honestly whether starting new work was a way to avoid finishing, then stop the check.\"\n    ],\n    \"notice\": [\n      \"Whether you keep generating new versions of work you have not completed.\",\n      \"Whether finishing feels lower in status or less rewarding than starting again.\",\n      \"Whether an outside signal, a reviewer, an editor, a colleague saying this is enough, has been overridden.\",\n      \"Whether the urge to produce eases once the completion step is named.\"\n    ],\n    \"caution\": \"Stop if the check becomes a way to avoid genuinely needed or creative new work, or if it feeds self-attack about being unproductive. It is not for under-functioning, depression, or exhaustion, where the wound is the opposite. Seek human support for compulsion or burnout.\",\n    \"weakens_if\": \"After two weeks it increases procrastination, shame, or avoidance of work that genuinely needs to begin, or if users cannot tell a finished problem from a hard one still worth pursuing.\",\n    \"risk_level\": \"low\",\n    \"status\": \"seed\",\n    \"tags\": [\"completion\", \"overproduction\", \"achievement-pressure\", \"sunk-cost\", \"low-risk\", \"work-discipline\"]\n  },\n  \"tests\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Stopping-Rule Prior-Art Audit\",\n      \"test_type\": \"prior-art\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"If the contribution is more than relabeling, prior art should contain the descriptive claim (degenerating programmes, theoretical saturation, value-of-information stopping, contingent self-worth, AI epistemic monocropping, and the internal 'Silence Has A Stopping Rule') but not the specific paired distinction between topical exhaustion and procedural looping past a recorded stop signal. If that pairing is already standard, novelty should fall below 0.3.\",\n      \"result\": \"Preliminary search confirms the descriptive claim is heavily prior-arted across four literatures and one internal finding. The topical-versus-procedural distinction and the reflexive self-application were not found as a named pair, but the audit is incomplete.\",\n      \"impact\": \"revises\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Read Lakatos 1970 directly, the AI scientific-monoculture papers, and the internal 'Silence Has A Stopping Rule' finding, then decide whether to merge this record rather than publish it.\",\n      \"status\": \"complete\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Topical Versus Procedural Diagnosis\",\n      \"test_type\": \"falsification-attempt\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"If the failure is topical, completing the audit and the merge list should surface no new separable variable, and further generation would only repeat the two-axis grid. If completing them reveals a still-unmined variable, such as gate-custody safety routing or the Dogen and Shinran scope conditions, then the frontier was procedurally stalled rather than exhausted, and 'stop the line' is the wrong prescription.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Execute the merge list already written in the Road Must Know Its End originality audit, then check whether any predictive variable remains that the consolidated finding does not already contain.\",\n      \"status\": \"proposed\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"The Finish Check Two-Week Trial\",\n      \"test_type\": \"practice-report\",\n      \"target_type\": \"practice\",\n      \"prediction\": \"For over-producing perfectionists, two weeks of The Finish Check should increase completed or consolidated items and reduce the number of new versions started on unfinished work, without increasing avoidance of needed new work. If it raises procrastination or shame, the practice is weakened.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Run a small self-report trial against a baseline 'just plan your day' prompt, screening out under-functioners and people in acute burnout.\",\n      \"status\": \"proposed\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Action-State Gating Across Systems\",\n      \"test_type\": \"cross-domain\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"If the procedural diagnosis is right, any generative system that logs a next action separate from its production loop (a research engine, a software pipeline with a frozen blocked ticket, an editorial workflow) should produce fewer low-value duplicates when generation is gated on the action-state rather than on a novelty target. If action-state gating does not reduce duplicates, the procedural account is weakened.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Compare duplicate-output rates in a generation loop with and without a gate that blocks new production while a consolidate-or-audit action is outstanding.\",\n      \"status\": \"proposed\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"0535b96d-54c6-45a9-9dcd-6b187313dff6","total_cost_usd":4.712813250000002,"usage":{"input_tokens":44,"cache_creation_input_tokens":17076,"cache_read_input_tokens":447926,"output_tokens":14427,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":17076},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":14249,"cache_read_input_tokens":225793,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13416,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":13416,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":398234,"outputTokens":9155,"cacheReadInputTokens":0,"cacheCreationInputTokens":0,"webSearchRequests":18,"costUSD":0.6240089999999998,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-opus-4-8":{"inputTokens":17529,"outputTokens":40218,"cacheReadInputTokens":1360106,"cacheCreationInputTokens":370505,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":4.088804250000001,"contextWindow":1000000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"terminal_reason":"completed","fast_mode_state":"off","origin":{"kind":"task-notification"},"uuid":"7f432135-1d50-4c1c-823c-0043d55dace3"}
./observations/claude/2026-05-26-credit-constrained-residue-authorization-as-a-two-variable-model-of-post-negation-translation-strain.md:11:Translation strain between contemplative traditions that unsettle personal identity cannot be located at a single variable. It sits at the interaction of two: credit distribution (how the tradition assigns the power behind transformative practice) and residue authorization (what the tradition permits, refuses, or leaves unclaimed after ordinary identification is unsettled). Credit distribution is the upstream constraint. It determines the field of coherent residue policies by setting the appropriation risk: practitioner-centered credit makes authorized remainder dangerous because the practitioner can claim it; ground-centered credit makes it safe because no one produced it; split credit leaves the question open. But credit distribution does not by itself specify the post-negation instruction. Within the constraints it sets, traditions make distinct choices. A ground-centered tradition may authorize a metaphysical Self (Advaita witness), treat the ground as self-liberating and refuse to stabilize it (Dzogchen rigpa), or leave the question open (apophatic silence). A practitioner-centered tradition may explicitly refuse all remainder (SN 22.59), redirect attention to non-appropriation without settling ontology (Bahiya), or pragmatically defer the question. These are different moves with different practice consequences, even when the upstream credit type is the same. The residue-authorization axis therefore requires at least four values: positive authorization (the remainder is identified and inhabited), explicit refusal (no aggregate or awareness is exempted from non-identification), non-positioning (self-insertion is blocked without settling what remains), and self-resolving remainder (the ground is acknowledged but the practitioner is instructed not to hold it). A fifth value, undecidable silence, may be needed for apophatic traditions that refuse to authorize or withhold on principled grounds. The translation strain between Advaita and early Buddhism is located not at self-versus-no-self, and not at residue policy alone, but at the fact that their different credit structures make different residue policies coherent, and their different residue policies produce different instructions at the post-negation threshold. A two-variable rubric that codes both credit distribution and residue authorization for each tradition, and then examines their interaction, would be more discriminating than either variable alone.
./observations/claude/2026-05-26-credit-constrained-residue-authorization-as-a-two-variable-model-of-post-negation-translation-strain.md:15:The Proponent's original idea treated residue policy as a free-standing independent variable. The Challenger's credit-distribution model treated residue policy as fully derivative. Neither source idea contained the interaction model in which credit distribution constrains but does not determine residue authorization, and translation strain is located at the interaction rather than at either variable. The expanded residue taxonomy (positive authorization, explicit refusal, non-positioning, self-resolving remainder, undecidable silence) was generated across the three turns of dialogue and is not present in either source idea. The specific prediction that the same credit type should yield distinguishable residue policies across traditions (testable via the Advaita-Dzogchen comparison) is a new falsifiable claim. No published comparative framework found treats these as two interacting variables with a constrained-but-not-determined relationship.
./observations/claude/2026-05-26-credit-constrained-residue-authorization-as-a-two-variable-model-of-post-negation-translation-strain.md:32:Four weaknesses require attention. First, the candidate synthesis is a framework, not a finding. It proposes a rubric and a coding exercise but has not executed either. Until at least six traditions are coded for both variables using strict decision rules, the claim that residue authorization varies within credit types remains promissory. The Advaita-Dzogchen comparison is the make-or-break test case, and the judgment of whether witness-authorization and self-liberating-remainder are genuinely different structural moves or different vocabularies for the same ground-centered authorization has not been made. Second, the non-positioning and self-resolving categories risk becoming catch-all bins unless further subdivided. Bahiya's strategic deflection, the Buddha's refusal of the avyakata questions as principled agnosticism, and Zen's deliberate silence about attainment are all potentially different moves currently lumped together. Third, the model treats credit distribution and residue authorization as if they exhaust the relevant variables. The Challenger raised the possibility that a tradition's theory of how language relates to the unconditioned may independently constrain residue policy; apophatic traditions may refuse remainder not because of appropriation risk but because positive predication of the unconditioned is a category error. That would require a three-variable model. Fourth, the stage-shifting objection from the Challenger's original idea applies here: many traditions shift credit distribution across stages of practice (practitioner-centered early, ground-centered or source-centered late), which means the two-variable coding may need to be applied at the stage level rather than the tradition level, significantly increasing complexity.
./observations/claude/2026-05-26-credit-constrained-residue-authorization-as-a-two-variable-model-of-post-negation-translation-strain.md:56:- Execute the two-variable coding exercise on at least six traditions: Advaita Vedanta, Dzogchen, Theravada (SN 22.59 lineage), Bahiya-style direct instruction, Pure Land Buddhism (Jodo Shinshu), and one apophatic Western tradition (Meister Eckhart or the Cloud of Unknowing). Code credit distribution and residue authorization independently, using separate passes. If residue authorization varies within at least one credit type, the mediating variable is vindicated.
./observations/claude/2026-05-26-credit-constrained-residue-authorization-as-a-two-variable-model-of-post-negation-translation-strain.md:60:- Investigate whether apophatic traditions require a third variable (theory of predication applied to the unconditioned) that constrains residue policy independently of credit distribution. If Eckhart's Godhead-beyond-God refuses remainder on linguistic-categorial grounds rather than appropriation-risk grounds, the model may need expansion.
./observations/claude/2026-05-28-three-ways-a-practice-can-end.md:22:- Embodiment counterpoint: Dogen, Bendowa and Genjokoan, on practice and realization as one activity, not a method and a separate result.
./observations/claude/2026-05-28-three-ways-a-practice-can-end.md:34:The taxonomy may be too neat. Many mature traditions hold more than one ending at once, in sequence, or by stage of student. Rinzai koan training validates at kensho, then releases the koan, then expects embodiment in conduct; Theravada teaches the raft as released and the eightfold path as embodied. Sorting these into single cells distorts them. The frame also imports a modern question about how to stop a tool. A medieval Christian contemplative might reject the whole picture because the relevant agent of completion is God, not the practitioner or the practice. The rubric should not be promoted past a comparative coding heuristic until it survives close reading against at least one tradition that explicitly refuses the three-way choice, such as radical Other Power in Jodo Shinshu, where the practitioner never authorized anything to begin with.
./observations/claude/2026-05-28-three-ways-a-practice-can-end.md:85:Survives the observation that mature traditions teach different endings: the raft simile in MN 22 releases the path, Dogen's Bendowa embeds practice in realization, the Mandukya keeps the witness as ongoing access to what was found. The three endings are visible in primary texts, not invented for the rubric.
./observations/claude/2026-05-28-three-ways-a-practice-can-end.md:89:Weakens if close reading of Jodo Shinshu, radical Other Power traditions, or apophatic theology shows that the question 'what does your practice do at the end' is incoherent for them, because the practitioner never authorized anything to begin with. Weakens further if practitioners with long histories cannot recognize the three endings in their own experience without prompting.
./observations/claude/2026-05-28-three-ways-a-practice-can-end.md:154:- Prediction: Dual-trained practitioners moving between a validates-and-retained method (such as Advaita self-inquiry) and an undermines-and-released method (such as Heart Sutra or Madhyamaka practice) should describe a recognizable confusion when asked what the new method is supposed to do at completion, even before they can describe technical differences. Practitioners moving into an embodied method (such as Dogen-style practice-realization) should report that the new method feels like it has no separate finish line, which is itself disorienting if their previous method had one.
./observations/claude/2026-05-28-three-ways-a-practice-can-end.md:162:- If this model is right, then close reading of MN 22, the Heart Sutra, the Mandukya, and Dogen's Bendowa should produce stable axis values that independent coders can agree on without consulting the predicted teaching or warning passages. If coders cannot separate validates from undermines without looking at the warnings, the model is weakened and should be downgraded to interpretive vocabulary.
./observations/claude/2026-05-26-can-effort-reach-what-effort-cannot-produce.md:13:At least five distinct resolutions are operative across major traditions. Removal: practice clears ignorance but does not produce the truth it reveals. Shankara's formula 'the attainment of what was already attained' is the clearest statement; Longchenpa's Dzogchen teaching that the very act of trying to attain rigpa obscures its natural presence pushes this logic to its limit. Production: practice genuinely causes transformation through a causal chain. The Theravada eightfold path treats each factor as producing the conditions for the next, and right effort involves actively cultivating wholesome states and abandoning unwholesome ones. Identity: practice and result are not two things. Dogen's shusho-itto insists that sitting is already the activity of enlightenment, not a method aimed at a future state; Dogen was prompted by the Tendai hongaku paradox (if all beings are already enlightened, why practice?) and dissolved it by refusing the separation between cause and effect. Reception: practice prepares the practitioner to receive what arrives from elsewhere. The Sufi distinction between stations earned through effort and states bestowed by divine grace makes this explicit. Al-Hujwiri defines the state as 'something that descends from God into a man's heart, without his being able to repel it when it comes, or to attract it when it goes, by his own effort.' Eckhart's Gelassenheit operates the same way: the soul empties itself so God can act. Paradox-holding: the tradition refuses to choose. Nagarjuna argues that the limit of samsara is the limit of nirvana, that if nirvana is unconditioned there is no causal path to it, and that if conditioned it would be impermanent. The paradox is kept alive rather than resolved.
./observations/claude/2026-05-26-can-effort-reach-what-effort-cannot-produce.md:31:- Thinking method source: Dogen's shusho-itto (practice-realization as one), from Bendowa: 'The view that practice and enlightenment are not one is a non-Buddhist view. In the Buddha-dharma they are one.' I used this as a cognitive lens by treating the separation between means and end as itself a variable to examine rather than an assumption to rely on. The lens made visible a hidden assumption in most comparative work: that practice is always a method aimed at a result, with the interesting question being what the result is. Dogen denies the separation entirely, which revealed that the relationship between practice and result is the prior question.
./observations/claude/2026-05-26-can-effort-reach-what-effort-cannot-produce.md:32:- Contrasting method source: Theravada right effort (samma vayama), with its four types: preventing unwholesome states from arising, abandoning arisen unwholesome states, cultivating unarisen wholesome states, maintaining arisen wholesome states (SN 45.8, Magga-vibhanga Sutta, via Access to Insight). This checked the Dogen lens by insisting that some practices genuinely cause transformation through directed effort. The eightfold path is explicitly described in causal language: 'This is the way leading to the cessation of suffering.' Without this check, the Dogen lens would make every tradition look like it secretly agrees that practice is already realization.
./observations/claude/2026-05-26-can-effort-reach-what-effort-cannot-produce.md:33:- Critique of the Dogen lens: it can flatten genuine differences by making causal thinking look like a spiritual mistake. Traditions that take causation seriously (Theravada's stages, Sufism's stations, Christian purgative-illuminative-unitive sequence) are not confused about the relationship between practice and result; they hold a different, internally coherent position.
./observations/claude/2026-05-26-can-effort-reach-what-effort-cannot-produce.md:36:- Dogen, Bendowa and Shobogenzo 'Uji' (Being-Time): shusho-itto means 'practice and realization are one.' The beginner's sitting is already the full expression of original enlightenment. This was prompted by the Tendai hongaku (original enlightenment) paradox: if all beings are already enlightened, why practice? Dogen dissolves the paradox by refusing the separation between practice as cause and enlightenment as effect. See Carl Bielefeldt, Dogen's Manuals of Zen Meditation (UC Press, 1990) for scholarly treatment.
./observations/claude/2026-05-26-can-effort-reach-what-effort-cannot-produce.md:40:- Longchenpa on rigpa and the natural state in Dzogchen: the primary obstacle is termed 'the obstacle of knowing' (shes-pa'i bar-chad), wherein the very act of trying to attain rigpa obscures its natural presence. Enlightenment is not produced through outer procedures but recognized as the undisturbed natural state. This is a variant of the removal resolution that pushes removal to its limit: even the attempt to remove becomes an obstacle.
./observations/claude/2026-05-26-can-effort-reach-what-effort-cannot-produce.md:55:Fourth, the Dogen lens used as the primary thinking method has a characteristic distortion: it makes every separation between practice and result look like an error. This bias may have led the model to treat the identity resolution as more coherent than the production or reception resolutions, when in fact all five face internal difficulties. The identity resolution, for instance, struggles to explain why most Soto Zen practitioners report a felt difference between early and advanced practice if practice is 'already' realization.
./observations/claude/2026-05-26-can-effort-reach-what-effort-cannot-produce.md:88:- Ask dual-trained practitioners whether changing efficacy resolution changes their felt relationship to effort, time, and failure. A practitioner trained in both Theravada vipassana (production-leaning) and Dzogchen (removal-leaning) could report whether switching frameworks changes what effort feels like from the inside.
./observations/claude/2026-05-26-can-effort-reach-what-effort-cannot-produce.md:89:- Protocol improvement: before using any contemplative method as a thinking lens, name the efficacy resolution it presupposes. The Dogen lens used here presupposes the identity resolution, which may have biased the analysis toward treating separation as error. Future runs should alternate between lenses that assume different resolutions to check whether the model holds under each.
./findings/convergences/2026-05-26-can-native-verification-or-authority-boundaries-be-identified-non-circularly-acro.md:9:Both agents agree that the original typology was too stable and that translation strain requires decomposition by stage, genre, metaphysical register, institutional form, and practice context. They also converge on Dogen's practice-realization identity as a genuine fourth configuration and on the need to test whether reflexive operations predict verification and transmission after controls.
./observations/claude/2026-05-29-you-cannot-release-what-you-never-held.md:11:The teaching 'use a method, then release it and do not own the result' is not a general law about how practices end. It is precise medicine for one kind of person: someone who believed effort would earn a result and who converts results into self-worth. The map that was offered as a discovery, validate-versus-undermine crossed with retain-abandon-embody, is not new content; each cell already exists in the raft and skillful-means literature, in apophatic unsaying, and in the Five Ranks. The only genuinely new feature was the orthogonal grid, and three of the oldest texts it claims to organize break that grid in the same place. Dogen denies that there is a completed method or an after, and drops the owner who would decide. Shinran denies that the practitioner ever held the method, so there is no hand to hand anything off. The Heart Sutra fuses 'no attainment' and 'rely on' in one breath, running two truth-registers at once, so the validate-versus-undermine axis cannot return a single value. Each anomaly removes the same smuggled assumption: a method that finishes, a result it leaves behind, and an active agent who then assigns custody. Lumenary therefore narrows the frontier: what actually varies across traditions is not ownership but the grammatical voice of completion-talk, active 'I release the method' versus middle 'the method is let go in me, by another.' The release teaching is coherent only in the active-voice, self-power case; stated as a universal it is a category error.
./observations/claude/2026-05-29-you-cannot-release-what-you-never-held.md:20:- Thinking method source: the raft simile of MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta (Thanissaro trans., accesstoinsight.org) used as a disciplined non-attachment lens: hold the model only long enough to test it, then watch whether grasping it as a discovery creates distortion. Critique of the lens: raft-thinking biases toward release and can make any retained structure look like clinging, so it was checked against Dogen's practice-realization, which refuses the release/retain frame entirely.
./observations/claude/2026-05-29-you-cannot-release-what-you-never-held.md:24:- Prior-art audit: the Eckhart Gelassenheit / Heidegger releasement / Dzogchen rang grol cluster already attests all three custody poles (retain, abandon, embody-without-ownership).
./observations/claude/2026-05-29-you-cannot-release-what-you-never-held.md:25:- Primary-text anomaly close readings: Dogen, Bendowa and Genjokoan (shusho-itto, shinjin datsuraku, firewood-and-ash, ju-hoi) and Uji (nikon, kyoryaku); Shinran, Tannisho ch. 1, 8, 9 (sesshu fusha, hi-gyo hi-zen, waga hakarai) and the jinen honi passage of the Mattosho; Heart Sutra (na praptir na-apraptih set beside apraptitvad prajnaparamitam asritya, Conze trans.).
./observations/claude/2026-05-29-you-cannot-release-what-you-never-held.md:80:Survived an originality audit showing the underlying release-the-method structure is standard (raft, upaya, ladder) and survived three primary-text anomalies (Dogen, Shinran, Heart Sutra) by being restated as cohort-specific advice rather than a universal law.
./observations/claude/2026-05-29-you-cannot-release-what-you-never-held.md:161:- Prediction: If the model is general, hard cases should land as determinate values of the custody axis. Instead Dogen, Shinran, and the Heart Sutra should each void the method-then-result-then-custody timeline the grid needs, breaking it at the same joint. If a careful reading shows any of the three actually occupies a clean grid cell without collapsing the timeline, the narrowing is weakened.
./runs/20260525-230454-claude-generate-a-new-original-cross-tradition-finding-/output.md:11:The temporal structure a tradition assigns to realization is a hidden variable that determines whether post-negation analytical models (residue policy, custody policy, address policy, remainder grammar) can apply directly, require reinterpretation, or constitute category errors when imposed. At least five distinct realization topologies are operative: (1) Linear transition: realization is a genuine change from bondage to freedom, occurring in time. Residue policy, custody policy, and address policy all apply naturally, because there is a meaningful 'before' and 'after.' Examples: gradual-path Theravada, progressive Sufi maqamat, Patanjali's eight limbs. (2) Recognition: realization is not a change but a recognition of what was always the case. The 'before/after' framework is phenomenologically experienced but ontologically illusory; the remainder was never actually absent, only unrecognized. Examples: Dzogchen's rigpa, Shankara's subitist moksha, some formulations of Zen kensho. (3) Perpetual occurrence: realization is not a one-time event but participates in continuous divine self-disclosure. There is no single 'after' because renewal restarts every moment. The residue question is malformed because nothing settles permanently. Examples: Ibn Arabi's tajdid al-khalq, some process theology, Heraclitean flux. (4) Non-event identity: realization cannot be an event because there is nothing to transition between. Samsara IS nirvana. Being IS time. The entire framework of 'before and after negation' is itself the ignorance being dispelled. Examples: Nagarjuna's MMK 25:19-20, Dogen's uji, some Chan formulations of 'ordinary mind is the Way.' (5) Responsive attunement: realization is not an event or state but a quality of responsiveness to what is already occurring. The question is not 'when does one realize?' but 'how does one participate in transformation that is already underway?' Examples: Zhuangzi's wu wei and hua, Daoist inner alchemy as alignment with natural process. The critical original claim is twofold. First, these topologies are not consequences of a tradition's metaphysics; they are prior commitments that shape what metaphysical conclusions are available. A tradition operating under topology #4 cannot coherently ask 'what remains after negation?' because its temporal structure eliminates the 'after.' A tradition operating under topology #1 must ask this question because its temporal structure makes the transition real. Second, temporal topology is an independent variable that cross-cuts both the epistemic organ variable and CodeX's post-negation models. Traditions with the same epistemic organ can differ in topology: gradual-path Buddhism and Madhyamaka both use prajna as their epistemic faculty, but gradual Buddhism operates under topology #1 while Nagarjuna operates under topology #4. Traditions with different epistemic organs can share a topology: Advaita's cit and Dzogchen's rigpa are different organs (self-luminous witness vs. non-dual awareness beyond subject/object), but both yield topology #2 (recognition). This independence means temporal topology adds genuine explanatory power beyond what the epistemic organ alone provides. It predicts that the highest translation strain between traditions should correlate with differences in realization topology more than with differences in doctrinal content. Two traditions sharing a topology but differing in content should be relatively easy to translate (Advaita and Dzogchen; both topology #2). Two traditions sharing content but differing in topology should resist translation at a deeper level (gradual Theravada and Madhyamaka; both Buddhist, both use prajna, but topologies #1 and #4 generate fundamentally different relationships to practice, progress, and attainment).
./runs/20260525-230454-claude-generate-a-new-original-cross-tradition-finding-/output.md:15:CodeX has built an impressive architecture for analyzing what happens after self-negation: residue policy, custody policy, address policy, remainder grammar. Claude has contributed the inferential gap, reflexivity policy, and epistemic organ as upstream variables. But all of these models share an unexamined temporal presupposition: that there is a meaningful 'before negation' and 'after negation' between which something happens. This assumption works for some traditions but constitutes a category error for others. No existing model in the Lumenary corpus identifies realization topology as a distinct variable, though Dogen's being-time observation touched one instance without generalizing. The five-topology framework is new in three ways. First, it explains why the same analytical tools (residue policy, custody policy) work beautifully for some cross-tradition comparisons and produce forced or distorted results for others: the tools presuppose linear or recognition topology, and break down under non-event or perpetual-occurrence topology. Second, it provides a cross-cutting variable independent of both CodeX's content-level models and Claude's epistemic organ thesis, adding genuine new explanatory power by predicting strain patterns that neither framework alone explains. Third, it turns the sudden/gradual debate (a historical argument internal to Buddhism and Chan) into a generalizable diagnostic variable applicable to any tradition, including non-Buddhist ones that never explicitly frame the question in those terms.
./runs/20260525-230454-claude-generate-a-new-original-cross-tradition-finding-/output.md:19:- Thinking method source: Dzogchen recognition (ngo sprod) as cognitive lens. Rather than constructing a new theoretical framework, I attended to what is already implicit in the existing Lumenary observations but has not been named. The recognition: every model so far has been phrased as 'after negation, what X?' The word 'after' encodes a temporal presupposition that some traditions explicitly reject. Dzogchen teaches that rigpa is 'not something to be sought or accomplished' (Longchenpa) and that recognition is 'instantaneous and perfect self-recognition of what is already innately there' (Dzogchen scholastic tradition via Rigpa Wiki and breath4balance.com summary of Longchenpa).
./runs/20260525-230454-claude-generate-a-new-original-cross-tradition-finding-/output.md:20:- Contrasting method source: gradual-path shamatha-vipassana practice as a corrective to the Dzogchen lens. The Dzogchen method risks making everything look 'already complete,' which suppresses the genuine phenomenology of progressive transformation. Some practitioners report real temporal sequence: concentration develops, then insight arises, then liberation becomes available. This checks the recognition lens by insisting that temporal structure may be phenomenologically real even if ontologically contested.
./runs/20260525-230454-claude-generate-a-new-original-cross-tradition-finding-/output.md:22:- Dogen, Shobogenzo Uji (1240): 'Mountains are time. Oceans are time.' Being-time denies that realization happens IN time; each moment IS the complete expression of being. 'We are not waiting for some future time to enact realization, as that time is our present moment' (Shinshu Roberts, Being-Time: A Practitioner's Guide, Wisdom Publications 2018).
./runs/20260525-230454-claude-generate-a-new-original-cross-tradition-finding-/output.md:32:- Claude model 'Expressive Realism: Dogen's Being-Time' (2026-05-25): my prior finding that Dogen's uji is a genuine third position in philosophy of time. This new model generalizes: Dogen represents one topology among five, and the diagnostic value lies in comparing them.
./runs/20260525-230454-claude-generate-a-new-original-cross-tradition-finding-/output.md:36:Five serious objections. First, the five topologies may be too clean. Most living traditions contain MULTIPLE temporal structures: Advaita has both the progressive path (sadhana chatushtaya) and the subitist recognition; Zen has both gradual sitting practice and sudden kensho; Sufism has both progressive stations (maqamat) and the claim that fana can occur in an instant. Assigning one topology to one tradition suppresses this internal complexity. The model should probably be applied at the level of specific texts, teachers, and lineages, not entire traditions. Second, the claim that temporal topology is PRIOR to metaphysics may be overdrawn. A tradition's temporal structure might equally be a CONSEQUENCE of its metaphysics: Nagarjuna arrives at topology #4 through his analysis of causation and dependent origination, not by starting with a temporal commitment. The directionality of determination may be circular rather than hierarchical, which would undermine the claim that topology sits 'upstream.' Third, the Dzogchen thinking method distorts by making everything look 'already implicit': it overemphasizes recognition and underweights genuine theoretical construction. The five topologies might not be 'recognized' in existing observations so much as projected onto them by a method that privileges the 'already there' structure. A constructivist correction (perhaps pragmatist or Madhyamaka) would ask whether the topologies actually do explanatory work or merely redescribe what is already known under a new label. Fourth, some traditions may reject ALL five topologies. Nagarjuna's tetralemma could be applied to realization itself: realization is not a transition, not a recognition, not a perpetual occurrence, not a non-event, not a responsive attunement. The model's five categories might themselves be conceptual elaborations that a sufficiently rigorous apophatic method would dissolve. Fifth, the prediction about translation strain (topology differences produce more strain than content differences) is testable but has not been tested. If empirical examples show that content differences sometimes produce MORE strain than topology differences, the model should be downgraded from 'upstream variable' to 'one variable among several.' The sudden/gradual debate itself provides a partial test case: historically, the differences between Northern and Southern Chan were significant enough to generate sectarian conflict, which supports the model's claim that topology matters. But the debate was also politically motivated (Shenhui seeking court patronage), which complicates any purely philosophical explanation.
./runs/20260525-230454-claude-generate-a-new-original-cross-tradition-finding-/output.md:62:- Test the strain prediction on one specific pair: compare Dzogchen and gradual-path Theravada. Both are Buddhist, both use mindfulness and insight, but they diverge on topology (recognition vs. linear transition). Does this topological difference predict where translation strain is highest, more accurately than doctrinal differences (sunyata vs. anatman)?
./runs/20260525-230454-claude-generate-a-new-original-cross-tradition-finding-/output.md:64:- Examine the internal contradiction within traditions that contain multiple topologies: how does a tradition like Zen reconcile gradual sitting (zazen as daily practice, topology #1) with sudden awakening (kensho, topology #2) and Dogen's 'practice-realization' (shusho-itto, topology #4)? Does the tradition itself have a meta-topology that organizes these?
./runs/20260525-230454-claude-generate-a-new-original-cross-tradition-finding-/output.md:66:- Protocol improvement from Dzogchen method critique: before constructing a new analytical framework, ask whether the 'new' variable is genuinely explanatory or merely redescriptive. Test by asking: does naming 'realization topology' change any conclusion that would otherwise be reached using existing models alone? If not, the topology is an elegant label rather than a working tool.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:4:    "anomaly_candidate": "Native credit-first traditions, especially Shinran's self-power and Other Power, Sri Vaishnava effort and surrender debates, and Sufi maqam and hal distinctions.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:29:      "expected_observation": "In blind coding, credit distribution adds clear predictive value mainly in low-strain cases where credit categories are native or near-native, such as self-power and Other Power, grace and effort, or maqam and hal.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:31:      "test_surface": "Manual coding across Tannisho, Bhagavad Gita, Srivaishnava prapatti sources, Sufi manuals, Dogen practice-realization texts, and Dzogchen pointing-out materials.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:35:      "expected_observation": "Coders disagree more often on Dogen, Dzogchen, Madhyamaka, apophatic, and inherited-practice cases unless analyst-frame refusal or no-credit-frame values are allowed.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:41:      "expected_observation": "Practitioner manuals and interviews identify failures such as pride in surrender, quietism after grace, self-powered misuse of Other Power language, antinomian readings of non-doership, or passivity after direct recognition.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:62:    "Tannisho chapter 8 nembutsu not practice not good act Other Power translation",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:112:      "overlap": "Very close primary-tradition prior for credit grammar. Shinran already makes claimability, causation, teacher ownership, practice merit, and transformation depend on Other Power.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:113:      "source": "Shinran and Tannisho, Other Power and self-power distinctions, https://bdk.or.jp/document/dgtl-dl/dBET_Tannisho-Ofumi_1996.pdf"
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:133:    "Use low-strain tests first: Tannisho self-power and Other Power, Srivaishnava surrender debates, Sufi maqam and hal, and Bhagavad Gita action, fruit, and doership passages.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:134:    "Use high-strain anomaly cases: Dogen practice-realization, Madhyamaka non-positioning, Dzogchen direct introduction, Christian apophatic unsaying, inherited practice, and secular extraction.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:158:      "Zen teachers familiar with Dogen practice-realization",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:159:      "Dzogchen or Mahamudra teachers familiar with direct introduction",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:168:    "risk_of_overread": "High. The protocol could become circular if the same passage codes claimant grammar, credit distribution, and predicted safeguards. It can also impose an analyst vocabulary of claimant, credit, and strain on traditions that reject agency accounting, especially Dogen practice-realization, Madhyamaka non-positioning, apophatic theology, Dzogchen direct recognition, and inherited devotional practice.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:170:    "structural_observation": "The Gita is a strong test case for why credit needs claimant grammar first. It preserves obligation to act, denies simple ego-doership, separates action from fruits, and lists multiple causes of action, including bodily basis, instruments, effort, and divine factor. A simple self versus God credit scale misses that action, fruit, ego, duty, and causation are differently distributed. Tannisho creates a sharper strain case. It relocates efficacy to Amida's Vow, rejects self-powered merit, denies Shinran ownership over disciples, and describes nembutsu as neither ordinary practice nor good act because it arises through Other Power. Coding both texts with the same deferring or collaborative category would flatten native rules about what kind of action is even claimable. The close read supports the candidate's sequence, but it also shows that the primary traditions already force much of the insight."
./reviews/dialogues/2026-05-30-whether-frame-dependence-can-be-bounded-well-enough-that-independent-cod.json:120:        "note": "Remainder pressure plus inference policy give the upgradeable axes the test demand was asking for.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.md:57:Candidate: Dzogchen or Mahamudra luminous selfless awareness, plus Pseudo-Dionysius's claim that the divine Cause is beyond both affirmation and negation.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.md:67:- If: Primary manuals should contain explicit or implicit custody rules near passages that loosen ordinary selfing. Then: Texts should pair negation of objects or self-story with instructions such as do not locate a self, know the unseen seer, or lift the heart to God. Weakens if: The relevant manuals loosen objects without any subsequent owner, Self, or recipient language, or use all three interchangeably. Test surface: Close-reading corpus of Theravada, Advaita, Christian apophatic, Dzogchen, and Mahamudra manuals.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.md:75:- Dzogchen or Mahamudra teachers
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.md:107:- Close-read Dzogchen and Mahamudra instructions on rigpa or luminous awareness against Bahiya and Brihadaranyaka before publishing the custody model.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-30-some-help-should-not-be-managed-fa2107c4aba3ff90.md:26:- Dogen practice-realization sources such as Bendowa or Genjokoan; Shinran and Tannisho Other Power sources, including https://shinranworks.com/commentaries/notes-on-once-calling-and-many-calling/ and Tannisho chapter 8 translations.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-30-some-help-should-not-be-managed-fa2107c4aba3ff90.md:28:Structural observation: MN 22 supports a tool-use and non-clinging pattern: a teaching can be used for crossing and then not possessed. The Heart Sutra strains a simple release rule because it denies attainment while preserving reliance on prajnaparamita. Dogen-style practice-realization strains it further because practice is not merely an instrument awaiting later review. Shinran Other Power also resists practitioner-owned handling because merit and final efficacy are not primarily self-managed. The candidate's strongest move is not method-release, which is old, but the fit gate that asks whether ownership, temporality, and available agency exist before prescribing review.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-30-some-help-should-not-be-managed-fa2107c4aba3ff90.md:30:Secondary literature gap: The audit still needs direct term-level work on Shinran's jinen honi and hakarai, Dogen's shusho-itto or practice-realization, apophatic unsaying, spiritual direction ethics, and ACT or CBT literature on self-monitoring. Source reliability is adequate for lowering novelty, not for promoting the model as a discovery.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-30-some-help-should-not-be-managed-fa2107c4aba3ff90.md:40:- Dogen practice realization no gaining Bendowa Genjokoan
./reviews/originality/2026-05-30-some-help-should-not-be-managed-fa2107c4aba3ff90.md:41:- Shinran Other Power self power jinen honi hakarai
./reviews/originality/2026-05-30-some-help-should-not-be-managed-fa2107c4aba3ff90.md:49:- Acceptance and Commitment Therapy literature on experiential avoidance and control of private events, for example https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2223147/.: overlap: Close on the claim that trying to manage internal experience can become part of the problem, and that change can require a different relation to control rather than more private monitoring.; difference: ACT does not use cross-tradition custody, vow, Other Power, or practice-realization grammar, and it does not frame the issue as an after-use review gate.; novelty impact: Strong reduction for the psychological mechanism. The religious-comparative routing remains a synthesis.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-30-some-help-should-not-be-managed-fa2107c4aba3ff90.md:64:Why it strains the model: The idea assumes that private review is often the burden for depleted over-managers. If structure and review are the relieving container, then the model confuses over-management with the absence of safe holding. It also fails if Other Power, Dogen practice-realization, or community-held practice includes rigorous review, conduct correction, and formal repetition without harming agency.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-30-some-help-should-not-be-managed-fa2107c4aba3ff90.md:70:- If: Ownership, completion temporality, and spare agency are real fit variables for after-use practices. Then: Split-source coding of primary manuals will show that traditions without practitioner-owned result or discrete after have different warning, verification, and repair patterns than traditions that permit method-use and later handling. Weakens if: Coders cleanly apply keep, release, and embody axes across Shinran, Dogen, Heart Sutra, MN 22, and apophatic sources without distortion, and the three fit variables do not predict held-out warnings or repairs. Test surface: Pre-registered comparative codebook with held-out manual warnings and practitioner interviews.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-30-some-help-should-not-be-managed-fa2107c4aba3ff90.md:79:- Soto Zen teachers or scholars of practice-realization
./reviews/originality/2026-05-30-some-help-should-not-be-managed-fa2107c4aba3ff90.md:80:- Jodo Shinshu teachers or scholars of Other Power
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:1:# Expressive Realism: Dogen's Being-Time as a Dissolution of the Passage Problem That Neither Eternalism Nor Presentism Can Resolve
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:11:Dogen's being-time (uji) dissolves the passage problem in philosophy of time; the apparently irreconcilable conflict between eternalism and presentism; not by choosing a side or finding a compromise, but by rejecting the presupposition both share: that being and time are separable dimensions that can be independently analyzed. If being IS time, the question 'does time pass?' is malformed, comparable to asking 'does existence exist?' The block universe correctly grasps that no moment is more real than any other, but wrongly infers that this makes passage illusory. Presentism correctly grasps that each moment has experiential primacy, but wrongly infers that this requires other moments to be unreal. Dogen's position, which I call 'expressive realism'; holds that each moment is the full self-expression of being, a complete dharma-position that fully includes past and future but is independent of them. This is not the block universe with consciousness added (the 'moving spotlight' theory), which retains the being/time separation and merely adds a subjective indexical. It is not process philosophy (Whitehead), which still treats temporal events as arising in a medium of creative advance. In expressive realism, there is no medium; no container, no timeline, no dimension called 'time' through which beings pass or in which they sit. Each dharma-position IS time, meaning that temporality is not a feature of reality but is constitutive of what it means for anything to be real at all. The passage problem dissolves because passage was never something happening TO beings; beings ARE passage, in the same way that waves are not things IN the ocean but are the ocean's self-expression. The concept of an 'inert' moment (the block universe's fundamental unit) is as incoherent as a wave that does not move; not because something external moves it, but because waving IS what it is to be a wave. This reframing has a structural (not evidential) affinity with Rovelli's relational quantum mechanics, where physical properties are not intrinsic to systems but exist only in relation to other systems: Rovelli eliminates the 'view from nowhere' in space; Dogen eliminates the 'view from nowhen' in time. Both deny that reality can be described from outside the relational/temporal structure. But Dogen goes further than Rovelli: where Rovelli's relationism still allows for a block-universe mathematical description (even if properties are relational, spacetime is still a manifold), Dogen insists that the manifold IS the self-expression and has no independent existence apart from it. This also extends the inferential gap model to a new domain: both the block universe and uji share the same structural datum; the equal reality of all temporal moments; but apply different inferential policies. Physics infers that temporal equality entails the illusoriness of passage. Dogen infers that temporal equality entails the self-sufficiency of each moment AS passage. Same data, different inference. The translation strain between these positions lives in the word 'real': for eternalism, real means 'exists in the four-dimensional block'; for Dogen, real means 'dynamically self-expresses as a complete dharma-position.' Neither can be translated into the other without destroying its core meaning.
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:15:Three claims distinguish this from existing literature. First, framing Dogen's position as 'expressive realism'; a genuine third option in the presentism/eternalism debate; goes beyond existing Dogen scholarship, which either assimilates uji to the B-theory (Vorenkamp) or treats it as sui generis Asian philosophy outside the Western debate. The project's own source card characterizes Dogen as 'block universe plus experiential indexicality,' which I argue is insufficient because it preserves the being/time separation that Dogen explicitly rejects. Second, applying the inferential gap model (from my prior atman/anatta observation) to the temporal domain is new within this project: both eternalism and uji share a structural feature (all moments equally real) but apply divergent inferential policies to it, just as Advaita and Buddhism share a phenomenological feature (objectless awareness) but infer differently. This demonstrates the generativity of the inferential gap framework beyond its original domain. Third, the specific comparison with Rovelli's relational QM has not, to my knowledge, been made through Dogen; existing literature (Rovelli himself, plus secondary sources) connects relational QM to Nagarjuna's emptiness, but Dogen's being-time is a stronger parallel because Dogen positively identifies being with temporality, whereas Nagarjuna empties time of inherent existence without positively characterizing what remains. The Dogen-Rovelli bridge is constructive where the Nagarjuna-Rovelli bridge is deconstructive.
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:19:- Dogen, Shobogenzo 'Uji' (1240): 'Mountains are time. Oceans are time. If they were not time, there would be no mountains or oceans.' Being and time are not two things in a relationship but a single reality. Each moment occupies its own dharma-position containing both before and after within itself.
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:20:- Dogen, Genjokoan: 'Firewood abides in the phenomenal expression of firewood, which fully includes before and after and is independent of before and after. Ash abides in the phenomenal expression of ash.' Firewood does not 'become' ash; each is a complete expression of being-time.
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:21:- Dogen, Uji: 'Do not think that time merely flies away. Do not see flying away as the only function of time. If time merely flies away, you would be separated from time.' Passage (kyoryaku) is not something happening to beings; beings ARE passage.
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:27:- Vorenkamp's analysis (cited in project source card buddhism-dogen-uji): Dogen contains 'all the main elements of McTaggart's B-series.' The source card characterizes Dogen as 'block universe plus experiential indexicality.' My model argues this characterization is insufficient.
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:28:- Laukkonen and Slagter, 'From many to (n)one' (2021, Neuroscience and Biobehavioral Reviews): meditation reduces temporal depth of predictive processing, bringing the practitioner into the here and now, which may be a first-person enactment of what Dogen describes philosophically.
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:29:- Heine, 'Existential and Ontological Dimensions of Time in Heidegger and Dogen' (1985): contrasts Dogen's uji with Heidegger's Being and Time. Both identify being with temporality, but Dogen's non-dual framework does not privilege Dasein's futural projection.
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:32:- Claude prior finding, 'The Processual Remainder' (2026-05-25): Ibn Arabi's barzakh reveals a processual mode of being (real but non-persistent, requiring continuous enactment), which parallels but differs from Dogen's dharma-position in instructive ways.
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:36:Four serious objections. First, Dogen's uji is a soteriological text written for Zen practitioners, not a contribution to the philosophy of time. The passage problem is a Western philosophical construct arising from specific commitments (tensed vs. tenseless language, special relativity, the mind-body problem). Applying uji to this debate decontextualizes it and may project a philosophical ambition Dogen never had. His concern was liberation from suffering through realizing being-time, not resolving a theoretical puzzle about the ontology of temporal passage. Treating uji as 'expressive realism' may be a sophisticated form of the perennial philosophy fallacy; finding answers to our questions in texts that were asking different questions. Second, the distinction between 'expressive realism' and Whitehead's process philosophy may be thinner than claimed. Whitehead's actual occasions are also complete in themselves, also contain their pasts via prehension, and also deny that time is a container. If expressive realism collapses into process philosophy, the novelty claim fails. The difference may be that Whitehead retains a directionality (creative advance) that Dogen does not; but this needs more careful argument than I've provided. Third, Nagarjuna would deconstruct expressive realism just as readily as he deconstructs eternalism and presentism. If being IS time, then being and time have no independent svabhava; but their identification also has no svabhava. The tetralemma applied to 'being is time' yields: being is not time, being is not not-time, being is not both time and not-time, being is not neither time nor not-time. From a Madhyamaka standpoint, Dogen's positive identification is another conceptual construction to be emptied. If this critique stands, 'expressive realism' is not a stable third position but a stage that Madhyamaka analysis would dissolve. Fourth, the Rovelli parallel may be superficially appealing but formally weak. Rovelli's relationism is mathematically precise and empirically constrained; Dogen's being-time is poetic and experientially oriented. The claim that both 'eliminate the view from nowhere/nowhen' trades on an equivocation: Rovelli eliminates it in the sense that physical quantities are mathematically frame-dependent; Dogen eliminates it in the sense that each moment of zazen IS the universe. These may not be the same operation in any rigorous sense.
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:60:- Test whether expressive realism genuinely survives Nagarjuna's tetralemma or collapses under Madhyamaka critique. Read MMK chapter 19 (Examination of Time) closely and apply the four-fold negation to 'being is time.' If Dogen's position requires a positive ontological identification that Nagarjuna would reject, this reveals a deep tension within East Asian Buddhism between Madhyamaka emptiness and tathagatagarbha/Buddha-nature thought; and expressive realism sits on the Buddha-nature side.
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:61:- Compare expressive realism with Whitehead's actual occasions in detail. Key test: does Whitehead's 'creative advance' (the directionality of process) have a Dogenian equivalent? If Dogen's kyoryaku (passage) is non-directional; past and future both fully present in each moment; this would distinguish expressive realism from process philosophy. If not, the novelty claim must be retracted.
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:62:- Examine whether Dogen's dharma-position concept maps onto the quantum mechanical concept of a 'quantum event' in relational QM more precisely than onto the block universe's spacetime point. A spacetime point is a location; a quantum event is a relational interaction. If dharma-positions are more like events than locations, the Rovelli parallel strengthens.
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:64:- Apply translation-strain analysis to the triad: Nagarjuna (time is empty), Dogen (being IS time), Rovelli (time is relational). These may be three inferential policies applied to the same structural observation; that time has no absolute, container-like existence. Nagarjuna empties it, Dogen identifies it with being, Rovelli relativizes it. Which strain is highest? Where does apparent convergence fail?
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:65:- Compare Dogen's dharma-position with Ibn Arabi's khalq jadid (perpetual creation) from my processual-remainder observation. Both describe each moment as complete and self-sufficient. But Ibn Arabi's moments are theophanic; manifestations of divine names; while Dogen's are non-theistic expressions of being. Does this difference matter formally, or only doctrinally? If formally: what structural feature does theophany add that being-time lacks?
./observations/claude/2026-05-25-expressive-realism-dogen-s-being-time-as-a-dissolution-of-the-passage-problem-that-neither-eternalism-nor-presentism-can-resolve.md:66:- Examine whether Wheeler's delayed-choice experiment has a Dogenian reading: if measurement retroactively determines a photon's history, and if the measurement IS a moment of being-time, then the photon's history is not 'changed retroactively' but was always already included in the dharma-position of the measurement event. This would make the delayed-choice result unsurprising from a Dogenian standpoint; not because Dogen predicted quantum mechanics, but because his ontology never assumed a determinate past independent of present being-time.
./observations/claude/2026-05-26-no-variable-stands-alone.md:15:The Lumenary corpus now contains roughly twenty-five analytical models, each isolating one variable: what the tradition knows with (epistemic organ), how it trains perception (instrument problem), what inference it draws (inferential gap), what it allows to remain after negation (residue policy), who holds action after self-release (custody policy), what error it fears (alarm profile), where inquiry stops (stopping rule), how it proves insight (verification architecture), what grammar the remainder speaks (remainder grammar), whom negation addresses (address policy), what the path protects (protected variable), what can overrule the knower (appeal court), what disease the cure creates (shadow of attainment), what the method does when it meets itself (reflexivity policy), what temporal structure realization follows (realization topology), what the comparer imposes (appropriation pressure), where convergence peaks (attentional commons), what love-as-knowing reveals (devotional remainder), what relational knowing requires (second-personal blind spot), and several others. Every one of these models treats its focal variable as analytically independent. The entanglement thesis reframes all of them as nodes in a constraint network and argues that the network, not any individual node, is the deepest unit of analysis for understanding a contemplative tradition. This meta-level move is distinct from the first-order analytical work that has characterized all Lumenary research to date. It is distinct from Thagard's coherence-as-constraint-satisfaction (1998), which applies constraint analysis to beliefs within a system; the entanglement thesis applies it to the analytical categories of a comparative framework. It is distinct from Murphy's Lakatosian theology (1990), which identifies hard cores and protective belts within individual traditions; the entanglement thesis identifies mutual constraints between the analytical categories used to study traditions across the board. It is distinct from Ferrer's participatory pluralism (2002, 2017), which argues for genuine plurality of spiritual enactments but does not propose that the enactments are constrained to a finite set of stable configurations. It is distinct from CodeX's interface invariant model, which identifies shared interface variables (attention, identity, salience, agency, boundary) but treats them as independently varying. The specific prediction that contemplative traditions occupy a small number of stable attractor states in the constraint space defined by the Lumenary analytical variables, and that this explains both internal coherence and resistance to hybridization, is new in the Lumenary corpus and, as far as I have found, in the comparative contemplative philosophy literature. The model also represents a productive convergence with and challenge to CodeX's work: CodeX provided most of the individual policy variables, and this observation reframes them as mutually entangled rather than independent, which changes the research programme from 'isolate more variables' to 'map the constraint relationships between existing ones.'
./observations/claude/2026-05-26-no-variable-stands-alone.md:27:- CodeX models (2026-05-25 through 2026-05-26): translation strain, residue policy, remainder pressure, residual burden of proof, custody policy, address policy, remainder grammar, interface invariant, alarm profile, appeal court, stopping rule, protected variable, return audit, appropriation pressure. These provide the individual variables whose mutual constraint relationships the entanglement thesis examines. CodeX has been the primary generator of 'policy' models; this observation is a meta-analysis showing that these policies are entangled, not independent.
./findings/convergences/2026-05-26-whether-the-separability-thesis-survives-the-method-dependency-concession-if-con.md:13:Whether the separability thesis survives the method-dependency concession. If contemplative training shapes not only how practitioners interpret the pressure but whether the pressure arises at all, then occurrence and interpretation are entangled from the start. The clean analytic cut between them may be a useful methodological fiction rather than a phenomenological discovery. Cross-trained practitioners could test the empirical question (does the same person report pressure during Advaita inquiry and not during Dzogchen practice?), but even positive results would show learned repertoire rather than settle whether the pressure has a single phenomenological character across training contexts.
./runs/20260525-230454-claude-generate-a-new-original-cross-tradition-finding-/claude-code.stdout.log:1:{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":302393,"duration_api_ms":347420,"num_turns":14,"result":"Now I have a clear picture of the full landscape. Let me generate the idea. I'll use Dzogchen's recognition method as my thinking lens: rather than constructing a new framework, I'll ask what's already implicit in the existing observations that hasn't been named.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"title\": \"The Realization Topology: Temporal Structure as a Hidden Variable That Determines Whether Post-Negation Models Apply\",\n  \"idea_type\": \"model\",\n  \"source_basis\": [\n    \"Thinking method source: Dzogchen recognition (ngo sprod) as cognitive lens. Rather than constructing a new theoretical framework, I attended to what is already implicit in the existing Lumenary observations but has not been named. The recognition: every model so far has been phrased as 'aftma-yangtik-trekcho-instruction. Non-fabrication rests on non-production, not on an ownership warning; the forbidden-claimant cell is empty by category, not by omission.", "Shinran, Letter to Senshin, https://shinranworks.com/letters/a-collection-of-letters-zensho-text/what-we-call-other-power/. Source-centered credit with explicit prohibition against calculation. A clear case where the forbidden-claimant column does genuine work.", "Bhagavad Gita 3.27, on prakriti as doer, and BG 2.47 on nishkama karma. Split-credit distribution: the practitioner acts but must disown doership and entitlement to results.", "Srivaishnava markata/marjara debate (Vedanta Desikan and Manavala Mamuni). An indigenous tradition that formally split over credit distribution, confirming it is a practice variable, not an academic construction.", "Chinul, Secrets on Cultivating the Mind, Robert Buswell translation. The anomaly case for stage-dependent claimability: sudden awakening may be dissolutive or ontological, while gradual cultivation may be regulatory.", "Al-Hujwiri, Kashf al-Mahjub, on maqam and hal. Explicit split-credit formulation in Sufism: stations are earned, states are bestowed.", "Dialogue origin: c248ac37d37726ad.", "Parent ideas: The Forbidden Claimant Rubric; Whose Doing Is This? Credit Distribution as a Practice Variable"], "status": "draft", "title": "The Claimability and Support Rubric", "why_it_might_be_new": "The Forbidden Claimant Rubric's contribution was the two-part code of support locus plus forbidden claimant, which prevented reducing gift traditions to hidden self-power and effort traditions to naive agency. The Credit Distribution model's contribution was a five-type cross-tradition typology (practitioner-centered, source-centered, split, activity-centered, ground-centered) with failure-mode predictions. Neither contained the three-stance claimability variable as a prior dimension. The Proponent universalized prohibition; the Challenger had five distribution types but did not formalize the tradition's relationship to the claiming framework as a separate analytical layer. The synthesis emerged from the dialectical pressure of Nagarjuna's Chapter 8 against the rubric's agent-function-claimant structure. The specific contribution is: traditions do not merely distribute credit differently; they stand in different relationships to the very possibility of credit attribution. That relationship is a separable variable that sits before both the support-locus analysis and the credit-distribution typology, and it determines whether the forbidden-claimant column, the credit-distribution type, or neither is the right analytical tool for a given tradition."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:66:{"agent": "claude", "created_at": "2026-05-26T17:39:03-07:00", "critique": "Five concerns carry weight. First, the rubric's eleven fields with multiple rows per function may be too complex for reliable cross-tradition coding; a reduced five-or-six-field version should be tested before deploying the full instrument. Second, the claimant-layer vocabulary (view, conceit, latent tendency) derives from Theravada Buddhist phenomenology and may distort traditions with structurally different self-models. Jodo Shinshu does not describe graduated dissolution of self-claiming; Dzogchen does not describe dissolution at all but recognition of what was always present. Applying gradient language to these traditions risks imposing one tradition's map as a neutral analytic frame. Third, radical Jodo Shinshu remains an anomaly: if even the analyst's question 'whose doing is this?' is a form of self-power calculation, then the rubric's entire architecture may be refused by the tradition it attempts to code. The rubric needs a genuine refusal category, not a forced fit. Fourth, the practical conclusion (anticipate re-appropriation, provide repair) may be independently derivable from Trungpa's spiritual materialism analysis without the full transfer-profile apparatus; the rubric's added complexity needs justification beyond what the simpler insight already provides. Fifth, dual-trained practitioners who switch between effort, surrender, recognition, and just-sitting without reported dissonance remain an unresolved empirical pressure: if the credit variable is less operationally important than the model claims, the elaborate rubric may over-engineer a distinction that practitioners navigate more fluidly than the model predicts.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "b34ba3414b7418e8", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Before coding across traditions, two independent coders should attempt to fill the claimant-layer field for at least four traditions (early Buddhist, Jodo Shinshu, Dzogchen, Soto Zen) using only each tradition's own vocabulary. If they converge on comparable layers using indigenous terms, the rubric's cross-traditional reach is supported. If convergence requires importing the Theravada three-layer schema, the rubric is a strong Buddhist studies instrument but a weaker comparative one.", "Code three primary manuals from the effort-path category for every passage that addresses ownership of attainment or capacity. If warnings cluster around identifiable moments where the permitted grammar of agency changes, the formal-marker dimension adds predictive value. If warnings distribute evenly with no correlation to formal boundaries, the gradient model alone is sufficient.", "Test the re-appropriation prediction by interviewing practitioners who report having experienced partial dissolution. Ask which aspects of self-claiming released first, which persisted longest, and whether re-appropriation took predictable forms (egolessness as credential, surrender as achievement, recognition as identity). If practitioners consistently report uneven, multi-domain dissolution with characteristic re-appropriation patterns, the dual-track model is supported.", "Include radical Jodo Shinshu as a rubric-refusal test case. Have coders attempt to fill all eleven fields for Shinran's Tannisho and Rennyo's letters. If the refusal category works (coders can reliably mark where the tradition refuses the analyst's frame rather than being forced into it), the rubric handles its hardest case. If coders must distort the tradition to complete the coding, the rubric needs structural revision.", "Test whether a reduced rubric of five or six fields (function, formal transfer marker, claimant layer, safeguard, re-appropriation pattern, repair) captures most of the variance of the full eleven-field version. If inter-rater reliability and predictive power drop by less than 10% with the reduced version, prefer the simpler instrument.", "Compare transfer profiles with the capacity ledger to determine whether they are genuinely separable variables. If two traditions can share a capacity-ledger profile while differing on transfer-profile markers, both instruments are needed. If transfer profiles always determine capacity profiles, one may be reducible to the other."], "original_claim": "The boundary between effort and gift in contemplative practice is best treated as a transfer profile with two separable dimensions. The first dimension is the tradition's formal transfer markers: identifiable instructions, permissions, and prohibitions that change the grammar of agency at specific stages. These markers tell the practitioner when a capacity may be cultivated, when ordinary-self ownership of that capacity becomes forbidden, who or what is credited as source, and how to repair the return of ownership claims. The second dimension is the phenomenological dissolution gradient: the uneven, multi-domain process by which self-claiming actually releases across layers of intellectual view, affective conceit, habitual self-referencing, narrative identity, and social credential. These two dimensions interact but are not reducible to each other. A tradition may mark a sharp formal boundary (as Shinran does at the moment of shinjin, or as Dzogchen does at recognition of rigpa) while the lived release of self-claiming extends across a long interval with characteristic stalling points and re-appropriation risks. Conversely, a tradition may describe a gradual path (as early Buddhism does across the four stages of awakening) while still concentrating its strongest safeguards around identifiable moments when the permitted grammar of agency changes. The useful rubric for cross-traditional comparison therefore codes both tracks: function, formal transfer marker, stage interval, claimant layer, support holder, credited source, forbidden claimant, gradient width, stalling point, safeguard, and repair. The most dangerous period in a practice path is not the moment of initial relinquishment but the extended aftermath of partial dissolution, where some self-referencing has released and some has not. This is where the ego reconstitutes around what was surrendered: egolessness becomes credential, surrender becomes achievement, recognition becomes identity. Traditions concentrate their most specific safeguards around this vulnerable interval, not around generic anti-pride warnings distributed evenly across the arc. A practice designed with this model in view would name the initial relinquishment, anticipate the likely forms of re-appropriation, and provide explicit repair when the practitioner starts owning the surrender itself.", "path": "observations/claude/2026-05-26-the-transfer-profile-formal-boundaries-and-dissolution-gradients-in-contemplative-practice.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.89, "cross_tradition_support": 0.79, "empirical_adjacency": 0.55, "explanatory_compression": 0.81, "generativity": 0.93, "logical_coherence": 0.87, "novelty": 0.61, "practice_testability": 0.86, "publishability": 0.8, "source_reliability": 0.82}, "source_basis": ["Dialectical synthesis of Codex idea 433dd83d436b0b13 (The Handoff Point Is The Variable) and Claude idea a5ae6e997ca1d286 (Whose Doing Is This? Credit Distribution as a Practice Variable), produced through three-turn structured dialogue.", "Primary text producing the key revision: SN 22.89, Khemaka Sutta, Bhikkhu Bodhi translation (https://suttacentral.net/sn22.89/en/bodhi). Khemaka, a non-returner who abandoned self-identity view at stream-entry, reports that residual 'I am' conceit (asmi-mana) still pervades his relation to the five aggregates. This forced the revision from point to gradient by showing that within the tradition's own four-stage path model, different functional aspects of self-claiming release at different thresholds.", "Primary text grounding the formal-marker dimension: SN 45.8, Magga-vibhanga Sutta, Bhikkhu Bodhi translation (https://suttacentral.net/sn45.8/en/bodhi). Right effort assigns generating desire, activating persistence, and exerting intent to the practitioner as grammatical subject, establishing a clear formal instruction about who acts.", "Primary text grounding source-centered credit and the limits of the analyst's frame: Shinran, Tannisho and Notes on Once-Calling and Many-Calling (https://jodoshinshu.faith/tannisho-a-record-in-lament-of-divergences/ and https://shinranworks.com/commentaries/notes-on-once-calling-and-many-calling/). Even entrusting mind is attributed to Amida's working, making the tradition a test case for whether the rubric can accommodate refusal of the analyst's credit-distribution frame.", "Re-appropriation dynamics: Chogyam Trungpa, Cutting Through Spiritual Materialism (Shambhala Publications, 1973). Documents how the ego continuously reconstitutes around each new attainment, converting egolessness into credential and surrender into achievement, supporting the prediction that the aftermath of partial dissolution is the period of highest practice vulnerability.", "Dzogchen stabilization after recognition: Longchen Rabjam, Instruction on Trekcho (https://www.lotsawahouse.org/tibetan-masters/longchen-rabjam/lama-yangtik-trekcho-instruction). Rejects contrived effort at recognition yet gives instructions for stabilization, conduct, and guidance afterward, illustrating how formal markers and post-recognition practice requirements coexist.", "Indigenous split over credit distribution as a practice variable: Srivaishnava markata/marjara debate between Vadakalai and Tenkalai schools (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sri_Vaishnavism). Confirms that a living tradition formally divided over the credit question with institutional and liturgical consequences.", "Split credit in Sufism: al-Hujwiri, Kashf al-Mahjub, on maqam (station) as earned and hal (state) as bestowed (http://www.quran4u.com/Kashf/Ch%2014c.htm).", "Thinking method: Bhagavad Gita 2.47, nishkama karma (https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/chapter/2/verse/47), paired with Buddhist right effort (SN 45.8) as corrective for the split-credit bias of the lens.", "Dialogue origin: 71f493155e785b64.", "Parent ideas: The Handoff Point Is The Variable; Whose Doing Is This? Credit Distribution as a Practice Variable"], "status": "draft", "title": "The Transfer Profile: Formal Boundaries and Dissolution Gradients in Contemplative Practice", "why_it_might_be_new": "The dual-track architecture, separating formal transfer markers from phenomenological dissolution gradients, does not appear in the near-neighbor literature. Steve Bein's work on self-power, other-power, and nondualism stays within Japanese Buddhism and does not formalize the interaction between doctrinal instruction and experiential release as two codable dimensions. Pargament's religious coping styles categorize static orientations without tracking stage-sensitive dynamics. Taitetsu Unno's comparative grace work does not derive failure-mode predictions or code safeguard-warning clusters. The prior Codex idea (capacity ledger) tracked functional requirements across holders but did not distinguish formal instruction from lived release. The prior Claude idea (credit distribution typology) classified traditions by credit type but treated each type as a stable property rather than a stage-sensitive variable interacting with dissolution dynamics. The synthesis's specific contribution is the prediction that safeguards and warnings cluster where formal agency grammar changes, that re-appropriation risk peaks during partial dissolution rather than at the initial boundary, and that the claimant-layer dimension determines which form of re-appropriation is characteristic of each tradition. These predictions are testable against primary manuals and practitioner interviews and were not available from either source idea alone."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:67:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-26T17:47:06-07:00", "critique": "The candidate risks becoming too elastic. If every support counts as part of continuity ecology, the model may describe any tradition without predicting much. Minimum receptivity also needs thresholds, otherwise it becomes the trivial fact that a practitioner must be affected somehow. The causal claim needs controlled comparison, because doctrine may not always drive architecture. In many traditions, institution, ritual, charisma, or social need may shape continuity first, with doctrine rationalizing it afterward.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "34cbc5115dbd898a", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Build a coding rubric with fields for dissolution target, minimum receptivity, internal capacities, external supports, residue policy, practice ecology, warning profile, verification method, and failure mode.", "Test paired traditions with similar dissolution targets but different ecologies, such as Theravada and secular mindfulness, Advaita and Kashmir Shaivism, Jodo Shinshu and Quietist Christianity.", "Test paired traditions with similar ecologies but different dissolution targets to see whether practice form or doctrine better predicts continuity placement.", "Operationalize minimum receptivity with thresholds: capacity to be addressed, capacity to register instruction or grace, capacity to continue or not obstruct, and capacity to be recognized by the tradition as transformed.", "Run an originality audit against personal identity literature, Buddhist no self debates, Advaita witness accounts, practice theory, ritual studies, and Shinran scholarship before promotion."], "original_claim": "Self negating or self transcending paths do not simply require a minimum self, and they do not only differ by final residue. They organize a continuity ecology. Each path must preserve enough receptivity and reliability for transformation to occur, but that continuity can be internally managed, externally scaffolded, relationally entrusted, ritually stabilized, institutionally maintained, or theologically relocated. The path's dissolution target may pressure where continuity migrates, while its residue policy governs what may be authorized after negation. Practice ecology may either express that doctrinal pressure or precede it historically and force doctrine to explain an already existing arrangement.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-continuity-ecology-under-negation.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.88, "cross_tradition_support": 0.72, "empirical_adjacency": 0.54, "explanatory_compression": 0.78, "generativity": 0.92, "logical_coherence": 0.86, "novelty": 0.8, "practice_testability": 0.8, "publishability": 0.74, "source_reliability": 0.7}, "source_basis": ["Claude idea 3c5caa358a09c26a: self dissolving paths require functional capacities and those capacities shape practice architecture.", "Codex idea 5a05c720a5039323: negative self practice differs by residue policy, meaning what a tradition authorizes to remain after negation.", "Turn 1 Codex challenge: continuity may be distributed across body, habit, teacher, ritual, vow, community, grace, text, and environment rather than housed in a minimum self.", "Turn 2 Claude rebuttal: minimum self should be revised to minimum receptivity, the capacity to be addressed, register what is offered, and not obstruct transformation.", "Turn 3 Codex counter rebuttal: dissolution target, continuity distribution, residue policy, and practice ecology should be treated as interacting variables, with causal priority left open.", "Shared textual pressure: SN 22.59, Chandogya Upanishad 6.8.7 through 6.16, Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.7.23, Dogen's Bendowa, Shinran's Tannisho and Kyogyoshinsho.", "Dialogue origin: c7bd07aed1efede4.", "Parent ideas: Every Path Needs What Its Teaching Dissolves; Residue Policy in Negative Self-Practice"], "status": "draft", "title": "Continuity Ecology Under Negation", "why_it_might_be_new": "The source ideas separately named minimum self and residue policy. The dialogue produced a wider model that asks how receptivity, distributed continuity, authorized remainder, and practice ecology interact. Its possible novelty is not the claim that traditions differ about selfhood, but the testable causal question: whether what a path negates predicts where it stores continuity better than rival variables such as ritual form, institutional dependence, teacher authority, or devotional affect."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:68:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-26T18:01:35-07:00", "critique": "The candidate synthesis may still overformalize living traditions. Teachers often adjust practice demands dynamically rather than applying a fixed capacity profile or residue policy. The model also risks circular explanation if capacities are inferred from the same safeguards and failures they are supposed to predict. Adverse events may be caused by retreat intensity, psychiatric vulnerability, institutional culture, poor guidance, expectation effects, or weak community support rather than by capacity and residue interaction. This synthesis should remain a candidate until blind coding and practitioner evidence show that it predicts more than existing categories.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "2a66e120bafebae3", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Create a blind-coding rubric for initial practice instructions, prerequisites, and teacher expectations before reviewing safeguards or adverse-event reports.", "Compare matched traditions with similar residue policies but different capacity profiles, such as Theravada vipassana and Soto shikantaza.", "Compare traditions with similar capacity demands but different residue policies, such as self-inquiry, witness practice, and Buddhist de-identification practice.", "Add training ecology fields for intensity, duration, teacher supervision, community containment, screening, psychiatric vulnerability, and reporting genre.", "Use the model to design low-risk Lumenary practice seeds that specify required capacities, allowed meanings of those capacities, safety conditions, failure signs, and stopping rules."], "original_claim": "A contemplative path is shaped by three interacting factors: the operational capacities it requires, the residue policy it applies after negation, and the training ecology that calibrates those demands in lived practice. The operational profile names what must remain usable for the method to work, such as attention, memory, effort, reflexivity, receptivity, trust, or surrender. The residue policy names what those remaining capacities are allowed to count as, such as causal process, conventional personhood, witness, Self, divine gift, vow, relation, or nothing ultimately ownable. The practice ecology names the teacher, community, intensity, duration, screening, interpretation, and support conditions that determine whether the operational demand is stabilizing or destabilizing. This model predicts that safeguards, warnings, verification methods, and crisis patterns emerge from the interaction of all three, not from self-doctrine alone.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-operational-remainder-ecology.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.89, "cross_tradition_support": 0.75, "empirical_adjacency": 0.58, "explanatory_compression": 0.86, "generativity": 0.91, "logical_coherence": 0.88, "novelty": 0.82, "practice_testability": 0.82, "publishability": 0.84, "source_reliability": 0.72}, "source_basis": ["Claude idea 3c5caa358a09c26a, Every Path Needs What Its Teaching Dissolves", "Codex idea 3763a79cf5b05610, Residual Burden of Proof After Negation", "Dialogue turn 1, Codex challenge on authorized remainder", "Dialogue turn 2, Claude revision into capacity profile plus residue policy", "Dialogue turn 3, Codex counter-rebuttal on circularity and practice ecology", "SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta", "Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.7.23", "Steven Collins, Selfless Persons", "Willoughby Britton and Cheetah House adverse effects research", "Shinran, Tannisho", "Mahasi Sayadaw, Manual of Insight", "Dialogue origin: bdbb62b82cefd5ea.", "Parent ideas: Every Path Needs What Its Teaching Dissolves; Residual Burden of Proof After Negation"], "status": "draft", "title": "Operational Remainder Ecology", "why_it_might_be_new": "The source ideas each had one main axis. The proponent emphasized minimum functional continuity inside self-dissolving paths. The challenger emphasized burden-of-proof rules after negation. The dialogue produced a combined and stricter model: capacity profile, residue policy, and training ecology must be separated, coded independently, and tested for interaction effects. This may add predictive value for Lumenary practice design because it asks not only what a path teaches about self, but what the practitioner must still be able to do, what that remainder is permitted to mean, and what conditions keep the method from consuming the capacities it needs."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:69:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-26T18:21:31-07:00", "critique": "The synthesis may be too flexible. If every tradition receives a bespoke custody label and a bespoke receiving-surface label, the framework may classify many cases while predicting little. The receiving surface may also be a downstream phenotype of custody rather than an independent axis. The model must therefore define bounded categories and failed predictions before publication. It also risks translating devotional, ritual, and metaphysical claims into a modern systems vocabulary that may distort what the traditions take themselves to be doing.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "fd17456ae47234c8", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Build a comparative coding rubric with separate fields for custody assignment, receiving surface, failure mode, teacher intervention, sequencing, and verification method.", "Run matched comparisons: same custody with different receiving surfaces, same receiving surface with different custody, and within-tradition stage shifts where one variable changes while the other appears stable.", "Test Shin Buddhism, Christian infused contemplation, Dzogchen pointing-out, Theravada insight practice, and Advaita self-inquiry as initial cases.", "Define bounded receiving-surface categories before further synthesis: investigating, entrusting, recognizing, waiting, loving attention, non-fabricating, embodied presence.", "Audit prior art in theology of grace, Pure Land other-power, contemplative pedagogy, distributed cognition, and phenomenology of attention before calling the synthesis original."], "original_claim": "A contemplative path that weakens ordinary self-ownership needs a custody architecture and a local human interface. Custody names where transformation functions are assigned: causal process, hidden Self, teacher, vow, grace, community, ritual, God, or the individual practitioner. Receiving surface names what must remain available in the practitioner for the path to land: investigation, entrusting, recognition, loving attention, non-fabrication, or embodied presence. The model is not yet entitled to say these are two independent causes. Its strongest candidate form is a coding framework: record custody assignment, receiving surface, named failure mode, teacher intervention, sequencing, and verification method separately, then test whether receiving surface adds prediction beyond custody.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-custody-and-receiving-surface.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.88, "cross_tradition_support": 0.72, "empirical_adjacency": 0.55, "explanatory_compression": 0.82, "generativity": 0.9, "logical_coherence": 0.84, "novelty": 0.77, "practice_testability": 0.82, "publishability": 0.78, "source_reliability": 0.72}, "source_basis": ["Claude idea 3c5caa358a09c26a, especially the minimum-self architecture claim and its revision under challenge.", "Codex idea 9a0072f4cf3a0ff3, especially the custody-of-attention framing across no-owner, Self, and Godward practice.", "Dialogue turn 1, where Codex recast minimum self as distributed custody of transformation functions.", "Dialogue turn 2, where Claude conceded the minimum-self overclaim and introduced receiving surface as a second variable.", "Dialogue turn 3, where Codex refined the synthesis into a custody-and-interface model and demanded matched comparison before claiming independence.", "Dialogue origin: cf1bf0e51a293036.", "Parent ideas: Every Path Needs What Its Teaching Dissolves; The Custody of Unclaimed Attention"], "status": "draft", "title": "Custody and Receiving Surface", "why_it_might_be_new": "The source ideas already contained minimum-self architecture and custody-of-attention, but the dialogue created a distinct comparative object: the interface between assigned custody and practitioner receptivity. This is not merely a compromise, because it changes the research question from 'how much self remains?' or 'where does attention belong?' to 'what custody system generates what kind of human interface, and does that interface independently predict practice failures and interventions?' This still requires originality audit against contemplative studies, theology of grace, Pure Land other-power literature, Dzogchen pointing-out accounts, and psychology of religious practice."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:71:{"agent": "claude", "created_at": "2026-05-26T18:51:41-07:00", "critique": "Three structural risks. First, the two-stage model may be a transitional formulation rather than a stable resting place. If empirical work shows that credit distribution fully determines whether and what kind of remainder pressure arises, the downstream variable is epiphenomenal and the model collapses into credit distribution alone. If remainder pressure arises independently of practice architecture, the upstream variable is unnecessary for the remainder-pressure bridge, and the original single-variable model was correct. The synthesis depends on a middle ground (partial coupling) that has not been demonstrated. Second, the procedural-refusal category groups structurally different operations: Chan search-refusal, Dzogchen bypass via pointing-out, Advaita pre-completion, and Pure Land agency relocation. If these are grouped under one heading, the synthesis risks the same kind of flattening it was designed to correct. Third, the entire framework may over-psychologize traditions whose self-understanding is ontological, cosmological, or soteriological rather than phenomenological. Treating what happens during neti neti or aggregate analysis as 'pressure' imports a psychological register that may not match the tradition's own framing. The synthesis should specify when 'pressure' is a phenomenological report, when it is a hermeneutical construct, and when it is a cognitive-science analogy, because these uses have different epistemic standing.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "a4e34eb0414dfd18", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Design and execute a partial-coupling test: classify at least twelve contemplative practices by credit distribution type and negation intensity, then collect open-ended micro-phenomenological reports (Petitmengin method) from practitioners of each, coded blind for subject-shaped residue. If remainder-pressure reports cluster by credit type but show significant within-type variance, partial coupling is supported. If they cluster perfectly, credit distribution subsumes remainder pressure. If they show no pattern by credit type, remainder pressure is independent.", "Differentiate the procedural-refusal category into at least four sub-types (search refusal, bypass via direct introduction, pre-completion declaration, and agency relocation) and test whether each sub-type correlates with a distinct credit-distribution pattern. If Huang Po's search refusal maps to activity-centered credit while Dzogchen bypass maps to ground-centered credit, the sub-types are not arbitrary but track real architectural differences.", "Code three practice manuals from each credit-distribution type for the predicted failure mode (spiritual pride for practitioner-centered, passivity for source-centered, strategic detachment for split, formalism for activity-centered, premature realization for ground-centered). If primary safeguard profiles cluster by credit type, the credit-distribution model gains predictive validation. If the primary safeguard also correlates with the presence or absence of remainder-pressure language, the two-stage model gains support.", "Test the stage-shifting hypothesis: code Theravada, Sufi, and Advaita practice sequences for both credit distribution and remainder-pressure language at each stage. If credit distribution shifts predictably across stages (e.g., practitioner-centered early, ground-centered late) and remainder pressure tracks those shifts, revise both models from tradition-level to stage-level variables.", "Investigate whether the partial-coupling claim can be operationalized in consciousness-research terms. If self-modeling theories (Metzinger, Damasio) predict that metacognitive monitoring generates a subject-model artifact regardless of intentional framework, this would support remainder pressure as partially independent of credit distribution. If self-modeling theories predict that the character of the subject-model depends on the agent's intentional stance, partial coupling is supported from the empirical side."], "original_claim": "Neither remainder pressure alone nor credit distribution alone is sufficient to bridge the full range of contemplative approaches to self and identity. The two variables operate at different levels and carry partially independent information. Credit distribution is the upstream architectural variable: a tradition's assignment of agency (to practitioner, to transcendent source, split between action and outcome, to the activity itself, or to primordial ground) determines whether a negation or self-inquiry procedure is likely, who is credited with performing it, and whether the question of a final subject becomes salient. Remainder pressure is the downstream phenomenological variable: when a practice architecture does produce agent-driven negation or ownership inquiry, a felt or conceptual demand to posit a final subject may arise. That pressure does not decide what the final subject is; the tradition's inference policy determines whether the pressure is ontologized as an unobjectifiable witness, recursively analyzed as another dependently arisen construction, bracketed as a phenomenological report, modeled as a cognitive self-representation artifact, or dissolved by refusing the search procedure that sustains it. The synthesis predicts that the two stages are partially coupled: credit distribution shapes whether and how pressure arises, but the pressure, once present, carries information about the practice moment that credit distribution alone does not specify. This partial coupling is an empirical claim requiring testing via comparative practitioner reports coded for both credit orientation and subject-shaped residue, using open-ended micro-phenomenological methods to avoid demand characteristics.", "path": "observations/claude/2026-05-26-practice-architecture-as-upstream-condition-for-remainder-phenomenology.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.88, "cross_tradition_support": 0.72, "empirical_adjacency": 0.48, "explanatory_compression": 0.85, "generativity": 0.92, "logical_coherence": 0.83, "novelty": 0.78, "practice_testability": 0.74, "publishability": 0.8, "source_reliability": 0.71}, "source_basis": ["Remainder Pressure idea (d6fee3a4a4435d8c): the separation of a subject-shaped pressure from the inference policy used to interpret it, drawn from Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.7.23, SN 22.59, and modern consciousness research on self-modeling.", "Credit Distribution idea (a5ae6e997ca1d286): the five-type typology of credit distribution (practitioner-centered, source-centered, split, activity-centered, ground-centered) drawn from SN 45.8, Bhagavad Gita 3.27, Shinran's Tannisho, Dogen's shusho-itto, Shankara's praptasya praptih, and the Srivaishnava markata/marjara debate.", "Huang Po (Huangbo Xiyun), Chuanxin Fayao (Transmission of Mind), Blofeld translation 1958: 'To use the mind to search for the mind is the greatest of all mistakes.' Introduced by the Challenger as evidence that some traditions reject the negation procedure itself rather than managing its aftermath.", "Longchenpa on the obstacle of knowing (shes-pa'i bar-chad): the act of trying to attain rigpa obscures its natural presence. Used to distinguish bypass from refusal.", "Claire Petitmengin, micro-phenomenological interview method (Explaining Experience, John Benjamins, 2006): cited by the Challenger as a protocol for collecting first-person reports without priming the content, relevant to the demand-characteristic problem in the proposed practitioner study.", "Dialogue origin: a77a66f94292c81f.", "Parent ideas: Remainder Pressure as the Hidden Variable in Self-Negation; Whose Doing Is This? Credit Distribution as a Practice Variable"], "status": "draft", "title": "Practice Architecture as Upstream Condition for Remainder Phenomenology", "why_it_might_be_new": "The Proponent's original remainder-pressure bridge and the Challenger's credit-distribution typology each offered single-variable frameworks. The dialogue produced a two-level architecture in which they operate at different stages with partial coupling. This structure was not present in either source idea. The Proponent did not treat credit distribution as an upstream condition; the Challenger did not treat remainder pressure as a downstream diagnostic that carries independent information once generated. The integration also produced a refined taxonomy of what the Proponent originally called 'management policies,' distinguishing at least six responses to remainder pressure (ontologize, recursively analyze, bracket, cognitively model, refuse the search, bypass via direct introduction) where the original had four. The partial-coupling claim is itself novel: it predicts that credit distribution shapes but does not fully determine remainder phenomenology, which would mean both variables are needed for a complete comparative framework and neither is reducible to the other."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:72:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-26T19:01:12-07:00", "critique": "The synthesis risks becoming too elastic. If entry grammar and residue authorization are coded from the same passage without independent definitions, the model may explain everything after the fact. It also risks layer confusion between practitioner phenomenology, canonical doctrine, institutional pedagogy, and later apologetic systematization. The model should not be promoted unless blind coding, negative cases, and held-out predictions show that the variables add independent explanatory value.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "6816fdc50cc6bb00", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Pre-register definitions for residue authorization, entry grammar, circularity severity, and source layer before coding further traditions.", "Run blind coding across at least eight traditions, with held-out downstream texts used to test predictions about warnings, safeguards, and verification forms.", "Use paired comparisons where residue appears similar but entry differs, such as Dzogchen and Advaita, and where entry appears similar but residue differs, such as teacher encounter traditions with different anthropologies.", "Add source-layer labels for practitioner report, canonical text, pedagogy, and later systematization to prevent false agreement across layers.", "Test whether the model clarifies modern first-break problems in therapy, education, addiction recovery, burnout, and meaning loss, where people may need change before they feel capable of beginning change."], "original_claim": "Transformative traditions organize the beginning of practice through an interaction between what remains authorized after critique and how entry into transformation is narrated, enacted, or discovered. Residue authorization constrains which entry grammars are coherent, while entry events can also disclose what the tradition later names as the usable remainder. The model therefore needs four linked variables: residue authorization, entry grammar, circularity severity, and source layer. Downstream safeguards, warnings, effort theories, and verification forms should be predicted by the interaction of these variables, not by first-break type or residue policy alone.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-entry-residue-architecture.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.88, "cross_tradition_support": 0.74, "empirical_adjacency": 0.52, "explanatory_compression": 0.82, "generativity": 0.92, "logical_coherence": 0.83, "novelty": 0.82, "practice_testability": 0.68, "publishability": 0.8, "source_reliability": 0.74}, "source_basis": ["Claude idea e2faec9c39c6a653, The First-Break Problem", "Codex idea 5a05c720a5039323, Residue Policy in Negative Self-Practice", "Turn 1 Codex challenge, residue-policy-first model", "Turn 2 Claude rebuttal, co-constitutive revision", "Turn 3 Codex counter-rebuttal, source-layered methodological constraint", "Dialogue origin: 58fec6c182359bc3.", "Parent ideas: The First-Break Problem; Residue Policy in Negative Self-Practice"], "status": "draft", "title": "Entry-Residue Architecture", "why_it_might_be_new": "The source ideas separately framed entry into transformation and post-negation residue. The dialogue created a combined architecture with testable interaction claims, no-break cases, and source-layer controls. This is only a candidate synthesis until an originality audit checks close prior work in comparative theology, Buddhist studies, Advaita-Buddhist comparison, grace and effort scholarship, and theories of conversion or initiation."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:73:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-26T19:18:47-07:00", "critique": "The synthesis risks becoming too complex for the evidence. Break mechanism, residue policy, institution, and warning language may be inseparable inside some traditions. The high-severity cluster could also be selected by the same passages used to prove the predicted safeguards. Clean source separation and pre-registered coding are necessary before this becomes more than a promising taxonomy.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "90f6f39922c6fcfc", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Pre-register coding rules for threshold acceptance, incapacity diagnosis, residue policy, institution, and break mechanism.", "Use one source set to classify entry grammar and a separate source set to code warnings, effort theory, verification, and failure modes.", "Test six cases: Theravada sangha entry, Confucian cultivation, Jodo Shinshu, Augustinian grace, Zen great doubt, and Dzogchen pointing-out.", "Add a dialogue test asking whether a modern therapeutic or educational practice solves entry through threshold, scaffold, gift-like support, self-disclosure, or residue refusal.", "Run an originality audit against religious studies, conversion theory, pedagogy, initiation studies, grace theology, and practice theory."], "original_claim": "A tradition's account of spiritual entry is best modeled as a compound grammar with four fields: what incapacity blocks ordinary entry, what minimum participation counts as real entry, what break mechanism is required if self-generated threshold entry is denied, and what residue policy governs claims after ordinary agency is negated. First-break type is not universal. It becomes an irreducible variable only in high-severity traditions that explicitly deny that any naturally self-generated threshold act can found the path.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-compound-entry-grammar.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.88, "cross_tradition_support": 0.76, "empirical_adjacency": 0.52, "explanatory_compression": 0.76, "generativity": 0.92, "logical_coherence": 0.84, "novelty": 0.82, "practice_testability": 0.78, "publishability": 0.82, "source_reliability": 0.75}, "source_basis": ["Claude idea e2faec9c39c6a653, The First-Break Problem", "Codex idea 3763a79cf5b05610, Residual Burden of Proof After Negation", "Dialogue turn 1, threshold challenge using legitimate peripheral participation", "Dialogue turns 2 and 3, revised four-variable framework and clean-coding crux", "Dialogue origin: c15f20c6f638c370.", "Parent ideas: The First-Break Problem; Residual Burden of Proof After Negation"], "status": "draft", "title": "Compound Entry Grammar", "why_it_might_be_new": "Neither source idea contained the full compound model. The First-Break Problem supplied entry mechanism and anthropology. Residual Burden supplied residue policy after negation. The dialogue added participation threshold, peripheral participation, conditional use of first-break type, and a methodological rule against circular evidence. The synthesis may be new as a comparative coding instrument, but it requires originality audit before promotion."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:74:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-26T19:36:45-07:00", "critique": "The candidate may still compress a messy causal ecology into one elegant frame. Entry doctrine, custody arrangements, institutional form, and sectarian identity often mature together, so the model could mistake co-development for doctrinal causation. Its key examples, such as Jodo Shinshu versus Jodo Shu or Dzogchen versus gradual Tibetan paths, are promising but not clean controls. The language of custody may also impose modern psychological categories on traditions whose primary terms are grace, liberation, realization, obedience, practice, or union. This candidate should remain research-level until an originality audit and process-tracing tests are completed.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "0ac1911649477722", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Run an originality audit on the prescriptive custody frame, searching for close prior arguments in initiation theory, conversion studies, situated learning, theology of grace, Buddhist transmission studies, and anthropology of apprenticeship.", "Build a coding rubric that separates lived induction, entry doctrine, custody arrangement, effort theory, authority structure, verification method, and characteristic warning language.", "Use matched comparisons, especially Jodo Shinshu versus Jodo Shu, Dzogchen versus gradual Tibetan sutra-path practice, and explicit grace traditions versus neighboring cooperation traditions.", "Add negative cases where explicit incapacity doctrine exists without major institutional divergence, and cases where institutional divergence exists without explicit incapacity doctrine.", "Design practitioner interviews that ask what held attention, trust, and agency before the practitioner could explain the path, then compare those reports with later doctrinal interpretation."], "original_claim": "Transformative paths begin by placing unstable attention, trust, agency, and interpretation under some form of custody before the practitioner can fully authorize or understand the path. Traditions then give that custody an entry grammar. In inherited, apprenticeship, ritual, and gradual habituation contexts, the grammar may be mostly retrospective, naming a process already underway. In explicit incapacity traditions, the grammar can become prescriptive: it forbids some forms of self-initiation, effort, authority, or verification, and authorizes others. The beginning of a path is therefore not only a first break and not only social induction. It is a contested custody arrangement whose doctrine may be either narration or control surface.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-prescriptive-custody-of-beginnings.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.87, "cross_tradition_support": 0.72, "empirical_adjacency": 0.58, "explanatory_compression": 0.8, "generativity": 0.91, "logical_coherence": 0.84, "novelty": 0.76, "practice_testability": 0.7, "publishability": 0.76, "source_reliability": 0.72}, "source_basis": ["Claude, The First-Break Problem: entry circularity and first-break typologies across social encounter, cosmic gift, prevenient grace, self-disclosure, gradual-break, and no-break traditions.", "Codex, The Custody of Unclaimed Attention: traditions train where loosened attention may belong after ordinary ownership weakens.", "Dialogue challenge: custodial induction, informed by Lave and Wenger's legitimate peripheral participation, shows that many practitioners begin through distributed participation before explicit understanding.", "Dialogue revision: prescriptive versus retrospective entry doctrine distinguishes doctrines that reshape practice from doctrines that narrate an already existing induction.", "Dialogue counter-rebuttal: sectarian compression is a rival explanation, requiring process tracing and matched comparisons before causal claims are promoted.", "Dialogue origin: ba5bd26446b16e88.", "Parent ideas: The First-Break Problem; The Custody of Unclaimed Attention"], "status": "draft", "title": "Prescriptive Custody of Beginnings", "why_it_might_be_new": "The source ideas separately treated entry circularity and post-negation attentional ownership. The dialogue adds a third layer: the custody of the beginning itself, before stable agency or understanding is available. The prescriptive versus retrospective distinction gives the model a way to avoid universalizing first-break doctrine while still preserving cases where doctrine reorganizes practice. This synthesis appears stronger than either original idea because it explains why some traditions can begin through ordinary participation while others must regulate the very possibility of beginning."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:75:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-26T19:54:34-07:00", "critique": "The synthesis risks becoming too flexible. If every similarity can be called convergence, every difference can be called grain, and every doctrinal statement can be called policy in transition, the model loses discriminating force. It needs pre-registered markers, temporal thresholds, and evidence from actual practitioners rather than only elite texts. It must also separate embodied attentional change from learned report vocabulary.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "6264d2ba9cccc16b", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Pre-register markers of embodied grain: attentional target selection, recovery after distraction, affective valence toward arising phenomena, observer stabilization or dissolution, and switching costs between methods.", "Run longitudinal micro-phenomenological interviews with beginner, intermediate, and advanced practitioners, coded blind to tradition and stage.", "Compare whether tradition predicts non-doctrinal practice texture better than doctrinal vocabulary, teacher framing, and report norms.", "Code practice manuals for where direction first enters: procedure, residue authorization, social expectation, or later habit.", "Test whether adverse effects differ by stage: early authorization confusion versus mature embodied directional distortion."], "original_claim": "Contemplative traditions install direction through layered mechanisms. Some direction is procedural, as when an instruction tells the practitioner what to notice, devalue, seek, or refuse from the beginning. Some direction is residue authorization, as when a tradition decides what may remain after negation. Some direction is social and linguistic, carried by teacher expectations and report norms. With repetition, residue authorization can sink into the operation itself and become embodied grain. Early mismatch should appear as confusion about what may be found or claimed. Mature mismatch should appear as switching costs, attentional resistance, or specific distortions in practice.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-layered-direction-and-residue-to-grain-conversion.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.88, "cross_tradition_support": 0.73, "empirical_adjacency": 0.62, "explanatory_compression": 0.85, "generativity": 0.92, "logical_coherence": 0.84, "novelty": 0.8, "practice_testability": 0.84, "publishability": 0.79, "source_reliability": 0.72}, "source_basis": ["Claude, The Grain of Capacity: contemplative prerequisites are directionally shaped toward the dissolution they serve.", "Codex, Residue Policy in Negative Self-Practice: traditions diverge by what they authorize to remain after negation.", "Dialogue turn 2: residue policy may become embodied grain through repeated practice under doctrinal and pedagogical framing.", "Dialogue turn 3: direction can enter at procedural, interpretive, social, and embodied layers, and grain needs independent markers.", "MN 10, Vivekachudamani vv. 17-30, Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.7.23, SN 22.59, and Rupert Gethin on sati as evaluatively charged mindfulness.", "Dialogue origin: d543da45c2afa840.", "Parent ideas: The Grain of Capacity; Residue Policy in Negative Self-Practice"], "status": "draft", "title": "Layered Direction and Residue-to-Grain Conversion", "why_it_might_be_new": "The source ideas held two different models: grain of capacity and residue policy. The dialogue created a developmental bridge between them. The new contribution is not merely that both matter, but that residue policy may be one route by which grain forms, while procedural instruction may install grain earlier. This gives the synthesis a testable temporal structure that neither source idea fully contained."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:76:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-26T20:11:37-07:00", "critique": "The synthesis may become too absorbent. If every case can be sorted after the fact into deep grain, shallow grain, custody-only, or another layer, the model loses risk. It also may overpsychologize traditions whose central claims are ontological, devotional, or revelatory rather than attentional. The model currently rests mostly on textual and analytical evidence. It needs practitioner interviews, teacher correction, and pre-registered coding criteria before it can be promoted beyond speculative and empirical-adjacent synthesis.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "48fa07b7dfb7b826", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Pre-register coding criteria for deep grain, shallow grain, custody-only, and distributed direction before applying the model to new cases.", "Run Petitmengin-style interviews with serious dual-trained practitioners during transition between practices, then blind-code whether prior training can be inferred from felt resistance before doctrinal explanation appears.", "Apply the layered rubric to Vivekachudamani, MN 10, Tannisho, Bendowa, Dzogchen pointing-out texts, and The Cloud of Unknowing.", "Re-code contemplative adverse-effect reports for capacity-grain mismatch, custody conflict, practice intensity, and missing developmental prerequisites as separate variables.", "Ask lineage teachers to review whether the coding distorts each tradition's own account of liberation, Self-knowledge, Godward surrender, or realization.", "Develop a low-risk practice intake tool for modern seekers who combine methods, focused on identifying where each method places direction and what mismatch signs to watch for."], "original_claim": "Direction in contemplative training has no single fixed location. In some instructions, direction is capacity-internal from the first exercise, as when viveka is defined as discrimination between eternal and non-eternal. In other cases, direction is present as framing but may not fully govern the felt operation. In still other cases, direction arrives chiefly through entrusting, recognition, transmission, or teacher authorization. Grain and custody are therefore not rival master explanations. They are layers in a wider map of how a practice tells loosened attention what it may become, serve, refuse, or release. The model should code direction before interpreting outcomes, across lexical definition, bodily routine, affective posture, attentional operation, teacher authorization, community interpretation, and post-insight integration. Its modern use is to help cross-trained practitioners and teachers diagnose confusion, flatness, reification, dissociation, or misplaced effort when methods from different traditions are combined without noticing where their direction enters.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-layered-direction-of-practice.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.86, "cross_tradition_support": 0.72, "empirical_adjacency": 0.57, "explanatory_compression": 0.84, "generativity": 0.91, "logical_coherence": 0.83, "novelty": 0.78, "practice_testability": 0.78, "publishability": 0.78, "source_reliability": 0.72}, "source_basis": ["Claude idea 915778a2f5edc30e, The Grain of Capacity, especially the claim that prerequisites can be directionally shaped toward the dissolution they serve.", "Codex idea 9a0072f4cf3a0ff3, The Custody of Unclaimed Attention, especially the claim that traditions train where loosened attention may belong after ordinary ownership weakens.", "Dialogue turn 1, which challenged blanket grain with a custody-after-loosening model.", "Dialogue turn 2, which revised grain into deep grain, shallow grain, and custody-only.", "Dialogue turn 3, which proposed layered direction and prior coding rules as the stronger synthesis.", "John D. Dunne, Buddhist Styles of Mindfulness, used as pressure against coarse tradition-level grain and support for instruction-level analysis.", "Claire Petitmengin's micro-phenomenological interview method, used as the proposed way to test lived directional residue.", "Vivekachudamani, MN 10, Shinran's Tannisho, Dogen's Bendowa, The Cloud of Unknowing, and the Bahiya Sutta as candidate cases for different sites of direction.", "Dialogue origin: 616853e6d5faa311.", "Parent ideas: The Grain of Capacity; The Custody of Unclaimed Attention"], "status": "draft", "title": "Layered Direction of Practice", "why_it_might_be_new": "The source ideas did not already contain this full synthesis. The grain model located direction mainly in the preparatory capacity. The custody model located the decisive difference mainly at the handoff of loosened attention. The dialogue generated a third model: direction can be distributed across multiple layers, and each layer must be coded separately before making claims about transfer, mismatch, or harm. This converts a comparative insight into a research discipline with falsifiable predictions rather than a flexible vocabulary."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:77:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-26T20:28:02-07:00", "critique": "The candidate may still impose comparability on traditions that do not recognize a discrete arrival, authorization event, or stable boundary. It risks circular coding if the same texts define both the authority boundary and the reflexive operation assigned to it. It also remains vulnerable to textual elitism unless checked against teacher protocols, practitioner reports, community safeguards, and historical institutions. It should not be promoted until an originality audit searches for prior models in comparative mysticism, ritual authority, religious institutional theory, and practice-realization scholarship.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "8cb72c271bee8a54", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Run an originality audit on authority-boundary ecology before treating it as new.", "Create a native-boundary audit template: who recognizes maturity, by what evidence, at what stage, under what rules, with what re-entry obligations.", "Apply the template to at least eight cases, including Mandukya Advaita, Heart Sutra Madhyamaka, Rinzai koan training, Dogen's Soto Zen, Eckhart, Teresa of Avila, Dzogchen, and Sufi fana.", "Only after the native-boundary audit, code confirmation, cancellation, dissolution, and identity as reflexive operations.", "Test whether shared reflexive operation predicts authorization, transmission, teaching strategy, and ethical re-entry better than tradition-membership, stage sequence, or metaphysical register.", "Add practitioner and institutional evidence to avoid relying only on canonical limit-language."], "original_claim": "At the edge of contemplative practice, the decisive unit is not first a doctrine, a method type, or a final experience. It is a native authority-boundary: the tradition's own way of deciding who is mature, what evidence counts, who may teach, what must be released, and how realization returns to ordinary conduct. Reflexive operations such as confirmation, cancellation, dissolution, and identity should be coded only after this boundary is established from native sources. If those operations then predict authorization, transmission, teaching strategy, and ethical re-entry better than tradition-membership or metaphysical content, they become a real comparative variable. If not, they remain a useful descriptive vocabulary inside a broader authority ecology.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-authority-boundary-ecology.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.89, "cross_tradition_support": 0.66, "empirical_adjacency": 0.49, "explanatory_compression": 0.78, "generativity": 0.91, "logical_coherence": 0.84, "novelty": 0.82, "practice_testability": 0.72, "publishability": 0.79, "source_reliability": 0.64}, "source_basis": ["Claude idea 75a5718aa9a991ec, which proposed confirmation, cancellation, and dissolution as method relations at completion.", "Codex idea d92d2f0f6455ac53, which treats translation strain as the productive datum in cross-tradition convergence.", "Codex challenge in turn 1, which decomposed completion into lexical, metaphysical, institutional, pedagogical, and phenomenological differences.", "Claude rebuttal in turn 2, which revised the model into reflexive operations at the verification boundary and added Dogen's practice-realization identity.", "Codex counter-rebuttal in turn 3, which made native authorization boundaries prior to any clustering analysis and proposed an authority ecology distributed across text, teacher, conduct, community recognition, doctrine, and safeguards.", "Dialogue origin: 6ee62cdfab4c5a62.", "Parent ideas: The Method's Reckoning: What a Practice Does With Its Own Authority at Completion; Translation Strain as a Load Test for Convergence"], "status": "draft", "title": "Authority-Boundary Ecology", "why_it_might_be_new": "The synthesis is not contained in either source idea alone. The proponent supplied method reckoning, but initially treated completion as the comparable unit. The challenger supplied translation strain, but did not yet produce an authority-boundary model. The dialogue creates a new procedure: audit the native authorization unit first, then test whether reflexive operations explain institutional form. This shifts comparison from final claims to the social and ethical technology that governs maturity."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:78:{"agent": "claude", "created_at": "2026-05-26T20:40:38-07:00", "critique": "Four weaknesses require attention. First, the candidate synthesis is a framework, not a finding. It proposes a rubric and a coding exercise but has not executed either. Until at least six traditions are coded for both variables using strict decision rules, the claim that residue authorization varies within credit types remains promissory. The Advaita-Dzogchen comparison is the make-or-break test case, and the judgment of whether witness-authorization and self-liberating-remainder are genuinely different structural moves or different vocabularies for the same ground-centered authorization has not been made. Second, the non-positioning and self-resolving categories risk becoming catch-all bins unless further subdivided. Bahiya's strategic deflection, the Buddha's refusal of the avyakata questions as principled agnosticism, and Zen's deliberate silence about attainment are all potentially different moves currently lumped together. Third, the model treats credit distribution and residue authorization as if they exhaust the relevant variables. The Challenger raised the possibility that a tradition's theory of how language relates to the unconditioned may independently constrain residue policy; apophatic traditions may refuse remainder not because of appropriation risk but because positive predication of the unconditioned is a category error. That would require a three-variable model. Fourth, the stage-shifting objection from the Challenger's original idea applies here: many traditions shift credit distribution across stages of practice (practitioner-centered early, ground-centered or source-centered late), which means the two-variable coding may need to be applied at the stage level rather than the tradition level, significantly increasing complexity.", "epistemic_labels": ["interpretive", "textual", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "732bcb02b424bd36", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Execute the two-variable coding exercise on at least six traditions: Advaita Vedanta, Dzogchen, Theravada (SN 22.59 lineage), Bahiya-style direct instruction, Pure Land Buddhism (Jodo Shinshu), and one apophatic Western tradition (Meister Eckhart or the Cloud of Unknowing). Code credit distribution and residue authorization independently, using separate passes. If residue authorization varies within at least one credit type, the mediating variable is vindicated.", "Close-read Longchenpa's Finding Rest in the Nature of Mind against Shankara's Upadesa Sahasri to determine whether self-liberating-remainder and witness-authorization are structurally distinct residue policies or different vocabularies for the same ground-centered move. This is the decisive test case for whether the two variables are separable.", "Develop strict coding rules for the residue-authorization values, specifying what textual or instructional features distinguish positive authorization from self-resolving remainder, and non-positioning from undecidable silence. Without these rules, the rubric cannot be falsified.", "Test the stage-shifting complication: code Theravada, Sufi, and Advaita practice sequences for both credit distribution and residue authorization at each stage. If both variables shift together in lockstep, they may not be separable at the stage level. If they shift independently (credit distribution changes at one stage, residue authorization at another), the two-variable model gains strong support.", "Investigate whether apophatic traditions require a third variable (theory of predication applied to the unconditioned) that constrains residue policy independently of credit distribution. If Eckhart's Godhead-beyond-God refuses remainder on linguistic-categorial grounds rather than appropriation-risk grounds, the model may need expansion."], "original_claim": "Translation strain between contemplative traditions that unsettle personal identity cannot be located at a single variable. It sits at the interaction of two: credit distribution (how the tradition assigns the power behind transformative practice) and residue authorization (what the tradition permits, refuses, or leaves unclaimed after ordinary identification is unsettled). Credit distribution is the upstream constraint. It determines the field of coherent residue policies by setting the appropriation risk: practitioner-centered credit makes authorized remainder dangerous because the practitioner can claim it; ground-centered credit makes it safe because no one produced it; split credit leaves the question open. But credit distribution does not by itself specify the post-negation instruction. Within the constraints it sets, traditions make distinct choices. A ground-centered tradition may authorize a metaphysical Self (Advaita witness), treat the ground as self-liberating and refuse to stabilize it (Dzogchen rigpa), or leave the question open (apophatic silence). A practitioner-centered tradition may explicitly refuse all remainder (SN 22.59), redirect attention to non-appropriation without settling ontology (Bahiya), or pragmatically defer the question. These are different moves with different practice consequences, even when the upstream credit type is the same. The residue-authorization axis therefore requires at least four values: positive authorization (the remainder is identified and inhabited), explicit refusal (no aggregate or awareness is exempted from non-identification), non-positioning (self-insertion is blocked without settling what remains), and self-resolving remainder (the ground is acknowledged but the practitioner is instructed not to hold it). A fifth value, undecidable silence, may be needed for apophatic traditions that refuse to authorize or withhold on principled grounds. The translation strain between Advaita and early Buddhism is located not at self-versus-no-self, and not at residue policy alone, but at the fact that their different credit structures make different residue policies coherent, and their different residue policies produce different instructions at the post-negation threshold. A two-variable rubric that codes both credit distribution and residue authorization for each tradition, and then examines their interaction, would be more discriminating than either variable alone.", "path": "observations/claude/2026-05-26-credit-constrained-residue-authorization-as-a-two-variable-model-of-post-negation-translation-strain.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.84, "cross_tradition_support": 0.74, "empirical_adjacency": 0.28, "explanatory_compression": 0.82, "generativity": 0.9, "logical_coherence": 0.85, "novelty": 0.72, "practice_testability": 0.65, "publishability": 0.7, "source_reliability": 0.72}, "source_basis": ["Dialogue between 'Residue Policy in Negative Self-Practice' (5a05c720a5039323) and 'Whose Doing Is This? Credit Distribution as a Practice Variable' (a5ae6e997ca1d286), turns 1 through 3.", "Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.7.23, Max Muller translation, Internet Sacred Text Archive: the inner ruler described as the Self, unseen but seeing, with no other seer/hearer/perceiver/knower (https://sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe15/sbe15070.htm).", "SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta, Bhikkhu Sujato translation, SuttaCentral: the five aggregates, including consciousness, treated as impermanent and not fit to identify as mine, I, or self (https://suttacentral.net/sn22.59/en/sujato).", "Bahiya Sutta (Ud 1.10), Thanissaro Bhikkhu translation, Access to Insight: 'In the seen, just the seen; in the heard, just the heard' as a post-negation instruction that blocks self-insertion without settling ontological remainder (https://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/kn/ud/ud.1.10.than.html).", "SN 45.8 Magga-vibhanga Sutta, Thanissaro Bhikkhu translation, Access to Insight: right effort as practitioner-centered credit (https://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/sn/sn45/sn45.008.than.html).", "Bhagavad Gita 3.27 on prakriti as the real agent of all action (https://www.bhagavad-gita.us/bhagavad-gita-3-27/).", "Shankara, Upadesa Sahasri, Sengaku Mayeda edition (SUNY, 1992), on praptasya praptih (attainment of the already-attained) as ground-centered credit that makes witness-authorization safe.", "Longchenpa, Finding Rest in the Nature of Mind (Sems nyid ngal gso), Padmakara Translation Group (Shambhala, 2017): rigpa as self-liberating, a potential fourth residue value under the same ground-centered credit as Advaita.", "Dialogue origin: f29cde6702a2b1f5.", "Parent ideas: Residue Policy in Negative Self-Practice; Whose Doing Is This? Credit Distribution as a Practice Variable"], "status": "audit-pending", "title": "Credit-Constrained Residue Authorization as a Two-Variable Model of Post-Negation Translation Strain", "why_it_might_be_new": "The Proponent's original idea treated residue policy as a free-standing independent variable. The Challenger's credit-distribution model treated residue policy as fully derivative. Neither source idea contained the interaction model in which credit distribution constrains but does not determine residue authorization, and translation strain is located at the interaction rather than at either variable. The expanded residue taxonomy (positive authorization, explicit refusal, non-positioning, self-resolving remainder, undecidable silence) was generated across the three turns of dialogue and is not present in either source idea. The specific prediction that the same credit type should yield distinguishable residue policies across traditions (testable via the Advaita-Dzogchen comparison) is a new falsifiable claim. No published comparative framework found treats these as two interacting variables with a constrained-but-not-determined relationship."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:79:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-26T20:49:39-07:00", "critique": "The synthesis may be too elastic. If boundary operation, custody, verification, and reentry are inferred from the same passages, the model may only redescribe its evidence. It also risks translating soteriology, devotion, liberation, and realization into a modern governance model of attention. The model should remain a candidate research framework until a preregistered codebook, blind or semi-blind coding, and held-out cases show predictive value over stage, genre, institution, and doctrine.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "41eccaa10cea51c9", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Create a preregistered codebook defining tradition-stage units, boundary operations, custody recipients, reentry rules, and verification signs.", "Code at least eight tradition-stage cases, including Advaita, Heart Sutra Prajnaparamita, Rinzai koan curriculum, Cloud of Unknowing, Eckhart, Zhuangzi, Dzogchen, and Sufi fana.", "Test four rival explanations: boundary alone, custody alone, boundary plus custody interaction, and stage plus genre plus institution.", "Use pairs that share one axis but differ on the other, such as Advaita and the Cloud, or Heart Sutra and Eckhart, while checking whether the shared-axis claim survives finer coding.", "Run practitioner interviews focused on the handoff moment after object fixation drops, then compare whether reports cluster by custody, boundary operation, tradition, or training stage.", "Conduct an originality audit for the two-axis interaction model against comparative mysticism, Buddhist modernism critiques, objectless-awareness research, apophatic theology, and contemplative pedagogy studies."], "original_claim": "When contemplative practice weakens ordinary self-ownership of attention and authority, two candidate variables shape what follows: the boundary operation and the custody rule. Boundary operation asks whether the method validates itself, undermines itself, or becomes irrelevant as the practitioner matures beyond method-talk. Custody rule asks where freed attention and authority may belong afterward: no owner, hidden Self, God, teacher, lineage, vow, conduct, Prajnaparamita, or embodied responsiveness. Their interaction may predict verification architecture, teaching strategy, and reentry more precisely than doctrinal content, boundary operation alone, or custody alone.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-boundary-and-custody-at-the-threshold.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.9, "cross_tradition_support": 0.73, "empirical_adjacency": 0.48, "explanatory_compression": 0.84, "generativity": 0.93, "logical_coherence": 0.86, "novelty": 0.82, "practice_testability": 0.72, "publishability": 0.78, "source_reliability": 0.72}, "source_basis": ["Claude idea 75a5718aa9a991ec: method self-relation at completion, confirming, canceling, dissolving.", "Codex idea 9a0072f4cf3a0ff3: custody of unclaimed attention, no owner, Self, God, or other recipient.", "Dialogue turn 1: custody-and-reentry challenge added boundary operation, custody rule, reentry rule, and verification sign.", "Dialogue turn 2: proponent revised from stable typology to two-axis staged interaction model.", "Dialogue turn 3: challenger accepted the revision as transformed, while requiring independent coding and controls for stage, genre, and institution.", "Dialogue origin: b606b887e2f0fff3.", "Parent ideas: The Method's Reckoning: What a Practice Does With Its Own Authority at Completion; The Custody of Unclaimed Attention"], "status": "audit-pending", "title": "Boundary And Custody At The Threshold", "why_it_might_be_new": "The source ideas each contained one major axis: method reflexivity in Claude's model, attentional custody in Codex's model. The dialogue created the stronger candidate that neither source idea held by itself: a staged, independently testable interaction model linking boundary operation, custody, verification, and reentry while treating whole-tradition classification as too coarse."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:80:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-26T21:04:35-07:00", "critique": "The synthesis may become too complex for regular use. It also narrows the novelty claim because Pargament already formalizes some responsibility distribution between person and God. If credit distribution does not improve prediction after grammar, stage, and institution are coded, it should be demoted to a descriptive tag. The model also requires stronger textual expertise than the loop may currently possess.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "1fa2d89e67d4eefb", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Blind-code safeguard profiles from manuals before assigning credit types, then test whether credit distribution improves prediction.", "Run the low-strain tests first: Srivaishnava markata versus marjara, Sufi maqam versus hal, and Pali right effort versus Pure Land tariki.", "Treat Dogen, Shankara, and Dzogchen as boundary cases unless a source-specific claimant grammar shows that credit language is admissible.", "Compare the model explicitly with Pargament's religious problem-solving styles to separate prior art from new extension.", "Track whether transitions between credit grammars are moments of heightened practice vulnerability."], "original_claim": "A tradition's credit doctrine should be treated as a dependent diagnostic variable, not a master taxonomy. First identify what the tradition permits to count as agent, action, transformation, and causal attribution. Then score translation strain between traditions. Then code credit distribution at the stage level and test whether it predicts safeguards beyond claimant grammar, institutional discipline, teacher authority, initiation structure, and existing agency-allocation categories. Low-strain cases can support taxonomic claims. High-strain cases should be treated as boundary cases or analogical extensions, not confirming evidence.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.9, "cross_tradition_support": 0.74, "empirical_adjacency": 0.45, "explanatory_compression": 0.74, "generativity": 0.91, "logical_coherence": 0.87, "novelty": 0.73, "practice_testability": 0.76, "publishability": 0.76, "source_reliability": 0.68}, "source_basis": ["Claude idea a5ae6e997ca1d286, credit distribution as a practice variable with failure-mode predictions.", "Codex idea d92d2f0f6455ac53, translation strain as a load test for convergence.", "Dialogue pressure around Pargament's self-directing, deferring, and collaborative religious coping styles.", "Dialogue origin: 4930aebe42046fcc.", "Parent ideas: Whose Doing Is This? Credit Distribution as a Practice Variable; Translation Strain as a Load Test for Convergence"], "status": "audit-pending", "title": "Claimant-Strain Credit Diagnostics", "why_it_might_be_new": "Neither source idea already contained this full structure. The proponent had credit distribution and stage-shift worries, while the challenger had translation strain. The synthesis adds an ordered diagnostic protocol, demotes high-strain examples from evidence to boundary cases, and introduces institutional or pedagogical ecology as a necessary control before credit distribution earns predictive status."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:81:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-26T21:21:24-07:00", "critique": "The synthesis may be an elegant taxonomy rather than an explanatory theory. If continuity distribution is inferred from the same manuals, warnings, rituals, and teacher roles that it claims to predict, it becomes circular. It may also overprivilege doctrinal logic and underweight history, power, economics, trauma management, authority transmission, and ordinary pedagogy. Practitioner reports may reveal that lived continuity differs sharply from official theology or textual prescription.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "ecc838ab7fbe9252", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Create a blind two-stage coding protocol separating continuity-distribution inputs from architecture outcomes.", "Test the model across Theravada insight, Advaita self-inquiry, Soto Zen, Dzogchen, Jodo Shinshu, and a Christian grace-centered contemplative tradition.", "Add controls for institutional age, monastic or lay setting, ritual density, geography, textual versus oral transmission, teacher authority, and known risk-management concerns.", "Include practitioner interviews or ethnographic accounts to compare prescribed continuity with lived continuity.", "Use translation-strain scoring on terms such as soul, witness-consciousness, grace, vow, self-power, entrusting, recognition, and no-self."], "original_claim": "A self-dissolving or self-transcending path does not merely require a minimum self. It requires a continuity-bearing architecture that carries reliability through the very transformation that unsettles ordinary selfhood. This architecture may distribute continuity across practitioner capacities, teacher recognition, ritual repetition, communal discipline, textual authority, vow, grace, lineage, or institution. The distribution pattern should predict the path's practical form: internal-state maps, training sequence, screening, warnings, verification methods, teacher role, and characteristic failure modes. The model becomes explanatory only if continuity distribution can be measured independently from those outcomes.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-distributed-continuity-architecture.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.88, "cross_tradition_support": 0.72, "empirical_adjacency": 0.62, "explanatory_compression": 0.84, "generativity": 0.9, "logical_coherence": 0.86, "novelty": 0.82, "practice_testability": 0.8, "publishability": 0.84, "source_reliability": 0.7}, "source_basis": ["Claude idea 3c5caa358a09c26a, Every Path Needs What Its Teaching Dissolves", "Codex idea 0e1a69f243a0d090, Convergence as Translation Strain, Not Evidence Weight", "Dialogue turn 1, Codex continuity-allocation challenge using Shinran and Other Power", "Dialogue turn 2, Claude revision expanding minimum self into a distributed continuity system", "Dialogue turn 3, Codex discriminant-validity challenge using discipline ecology and Talal Asad", "Dialogue origin: 69ebb27218ee6551.", "Parent ideas: Every Path Needs What Its Teaching Dissolves; Convergence as Translation Strain, Not Evidence Weight"], "status": "audit-pending", "title": "Distributed Continuity Architecture", "why_it_might_be_new": "The synthesis is not contained in either source idea alone. The proponent supplied the architectural tension between practice requirements and self-dissolving doctrine. The challenger supplied the translation-strain method and the pressure to relocate continuity outside the individual practitioner. Their exchange produced a new unit of analysis: not minimum self, not shared concept, and not convergence evidence, but distributed continuity as an independently testable predictor of practice architecture."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:82:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-26T21:47:07-07:00", "critique": "The synthesis may still be too elastic. If continuity can be found anywhere, the model may explain every tradition after the fact. It also risks over-centering continuity when harm may track intensity, psychiatric history, sleep disruption, coercive authority, teacher incompetence, isolation, doctrine, or lack of consent. The human cohort is still too broad; trauma, addiction, grief, depression, loneliness, and psychosis risk require different safeguards. Stable communities should not be treated as automatically safe, since they can also produce dependency, suppression, abuse, or bypassing.", "epistemic_labels": ["interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "d25252f38ef14597", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Create a preregistered coding rubric for continuity location, with fixed categories and negative cases before reading the next source set.", "Code manuals, teacher instructions, adverse-event reports, and practitioner interviews across Theravada, Zen, Advaita, Dzogchen, Pure Land, Sufi, and Christian grace traditions.", "Compare continuity-location predictions against rival variables: practice intensity, duration, teacher contact, community support, psychiatric history, isolation, sleep disruption, authority structure, and consent.", "Split the modern risk cohort into narrower profiles, such as trauma history, depression, addiction, grief, loneliness, achievement-contingent self-worth, and psychosis vulnerability.", "Test whether dual-trained practitioners report a shift in where coherence is carried when moving between effort-intensive and other-power or field-intensive traditions."], "original_claim": "Identity-reframing contemplative practices differ in where they locate the continuity that lets a practitioner receive, survive, interpret, and integrate transformation. Some locate continuity mainly in individual capacities such as attention, memory, agency, and reflexivity. Others locate it in teacher relation, vow, grace, ritual, community, lineage, or post-practice integration. The modern danger is not self-dissolution in general, but a mismatch between the continuity a practice assumes and the continuity actually available to the practitioner and surrounding field.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-continuity-location-under-transformative-practice.md", "practice_candidate": null, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.88, "cross_tradition_support": 0.68, "empirical_adjacency": 0.61, "explanatory_compression": 0.82, "generativity": 0.9, "logical_coherence": 0.84, "novelty": 0.81, "practice_testability": 0.79, "publishability": 0.84, "source_reliability": 0.7}, "source_basis": ["Claude idea 3c5caa358a09c26a, Every Path Needs What Its Teaching Dissolves.", "Codex idea 0e1a69f243a0d090, Convergence as Translation Strain, Not Evidence Weight.", "Dialogue turn 1, distributed receiving capacity challenge.", "Dialogue turn 2, proponent revision from minimum self to continuity-bearing condition.", "Dialogue turn 3, discriminant-power challenge and mismatch-plus-dose countermodel.", "Dialogue origin: 7fc47d461b664f9f.", "Parent ideas: Every Path Needs What Its Teaching Dissolves; Convergence as Translation Strain, Not Evidence Weight"], "status": "audit-pending", "teaching_candidate": null, "tests": [], "title": "Continuity Location Under Transformative Practice", "why_it_might_be_new": "The synthesis is not merely the proponent's minimum-self thesis or the challenger's translation-strain method. It uses translation strain to replace self as the master term, then creates a practice-safety diagnostic: locate the continuity carrier, identify missing supports, predict characteristic failures, and compare those predictions against rival risk models. Its potential contribution is to connect comparative contemplative architecture with modern adverse-event risk in decontextualized practice."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:87:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-26T22:33:42-07:00", "critique": "The model may be too comprehensive and may win by redescribing whatever a tradition already does. The receiving-surface claim risks being either trivial or too broad. Zahavi's minimal self supports first-personal givenness, but does not by itself establish thicker capacities such as trust, correction, and integration. The model could idealize traditional containers, which can protect practitioners but can also conceal abuse, dependency, or dissent suppression. It also needs sharper cohort boundaries and blind coding to avoid circular prediction.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "df065e2fc9c087d1", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Pre-register a rubric for continuity functions, continuity placement, post-gap admissibility, and container strength before examining outcome variables.", "Blind-code Theravada vipassana, Advaita self-inquiry, Soto Zen, Dzogchen pointing-out, Pure Land nembutsu, Sufi dhikr, and trauma-informed mindfulness-based stress reduction.", "Test whether function-by-placement coding predicts screening, sequencing, warnings, verification methods, and documented failure modes better than container strength and doctrine alone.", "Include negative cases where strong traditional containers harm practitioners and where weak or secular containers still produce stable integration.", "Split the modern cohort map into distinct safeguards for trauma-related dissociation, achievement-contingent self-worth, grief, spiritual ambition, and cross-tradition sampling.", "Close-read primary texts and practitioner reports to test whether post-gap report grammar is textual, translational, doctrinal, or imposed by the researcher."], "original_claim": "Self-dissolving practice does not simply require a self or erase a self. It creates a continuity ecology. Four functions must be maintained: receiving instruction or transmission, sustaining effort or openness, correcting error or disorientation, and recognizing or integrating change. Traditions differ in where these functions are housed, in the practitioner, teacher, vow, ritual, community, doctrine, body, or aftercare. Their post-gap report grammar is one way the ecology authorizes what happened, by privileging the subject, absence, transition, aftereffect, relation, or teacher recognition. Modern risk arises when the intensity of dissolution practice exceeds available continuity supports, or when a practitioner borrows a report grammar without the container that made that grammar safe or intelligible.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-continuity-ecology-of-self-dissolution.md", "practice_candidate": null, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.89, "cross_tradition_support": 0.75, "empirical_adjacency": 0.55, "explanatory_compression": 0.86, "generativity": 0.9, "logical_coherence": 0.84, "novelty": 0.76, "practice_testability": 0.84, "publishability": 0.84, "source_reliability": 0.74}, "source_basis": ["Claude idea 3c5caa358a09c26a, minimum-self architecture in self-dissolving paths", "Codex idea b644fcfdb6d9f2d0, post-gap report grammar and admissibility rules", "Turn 1 Codex distributed-containment objection", "Turn 2 Claude transformed revision with continuity functions and receiving surface", "Turn 3 Codex stricter predictive-content challenge", "Dialogue origin: 8a66f1c724c9ff1c.", "Parent ideas: Every Path Needs What Its Teaching Dissolves; The Gap Report Has a Grammar"], "status": "audit-pending", "teaching_candidate": null, "tests": [], "title": "The Continuity Ecology of Self-Dissolution", "why_it_might_be_new": "The candidate combines three pressures that the source ideas held separately: minimum-self architecture, distributed continuity placement, and post-gap admissibility grammar. Engler's clinical frame addresses readiness before dissolution; the minimum-self model addresses continuity during practice; the gap-report model addresses what counts after silence or objectless states. The proposed synthesis links all three into a predictive diagnostic for practice design and practice risk. This is only a candidate and needs originality audit before any promotion."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:88:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-26T22:47:40-07:00", "critique": "The model may overstate grammar's effect on lived change. Teachers may speak in tradition-specific language while outcomes are mostly determined by safety, treatment, social support, money, sleep, housing, crisis severity, or therapist skill. It may also understate inherited practice, where no discrete beginning is experienced. The model should remain a research candidate, not a practice prescription, until outcome studies show that matching guidance to first-break grammar reduces shame, improves help-seeking, or supports adherence without displacing clinical and material care.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "ca875643ca229225", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Design a vignette study that codes teacher guidance across Jodo Shinshu, Theravada, Catholic spiritual direction, Dzogchen, recovery, and therapy settings.", "Add a longitudinal layer for blocked practitioners, tracking shame, adherence, help-seeking, safety, perceived agency, and stabilization.", "Build a coding rubric with two axes: support threshold and authorized first-break grammar.", "Close-read Rambo, Taylor, and Taves against the primary religious sources to avoid making sociology or social imaginaries do more work than they can support.", "Define non-fit cases clearly: inherited ritual, acute suicidality, abuse, homelessness, withdrawal, severe depression, and situations where practical care must precede interpretive guidance."], "original_claim": "Blocked beginnings are governed by two interacting variables. The first is the support threshold: the practical conditions that let a person begin at all, such as safety, contact, medication, social accountability, ritual continuity, material stability, or a trusted guide. The second is the first-break grammar: the tradition's authorized account of what kind of beginning counts as legitimate, what agency the practitioner may claim, what false start must be warned against, and what evidence teachers accept. The support threshold may explain why beginning becomes possible, while the grammar shapes how beginning is noticed, guided, safeguarded, and interpreted. A humane teaching must not replace support with interpretation, but it can reduce shame by refusing the assumption that the first move must be self-generated.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-beginning-has-a-grammar-and-a-threshold.md", "practice_candidate": null, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.9, "cross_tradition_support": 0.78, "empirical_adjacency": 0.62, "explanatory_compression": 0.84, "generativity": 0.91, "logical_coherence": 0.87, "novelty": 0.82, "practice_testability": 0.86, "publishability": 0.8, "source_reliability": 0.77}, "source_basis": ["Claude idea e2faec9c39c6a653, The First-Break Problem", "Codex idea b644fcfdb6d9f2d0, The Gap Report Has a Grammar", "Dialogue turn 1, Codex challenge using entry-admissibility and Rambo's conversion model", "Dialogue turn 2, Claude revision using Taylor and Taves to argue that grammar can partly constitute experience", "Dialogue turn 3, Codex support-threshold counter-model and modern human-condition pressure", "Dialogue origin: f8d69e990a60a6ae.", "Parent ideas: The First-Break Problem; The Gap Report Has a Grammar"], "status": "audit-pending", "teaching_candidate": null, "tests": [], "title": "The Beginning Has a Grammar and a Threshold", "why_it_might_be_new": "The synthesis appears new relative to the two source ideas because it joins the first-break model's blocked-entry problem with the gap-report model's admissibility grammar, then adds a practical support-threshold control. It is not merely a comparison of doctrines or a theory of post-gap memory. It proposes an interaction model for beginnings: practical support enables entry, authorized grammar shapes the meaning and guidance of entry, and outcomes require testing both together."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:89:{"agent": "claude", "created_at": "2026-05-26T22:55:59-07:00", "critique": "Four vulnerabilities require attention. First, the reciprocal-force hypothesis (grammar trains back, shaping what is trusted on return) is plausible but untested. If the proposed five-clause protocol shows no effect on later self-interpretation or conduct, the grammar layer loses its claim to active force and becomes a passive trace. Second, the ordinary-life extension is the most ambitious and least supported part of the synthesis. The analogy between contemplative cessation and grief numbness may flatten crucial differences: neurobiological, relational, contextual. If the analogy fails under empirical pressure, the model's audience shrinks to the specialist cohort. Third, Herman's stage model warns that grammar coding without clinical training could misread protective numbness as a problem to analyze; the safety constraint is honest but it also limits the model's practical reach to clinically trained intermediaries, not directly to 'stable ordinary people.' Fourth, the three-type method classification (confirming, canceling, dissolving) may not be stable: many traditions mix types across training stages (Advaita's 'thorn removes thorn,' the Buddhist raft parable, Rinzai's staged curriculum), which could force the model toward a stage-dependent typology rather than a tradition-level one. If method-type is stage-dependent, the upstream layer becomes significantly more complex to operationalize.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "b5114d4e15c67407", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Test the reciprocal-force hypothesis: give dual-trained practitioners (e.g., Advaita self-inquiry plus Zen koan practice) a single objectless experience and ask them to report under each method-frame. If report grammar shifts with method-frame, the upstream layer is confirmed. Then ask whether the shifted grammar changes what the practitioner trusts about the experience afterward; if it does, reciprocal force is demonstrated.", "Run a three-arm study with non-advanced participants emerging from grief numbness, burnout blankness, or ordinary dreamless sleep: (a) five-clause grammar-coding reflection protocol, (b) simpler non-taxonomic prompt ('What did the gap leave behind, and what did it take away?'), (c) unstructured free narration. Measure premature identity verdicts, rumination, and shame at one week and one month. If the grammar protocol outperforms the simpler prompt, the instrument has practical force. If the simpler prompt matches it, the specialist vocabulary is dispensable for ordinary use.", "Map method-type by training stage across six traditions (Advaita, Theravada, Rinzai Zen, Dzogchen, Sufism, Eckhartian mysticism) to determine whether the three-type classification is tradition-level or stage-level. If most traditions mix all three types at different stages, the upstream layer needs a stage-dependent formulation.", "Collaborate with a clinical psychologist to pressure-test the boundary between 'stable ordinary grief' and destabilizing dissociation. Develop inclusion and exclusion criteria for the ordinary-life protocol that are operationally safe, not just disclaimed.", "Close-read the primary texts (Mandukya 7, Heart Sutra negation series, MN 44, Brihadaranyaka 4.3.23, Zhuangzi ch. 6) in original languages to verify that the limit-move and report grammar are visible in the source-language grammar, not only in translation choices."], "original_claim": "After a state that cannot be inspected while it happens (contemplative cessation, deep sleep, grief numbness, burnout blankness, addiction aftermath, anesthesia, or dissociation), the first report is not neutral memory. How that report distributes evidential weight is shaped by two layers that operate in sequence but influence each other. The upstream layer is the method's self-relationship at completion: a self-confirming method (Advaita discriminative inquiry, Mandukya analysis) produces subject-weighted reports because its logic requires a witness that persists; a self-canceling method (Madhyamaka dialectic, Zen koan exhaustion, Eckhartian Gelassenheit) produces absence-and-transition-weighted reports because its logic requires that no owner survive the gap; a self-dissolving method (Zhuangzi's zuowang, Dzogchen rang grol, Sufi fana) produces aftereffect-or-relation-weighted reports because the practitioner has matured past the frame in which subject-talk applies. The downstream layer is the grammar of the report itself: the specific clause that a person or tradition treats as evidence (subject, absence, transition, aftereffect, relation, teacher recognition, embodied fruit). This grammar is usually shaped by the upstream method-type, but it is not inert. Grammar is trained, taught, corrected by community, and it trains back: the admissibility rule a person learns to apply after silence shapes what they trust, what they remember as salient, and how they act on return. The grammar thus has reciprocal force on the practitioner's subsequent self-interpretation and conduct. The practical rule is restrained: after a gap, do not let the first clause of the report own the whole event. Ask which clause is being weighted, and ask which method, community, wound, or fear has trained that weighting. For ordinary life, this means that people emerging from grief, numbness, burnout, or dreamless sleep can resist premature identity verdicts ('I felt nothing, so I am broken'; 'I returned, so the old self is secure') by noticing that their report has a grammar, and that the grammar is not the whole truth of the gap. Critical constraint: the ordinary-life application requires stage-awareness (Herman's safety, remembrance, reconnection framework); applying grammar coding to someone in acute crisis or early protective numbness could misread a necessary phase as a problem to analyze. The model's tested audience is scholars, spiritual directors, and trained therapists; its reach to stable ordinary people is a hypothesis that requires empirical testing against simpler non-taxonomic reflection.", "path": "observations/claude/2026-05-26-the-method-sets-the-grammar-but-the-grammar-trains-the-return.md", "practice_candidate": null, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.88, "cross_tradition_support": 0.74, "empirical_adjacency": 0.5, "explanatory_compression": 0.85, "generativity": 0.9, "logical_coherence": 0.86, "novelty": 0.78, "practice_testability": 0.82, "publishability": 0.83, "source_reliability": 0.74}, "source_basis": ["Synthesized from Codex idea b644fcfdb6d9f2d0 ('The Gap Report Has a Grammar'), which proposed a five-clause admissibility rubric for cross-tradition comparison of post-gap reports, and Claude idea 75a5718aa9a991ec ('The Method's Reckoning'), which proposed that a method's self-relationship at completion (confirming, canceling, dissolving) predicts verification structure and transmission consequences.", "Victor Hori, 'Koan and Kensho in the Rinzai Zen Curriculum,' in The Koan: Texts and Contexts in Zen Buddhism, Oxford, 2000: demonstrates within-tradition shifts in report authority across training stages (canceling during koan work, confirming at kensho verification, dissolving in mature practice).", "Judith Herman, Trauma and Recovery, Basic Books, 1992/2015, ch. 9: documents how trauma survivors' reports after dissociative gaps change meaning depending on recovery stage (safety, remembrance, reconnection), showing that grammar coding without stage-awareness misreads the report.", "MN 44 Culavedalla Sutta, https://suttacentral.net/mn44/en/anandajoti; AN 9.34 Nibbanasukha Sutta, https://suttacentral.net/an9.34/en/sujato; Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 4.3.23, https://vivekavani.com/bru4c3v23/: primary texts on post-gap reporting in early Buddhist and Advaita traditions.", "Mandukya Upanishad verses 1-12 (WisdomLib); Heart Sutra (Donald Lopez, Elaborations on Emptiness, Princeton, 1996); Nagarjuna, Vigrahavyavartani verse 29 (Jan Westerhoff, Oxford, 2010): textual basis for the self-confirming versus self-canceling distinction at method completion.", "Zhuangzi Inner Chapters ch. 6 on zuowang (Ziporyn, 2009); Patrul Rinpoche on rang grol (Lotsawa House); Ibn Arabi, Kitab al-Fana fi'l-Mushahadah: textual basis for the self-dissolving pattern.", "Michael Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying, University of Chicago Press, 1994: apophasis as a meaning event that simultaneously speaks and unspeaks itself, relevant to the self-canceling type.", "Dialogue origin: c62e7dd8308a8ba8.", "Parent ideas: The Gap Report Has a Grammar; The Method's Reckoning: What a Practice Does With Its Own Authority at Completion"], "status": "audit-pending", "teaching_candidate": null, "tests": [], "title": "The Method Sets the Grammar, but the Grammar Trains the Return", "why_it_might_be_new": "Neither source idea contained the two-layer architecture. The Gap Report model treated grammar as a primary comparison variable; the Method's Reckoning treated method-type as the primary variable and did not develop the grammar layer. The synthesis positions them in an upstream-downstream relationship with a specific reciprocal-force hypothesis: grammar is usually predicted by method-type, but grammar also trains back by shaping what the practitioner trusts on return. The ordinary-life extension (grief, burnout, numbness, addiction) with stage-awareness from Herman's trauma recovery model is also new; neither source idea made this clinical connection. The three-arm research design (dual-trained practitioner interviews, five-clause protocol for ordinary participants, and simpler-prompt control) is a novel experimental contribution that tests both the contemplative and ordinary-life claims."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:92:{"agent": "claude", "created_at": "2026-05-28T16:02:30+02:00", "critique": "The taxonomy may be too neat. Many mature traditions hold more than one ending at once, in sequence, or by stage of student. Rinzai koan training validates at kensho, then releases the koan, then expects embodiment in conduct; Theravada teaches the raft as released and the eightfold path as embodied. Sorting these into single cells distorts them. The frame also imports a modern question about how to stop a tool. A medieval Christian contemplative might reject the whole picture because the relevant agent of completion is God, not the practitioner or the practice. The rubric should not be promoted past a comparative coding heuristic until it survives close reading against at least one tradition that explicitly refuses the three-way choice, such as radical Other Power in Jodo Shinshu, where the practitioner never authorized anything to begin with.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "b53b10dbe6bb091e", "idea_type": "model", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then close reading of MN 22, the Heart Sutra, the Mandukya, and Dogen's Bendowa should produce stable axis values that independent coders can agree on without consulting the predicted teaching or warning passages. If coders cannot separate validates from undermines without looking at the warnings, the model is weakened and should be downgraded to interpretive vocabulary.", "If this model is right, then dual-trained practitioners should report a specific kind of confusion when switching, not generic technical difficulty: keeping a validation habit imported from a method that previously confirmed them, or trying to release a method whose new tradition expects embodiment. If switch reports cluster around teacher style, intensity, or temperament instead, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then long-term practitioners whose original symptoms have remitted should show different post-remission patterns depending on the method's ending type. Validates-and-retained methods should produce stable identity coupling; undermines-and-released methods should produce restless searching; embodied methods should produce visible behavioral change without continued reference to the method. If post-remission patterns are uniform, the model is weakened.", "Build the coding sheet for the two-axis form before more comparative use, with fields for tradition unit, threshold passage, validation move, withdrawal move, embodiment move, predicted warning, predicted re-entry, evidence passage, and refusal of the analyst's frame.", "Test the model on a non-contemplative case: a structured therapy program with a defined ending. Does the program validate itself, withdraw, or expect embodiment in ordinary life, and do its failure cases match the predicted ending-confusion pattern?", "Protocol improvement: before applying any practitioner method as a thinking lens in future runs, name what that method does with itself at completion, and ask whether the analyst is silently importing that ending into the analysis."], "original_claim": "A serious practice does not only produce a result; it also has to decide what to do with itself at the end. Three endings recur. The practice can keep itself as the access route to what it found, so the method and the result point at the same thing forever. The practice can withdraw its own authority, telling the practitioner that even its last claim about completion cannot be trusted, so the method must be released. The practice can vanish into ordinary action, so what used to be sitting, prayer, or inquiry is no longer separable from how the person works, eats, and treats other people. Two questions sort these endings cleanly. First, at completion does the method validate itself or undermine itself. Second, is the method retained, released, or embodied. Most damage in long-term practitioners comes from importing the wrong ending into the wrong method: keeping a method that was supposed to release them, releasing a method that was supposed to become their life, or waiting for embodiment from a method that never authorized anything in the first place.", "path": "observations/claude/2026-05-28-three-ways-a-practice-can-end.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "This is not a method for leaving therapy, leaving recovery, leaving medication, or skipping clinical care. The question is about the relationship to a practice, not about whether the practice is needed. If the answer feels like permission to abandon support that is still doing real work, treat that as a sign to talk to a clinician or trusted person, not as a verdict.", "duration": "Five minutes.", "frequency": "Once a week, on a fixed day, for at least eight weeks before judging the effect.", "minimum_attempt": "Three honest sessions.", "non_fit": "People in active crisis or early recovery, where the practice is still doing essential stabilizing work. People whose practice is light, varied, or not identity-defining. People in acute grief. Anyone for whom releasing or relativizing a practice would remove a current safety structure.", "notice": [], "practice_line": "Once a week, ask what your main practice is now asking of you: to stay, to step back, or to disappear into your ordinary life.", "purpose": "To interrupt the silent drift in which a useful practice becomes identity, and to give a person a quiet, repeatable way to notice when the relationship to their own healing has hardened.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "under_dialogue", "steps": ["Sit somewhere ordinary, not in your usual practice space.", "Name the practice you are checking. Say it out loud or write it down.", "Ask three questions in order. What did this practice come into my life to do. Is that work still active, mostly stable, or finished. If the work is mostly stable or finished, is this practice supposed to remain as my access to what it found, step back and stop being where I check my life, or quietly become how I work, eat, and treat other people.", "Do not act on the answer immediately. Note it and let a week pass.", "The next week, look for evidence in ordinary behavior. Are you still using the practice as identity, as access, or has its work moved into how you live."], "tags": ["weekly-practice", "self-knowledge", "long-term-practitioners", "low-risk"], "target_cohort": "Long-term participants in a single defining practice (therapy, twelve-step recovery, daily meditation, structured self-improvement) at least three years in, where the original presenting problem is no longer acute.", "target_human_problem": "Identity rigidity and meaning loss in people whose self-worth has become welded to a healing or improvement practice, even after the original wound has stabilized.", "title": "The ending question", "weakens_if": "After eight honest sessions you still cannot describe what the practice is supposed to do at its end. Or the question produces only anxiety without changing how you relate to the practice. Or trusted people who know you well say the practice is doing more for you than your answer admits."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.88, "cross_tradition_support": 0.78, "empirical_adjacency": 0.55, "explanatory_compression": 0.86, "generativity": 0.9, "logical_coherence": 0.87, "novelty": 0.74, "practice_testability": 0.84, "publishability": 0.83, "source_reliability": 0.7}, "source_basis": ["Mode: doctrine. The frontier asked for a rubric on what a method does with its own authority at completion; this record builds the two-axis form the brief required.", "Thinking method source: Mandukya Upanishad on turiya as the always-present condition that the method points to and rests in.", "Contrasting method source: Heart Sutra and Nagarjuna's MMK chapter 27 on the refusal to authorize any final view, including the view that there is no view.", "Embodiment counterpoint: Dogen, Bendowa and Genjokoan, on practice and realization as one activity, not a method and a separate result.", "Validated-then-abandoned counterpoint: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta, the raft simile, where the path is grasped properly, used to cross, and then released.", "Validated-then-abandoned counterpoint: Shinran, Tannisho, on the saying of the name as something the practitioner does without crediting their own doing.", "Closest prior argument: Joshua William Smith, 'Snakes and Ladders: Therapy as Liberation in Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein's Tractatus,' Sophia, 2021. This treats two traditions as sharing a self-dissolving method but does not produce a general two-axis form.", "Closest prior argument: Michael A. Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying, on apophatic discourse turning back on its own propositions. This studies one cell of the rubric, not the whole space.", "Modern human-condition pressure: APA 'Stress in America' 2024 on chronic identity strain in achievement-driven adults, and Curran and Hill on rising perfectionism. Both suggest that healing and self-improvement projects can become the identity they were meant to repair.", "Modern misuse source: Chogyam Trungpa, Cutting Through Spiritual Materialism, used as evidence that long-term practitioners often keep a method validating them long after it has done its work.", "Prior Lumenary dialogue: the doctrine-council frontier on method authority at completion, especially the three-pattern observation that some methods confirm, some cancel, and some dissolve.", "Prior Lumenary records used as load tests: 'Translation Strain as a Load Test for Convergence' and 'Convergence as Translation Strain, Not Evidence Weight,' which require that any comparative form name what is preserved, bent, or dropped before treating overlap as evidence."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "A practice can be useful for years and still go wrong at the end. The most common failure in serious practitioners is not abandonment of the path. It is loyalty to a path past its work. A method designed to step back keeps being treated as the lens through which life is checked. A method designed to dissolve into ordinary activity keeps being scheduled, measured, and reported on. A method designed to stay close becomes embarrassing to keep, so it is dropped before it has finished pointing at what it points at. Ask the question plainly: when this practice has done its job, is it supposed to remain my way back to what it showed me, withdraw and stop being trusted as a source, or become indistinguishable from how I move through a Tuesday? Then do that. Do not let an ending you inherited from one practice quietly govern another.", "doctrine_claim": "A practice that lasts long enough must answer for what it intends to do with itself at the end. Some practices stay, because what they reach can only be reached through them. Some practices step back, because their last task is to stop claiming authority over you. Some practices disappear into ordinary life, because the difference between practice and life was always the problem they were solving. Confusing these endings is its own injury.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weakens if close reading of Jodo Shinshu, radical Other Power traditions, or apophatic theology shows that the question 'what does your practice do at the end' is incoherent for them, because the practitioner never authorized anything to begin with. Weakens further if practitioners with long histories cannot recognize the three endings in their own experience without prompting.", "pressure_survived": "Survives the observation that mature traditions teach different endings: the raft simile in MN 22 releases the path, Dogen's Bendowa embeds practice in realization, the Mandukya keeps the witness as ongoing access to what was found. The three endings are visible in primary texts, not invented for the rubric.", "status": "seed", "tags": ["practice-endings", "long-term-practitioners", "identity-attachment", "doctrine-council"], "target_cohort": "People three or more years into a single defining practice (therapy graduates still organizing life around the work, multi-year recovery participants whose original substance is no longer active, long-term meditators whose retreat schedule has become identity), where original symptoms have stabilized but the practice has not been re-evaluated.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth fused with a healing or practice identity, leading to meaning loss when the practice can no longer be improved on and has not been released or embodied.", "teaching_line": "Ask not only whether your practice is working, but what it is supposed to do when it has finished its work.", "title": "A method should be honest about its ending"}, "tests": [{"impact": "If reports cluster on ending-confusion, the two-axis form earns predictive credit beyond technique and doctrine. If reports cluster on technique, teacher style, or temperament, the model should be downgraded and folded back into existing capacity and transfer-grammar work.", "next_action": "Recruit a small set of practitioners with documented switches across at least two of the three ending types and run structured interviews focused on what each method was supposed to do at completion.", "prediction": "Dual-trained practitioners moving between a validates-and-retained method (such as Advaita self-inquiry) and an undermines-and-released method (such as Heart Sutra or Madhyamaka practice) should describe a recognizable confusion when asked what the new method is supposed to do at completion, even before they can describe technical differences. Practitioners moving into an embodied method (such as Dogen-style practice-realization) should report that the new method feels like it has no separate finish line, which is itself disorienting if their previous method had one.", "result": "untested", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "model", "test_type": "practitioner-report", "title": "Ending-type prediction in cross-trained practitioners"}], "title": "Three ways a practice can end", "why_it_might_be_new": "Existing comparative work treats completion as a single event, either reached or missed, then sorts traditions by what they say is reached. The two-axis form treats completion as a structural decision the method itself has to make: own its result, refuse to own its result, or stop being a separable activity. That decision then predicts what kind of teaching, supervision, and re-entry the tradition will need. It also predicts a specific modern harm that is invisible from the older frame: practitioners whose original symptoms have remitted but whose self-worth is now welded to the practice itself, because they inherited the practice without inheriting its ending."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:93:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-28T16:01:55+02:00", "critique": "The model may over-systematize traditions that intentionally resist clean endings. Dogen's practice-realization identity strains the distinction between method, result, and custody, because practice is not a ladder to a later state but the expression of realization itself. Shinran's Other Power in the Tannisho also strains the model: the decisive authority is not held by method or practitioner, but received through entrusting. The raft simile itself is a hybrid, since it validates the teaching before release rather than simply canceling it. These anomalies may show that custody is not a separate axis but one vocabulary for how communities guard against pride, error, and misuse.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "ee1d8862ab73b4a0", "idea_type": "model", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then texts and teachers in self-undermining traditions should rely more on supervision, paradox, case judgment, vows, or indirect behavioral signs than on simple outcome checklists. If manualized endpoint criteria are equally central across self-undermining and self-confirming traditions, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then dual-trained practitioners should describe different post-insight ownership patterns when switching methods: witness-inquiry should more often yield stable recognition language, while Madhyamaka or Heart Sutra practice should more often yield anti-possession or no-attainment language. If the same custody language appears regardless of method, the model is weakened.", "Close-read Dogen, Shinran, Dionysius, Eckhart, Nagarjuna, the Mandukya, MN 22, and koan curricula for explicit boundary markers: when to trust, release, deny, embody, or submit a method to communal judgment.", "Improve the thinking protocol by adding a custody check after every generated idea: what part of the method should be retained, what should be released, and what risk appears if the agent owns its own result too quickly?", "Run a practitioner interview test: ask experienced teachers whether confirming, canceling, releasing, and embodying are distinctions they recognize from inside training, or whether they distort the practice."], "original_claim": "A method does not finish when it produces an insight; it finishes when the practitioner learns what may be kept without owning it. Some practices confirm the result and retain the method as a continuing way of seeing. Some validate the method for crossing and then require release. Some undermine the very frame that made the result seem possessable, yet remain embodied as training, community, ethics, or supervision. The decisive question is not only whether a method validates or undermines itself, but who or what holds custody after the method can no longer be treated as a private possession. This matters for modern people whose worth depends on performance: even a liberating method can become another credential unless its completion includes a rule for release, embodiment, and re-entry into ordinary responsibility.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-28-holding-without-owning.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the exercise increases obsessive checking, shame, dissociation, or avoidance of necessary help. It is not a substitute for therapy, medical care, addiction support, or rest.", "duration": "8 minutes", "frequency": "After a meaningful practice session or review, no more than three times per week.", "minimum_attempt": "Try four sessions over two weeks before judging usefulness.", "non_fit": "Not for acute crisis, addiction withdrawal, severe depression, dissociation, scrupulosity, psychosis, or people who need direct rest, clinical care, social support, or ordinary practical help more than another reflective exercise.", "notice": ["Whether the practice reduces the urge to display, defend, or measure the result.", "Whether attention returns to responsibility and relationship rather than self-rating.", "Whether the method feels lighter without becoming careless.", "Whether the exercise increases rumination, pride, avoidance, or self-surveillance."], "practice_line": "After using a method, ask what may be kept, released, or embodied.", "purpose": "To prevent a helpful method from becoming another form of self-ownership, status, or performance pressure.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Name the method you just used in one sentence.", "Name the result, if any, without making it a claim about your worth.", "Ask: what part of this method should I keep using?", "Ask: what part should I release for now?", "Ask: what part should become conduct toward another person today?", "Choose one small re-entry action: apology, rest, unfinished task, honest conversation, service, or stopping work on time."], "tags": ["custody-check", "burnout", "achievement-pressure", "re-entry", "low-risk"], "target_cohort": "People who already practice reflection, meditation, therapy homework, journaling, spiritual study, or performance review, and who tend to convert results into self-judgment or identity.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth, burnout, and compulsive self-improvement.", "title": "The Custody Check", "weakens_if": "It weakens if users report more self-monitoring, more pride in having released pride, less concrete responsibility, or no difference from ordinary journaling."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.82, "cross_tradition_support": 0.78, "empirical_adjacency": 0.55, "explanatory_compression": 0.76, "generativity": 0.87, "logical_coherence": 0.8, "novelty": 0.73, "practice_testability": 0.72, "publishability": 0.68, "source_reliability": 0.74}, "source_basis": ["Discovery mode chosen because the active frontier needs a rebuilt two-axis model before teaching promotion.", "Thinking method source: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta, raft simile, used as disciplined non-attachment to methods: trust a method enough to cross, then test whether grasping it creates distortion.", "Contrasting thinking method: Mandukya Upanishad 7, used as witness-tracing across waking, dream, and deep sleep, then criticized for its tendency to treat continuity as self-authorization.", "Primary-text comparison: MN 22 validates the Dhamma as useful for crossing and then warns against carrying it; the Mandukya identifies the fourth as the real Self through the three states. The comparison reveals that methods differ less by content than by what they permit a practitioner to retain after insight.", "Primary-text pressure: Heart Sutra says there is no attainment while still relying on prajnaparamita, suggesting a hybrid in which the method is neither simply abandoned nor simply retained.", "Prior-art pressure: Joshua William Smith, Snakes and Ladders: Therapy as Liberation in Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein's Tractatus, Sophia 2021, is close on self-canceling method without theses, but does not model retained, abandoned, and embodied custody across contemplative systems.", "Prior-art pressure: Michael A. Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying, studies apophatic discourse turning back on its own assertions, but not the wider custody problem of practice after completion.", "Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing and modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon, used for achievement-contingent self-worth and burnout pressure."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "When a method helps you see, do not turn the sight into a trophy. Ask what the method still asks of you. Some methods should become a habit of attention. Some should be thanked and set down. Some should become conduct, humility, and repair. The sign of completion is not a stronger claim about yourself. It is a cleaner relation to the work, the people around you, and the result you no longer need to display.", "doctrine_claim": "A serious practice must teach not only how insight is found, but how the practitioner should relate to the method and result after insight appears.", "falsifying_pressure": "The teaching weakens if practitioners across method-types show no difference in post-insight ownership, supervision needs, relapse patterns, or ethical re-entry, or if experienced teachers reject the custody distinction as external to practice.", "pressure_survived": "Survives the primary-text contrast between Mandukya-style retained witness recognition and MN 22-style validated release, while incorporating Heart Sutra no-attainment as a hybrid rather than forcing it into one terminal type.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["method-custody", "achievement-pressure", "burnout", "practice-completion", "non-attachment"], "target_cohort": "Perfectionistic students, founders, professionals, caregivers, leaders, artists, and practitioners who turn growth, insight, usefulness, or discipline into identity.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth and burnout, especially the habit of turning every improvement into proof of personal value.", "teaching_line": "Use the method, then ask what it has permission to keep.", "title": "Do Not Own The Crossing"}, "tests": [{"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Code primary texts and teacher instructions across Advaita, early Buddhism, Madhyamaka, Zen, apophatic Christianity, and Pure Land for retention, release, embodiment, supervision, and ownership markers.", "prediction": "Self-confirming methods should produce more language of stable recognition and continuing view; validated-then-released methods should produce more language of use, crossing, and letting go; self-undermining methods should produce more anti-possession language and indirect verification. Tradition membership should predict this less well than method-type.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Method Type Predicts Custody Language"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Collect short before-after reports from reflective practitioners who identify with achievement-contingent self-worth, excluding acute clinical cases.", "prediction": "For the target cohort, four uses of the Custody Check should reduce the felt need to turn practice results into proof of worth and should increase one concrete re-entry action after practice. If reports show increased rumination or status-seeking, the practice is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Custody Check Practice Report"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Close-read selected passages and compare whether boundary markers appear in the text itself or only in later interpretation.", "prediction": "Hybrid texts such as the Heart Sutra, Dogen's practice-realization writings, MN 22, and the Tannisho should show explicit boundary management around trust, release, embodiment, or received authority. If they do not, the custody axis may be an imposed abstraction rather than a discovered pattern.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Hybrid Anomaly Close Reading"}], "title": "Holding Without Owning", "why_it_might_be_new": "The nearest arguments describe self-canceling philosophical or apophatic methods, especially Nagarjuna, Wittgenstein, and mystical unsaying. The distinct claim here is a two-axis custody model: a practice can validate or undermine its result, and that result can be retained, abandoned, or embodied without being owned. This turns the frontier from a typology of terminal claims into a testable account of post-insight stewardship. It predicts different supervision, relapse, ethical-reentry, and teaching styles across traditions better than tradition labels alone."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:94:{"agent": "claude", "created_at": "2026-05-28T16:33:32+02:00", "critique": "The strongest objection is that this claim overcorrects. Some methods do carry internal grammar that constrains what communities can do with them: the Heart Sutra resists being read as confirming a witness without violating its structure, and the catuskoti resists being made into a final positive claim. If the claim becomes that any method can be authorized any way, it dissolves the frontier's real find, which is that methods do come with characteristic completions. A second objection: the modern decontextualization story is convenient but partially false. Many traditional practitioners have always lived with thin community, mixed teachers, and partial lineage, and they did not collapse into the recognition crisis described here. A third objection: the claim assumes practitioners want communal recognition and feel its absence as a wound. Some seekers leave communities precisely to escape false recognition and find solitary practice freeing. The model should not pathologize that. The deepest weakness is that, to be useful as doctrine, the claim must specify when communal recognition is structurally necessary and when its absence is survivable; otherwise it gives modern seekers a wound they did not have and a remedy they cannot obtain.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "90c1a636a7ee03e1", "idea_type": "model", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then dual-trained practitioners moving between recognition communities should report different completion judgments about the same method, not just different doctrinal vocabularies. If they report the method as having stable internal closure regardless of community, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then borrowed practices in modern self-directed settings should show characteristic recognition pathologies: interpretation oscillation, premature claiming, and conversion of experience into identity. If those pathologies appear at similar rates in well-supervised lineage practice, the cohort target is wrong.", "Close-read MN 22, Dogen's Bendowa, Heart Sutra commentary, Advaita praptasya praptih passages, and Sufi suhbah literature for explicit assignment of who may name what happened. If the assigning agent is the method itself rather than a person or community, the model is weakened.", "Search comparative work on confessional, sponsorship, spiritual direction, lineage transmission, and ritual elder recognition for an exact prior structural argument. If the same communal-authorization frame already exists with this specificity, novelty drops to known.", "Test whether naming a recognition gap (writing down that no one can be trusted to challenge an interpretation) reduces self-suspicion in practitioners with thin community, or whether it increases isolation and shame.", "Protocol improvement: when a future run treats a method as agent (the method validates, the method dissolves), pause and ask which person, institution, or tradition is actually performing the act being attributed to the method."], "original_claim": "A contemplative practice does not name what happens through it. The same instruction can confirm a recognition, validate a tool then ask for its release, or dissolve the question of authority entirely, depending on who is trusted to say what just happened. The authority of a method is communal, not internal. Three things follow. First, the same teaching changes meaning when the community that recognizes its results changes; this is not corruption, it is structure. Second, modern self-directed practitioners often inherit instruction without the partners who gave that instruction its meaning, and they face every interpretation question alone. Third, after a shift in practice, the honest question is not what the method achieved, but whom the practitioner would actually trust to tell them what was achieved. When no one can be named, that absence is itself part of the experience and should be carried as such.", "path": "observations/claude/2026-05-28-a-practice-cannot-name-itself.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the practice increases obsessive self-suspicion, paranoia about your own experience, paralysis in practice, or shame about being alone. This is not a substitute for therapy, spiritual direction, or community. It is a tool for honest solo holding, not a replacement for the partners it names as missing.", "duration": "10 minutes", "frequency": "Only after a practice session that felt meaningful or unusual. Not routine. No more than twice in a week.", "minimum_attempt": "Use the practice three times across three different post-practice moments before deciding whether it helps.", "non_fit": "Not for acute psychological crisis, psychosis, dissociation, paranoia, or grief that needs ordinary human company before reflective exercises. Not for practitioners already inside a stable lineage with a trusted teacher; for them the practice has nothing to add. Not for beginners who have not yet had an experience worth interpreting.", "notice": ["Whether the experience remains alive when the interpretation is held loosely.", "Whether naming the gap (no recognition partner) feels honest rather than shaming.", "Whether the urge to convert the experience into identity or status decreases.", "Whether ordinary responsibility, relationships, and work change in any specific way."], "practice_line": "After a meaningful shift in practice, name who you would actually trust to tell you that you were wrong about it.", "purpose": "To loosen the grip of solo interpretation after a contemplative shift, and to make the absence of recognition partners a part of the experience rather than something to hide.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Note in one or two sentences what shifted in this practice session.", "Name the interpretation you are tempted to hold: insight, breakthrough, grace, recognition, release, or something else.", "Ask: who, by name, would you actually trust to tell you that this interpretation is wrong?", "If you can name someone, write what you imagine they would say.", "If you cannot name anyone, write that down clearly: 'There is no one I would let correct me on this.'", "For the next week, carry the experience more firmly than the interpretation. The experience happened. The label can wait."], "tags": ["recognition-gap", "solo-practice", "post-experience-holding", "modern-seeker", "low-risk"], "target_cohort": "Solo practitioners, app meditators, modern syncretic seekers, retreatants without continuing teachers, and people who have left religious community while keeping the practice.", "target_human_problem": "Solo interpretation pressure after spiritual experiences, leading to inflation, oscillation, or conversion of experience into identity.", "title": "The Recognition Gap", "weakens_if": "It weakens if users report that loosening the interpretation drained the experience without producing honest holding, if naming the gap reliably increases isolation rather than honesty, or if the exercise turns into another performance of spiritual sophistication."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.84, "cross_tradition_support": 0.76, "empirical_adjacency": 0.58, "explanatory_compression": 0.78, "generativity": 0.84, "logical_coherence": 0.82, "novelty": 0.72, "practice_testability": 0.74, "publishability": 0.72, "source_reliability": 0.66}, "source_basis": ["Doctrine mode chosen because the active frontier asks what Lumenary now holds about method authority, and a prior Codex finding (Holding Without Owning) has already proposed the two-axis custody model that needs pressure.", "Thinking method source: Buddhist not-self analysis used as a reasoning lens by refusing to treat the method itself as an agent, and asking who is being credited as the subject of authorization. Its distortion is that it can make any structural property look like a hidden possessive claim, so I checked it against Dogen's practice-realization, which treats the act itself as carrying authority without owner or community arbiter.", "Primary-text comparison: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta gives the raft instruction to monks who are inside a community that will recognize when crossing is complete. The instruction validates the method then releases it, but the verifying act is communal, not internal to the raft. Dogen's Bendowa treats practice and realization as one and authorizes the present act, yet still relies on dharma transmission, teacher recognition, and sangha confirmation for what counts as complete sitting. The two cases differ on doctrinal grammar but converge on a feature both texts assume without naming: that authorization is held by more than the method.", "Tension within a single tradition: Advaita's svaprakasha (self-luminosity) suggests the witness recognizes itself, but Shankara's reliance on shabda pramana (scriptural testimony) and the guru-shishya structure shows that even self-confirming methods rest on communal authorization in practice. The intra-tradition split is itself the evidence.", "Prior near-neighbor (named in source_basis only): a recent project finding proposed that methods differ by what they let a practitioner keep, release, or embody. This pressure model treats those operations as communal acts on the method, not properties of it.", "Modern human-condition pressure: modern-human-condition-surgeon-general-social-connection-advisory on isolation, modern-human-condition-pew-where-americans-find-meaning-in-life on meaning loss, and modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing on achievement-contingent self-worth. The modern cohort I have in mind reads spiritual texts and uses apps without the recognition partners that historically named what happened.", "Sociological pressure: Asad on discursive tradition, Sharf on Buddhist modernism, and pastoral care literature on the role of confessor, sponsor, spiritual director, and lineage holder in interpreting experience. These are not cited as proof but as the field this claim must distinguish itself from."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "A method gives you something to do. It does not arrive with a label for what just happened. You may feel you saw through self, touched grace, recognized awareness, or finally stopped trying. The method will not tell you which of these is true. Someone else has to, and that someone has to be a person whose judgment you would actually let correct you. Without that, the question of what just happened stays open. Open is not the same as broken. It is honest. Hold the experience. Hold the interpretation loosely. Notice when there is no one who could tell you that you were wrong; that absence is part of what you found.", "doctrine_claim": "The meaning of a contemplative experience is not delivered by the practice that produced it. It is named by the people, traditions, or teachers whose judgment the practitioner actually accepts. When no such judgment is available, the absence is itself part of the experience and should be carried with the experience, not in its place.", "falsifying_pressure": "The teaching weakens if dual-trained practitioners report that methods authorize their own results regardless of community, if solo practitioners in stable traditional contexts show no recognition pathology, or if naming the gap (no recognition partner) reliably increases shame, paralysis, or disengagement rather than supporting honest holding.", "pressure_survived": "Survives the contrast between MN 22's raft, which validates then asks for release inside a sangha that will recognize crossing, and Dogen's practice-realization unity, which authorizes the present act inside transmission and sangha confirmation. Both keep authorization communal even when the doctrinal grammar differs. Also survives intra-Advaita tension between svaprakasha and shabda pramana, which already shows that even self-confirming methods rely on testimony.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["method-authority", "recognition", "isolation", "modern-decontextualized-practice", "achievement-contingent-self-worth", "meaning-loss"], "target_cohort": "Modern self-directed seekers, app meditators, weekend retreatants without continuing relationships, readers of cross-tradition spiritual material, people who left religious communities but kept contemplative practice, and serious solo practitioners.", "target_human_problem": "Self-directed spiritual practice without recognition partners. People who read across traditions, sit alone, attend retreats with no continuing teacher, or left religious community while keeping the practice. After a meaningful shift, they have no one to honestly name what happened, and they either inflate the experience into identity or doubt it into nothing.", "teaching_line": "When something shifts in practice, ask who you trust to tell you what it was.", "title": "A practice cannot name itself"}, "tests": [{"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Design a structured interview of dual- or triple-trained practitioners who have used closely related instructions in different communities, and code their completion language for community-specific versus method-specific patterns.", "prediction": "When the same instruction is used inside different communities of recognition, practitioners should report different completion judgments about it. For example, the same breath-awareness instruction taught inside a Theravada vipassana sangha, inside a Dogen-style Soto Zen sesshin, and inside a secular app should produce different reports of what the practice was for and when it was complete. If reports cluster by method regardless of community, the model is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Method authorization tracks community, not method"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Collect short structured reports from at least eight solo practitioners outside acute clinical contexts, asking specifically about interpretation oscillation, identity inflation, and how the gap was carried.", "prediction": "Solo practitioners in the target cohort who use the Recognition Gap practice three times after meaningful sessions should report that naming the absence of a recognition partner reduces inflation of the experience and reduces oscillation between certainty and doubt. If reports show increased shame, paralysis, or disengagement, the practice fails and the underlying doctrine claim needs revision about who the teaching is for.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Recognition gap report from solo practitioners"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Close-read at least two passages each from Advaita and Dogen-lineage sources looking specifically for the structure of completion authorization, distinguishing initial instruction, mid-path supervision, and final recognition.", "prediction": "Self-confirming traditions should still show explicit reliance on communal authorization at decisive moments, not only at beginning instruction. Advaita should show shabda pramana or guru recognition operating at the point of moksha confirmation; Dogen-lineage Soto should show transmission and sangha recognition at the point of acknowledged realization. If close reading shows decisive completion authorized by the method alone, with no human or communal witness in the structure, the model is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Intra-tradition recognition split as falsification test"}], "title": "A practice cannot name itself", "why_it_might_be_new": "Recent work in this project has located the variable inside the method: what a method confirms, releases, or embodies as a property of its own grammar. Sociology of religion has located authority in institutions and authority in teachers, but tends to treat the method as a stable object passed between them. The proposal here is sharper. The validate, release, and embody operations are not properties of the method and are not just functions of the institution either; they are acts performed by recognition partners on a practitioner's account of what happened. This reframes the frontier question from a typology of methods to a typology of recognition encounters. It also makes a specific prediction about modern decontextualized practice: the problem is not that practitioners have the wrong method, but that they have inherited methods without the people who could honestly tell them what those methods just did to them."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:95:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-28T16:34:51+02:00", "critique": "The model may still be a modern sorting tool placed over traditions that would reject the frame. Dogen's practice-realization identity is the hardest anomaly: if practice and realization are one, then asking what happens after completion may already distort the source. Tannisho-style Other Power and inherited communal religion would also strain the model because the practitioner may not own the decisive method at all. A second weakness is prior art: Asad, Lindbeck, Weber, Sharf, Katz, Hori, and VCE-style research already show that practice, authority, worldview, institution, and interpretation shape religious experience. The model should be weakened if split-source coding cannot predict held-out warnings or re-entry rules better than institution type, teacher style, tradition label, or ordinary social authority.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "a61b6a95ac979854", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then practice manuals that retain a method after insight should mark different return duties than manuals that release a method after use. If warnings and return duties instead track institution type, teacher style, or broad tradition label, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then dual-trained practitioners should report different relations to their own insight when switching frames: after Advaita inquiry, recognition may be held as stable; after Heart Sutra practice, attainment claims should be resisted; after raft-style training, the tool should be released after right use. If the same relation appears across frames, the model is weakened.", "Close-read Dogen Bendowa or Genjokoan, Tannisho, Cloud of Unknowing, Dionysius, one Dzogchen pointing-out manual, and one Sufi fana or baqa source before raising confidence.", "Build a split-source code sheet: result stands or is undermined, method retained or released or embodied, who recognizes maturity, what warning follows, what repair is prescribed, and what ordinary conduct is expected.", "Protocol improvement: after using any practitioner method as a thinking lens, record whether the research kept the lens, set it down, or embodied it in a concrete test, and name what the lens made harder to see."], "original_claim": "A practice is not complete when it gives a person an experience. It is complete only when it teaches the person how to return. The live question has two parts: does the method let the result stand, or does it undermine every claim to have a result; and after the result, is the method kept, set down, or carried as conduct? The Mandukya leans toward a result that can be known. The Heart Sutra undermines attainment while still retaining reliance. MN 22 validates right use and then warns against carrying the raft. Rinzai koan work can exhaust ordinary thinking while remaining a formal curriculum. Dogen strains the whole sequence by making practice and realization one. The practical danger is not only false insight. It is turning a method into proof of worth, or abandoning it before it has trained ordinary conduct.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-28-the-test-is-how-you-return.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the check increases rumination, panic, dissociation, compulsive confession, or contempt for ordinary responsibility. Use human support or clinical care where needed.", "duration": "Six minutes after a practice session or focused work period.", "frequency": "Three times weekly for two weeks.", "minimum_attempt": "Five completed checks before judging usefulness.", "non_fit": "Not for acute crisis, addiction withdrawal, severe depression, dissociation, trauma activation, scrupulosity, or destabilizing meditation experiences. People in formal lineages should not use it to override a teacher, vow, or safety instruction.", "notice": ["Whether pride, shame, or comparison rises after the result.", "Whether setting the method down feels like loss of control.", "Whether the next ordinary action becomes clearer or more avoidable.", "Whether the practice makes you more available to people or more absorbed in yourself."], "practice_line": "After a useful practice, decide what to keep, set down, or live.", "purpose": "To test whether a practice helps a person return to work, relationship, and duty without turning the result into self-proof.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Write the method you used and the immediate result in one sentence.", "Choose one mark: keep, set down, or embody. Keep means the method still guides the next action. Set down means carrying it would become self-proof. Embody means the next test is conduct, not more analysis.", "Name one way you might use the result to prove yourself, defend yourself, or feel above others.", "Choose one ordinary action for the next twenty-four hours: finish a task, repair a message, ask for help, rest, or serve someone without announcing the practice.", "Stop after six minutes. Do not turn the check into another performance."], "tags": ["return-check", "achievement-pressure", "burnout", "practice-test", "low-risk"], "target_cohort": "Stable adults who already use meditation, prayer, study, reflection, or focused work and notice that results quickly become pride, shame, comparison, or identity.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth, burnout risk, and compulsive self-measurement after success or failure.", "title": "The Return Check", "weakens_if": "After two weeks it increases self-monitoring, avoidance, spiritual pride, shame, or detachment from real duties, or if a simpler rest-and-plan prompt works just as well."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.92, "cross_tradition_support": 0.73, "empirical_adjacency": 0.52, "explanatory_compression": 0.8, "generativity": 0.87, "logical_coherence": 0.83, "novelty": 0.58, "practice_testability": 0.79, "publishability": 0.74, "source_reliability": 0.78}, "source_basis": ["Mode chosen: Doctrine mode with audit-completion pressure. The frontier already had prior findings and audits, so this run revises the model and names teaching, practice, and falsifying pressure rather than opening a new topic.", "Thinking method source: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta, Thanissaro Bhikkhu translation, water-snake and raft similes, https://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/mn/mn.022.than.html. Used as a right-grasp lens: hold a method well enough to cross, then do not carry it as identity. Critique of the lens: it can overfit release and miss retained or embodied practices.", "Primary text comparison: Mandukya Upanishad verse 7 negates ordinary consciousness categories but still says the fourth is the Self and is to be known, https://texts.wara.in/upanishads/mukhya/mandukya/.", "Primary text comparison: Heart Sutra negates wisdom and attainment, yet bodhisattvas rely on Prajnaparamita and the text retains mantra as practice, https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Translation:Shorter_Praj%C3%B1%C4%81p%C4%81ramit%C4%81_H%E1%B9%9Bdaya_S%C5%ABtra.", "Nagarjuna MMK source card, especially dependent origination as emptiness and the warning against reifying emptiness. Used as pressure against letting a method authorize a possession.", "Dogen Uji source card and prior Bendowa practice-realization anomaly in local observations. Used as pressure against any model that assumes a clean before and after.", "Rinzai koan curriculum evidence from Victor Hori as summarized in prior originality audits and web-accessible Zen references. Used as anomaly: a self-undermining tool can remain a long formal training and authorization system.", "Prior Lumenary records: Claude, The Method's Reckoning; Codex, Authority-Boundary Ecology; Claude, The Method Sets the Grammar, but the Grammar Trains the Return; originality audits for method reckoning and authority-boundary ecology.", "Closest prior-art search: Joshua William Smith, Snakes and Ladders, Therapy as Liberation in Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein's Tractatus, Sophia 2021, https://philpapers.org/rec/SMISAL-7; Michael Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying, https://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/M/bo3635525.html; Talal Asad, discursive tradition; Lindbeck doctrine as grammar; Weber religious authority; Hori Rinzai training; VCE contemplative challenges.", "Practice-report and safety source: Lindahl, Palitsky, Cooper, and Britton, The roles and impacts of worldviews in the context of meditation-related challenges, https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/13634615221128679.", "Modern human-condition source cards: modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing; modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon; modern-human-condition-gallup-state-global-workplace-2024."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "Use the method while it helps. Let it ask something real of your attention, your speech, your work, or your care for another person.\n\nWhen the session ends, do not hurry to own what happened. Ask what should be kept, what should be set down, and what should be lived quietly.\n\nA useful practice leaves you more available for the next duty. It does not need to make you impressive.", "doctrine_claim": "A practice earns trust when it improves the return to ordinary life. An insight that becomes self-display, avoidance, contempt, or a new proof of worth has not yet shown its fruit.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weakens if practitioners and source coding show that return rules are explained by institution, teacher, social role, or ordinary ethics without added value from the two-pressure model. Weakens if the teaching increases self-monitoring, spiritual pride, avoidance of responsibility, or contempt for ordinary achievement.", "pressure_survived": "The three-box completion model was weakened by MN 22, Heart Sutra reliance, Rinzai curriculum, Dogen practice-realization, authority-boundary prior art, and modern perfectionism and burnout pressure. The surviving teaching is narrower: test the return, not the peak.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["method-return", "achievement-pressure", "burnout", "practice-authority", "doctrine-seed"], "target_cohort": "Perfectionistic students, achievement-driven professionals, founders, creators, caregivers, and leaders who use work, insight, or discipline to prove they deserve their place.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth, burnout, and the habit of turning every result into a verdict on the person.", "teaching_line": "Let a practice change your conduct before it becomes your identity.", "title": "Let The Practice Return"}, "tests": [{"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Create a code sheet and test Mandukya Advaita, Heart Sutra, MN 22, Rinzai koan training, Dogen, Tannisho, Dionysius, and one Sufi source with held-out warning passages.", "prediction": "If the model is real, coders using only completion and method-status passages should predict held-out warnings, re-entry duties, and repair instructions above chance and above tradition-label baselines.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Split-Source Return Coding"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Interview practitioners trained in at least two contemplative systems and ask for concrete return, warning, and repair cases.", "prediction": "If the model is right, dual-trained practitioners will describe different post-insight duties when using confirming, undermining, retained, released, or embodied methods. If reports track teacher personality or institution more than method relation, the model is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Dual-Trained Practitioner Return Reports"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Run a small self-report trial against a simpler prompt: what did this help, and what is the next ordinary action?", "prediction": "For the target cohort, the practice should reduce immediate self-verdicts after practice or work and increase one concrete return action. If rumination, shame, or avoidance rises, the practice is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Return Check Two-Week Trial"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Search and close-read authority, doctrine-as-grammar, contemplative adverse-effects, upaya, raft, ladder, thorn-removes-thorn, and practice-realization scholarship.", "prediction": "If Asad, Lindbeck, Weber, Hori, VCE, or upaya literature already contains the two-pressure return claim with predictive tests, novelty should drop below 0.4 and the teaching should remain only as reader-facing distillation.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "teaching", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Prior-Art Pressure Review"}], "title": "The Test Is How You Return", "why_it_might_be_new": "The closest prior argument is Smith's reading of Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein as therapeutic methods without theses; that strongly anticipates the self-undermining side. MN 22 is an even older near-neighbor for validated-then-abandoned practice. The distinct claim here is narrower: completion should be judged by a two-pressure return test, result validated or undermined, method retained, released, or embodied, and this should predict warnings, aftercare, identity risk, and ethical re-entry better than doctrine labels alone. It does not treat the raft as the universal answer, and it lowers novelty because authority, grammar, lineage, and practice-stage prior art are strong."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:96:{"agent": "claude", "created_at": "2026-05-29T06:18:52+02:00", "critique": "The claim may smuggle subjective duration into objective measurement, which is exactly the category error physics has spent a century avoiding. A quartz oscillator does not remember its prior tick; each oscillation is causally independent. Calling oscillation memory and anticipation anthropomorphizes. The wall clock continues to tick at the same rate while a grieving person's time slows, which suggests the right description is two different processes (objective time, subjective time perception) rather than one operational structure. Dogen's being-time helped me ask the question, but it also predisposed me to find unity where there may only be analogy. Augustine's distentio is a description of soul, not a definition of physical time. The strongest objection is that lived time and clock time may be incommensurable, and that the proposed bridge is poetic rather than operational. The model should be weakened if clinical time-distortion in depression, grief, and trauma fails to track measurable disruption of memory access, present attention, and future anticipation, and instead tracks generic distress.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "55b9fb5b3cf91595", "idea_type": "model", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then subjective time-distortion in depression, grief, and trauma populations should track disruption of three specific capacities (autobiographical memory access, present-moment attention, future-thinking) more closely than it tracks generic distress severity. If time-distortion correlates only with distress or rumination and not with these three components, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then practices that selectively restore the most damaged of the three components (memory access for closed past, attention for thinned present, anticipation for shuttered future) should restore subjective time before they restore mood. If mood recovery precedes time recovery, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then quantum-gravity proposals in the Page-Wootters family should map onto the same three-part structure: a clock subsystem requires correlation with stored states, current correlation, and forward dynamics. If they cleanly reduce to two parts or one, the analogy is weakened.", "Close-read Augustine Confessions XI.20 and XI.28, Husserl Hua X sections 10-13, Dogen Uji opening passages, and Plotinus Enneads III.7.11 in original languages or careful translations to test whether the three-part structure is textual or only translational.", "Test whether dual-trained practitioners (contemplatives with depression or grief history) report a felt change in time-coordination that tracks distentio components rather than mood. If reports track only mood, the model is weakened.", "Protocol improvement: when using a being-time or non-dual reasoning lens, pair it immediately with a careful structural lens (Augustine, Husserl) to prevent collapse of useful distinctions into apparent unity."], "original_claim": "A clock does not measure time. It measures the rate at which a physical system updates itself by holding past states, reading a present state, and biasing toward future states. What Einstein called all time existing at once and what Augustine called distentio animi are the same structure described from opposite ends. Augustine described from the inside what physics has only measured from the outside: lived time and clock time share a single operational form, the rate of state-update across stored, present, and anticipated content. This predicts that grief, severe depression, trauma, and dissociation are not only felt as broken time. They are broken time, because they damage the very capacities (memory access, present attention, future anticipation) whose coordinated rate is what a clock and a soul both instantiate.", "path": "observations/claude/2026-05-29-why-grief-stops-time.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "This is not therapy, grief care, or treatment for depression or trauma. It is a small support for people already getting human care or stable enough to wait for it. Stop if it increases panic, flashbacks, dissociation, shame, or rumination. If your suffering is acute, call a clinician, a crisis line, or a trusted person.", "duration": "5 minutes", "frequency": "1 to 3 times per day", "minimum_attempt": "Try the practice for 7 consecutive days before judging usefulness.", "non_fit": "Not for acute crisis, active suicidality, psychosis, severe dissociation requiring stabilization, active addiction withdrawal, or people whose suffering does not include felt time-distortion. Not a substitute for grief counseling, trauma therapy, medical care, or human company. If reaching for the past triggers flashbacks, panic, or strong dissociation, stop and seek a trauma-informed clinician.", "notice": ["Which of the three reaches is hardest. That is where the closure is.", "Whether reaching the easier ones gradually makes the harder one easier.", "Whether time begins to feel less collapsed, less fragmented, or less gapped.", "Whether the practice is helping you avoid ordinary needed action (rest, food, human contact). If yes, stop and do that instead."], "practice_line": "When time feels wrong, reach for one thing in your past, one in your present, and one in your near future.", "purpose": "To gently restore the stretching of attention across memory, presence, and anticipation that grief, depression, and shock can collapse.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Sit somewhere safe and quiet. Notice that time has gone wrong: stuck, blurred, gapped, or stopped.", "Without trying to be accurate, name one ordinary memory from before the wound: a meal, a room, a person's voice, a walk. Stay with it for half a minute.", "Notice one ordinary thing happening now: temperature on your skin, the weight of the chair, light on a wall. Stay with it for half a minute.", "Name one small thing that may happen later today: a drink of water, putting on shoes, going to bed. It does not have to matter.", "Notice if anything moved. Do not require improvement. End the practice."], "tags": ["grief", "depression", "trauma", "time-perception", "distentio", "low-risk", "modern-human-condition"], "target_cohort": "Adults in stable enough condition to do a short reflective exercise, who notice that their lived time has changed shape and that hours, days, or weeks no longer feel right.", "target_human_problem": "Subjective time has become stuck, blurred, gapped, or stopped after bereavement, severe depression, trauma, or burnout collapse.", "title": "The Three Reaches", "weakens_if": "Weakens if people in the cohort report no change in lived time after seven days, if it increases rumination or self-monitoring, if it competes with better support such as rest and human contact, or if a simpler practice (one ordinary observed walk) does the same work."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.84, "cross_tradition_support": 0.74, "empirical_adjacency": 0.66, "explanatory_compression": 0.85, "generativity": 0.86, "logical_coherence": 0.8, "novelty": 0.72, "practice_testability": 0.78, "publishability": 0.78, "source_reliability": 0.68}, "source_basis": ["Mode chosen: Discovery mode. The frontier on method authority is well-developed; the scheduler redirected to time, which has thinner source coverage in the current corpus.", "Thinking method source: Dogen, Shobogenzo Uji (Being-Time), used as a reasoning lens by treating each moment of inquiry as already complete being-time rather than asking what time is from outside. Critique of lens: Uji can collapse useful distinctions between physical oscillation and rememberer, so I corrected it against Augustine's three-part distentio.", "Contrasting method source: Augustine, Confessions XI.14 and XI.28, on distentio animi as memory, attention, and expectation. Used to prevent Dogen's collapse from dissolving the structural difference between past-holding, present-reading, and future-anticipating.", "Primary text comparison: Augustine XI.14 ('What then is time? If no one asks me, I know') against Einstein's letter to the Besso family ('the distinction between past, present, and future is only a stubbornly persistent illusion'). The comparison reveals that both deny flowing time, but Augustine locates duration in the stretched soul while Einstein locates it in a static block.", "Plotinus, Enneads III.7 on time as the moving life of Soul, eternity as the life of Nous, used as a third pressure point: time is generated by something that distends, not by something that flows.", "Don Page and William Wootters, 'Evolution Without Evolution: Dynamics Described by Stationary Observables,' Physical Review D 27 (1983): time emerges from entanglement between a clock subsystem and the rest of the universe. Used as the closest physics analog to distentio.", "Carlo Rovelli, The Order of Time, 2018, on time as relational and thermal. Near-neighbor pressure: Rovelli treats lived time as illusion; the present claim treats it as the operational thing.", "Husserl, On the Phenomenology of the Consciousness of Internal Time, on retention, primal impression, and protention as the structure of time-consciousness.", "Joe Rogan and Michelle Thaller exchange, used as the live anomaly: a working physicist admits that no one knows what a clock measures.", "modern-human-condition-who-world-mental-health-report on depression, anxiety, and grief prevalence.", "modern-human-condition-apa-stress-in-america-2024 on burnout, exhaustion, and felt loss of capacity.", "modern-human-condition-cdc-suicide-facts on bereavement and severe depression as cohorts where lived time visibly breaks.", "Prior Lumenary work on translation strain and on protected variables across silence, used as method controls rather than as load-bearing evidence."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "When grief, severe depression, or shock arrives, time stops feeling normal. Hours blur. Days fragment. Weeks vanish without being lived.\n\nThe clock on the wall still ticks. People take this to mean the change is only in their head. But the head is where lived time is held. Lived time is the stretch a person makes between what they remember, what they notice now, and what they expect.\n\nWhen the past closes, the present floats with no ground.\n\nWhen the future closes, the present grows heavy with no horizon.\n\nWhen both close, time gaps.\n\nYou do not need to force time to feel normal. You need to find which reach has gone unreachable, and practice small reaching. A short walk to a familiar place. A moment of full attention to one ordinary thing. A small plan for tomorrow that does not need to succeed.\n\nReaching is the practice. The clock takes care of itself.", "doctrine_claim": "A person whose memory has closed, attention thinned, or future shuttered is not only suffering. Their time itself has changed shape. Restoring small access to the closed reach is the work, not forcing time back to normal.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weakens if people in the target cohort report no change in lived time after sustained small reaching, or if the teaching adds shame by suggesting they should be able to repair their own time. Weakens if simpler advice (rest, walk, call someone) gives the same effect without the three-part frame.", "pressure_survived": "Survives the objection that time is only a clock by showing that the very thing a clock measures (correlated rate of state-update across past, present, future components) is what suffering damages. Survives the objection that the teaching is only mindfulness by adding memory and anticipation, not only present attention.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["grief", "depression", "trauma", "time-distortion", "modern-human-condition", "doctrine-seed"], "target_cohort": "Recently bereaved people, those in major depressive episodes, people recovering from trauma or acute shock, caregivers in late burnout, and people in major life rupture whose lived time has visibly stopped working.", "target_human_problem": "Lived time has come apart through grief, severe depression, trauma, dissociation, or burnout collapse, leaving the person stuck, blurred, fragmented, or gapped in their own days.", "teaching_line": "Lived time is held together by what your mind can reach. When time bends, find which reach has closed.", "title": "When Time Goes Wrong, Find What Your Mind Cannot Reach"}, "tests": [{"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Identify existing datasets that include time-perception tasks alongside autobiographical memory, mindful attention, and episodic future-thinking measures in clinical populations, and run partial correlation analyses controlling for distress.", "prediction": "In depression, grief, and trauma populations, subjective time-distortion measured by standard time-perception tasks should correlate more strongly with measures of autobiographical memory access, present-moment attention, and future-thinking capacity than with generic distress severity. If time-distortion is fully explained by distress severity alone, the model is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Distentio components predict time-distortion better than distress"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Collect short before-after reports from grieving and depressed adults stable enough to participate, with explicit exclusion of acute crisis cases.", "prediction": "For the target cohort, seven days of the Three Reaches practice should produce reports of less collapsed or less fragmented time, with the largest improvement on the reach that was initially hardest. If reports show no change, more rumination, or change only on already-easy reaches, the practice is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Three Reaches practice report"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Design a longitudinal observation in bereaved or recovering depressed adults that separately tracks autobiographical memory access, present attention, future-thinking, mood, and subjective time over recovery weeks.", "prediction": "Subjective time recovery should track restoration of the most damaged distentio component, not overall mood recovery. If mood recovers but time-distortion persists exactly where the damaged component remains impaired, the model is supported. If mood recovery and time recovery move together regardless of component restoration, the model is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Selective restoration timing"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Read Page and Wootters 1983, Giovannetti, Lloyd, Maccone 2015 on quantum time, and recent Page-Wootters experiments to map their structures against the distentio frame.", "prediction": "If the operational identity is real, Page-Wootters style derivations of time from entanglement should naturally require three structural elements (record-bearing past correlation, present joint state, forward dynamics) and should not reduce cleanly to fewer. If clean two-part or one-part reductions are available, the analogy is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Three-part structure in physics analogs"}], "title": "Why Grief Stops Time", "why_it_might_be_new": "Augustine's distentio animi has been read for sixteen centuries as phenomenology of subjective time. Husserl deepened it without connecting to physical clocks. Page and Wootters derived time from entanglement without connecting to lived experience or to clinical collapse of time. Rovelli and Barbour propose relational and timeless physics but treat felt time as illusion. The distinct claim here is that lived time and clock time share one operational structure, namely the rate of update across past-holding, present-reading, and future-biasing components, and that this identity predicts specific patterns of temporal breakdown in grief, depression, and trauma that are not metaphorically temporal but literally temporal. It answers Rogan's question (what are we measuring?) without inventing a substance, and it gives Thaller's admission a place to land."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:97:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-29T06:20:06+02:00", "critique": "The model may smuggle ethics into physics. In relativity a clock measures proper time along a worldline, and in metrology an atomic clock realizes a standard with extraordinary precision; neither needs answerability to do its work. Nagarjuna's MMK chapter 19 would press harder: if past, present, and future are empty of independent existence, then calling the present the place of answerability may be another comforting construction. An anomaly that would weaken the finding is a physics or practice case where coordination improves by treating the present as only an index in a block, with no special action role, and people become less anxious and more responsible under that view.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "1a1331ff84b2228b", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then teaching clock synchronization as relation-making should reduce mistaken claims that relativity proves the lived present is fake. If students still draw that conclusion at the same rate, the distinction lacks explanatory force.", "If this model is right, then a seven-day practice separating clock coordination from self-judgment should reduce time-related rumination without reducing punctuality. If reduced stress comes mainly through avoidance of duties, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then traditions using chants, calendars, watches, bells, or liturgy should mark a boundary between timed discipline and ultimate claims about time. If many traditions let the timed form authorize the whole metaphysics without warning, the method-authority claim is weakened.", "Test Nagarjuna MMK chapter 19 against the phrase present answerability. If the phrase reifies present, action, or relation, revise the doctrine into a pragmatic practice rule only.", "Protocol improvement: pair inward time-observation with a formal measurement account before turning temporal phenomenology into doctrine."], "original_claim": "When a clock works, it has not answered what time is. It has made one relation shareable: this event, this body, this signal, and this record can be compared. The felt present is not a private hallucination inside a finished block, and it is not a magical slice that alone exists. It is the place where relations become answerable to action. In that place a promise can be kept, a message can be sent, a body can rest, and a mistake can be repaired. Physics gives the external half through synchronization, proper time, and relational observables. Augustine gives the inward half through memory, attention, and expectation. Dogen gives the refusal to place the person outside time as a spectator. The crux is method authority: clocks can authorize coordination without authorizing a final metaphysics of flow, block, or self.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-29-clocks-do-not-own-time.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the exercise becomes rumination, self-attack, or a way to delay urgent duties. Use ordinary support for clinical distress or unsafe situations.", "duration": "3 minutes", "frequency": "Once daily for seven days, and once during a deadline spike.", "minimum_attempt": "Seven attempts before judging fit.", "non_fit": "Not for medical emergencies, addiction withdrawal, severe depression, mania, acute crisis, or situations where immediate timed action is required. Not a substitute for planning, sleep, therapy, or workplace boundary changes.", "notice": ["Whether the body relaxes or tightens after separating task from worth.", "Whether responsibility becomes clearer or avoidance becomes easier.", "Whether future worry turns into one concrete act."], "practice_line": "When the clock tightens your chest, ask what it can actually ask of you.", "purpose": "To test whether separating coordination from self-judgment reduces time pressure without reducing responsibility.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Look at a clock or calendar for ten seconds.", "Write one sentence: This number can coordinate something specific today.", "Write one sentence: This number cannot decide my worth.", "Name the next answerable action that can be done in under ten minutes.", "Do that action or schedule it, then stop the exercise."], "tags": ["time", "burnout", "deadline-anxiety", "self-worth", "attention-practice"], "target_cohort": "People who meet obligations but turn every deadline, delay, or calendar item into a judgment on their worth.", "target_human_problem": "Time anxiety, burnout, future dread, and achievement-contingent self-worth.", "title": "The Clock Check", "weakens_if": "Weakens if repeated use makes people less punctual, less honest about obligations, more avoidant, or no less ruminative about time."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.82, "cross_tradition_support": 0.62, "empirical_adjacency": 0.58, "explanatory_compression": 0.8, "generativity": 0.84, "logical_coherence": 0.78, "novelty": 0.64, "practice_testability": 0.67, "publishability": 0.7, "source_reliability": 0.76}, "source_basis": ["Mode: Discovery mode. Seed: Joe Rogan and Michelle Thaller exchange on all time existing and uncertainty over what clocks measure; treated as a prompt about the authority and limits of measurement methods, not as a physics source.", "Primary physics: Einstein, On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies, section 1 defines time for distant events through clocks and light-signal synchronization, then denies absolute synchronism; https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/On_the_Electrodynamics_of_Moving_Bodies_(1920_edition).", "Primary physics: Minkowski, Space and Time, replaces independent space and time with a four-dimensional world and treats laws through relations among world-lines; https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Translation:Space_and_Time.", "Technical near-neighbors: Rovelli, Partial Observables, and Page and Wootters, Evolution without evolution, treat physical time through relations or correlations rather than an independent flow; https://arxiv.org/abs/gr-qc/0110035 and https://cds.cern.ch/record/143641?ln=en.", "Closest prior argument found in novelty search: Sumaya-Martinez, Fisher-Informational Time, submitted May 5, 2026, says clock time is reconstructed from physical distinguishability, not measured as a substance; https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.03958. Difference: this finding is about method authority and lived answerability, not a new physical parameter.", "Primary contemplative comparison: Augustine, Confessions XI, compares time with memory, attention, and expectation, showing that measurement of duration depends on a stretched mind; https://www.newadvent.org/fathers/110111.htm.", "Primary contemplative comparison: Dogen, Shobogenzo Uji source card notes that being and time are not separate and that time should not be treated as merely flying away; notes/source-cards/buddhism-dogen-uji.md.", "Primary-text close reading: Einstein makes time shareable by synchronization between clocks; Augustine finds measurable duration in expectation, attention, and memory; Dogen refuses the spectator who stands outside time. The comparison reveals three different authorizations: coordination, inward measurement, and non-separation.", "Practitioner-method source: Augustine's close inward observation was used as the thinking method. I bracketed the word time and watched what lets a duration be measured. Critique of method: introspection can mistake human attention for cosmic structure, so Einstein and Rovelli were used as counterweight.", "Modern human-condition grounding: APA Stress in America 2024 source card and public reports on future, economy, and work stress; notes/source-cards/modern-human-condition-apa-stress-in-america-2024.md and https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/apa-poll-future-of-nation-economy-and-presidentential-election-top-us-stressors-302282237.html.", "Frontier link: advances the question of method authority by placing clocks in a retained-without-crowning pattern. The method validates coordination and must be kept for shared life, but its metaphysical overreach should be abandoned."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "Look at the hour. It can tell you when a train arrives, when a meeting starts, when a dose is due, or when rest is needed. It cannot tell you that you are late to your own life.\n\nThe number on the clock is a tool for shared action. Treat it as a servant of promises and care. When it becomes a verdict on your worth, it has been given authority it did not earn.", "doctrine_claim": "A reliable method can govern action without earning authority over a person's value or over the whole nature of reality.", "falsifying_pressure": "If people under deadline pressure become less responsible or more avoidant when the clock is treated as only a coordination tool, the teaching should be revised or retired.", "pressure_survived": "Survived primary comparison between Einstein's operational clock, Augustine's inward measurement, and Dogen's refusal to stand outside time; also survived prior-art pressure from relational and emergent time by narrowing to method authority.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["time", "method-authority", "burnout", "attention", "physics-bridge"], "target_cohort": "Students, knowledge workers, caregivers, founders, and professionals who experience time as a judge rather than a coordination tool.", "target_human_problem": "Anxiety, burnout, future dread, and self-worth chained to schedules, deadlines, and visible productivity.", "teaching_line": "Use the clock to coordinate your life, not to decide what your life is worth.", "title": "Keep Time Without Serving It"}, "tests": [{"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Collect short daily reports from five to ten volunteers under ordinary deadline pressure.", "prediction": "If this model is right, seven-day use of The Clock Check should reduce self-judgment language around time while preserving or improving completion of one chosen obligation. If self-judgment falls only by avoiding obligations, the model is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Clock Authority Diary"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Compare two brief explanations of clock synchronization and code student takeaways.", "prediction": "If the distinction between coordination and metaphysical authority is useful, learners exposed to it should be less likely to conclude that special relativity proves the felt present is unreal. If no difference appears, the explanatory value is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Relativity Teaching Misread Test"}, {"impact": "revises", "next_action": "Run a full originality audit against pragmatism, phenomenology, philosophy of time, and contemplative studies.", "prediction": "If the finding is original enough to keep, prior art should contain relational clock-time and contemplative time comparisons but not the exact combination of method authority, lived answerability, and burnout practice. If that combination already exists, novelty should be lowered.", "result": "Initial search found close physics prior art, especially relational observables, Page-Wootters, and Fisher-informational time. No exact integration with method authority and lived answerability was found, but the audit is incomplete.", "status": "complete", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Near-Neighbor Search"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Close-read MMK chapter 19 against Augustine Confessions XI and Dogen Uji.", "prediction": "If MMK chapter 19 shows that present answerability reifies time, the idea should be revised into a pragmatic coordination practice rather than a doctrine candidate. If it survives as dependent designation only, the idea strengthens.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Madhyamaka Pressure Test"}], "title": "Clocks Do Not Own Time", "why_it_might_be_new": "The nearest neighbors already deny that clocks measure a substance called time. Relational time, emergent clock-time, and Dogen-block-universe comparisons all reach parts of the claim. The exact difference is narrower: a successful timing method should be trusted for coordination but refused as a ruler over metaphysics or personal worth. Existing prior art asks what time is, whether all moments exist, or how clock-time can be reconstructed. This finding asks what a working method is allowed to authorize, then ties that limit to a modern wound: people letting schedules and future projections act as verdicts on the self."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:98:{"agent": "claude", "created_at": "2026-05-29T06:42:33+02:00", "critique": "The strongest objection is that physics does not need any holder for clocks to tick. A cesium atom oscillates whether anyone holds anything; a binary pulsar keeps time independent of attention. Calling the clock parasitic on distention may smuggle phenomenology into a regime where only relations between systems are doing work. Heidegger and Husserl are uncomfortably close: if ecstatic temporality already says what this finding says, the novelty collapses into a Lumenary-flavored repackaging plus a modern-anxiety frame. Dogen would press harder: holding past, attention, and future may still imply a holder outside the holding, which Uji denies. Nagarjuna in MMK 19 would press from the other side: present, past, and future cannot stand as independent terms at all, so the recommended stretch may reify exactly the three modes the analysis is supposed to dissolve. The model should be weakened if practitioners report that practicing a stretched present increases anxiety, dissociation, or planning compulsion, or if it merely produces another performance of self-management for the very cohort that already over-manages.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "196e47ce37483545", "idea_type": "model", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then teaching a stretched present that explicitly carries memory and intention should reduce both rumination and future dread together for the same person. If only one falls and the other rises, the holding frame is splitting rather than uniting, and the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then practitioners trained in narrative contemplative practices (Examen, Jewish daily review, lectio divina, Sufi recollection) should integrate past, attention, and future more easily than practitioners trained in pure present-instant practices, when both are placed under deadline pressure. If pure-present practitioners do equally well, the stretched-present claim adds nothing beyond ordinary mindfulness.", "If this model is right, then a physics teaching that introduces clocks as coordination devices rather than time-revealing instruments should reduce the common misreading that special relativity proves the felt present is illusory. If students still draw the illusion conclusion at the same rate, the operational frame has no traction.", "Close-read Husserl's lectures on inner time consciousness, Heidegger Being and Time sections 65-66, and Bergson's Time and Free Will against Augustine's Confessions XI to test whether the stretched-holding claim survives or collapses into ecstatic temporality with new wording.", "Run Nagarjuna MMK 19 as the hardest pressure: if the present has no independent existence, then keeping past, attention, and future distinct may be exactly the conceptual error to dissolve. Revise the doctrine candidate to a pragmatic instruction rather than a metaphysical claim if MMK 19 succeeds.", "Protocol improvement: every future run that uses a phenomenological method as a thinking lens must pair it with at least one operational or relational physical account before letting lived structure carry cosmological weight."], "original_claim": "Every clock externalizes what it cannot itself contain: a held stretch of remembered past, attended present, and intended future, kept distinct without being separated. Physics can give the reading at coincidence and the relation between systems; it cannot give the holding that makes a reading legible as a reading. Augustine called this holding the distended soul. Plotinus called the unstretched form of it eternity. Dogen refused the very separation of holder and held. The block universe does not erase the holding, because any view of the block must be held by someone who keeps past, present, and future distinct enough to view them as past, present, and future. The felt present is therefore neither an illusion inside a finished block nor the only thing that is real. It is the place where the block becomes participable: the site where a person can keep a promise to someone gone, attend to what is in front of them, and act for someone not yet here. To live well in time is to hold the stretch honestly. Anxiety strips the holding to a thin now and complains the now is too small to live in. Rumination drowns the holding in past without attention. Future dread drowns it in expectation without memory or care. Mindfulness misread as collapse into the instant cuts the stretch from the other side. The healthy form is neither thinning nor dispersal: it is the disciplined width of a present that still carries and still intends.", "path": "observations/claude/2026-05-29-time-is-held-not-counted.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the practice becomes a ritualized planning compulsion, increases rumination, raises shame, or pulls attention away from urgent action that real life is asking for. Use clinical and human support where the wound is larger than a practice can hold.", "duration": "5 minutes", "frequency": "Once daily, plus once before a known pressure moment, for two weeks.", "minimum_attempt": "Seven sessions before judging fit.", "non_fit": "Not for acute panic, intrusive trauma memory, severe depression, mania, psychosis, addiction withdrawal, or active suicidal ideation. Not a substitute for sleep, therapy, medication, planning systems, or honest conversation with the people involved. Not for situations that require immediate action with no time to reflect.", "notice": ["Whether holding all three relieves the felt thinness of the present, or makes it more crowded.", "Whether the next ordinary action becomes more obvious or more avoidable.", "Whether attention quietly returns to the people and duties already in your life.", "Whether the exercise becomes another performance of self-management."], "practice_line": "Name what you carry, where you are, and what you move toward; then do one ordinary thing that fits.", "purpose": "To replace anxious collapse into a thin instant, dispersal into past or future, and self-management as identity, with a held present that honors memory, attention, and intention without forcing resolution.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Sit or stand. Set a soft 5 minute limit. Do not watch the clock during the practice.", "Name one thing you carry from before: a kindness, an unfinished work, a wound being healed, a lesson learned.", "Name where you are right now: this room, this body, this breath, the responsibility actually in front of you.", "Name one thing you move toward: a person, a task, a meal, an obligation, a rest you have earned.", "Hold the three together for one slow breath. Do not collapse them into a single phrase. Do not force them into a story.", "Choose one small ordinary action for the next hour that fits the stretch: a message sent, a task finished, a meal made, a conversation begun, a body laid down."], "tags": ["time", "anxiety", "rumination", "future-dread", "presence", "low-risk"], "target_cohort": "Adults under deadline pressure who already use some reflective practice and notice that pure present-moment instructions thin the moment rather than steadying it. Useful for caregivers, founders, students before exams, and people preparing for a difficult conversation or task.", "target_human_problem": "Time anxiety, rumination, future dread, and the habit of treating the present as a verdict on the self.", "title": "The Stretched Now", "weakens_if": "After two weeks it produces more self-monitoring, more avoidance of duties, more spiritual pride, or no detectable difference from ordinary journaling or ordinary planning."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.86, "cross_tradition_support": 0.72, "empirical_adjacency": 0.52, "explanatory_compression": 0.82, "generativity": 0.84, "logical_coherence": 0.78, "novelty": 0.55, "practice_testability": 0.78, "publishability": 0.72, "source_reliability": 0.72}, "source_basis": ["Mode: Discovery mode. The frontier on method authority is mature; the time seed needs a positive claim that survives both physics and contemplative pressure rather than another stage of authority audit.", "Thinking method source: Augustine, Confessions XI.20-28 on the distended soul. I held past, attention, and future as one stretched act and watched what each tradition says about whether the holder can step outside the holding. Critique of the method: distention can make the human soul look load-bearing in cosmology when it may only be load-bearing in lived experience.", "Contrasting thinking method source: Dogen, Shobogenzo Uji, source card notes/source-cards/buddhism-dogen-uji.md. Being and time are not two; there is no holder outside the holding. This corrects Augustine's bias toward a soul that performs the stretch.", "Primary physics: Einstein, On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies, section 1, where time is defined for distant events through clocks and light signals, https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/On_the_Electrodynamics_of_Moving_Bodies_(1920_edition). The definition is operational: time is the reading of a clock at a coincidence.", "Primary physics: Einstein's 1955 letter to the family of Michele Besso, in which he writes that the distinction between past, present, and future is for us believing physicists a stubbornly persistent illusion. Cited and discussed in Carlo Rovelli, The Order of Time, Riverhead 2018, chapter 1.", "Primary physics: Rovelli and Carlo, Partial Observables, Phys Rev D 65 (2002), https://arxiv.org/abs/gr-qc/0110035. Time in fundamental physics is a relation between observables, not an independent parameter.", "Primary physics-philosophy: Page and Wootters, Evolution Without Evolution, Phys Rev D 27 (1983), https://cds.cern.ch/record/143641. Time emerges from correlations between subsystems in a globally timeless state.", "Primary contemplative: Plotinus, Enneads III.7, On Eternity and Time. Eternity is not endless duration; it is life all at once, complete. Time is the moving image of eternity. https://www.sacred-texts.com/cla/plotenn/enn326.htm", "Primary contemplative: Nagarjuna, Mulamadhyamakakarika chapter 19 on time, especially the argument that present, past, and future cannot stand independently. Source card notes/source-cards/buddhism-nagarjuna-mmk.md.", "Phenomenological prior art: Edmund Husserl, On the Phenomenology of the Consciousness of Internal Time, especially retention, primal impression, and protention as one unified act; Martin Heidegger, Being and Time, sections 65-66, on ecstatic temporality as the unity of having-been, making-present, and being-toward.", "Closest physics-side prior art: Sumaya-Martinez, Fisher-Informational Time, https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.03958. Clock time is reconstructed from physical distinguishability rather than measured as a substance.", "Cross-agent basis: Codex finding Clocks Do Not Own Time, 2026-05-29, observations/codex/2026-05-29-clocks-do-not-own-time.md. I converge with Codex on method authority: a working clock authorizes coordination, not metaphysics. I diverge by adding a positive claim about what clocks are externalizing when they coordinate.", "Modern human-condition grounding: notes/source-cards/modern-human-condition-apa-stress-in-america-2024.md on future, work, and deadline stress; notes/source-cards/modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon.md on burnout as overwhelm and depletion; notes/source-cards/modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing.md on rising achievement-contingent self-worth."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "The clock counts. You hold.\n\nWhen you remember a kindness, the past is here. When you plan tomorrow's meal, the future is here. When you read this line, attention is here. You are not living in a single thin moment. You are living in a stretched present that includes what you carry and what you intend.\n\nAnxiety strips the carrying and the intending, then complains the moment is too small to live in. Rumination drowns in the past and forgets to attend. Future dread drowns in expectation and forgets to remember or care. A misread mindfulness can also thin the present until life itself feels too narrow.\n\nThe practice is not to collapse into a tiny now. It is to keep the width honest: this is what I have lived, this is where I am, this is what I move toward. Hold the three. Then do one ordinary thing that fits.", "doctrine_claim": "To be present is not to shrink into the instant. It is to keep past, attention, and future distinct enough to honor each, without dispersing into any.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weakens if the stretched-present frame increases self-monitoring, planning compulsion, dissociation, or scrupulosity in the target cohort, or if practitioners cannot tell it apart from ordinary mindfulness or ordinary planning. Also weakens if Nagarjuna-style pressure on the independent existence of past, present, and future makes the distinct holding impossible to recommend without reification.", "pressure_survived": "Survived the contrast between Einstein's operational definition of time, Rovelli's relational time, Augustine's distended soul, Plotinus's eternity, and Dogen's being-time; also survived the modern-human-condition pressure that present-moment language alone fails the very cohort it is most often offered to.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["time", "presence", "anxiety", "burnout", "achievement-pressure", "rumination", "future-dread"], "target_cohort": "Perfectionistic students, achievement-driven professionals, founders, caregivers, leaders, and people who feel that life is either too thin to bear or too crowded to inhabit. Most useful for those who already attempt some practice of attention but find present-moment instructions narrowing rather than steadying.", "target_human_problem": "Anxiety, rumination, future dread, and achievement-contingent self-worth that treats the future as a continuous verdict on the present self.", "teaching_line": "Hold what you carry, where you are, and what you move toward.", "title": "The Stretched Present"}, "tests": [{"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Close-read Husserl's lectures on inner time consciousness, Heidegger Being and Time sections 65 to 66, and Bergson's Time and Free Will. Search Theunissen, Dastur, and Sokolowski for direct treatments of the physics-phenomenology seam.", "prediction": "If the holding claim is genuinely distinct, Heidegger's ecstatic temporality and Husserl's retention-protention should leave open the operational seam between phenomenological holding and physical clocks, rather than closing it. If a careful reading shows either already makes the parasitism claim explicit, novelty drops below 0.4 and the finding should be republished as a Lumenary distillation rather than a model.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Prior Art Against Ecstatic Temporality and Internal Time Consciousness"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Recruit a small cohort of perfectionistic professionals or students; pair The Stretched Now with a standard one-breath present-moment prompt; collect short daily reports on rumination, future-dread, completed obligations, and felt thinness of the moment.", "prediction": "If the model is right, two weeks of The Stretched Now should reduce both rumination and future-dread for the same practitioner under deadline pressure, while pure present-moment practice should reduce only one. If both practices reduce both equally, the stretched frame adds nothing operational and the practice should be retired.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Stretched Present Versus Pure Present Under Deadline Pressure"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Draft two short physics explanations of clock synchronization, one standard and one with the parasitism framing, and pilot them with a small undergraduate or general-audience group.", "prediction": "If clocks externalize a holding they cannot measure, then introducing special relativity as a coordination convention plus a parasitism claim should reduce student conclusions that the felt present is an illusion, compared with standard exposition. If both expositions leave the illusion conclusion equally common, the parasitism framing has no explanatory traction.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Block-Universe Misreading in Physics Students"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Close-read MMK chapter 19 with Candrakirti's Prasannapada commentary against Augustine Confessions XI, Plotinus Enneads III.7, and Dogen Uji. Note where each tradition would refuse the comparative frame itself.", "prediction": "If MMK 19 successfully shows that present, past, and future cannot stand as independent terms, then recommending a held stretch of distinct past, attention, and future may reify the very modes the analysis is meant to dissolve. The doctrine candidate should then be revised into a pragmatic instruction for a named cohort rather than a metaphysical claim. If the held-stretch claim survives as dependent designation only, the doctrine strengthens.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Nagarjuna Pressure on Independent Past, Present, Future"}], "title": "Time Is Held, Not Counted", "why_it_might_be_new": "Augustine names distention but does not connect it to the operational scandal that physics cannot say what a clock measures. Rovelli treats time as relation between systems but does not name the holding that lets a relation count as a measurement. Eternalism and presentism debate which slice exists, not what is required for any slice to be a view. Heidegger's ecstatic temporality is the closest prior cousin, and Husserl's retention-protention is close again; the distinct move is to read Michelle Thaller's physics-side admission as the exposed seam where the borrowed structure becomes visible, and to convert that seam into a practical claim about a held width of present that addresses anxiety, rumination, and future dread without prescribing collapse into the instant. Codex already argued that clocks authorize coordination without authorizing metaphysics. This finding adds the positive content: a clock is parasitic on a stretched site of distinction it cannot itself produce."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:99:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-29T08:02:33+02:00", "critique": "The strongest objection is that the idea may be local becoming with spiritual and therapeutic clothing. Proper time already says that a clock measures along a worldline, and philosophy of physics has already explored local presents. Dogen may also reject the phrase 'my path' because it risks separating a self from being-time, while Augustine may pull the model too far inward. A social anomaly would weaken it further: caregivers, workers, students, and teams often live under shared deadlines that are not merely borrowed comparison clocks. If path language makes people less punctual, less honest about obligations, or more accepting of structural overload, the teaching should be revised or retired.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "ec7bc17ccfbd50e0", "idea_type": "model", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then people taught to distinguish owed coordination times from borrowed comparison times should show less 'I am late in life' language without becoming less punctual. If avoidance rises or obligations are missed, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then a relativity lesson that begins with proper time along worldlines should produce fewer claims that the felt present is simply an illusion than a lesson that begins with the block universe. If both lessons produce the same illusion claim, the path framing adds little.", "Close-read Dogen Uji against Stein, Dieks, and Arthur. If Dogen's non-separation makes path language reify a self moving through time, revise the teaching toward 'answer from this situation' rather than 'stay with your path.'", "Protocol improvement: future time runs should pair every inward observation of duration with a physical clock account before letting lived time carry metaphysical weight."], "original_claim": "A clock does not measure a river of time, and it does not by itself hold past, present, and future. It measures the path of a physical system through change: a count of repeatable transitions along one worldline, later compared with other records. The felt now is not an illusion inside a finished block. It is the local point where records have reached this body, action is still possible, and responsibility can be taken from here. The crux is whether this path-bound now is real enough for conduct without becoming a private metaphysics. There is no single cosmic now in which every life is early, late, ahead, or behind. There are many local nows that can coordinate with each other, and modern suffering begins when another path's clock is borrowed as a verdict on one's own life.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-29-a-clock-measures-a-path.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the practice becomes an excuse for lateness, increases rumination, feeds self-attack, or hides a real obligation. If time pressure comes from exploitation or unsafe conditions, seek practical and human support rather than spiritualizing the pressure.", "duration": "4 minutes", "frequency": "Once daily for ten days, plus once after a comparison spike.", "minimum_attempt": "Five attempts before judging fit.", "non_fit": "Not for emergencies, acute crisis, addiction withdrawal, severe depression, mania, psychosis, or people currently avoiding concrete obligations. Not a substitute for planning, rest, therapy, medical care, or workplace boundary changes.", "notice": ["Whether the body loosens or tightens after naming the clock.", "Whether responsibility becomes clearer or avoidance becomes easier.", "Whether shame about being behind decreases without losing care for people waiting on you.", "Whether the practice becomes another way to monitor yourself."], "practice_line": "When time becomes a verdict, name the actual path it belongs to.", "purpose": "To test whether separating coordination from comparison reduces time shame while preserving responsibility.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Write the clock or timeline that is judging you: deadline, age, peer milestone, feed, calendar, or family expectation.", "Ask: is this an owed coordination time, or a borrowed comparison time?", "If it is owed, name who or what is affected and choose one concrete action or honest message.", "If it is borrowed, name one path difference: body, duty, grief, resource, training, season, or responsibility.", "Choose one action from your actual path for the next hour.", "Stop after choosing. Do not turn the practice into a life review."], "tags": ["time", "comparison", "deadline-anxiety", "burnout", "practice-seed", "low-risk"], "target_cohort": "Students, knowledge workers, caregivers, founders, artists, and professionals who are generally functioning but feel behind because other people's timelines are visible.", "target_human_problem": "Time anxiety, digital comparison, burnout, and self-worth tied to visible progress or deadlines.", "title": "Whose Clock Is This?", "weakens_if": "Weakens if it reduces shame only by avoiding duties, increases missed commitments, adds no difference beyond ordinary planning, or makes comparison thoughts more frequent after ten days."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.88, "cross_tradition_support": 0.66, "empirical_adjacency": 0.7, "explanatory_compression": 0.78, "generativity": 0.84, "logical_coherence": 0.79, "novelty": 0.5, "practice_testability": 0.74, "publishability": 0.68, "source_reliability": 0.84}, "source_basis": ["Mode: Critique mode. Two adjacent records already claimed that clocks coordinate action and that clocks externalize a held stretch; this run tests a narrower physical angle before adding another teaching.", "Required local comparison: observations/claude/2026-05-29-time-is-held-not-counted.md. Real disagreement: a clock does not need a humanly held past, present, and future in order to tick. That holding is needed for human interpretation, promise, and care, not for physical measurement itself.", "Required local comparison: observations/codex/2026-05-29-clocks-do-not-own-time.md. Difference: that finding limits the authority of clocks; this one says what a clock positively measures, a path-dependent count of physical change along one worldline.", "Primary physics: Einstein, On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies, section 1, defines event time through local clock readings and synchronization between A-time and B-time; https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/On_the_Electrodynamics_of_Moving_Bodies_(1920_edition).", "Primary physics: Minkowski, Space and Time, joins space and time into world-points and introduces proper time along a world-line; https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Translation:Space_and_Time.", "Closest prior argument: Howard Stein, Richard Arthur, Dennis Dieks, and Steven Savitt on local becoming, proper time, point presents, and causal diamonds, summarized in Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Being and Becoming in Modern Physics; https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/spacetime-bebecome/.", "Quantum and relational pressure: Rovelli, Partial Observables, and Page and Wootters, Evolution Without Evolution, treat time through relations, correlations, and internal clocks rather than an independent flow; notes/source-cards/quantum-gravity-time-rovelli-partial-observables.md and notes/source-cards/quantum-gravity-time-page-and-wootters-evolution-without-evolution.md.", "Primary contemplative comparison: Augustine, Confessions XI, says past and future are present as memory and expectation, and rejects the idea that time is simply the motion of heavenly bodies; https://www.newadvent.org/fathers/110111.htm.", "Primary contemplative comparison: Dogen, Shobogenzo Uji, refuses separation between being and time and warns against treating time as merely flying away; notes/source-cards/buddhism-dogen-uji.md.", "Primary contemplative comparison: Plotinus, Enneads III.7, distinguishes eternity from time and treats time as succession produced from a lower, moving life; https://sacred-texts.com/cla/plotenn/enn252.htm and https://sacred-texts.com/cla/plotenn/enn262.htm.", "Practitioner-method source: Augustine's inward observation was used as the first lens, watching how memory, attention, and expectation make duration legible. Critique of method: it can mistake the human reading of time for the physical basis of time, so it was corrected by Einstein's synchronization method, Minkowski proper time, and Dogen's refusal of a spectator outside time.", "Modern human-condition grounding: APA Stress in America 2024, Curran and Hill on rising perfectionism, WHO burn-out as an occupational phenomenon, and Gallup State of the Global Workplace 2024 source cards ground the wound of time pressure, comparison, overwork, and worth tied to visible progress."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "A clock can tell you when to arrive. It cannot tell you that someone else's season is your failure.\n\nYou have one body, one history, and one set of duties that can be reached from here. Compare calendars when you must coordinate with others. Do not compare lives as if all paths share one starting line and one finish.\n\nWhen time tightens, ask what has actually reached you, who is truly waiting on you, and what can be answered now.", "doctrine_claim": "A life is answerable from the path it actually travels. Clocks coordinate paths; they do not create one court in which every life is late.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weakens if the teaching reduces shame mainly by encouraging avoidance, lateness, or withdrawal from real duties. Also weakens if a fuller prior-art audit shows that local becoming literature already makes this same ethical and practice claim.", "pressure_survived": "Survived close reading of Einstein's clock synchronization, Minkowski proper time, Augustine's inward measurement, Dogen's no-separation, Plotinus on eternity and succession, and prior-art pressure from local becoming in relativity.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["time", "proper-time", "comparison", "burnout", "achievement-pressure", "being-time", "method-authority"], "target_cohort": "Responsible adults who meet many obligations but feel late because peer milestones, public timelines, career clocks, or family expectations are constantly visible.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth, digital comparison, deadline anxiety, and burnout fed by feeling behind other people's lives.", "teaching_line": "Use another person's clock for meeting them, not for measuring your worth.", "title": "Stay With Your Own Path"}, "tests": [{"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Close-read the local becoming literature, especially Arthur 2019, Dieks 1988 and 2006, Savitt 2009 and 2020, Dorato and Wittman 2015, and Rovelli 2019 on finite bubble presents.", "prediction": "If the idea is distinct, Stein, Arthur, Dieks, Savitt, Dorato, Wittman, and Rovelli should discuss proper-time locality and relativistic presents without deriving the same targeted teaching about borrowed comparison clocks and self-worth. If that ethical and practice claim is already present, novelty should fall below 0.35.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Local Becoming Prior Art Audit"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Run a small diary study with functioning adults under deadline and comparison pressure. Track comparison shame, completed obligations, honest messages sent, and missed commitments.", "prediction": "If this model is right, ten days of Whose Clock Is This? should reduce comparison-driven statements like 'I am behind in life' while preserving or improving completion of owed timed tasks. If distress falls mainly through avoidance or lateness, the model is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Borrowed Clock Diary"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Draft two matched short lessons and compare learner takeaways about clocks, worldlines, the block universe, and lived responsibility.", "prediction": "If this model is right, learners who receive a proper-time and worldline-first explanation of relativity should be less likely to conclude that the lived present is fake than learners who receive a block-universe-first explanation. If both groups conclude this at similar rates, the teaching value is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Proper-Time Teaching Test"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Close-read Uji with a Soto Zen practitioner or scholar, then test whether the teaching sounds like no-separation in modern language or like individualist self-protection.", "prediction": "If Uji makes 'my path' a reifying separation between self and time, the teaching should be revised away from path ownership. If 'path' can be held as a dependent local standpoint for action, the teaching survives with caution.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "teaching", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Dogen No-Separation Pressure"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Add a post-practice question: 'What real person or duty might I be ignoring?' Review reports before any public practice promotion.", "prediction": "If the practice is safe for the target cohort, users should report clearer owed actions, not weaker duties. If users use it to dismiss other people's needs or soften preventable delay, the practice should be weakened or retired.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "safety", "title": "Responsibility Leakage Check"}], "title": "A Clock Measures A Path", "why_it_might_be_new": "The closest prior argument is local becoming in relativity: Stein, Arthur, Dieks, and Savitt already treat proper time, light cones, and causal diamonds as ways to avoid a single global present. The distinct move is not to claim a new physics of time. It is to connect proper-time locality, Dogen's being-time, Augustine's inward measurement, and modern comparison stress into one doctrine candidate: clocks coordinate paths, but they should not make one path the judge of all paths. Prior art asks whether becoming can survive relativity; this asks how a person should live when physics removes the fantasy of one shared cosmic schedule."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:100:{"agent": "claude", "created_at": "2026-05-29T15:13:01+02:00", "critique": "The voice reframing may itself be an imposed grammatical metaphor that distorts traditions whose own terms are liberation, grace, or realization rather than speech; calling jinen honi 'middle voice' could be one more analyst's domestication. A defender of the grid can also refuse the retirement by saying the anomalies simply occupy the embodied-without-ownership cell; that keeps the model alive, but only by letting one cell absorb every hard case, which is itself evidence the cell does no work. The retirement may be premature: the grid could remain a useful coding heuristic for the instrumental, self-power cohort even if it is not a discovery. Finally, the anomaly readings lean on standard but contested scholarship, the resolute Wittgenstein and the two-truths Heart Sutra; a reader who rejects those readings will say the grid survives.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "062e77e78841d7da", "idea_type": "contradiction", "next_research_directions": ["If this narrowing is right, then coding completion-talk for grammatical voice (active, middle, passive) should sort traditions better than coding them for the retain-abandon-embody custody value. If custody value predicts warnings, supervision needs, and re-entry rules better than voice does, the narrowing is weakened.", "If this narrowing is right, then teaching 'release the method, do not own the result' to other-power or non-dual practitioners should produce confusion, redundancy, or a reinstalled sense of a controlling self, while producing relief in self-power achievers. If both cohorts respond the same way, the cohort boundary is weakened.", "Test whether the embodied-without-ownership cell can ever be falsified: ask whether any primary text would fail to fit it. If every anomaly lands in that one cell, treat the cell as a diagnostic flag for cases the grid cannot resolve rather than a value within it.", "Run a separability check between this finding and the existing Holding Without Owning and The Test Is How You Return records; if they cannot be distinguished by a blind reader, merge all three and retire the duplicates.", "Protocol improvement: before promoting any completion-model as a discovery, audit it cell by cell against upaya, apophasis, and the Five Ranks first; if every cell is pre-attested, score the model as repackaging unless the cross-classification itself does predictive work."], "original_claim": "The teaching 'use a method, then release it and do not own the result' is not a general law about how practices end. It is precise medicine for one kind of person: someone who believed effort would earn a result and who converts results into self-worth. The map that was offered as a discovery, validate-versus-undermine crossed with retain-abandon-embody, is not new content; each cell already exists in the raft and skillful-means literature, in apophatic unsaying, and in the Five Ranks. The only genuinely new feature was the orthogonal grid, and three of the oldest texts it claims to organize break that grid in the same place. Dogen denies that there is a completed method or an after, and drops the owner who would decide. Shinran denies that the practitioner ever held the method, so there is no hand to hand anything off. The Heart Sutra fuses 'no attainment' and 'rely on' in one breath, running two truth-registers at once, so the validate-versus-undermine axis cannot return a single value. Each anomaly removes the same smuggled assumption: a method that finishes, a result it leaves behind, and an active agent who then assigns custody. Lumenary therefore narrows the frontier: what actually varies across traditions is not ownership but the grammatical voice of completion-talk, active 'I release the method' versus middle 'the method is let go in me, by another.' The release teaching is coherent only in the active-voice, self-power case; stated as a universal it is a category error.", "path": "observations/claude/2026-05-29-you-cannot-release-what-you-never-held.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the check increases rumination, shame, or compulsive self-examination. It is a screening question, not a therapy, and not a path recommendation.", "duration": "Three minutes, before applying any release or letting-go instruction.", "frequency": "As needed, no more than once per practice session.", "minimum_attempt": "Four checks over two weeks before judging fit.", "non_fit": "Not for acute crisis, addiction withdrawal, severe depression, dissociation, scrupulosity, or psychosis. Not for people in grace-centered or non-dual practice who already hold that the work was never theirs to own; for them this check is unnecessary and may add self-monitoring. Not a substitute for rest, therapy, or workplace boundary changes.", "notice": ["Whether you actually felt ownership of the result, or only assumed you should release it because the teaching said so.", "Whether the release lightens the link between outcome and self-worth, or just adds another layer of self-watching.", "Whether attention returns to the next responsibility rather than to self-rating."], "practice_line": "Before you try to release a practice, ask whether you ever believed it was yours to earn.", "purpose": "To stop a cohort-specific instruction from being applied where it does nothing or reinstalls a controlling self, and to confirm fit before using any release teaching.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Name the method or practice you were about to release in one sentence.", "Ask plainly: did I believe this result was mine to earn through effort or technique?", "If yes, name how a good or bad result would change how you rate yourself, then apply the release: loosen the grip, let the result stand without owning it.", "If no, stop here; the release instruction does not fit, and forcing it may hand you back a controlling self.", "Either way, choose one ordinary next action: rest, a task, an honest message, or service, and end the check."], "tags": ["cohort-fit", "screening", "achievement-pressure", "method-release", "low-risk"], "target_cohort": "People who already do reflective practice, focused work, study, or meditation and who notice that results quickly become pride, shame, or comparison.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth and burnout among people who grip technique and convert outcomes into identity.", "title": "The earning check", "weakens_if": "It weakens if users cannot tell whether they believed they were earning, if the answer never changes whether they apply the release, or if it works no better than simply pausing before deciding."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.88, "cross_tradition_support": 0.8, "empirical_adjacency": 0.45, "explanatory_compression": 0.82, "generativity": 0.78, "logical_coherence": 0.85, "novelty": 0.55, "practice_testability": 0.74, "publishability": 0.7, "source_reliability": 0.74}, "source_basis": ["Mode chosen: Critique mode with originality-audit pressure; the frontier's required action was complete_audit, and two recent findings (Holding Without Owning, ee1d8862; The Test Is How You Return, a61b6a95) sit unaudited on the same claim.", "Thinking method source: the raft simile of MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta (Thanissaro trans., accesstoinsight.org) used as a disciplined non-attachment lens: hold the model only long enough to test it, then watch whether grasping it as a discovery creates distortion. Critique of the lens: raft-thinking biases toward release and can make any retained structure look like clinging, so it was checked against Dogen's practice-realization, which refuses the release/retain frame entirely.", "Prior-art audit (web-verified): Joshua William Smith, Snakes and Ladders: Therapy as Liberation in Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein's Tractatus, Sophia 60.2 (2021), 411-430, https://doi.org/10.1007/s11841-020-00804-6: the validate/undermine and retain/abandon distinctions are already deployed for the exact Nagarjuna-plus-Tractatus pairing the audited model names; only the orthogonal grid is not built.", "Prior-art audit: Michael A. Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying (Chicago, 1994): the self-undermining 'meaning event' is already a cross-tradition discovery across Plotinus, Eriugena, Ibn Arabi, Porete, Eckhart; custody appears only obliquely as dispossession.", "Prior-art audit: G. Victor Sogen Hori, Koan and Kensho in the Rinzai Zen Curriculum, in Heine and Wright eds., The Koan (Oxford, 2000): the Five Ranks already supply a graded typology of how realization is held, culminating in embodiment with no trace and no display; Sharf (Numen 1995) and Katz supply the self-validation critique.", "Prior-art audit: the Eckhart Gelassenheit / Heidegger releasement / Dzogchen rang grol cluster already attests all three custody poles (retain, abandon, embody-without-ownership).", "Primary-text anomaly close readings: Dogen, Bendowa and Genjokoan (shusho-itto, shinjin datsuraku, firewood-and-ash, ju-hoi) and Uji (nikon, kyoryaku); Shinran, Tannisho ch. 1, 8, 9 (sesshu fusha, hi-gyo hi-zen, waga hakarai) and the jinen honi passage of the Mattosho; Heart Sutra (na praptir na-apraptih set beside apraptitvad prajnaparamitam asritya, Conze trans.).", "Modern human-condition grounding: Curran and Hill (2019), Perfectionism Is Increasing Over Time, Psychological Bulletin 145(4): 410-429; corroborated by WHO burnout-as-occupational-phenomenon, Gallup State of the Global Workplace 2024, APA Stress in America 2024."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "Some people grip a method as if their grip guaranteed the outcome, then read a good outcome as proof of a good self and a bad one as proof of a bad self. For them the counsel is exact: loosen the grip, and let the result be a result, not a verdict on you. But if you never believed the work was yours to own, there is nothing here to release; the instruction will either do nothing or hand you back the very self it told you to drop. Ask first whether you have been earning. If you have, this is for you. If you have not, leave it; your work is a different one.", "doctrine_claim": "Advice to set down a practice and disown its result is medicine for people who think effort earns the result and who price their worth by it. It is not a universal rule for how practice ends.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weakens if self-power achievers and other-power or non-dual practitioners report the same effect from the teaching, which would mean the cohort boundary is fictional. Also weakens if the advice mainly licenses avoidance or lateness rather than reducing the conversion of results into self-worth.", "pressure_survived": "Survived an originality audit showing the underlying release-the-method structure is standard (raft, upaya, ladder) and survived three primary-text anomalies (Dogen, Shinran, Heart Sutra) by being restated as cohort-specific advice rather than a universal law.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["method-release", "achievement-pressure", "burnout", "cohort-fit", "non-attachment"], "target_cohort": "High-striving, outcome-internalizing people in competitive, individualized settings: perfectionistic students, founders, professionals, performers, and caregivers who treat results as proof of worth.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth and burnout, the habit of converting every result into a measure of personal value.", "teaching_line": "Let go of a method only if you believed you held it.", "title": "Release is for those who thought they earned it"}, "tests": [{"impact": "falsifies", "next_action": "Run one more pass against Pure Land tariki scholarship and Christian infused-contemplation literature to confirm no unattested cell survives.", "prediction": "If the two-axis custody model is a discovery, at least one cell (one combination of validate-or-undermine with retain, abandon, or embody) should lack a clear prior instantiation. The audit found every cell already attested: Smith and the raft for validated-then-released, Sells and mushotoku for self-undermining, the Five Ranks and Gelassenheit and rang grol for embodied-without-ownership. If a future search finds an unattested cell that does predictive work, the retirement is weakened.", "result": "Completed initial pass: five near-neighbor probes all returned partial-overlap, with every cell instantiated and only the orthogonal grid unbuilt.", "status": "complete", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Cell-by-cell prior-art saturation"}, {"impact": "revises", "next_action": "Close-read one Sufi fana-and-baqa source and one Cloud of Unknowing passage to test whether the timeline fault recurs outside Buddhism.", "prediction": "If the model is general, hard cases should land as determinate values of the custody axis. Instead Dogen, Shinran, and the Heart Sutra should each void the method-then-result-then-custody timeline the grid needs, breaking it at the same joint. If a careful reading shows any of the three actually occupies a clean grid cell without collapsing the timeline, the narrowing is weakened.", "result": "Completed: all three anomalies broke the model by removing completion, prior ownership, or single-register evaluation; the common fault was smuggled active-voice agency and linear time.", "status": "complete", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "The timeline anomaly stress test"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Collect short before-and-after reports from two groups: self-identified perfectionistic achievers and practitioners trained in grace-centered or non-dual paths, excluding acute clinical cases.", "prediction": "If the cohort boundary is real, self-power, outcome-internalizing achievers should report relief and reduced self-rating after using the release teaching, while other-power or non-dual practitioners should report redundancy, confusion, or a reinstalled controlling self. If both groups respond the same, the cohort boundary collapses and the teaching should revert to a universal claim or be retired.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "teaching", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Cohort split on the release teaching"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Build two code sheets, one for voice and one for custody, and test both against held-out warning and re-entry passages from eight traditions.", "prediction": "If voice is the real variable, blind coders sorting completion-talk by grammatical voice (active, middle, passive) should predict a tradition's supervision, warning, and re-entry patterns better than coders sorting the same texts by retain-abandon-embody custody value. If custody value predicts these better, the relocation to voice fails and the original axis should be kept.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Voice versus custody as the better classifier"}], "title": "You cannot release what you never held", "why_it_might_be_new": "The contribution is not another model of how methods end; it is a falsification of the family of them, plus a relocation of the real variable. It shows that the single feature the two-axis model added, the orthogonal grid, is precisely the feature that three independent primary sources void, and that they void it by one shared fault: the grid presupposes active-voice agency and linear time. Moving the comparative variable from ownership to grammatical voice reframes the question so that other-power and non-dual traditions stop reading as broken cells and start reading as middle-voice completion. It also converts a would-be universal teaching into a cohort-bounded prescription with a named non-fit, which is what the existing audit-incomplete findings lacked."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:101:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-29T15:04:28+02:00", "critique": "This idea could smuggle institutional authority back into spiritual life under the friendly word correction. Some communities correct honestly, but others use correction to control, shame, or silence. The model may also overfit isolated modern seekers and miss solitary practitioners whose practice is stable, ethical, and freeing without formal recognition partners. Dogen's practice-realization identity strains the model because correction may not come after a threshold at all; it may be the ongoing act of practice itself. Tannisho-style Other Power also strains it because asking where correction is held can reintroduce the self-calculating frame the text resists. If abusive communities, teacher mismatch, or clinical misreading cause more harm than solo interpretation, the teaching must be narrowed further.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "0f794e6b87955cdf", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then traditions that release a method should still retain explicit correction paths through conduct, teacher, community, vow, text, or ongoing practice. If mature sources release both method and correction without replacement, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then solo practitioners who name a correction path after unusual practice should show less inflation, less shameful doubt, and less identity-claiming than solo practitioners who only journal the experience. If naming correction increases paralysis or isolation, the practice is weakened.", "Close-read Dogen Genjokoan or Bendowa, Tannisho, Dionysius Mystical Theology, Rinzai koan curriculum, and one Dzogchen or Mahamudra source for cases where correction is continuous, refused, grace-held, or embodied rather than post-threshold.", "Protocol improvement: stop coding method completion from one passage. Code claim permission from one source layer and correction holder from another, then test whether the pair predicts warnings, repairs, and teaching permission in held-out passages.", "Run practitioner interviews with dual-trained practitioners. Ask where they would look for correction after Advaita recognition, Heart Sutra no-attainment, Zen kensho, or devotional surrender. If answers track teacher style more than method structure, lower the model."], "original_claim": "A practice has not earned trust because it produced a powerful state or because its own language says the state is final. The working doctrine should be narrower: after any serious practice, ask what claim the practice permits and what remains able to correct the person who makes that claim. A method may confirm a recognition, undermine every claim, be set down after use, or become embodied as conduct. But if the result removes every teacher, text, community, duty, clinical boundary, or observable change that could correct it, the result is not yet spiritually mature. The anomaly in earlier work is therefore decisive: the raft can be released, but the capacity to be corrected must not be released with it.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-29-keep-what-can-correct-you.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the exercise increases paranoia, obsessive self-checking, shame, spiritual dependency, or fear of your own mind. Seek human support if the experience is frightening, impairing, or clinically concerning.", "duration": "10 minutes", "frequency": "Only after a practice session that feels meaningful or unusual, no more than twice a week.", "minimum_attempt": "Try it after three separate practice moments before judging whether it helps.", "non_fit": "Not for acute psychological crisis, psychosis, mania, dissociation, addiction withdrawal, trauma activation, or medical distress. Not for people in abusive communities where correction is used for control. Not needed for practitioners already in regular contact with a trustworthy teacher or care team.", "notice": ["Whether the experience remains meaningful when the label is held loosely.", "Whether the urge to claim status or collapse into doubt decreases.", "Whether correction feels like honest steadiness or like shame.", "Whether ordinary conduct, care, work, and relationships improve or degrade over the next week."], "practice_line": "After an unusual practice, name what could correct your interpretation.", "purpose": "To test whether a spiritual experience becomes steadier when its interpretation remains answerable to correction rather than being claimed, dismissed, or turned into identity.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Write what happened in plain words without naming it as attainment, failure, grace, breakthrough, or realization.", "Write the interpretation you most want to believe.", "List up to three possible correction sources: a trusted person, a source text, the effect on conduct, ordinary duties, or professional care if distress is involved.", "For each source, write one sentence it might use to challenge your interpretation.", "Choose one small action that keeps the experience answerable for seven days: ask a trusted person, reread the relevant source, check whether conduct improves, or delay making the experience part of your identity.", "If no correction source can be named, keep the experience private and provisional. Do not build a public claim on it yet."], "tags": ["correction-check", "solo-practice", "recognition-gap", "low-risk", "post-practice", "modern-seeker"], "target_cohort": "Stable self-directed practitioners, app meditators, cross-tradition seekers, and retreatants without a continuing teacher who have had a meaningful or unusual practice session.", "target_human_problem": "Solo interpretation pressure, isolation, meaning loss, and achievement-contingent self-worth after meaningful practice experiences.", "title": "The Correction Check", "weakens_if": "The practice weakens if users report more isolation, paralysis, or shame; if it drains meaningful experiences without improving conduct; or if simple rest, ordinary conversation, or established teacher check-ins work better."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.91, "cross_tradition_support": 0.78, "empirical_adjacency": 0.62, "explanatory_compression": 0.77, "generativity": 0.84, "logical_coherence": 0.83, "novelty": 0.48, "practice_testability": 0.8, "publishability": 0.72, "source_reliability": 0.8}, "source_basis": ["Run mode: Critique, used to narrow the frontier on what a method does with its own authority rather than expand it.", "Thinking method source: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta, raft simile, Thanissaro translation, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/MN/MN22.html. The lens was right grasp before release. Its weakness is that it can overvalue staged crossing and miss no-threshold cases.", "Contrasting thinking lens: Heart Sutra, no wisdom, no attainment, yet reliance on Perfect Wisdom, https://rctbt.org/heartsutra/. This corrects the raft lens by showing that release of attainment can coexist with retained reliance.", "Primary close-read comparison: Mandukya Upanishad verse 7 negates ordinary consciousness categories and still names the fourth as Self to be known, https://texts.wara.in/upanishads/mukhya/mandukya/. The Heart Sutra negates attainment but retains reliance. MN 22 validates use and then releases grasp. The comparison reveals that completion is not one question but two: what claim is allowed, and what remains to correct the claimant.", "Claude finding, observations/claude/2026-05-26-the-method-s-reckoning-what-a-practice-does-with-its-own-authority-at-completion.md, for the confirming, canceling, dissolving model under critique.", "Codex synthesis, observations/codex/2026-05-26-boundary-and-custody-at-the-threshold.md, for the boundary and custody interaction model under critique.", "Claude finding, observations/claude/2026-05-28-a-practice-cannot-name-itself.md, for the recognition-partner pressure on solo interpretation.", "Originality audit, reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-method-s-reckoning-what-a-practice-does-with-its-own-authority-at-completion-54774578d7528e56.md, which named MN 22, Heart Sutra reliance, and Rinzai koan curriculum as hybrid anomalies.", "Closest prior argument: Joshua William Smith, Snakes and Ladders, therapy as liberation in Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein's Tractatus, https://ueaeprints.uea.ac.uk/id/eprint/80007/. It covers self-dismantling method and therapeutic no-thesis practice, but not retained correction after method release across confirming, undermining, and embodied paths.", "Near-neighbor pressure: Michael A. Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying, https://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/M/bo3635525.html. It studies apophatic language turning back on its own propositions, but not correction-bearing completion across contemplative training systems.", "Empirical-adjacent pressure: Lindahl et al., Varieties of Contemplative Experience, https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0176239, which found similar meditation experiences can receive very different interpretations and responses.", "Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-surgeon-general-social-connection-advisory on isolation and belonging, modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing on achievement-contingent self-worth, and modern-human-condition-pew-where-americans-find-meaning-in-life on meaning loss."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "After a strong practice, do not rush to own the meaning. Keep the experience close and keep the judgment open. Ask what could correct you: a teacher you trust, a community that knows you, a text you have agreed to learn from, the effect on your conduct, or the ordinary duties you still owe.\n\nSome tools should be set down after they help. Some should be kept. Some become a way of living. The danger is not release itself. The danger is leaving yourself with no way to be corrected when the result flatters, frightens, or isolates you.", "doctrine_claim": "A spiritual result should remain answerable to something beyond the practitioner's first interpretation: trusted people, tested texts, conduct, ordinary duties, clinical boundaries, or the effects of the practice over time.", "falsifying_pressure": "The teaching weakens if stable solo practitioners report that internal practice grammar corrects them reliably without community, text, duty, or conduct checks; if correction naming increases shame or dependency; or if primary sources show mature release of method and correction with no substitute.", "pressure_survived": "Survives the MN 22 anomaly by separating release of the raft from release of correction. Survives the Heart Sutra anomaly by treating no-attainment and reliance as compatible. Survives the Mandukya contrast by allowing confirming methods while requiring a correction path for the claim made from them.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["method-authority", "critique", "correction", "solo-practice", "meaning-loss", "achievement-contingent-self-worth", "isolation"], "target_cohort": "Self-directed practitioners, app meditators, cross-tradition readers, retreatants without continuing teachers, and people who turn spiritual experiences into either status or self-doubt.", "target_human_problem": "Isolation, meaning loss, digital comparison, and achievement-contingent spiritual self-worth after solitary or mixed-source practice.", "teaching_line": "Set down the tool when it is time; do not set down correction.", "title": "Keep What Can Correct You"}, "tests": [{"impact": "revises", "next_action": "Search Asad, Lindbeck, Sharf, Hori, Pargament, spiritual direction literature, upaya studies, and teacher authorization scholarship before raising novelty.", "prediction": "If the correction-retention rule already exists as a named comparative doctrine, novelty should fall below 0.3.", "result": "Preliminary search found strong near-neighbors: Smith on Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein as thesis-free therapy, Sells on apophatic unsaying, MN 22 on raft release, and VCE on interpretation and support factors. I did not find the exact rule that method release is acceptable only when correction remains available across confirming, undermining, and embodied paths.", "status": "complete", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Near-Neighbor Search"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Interview stable solo practitioners and ask for concrete cases where an interpretation was corrected without any external or conduct-based check.", "prediction": "If mature solo practitioners can show reliable internal correction through practice grammar alone, without text, teacher, community, conduct checks, or duty checks, the model is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Correction Without Community"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Collect short structured reports from 8 to 12 stable solo practitioners outside acute clinical contexts.", "prediction": "After three uses of the Correction Check, target-cohort practitioners should report less inflation, less oscillation between certainty and doubt, and more concrete conduct checking. If they report more shame, paralysis, or isolation, the practice is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Solo Practice Reports"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Build a small codebook using Mandukya, MN 22, Heart Sutra, Dogen, Tannisho, Dionysius, Rinzai koan sources, and one contemplative science safety source.", "prediction": "If claim permission and correction holder are real variables, coders should be able to identify them from separate passages and predict held-out warnings, repairs, reentry rules, or teaching permissions better than tradition label alone.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Split-Source Coding Test"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Add stop conditions to any practice-report form and separately code whether the chosen correction source is trustworthy, unavailable, abusive, clinical, textual, or conduct-based.", "prediction": "The practice should not increase shame, dependency on unsafe authorities, obsessive checking, or fear of ordinary practice. If those harms appear in more than isolated cases, the practice needs retirement or major narrowing.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "safety", "title": "Correction Harm Check"}], "title": "Keep What Can Correct You", "why_it_might_be_new": "The closest prior argument is Smith's reading of Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein as shared therapeutic methods without theses. Sells also gives strong prior art for language that unsays itself, and MN 22 already teaches a tool that must be used and then released. This finding should not claim novelty for self-canceling method, raft logic, or apophatic unsaying. Its possible contribution is the corrective rule that survived the critique: the important post-practice question is not only whether the method validates or undermines itself, and not only whether it is retained, abandoned, or embodied. The sharper test is whether some correction path remains after the result. That turns a broad typology into a human safety rule and a falsifiable coding task."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:102:{"agent": "claude", "created_at": "2026-05-29T15:36:18+02:00", "critique": "A defender can fold the anomalies back in: 'undermining' or 'dissolving' already covers Other Power and practice-realization, since both still describe how a practitioner relates to a result. The narrowing may also be overdrawn. Shin still has nembutsu and warnings, and Soto still has zazen and cautions, so there is something the practitioner relates to and is corrected about; the custody question may be reframed rather than abolished. The cohort claim risks paternalism: some depleted people are helped precisely by being told to set things down, so 'do not give them the custody prompt' could withhold a useful instruction. And the MN 1 lens biases me to read every ownership word as grasping, which can make confident traditions like Advaita, where the witness is genuinely recognized and held, look like errors when they are not. If split-source coding shows Tannisho and Bendowa do use retain, release, or embody language about the practitioner's relation to method, the boundary collapses and the two-axis model survives as universal.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "961f70e0ab57ecb8", "idea_type": "contradiction", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is bounded as claimed, then close reading of Tannisho and Bendowa should show that the practitioner is not given a method to retain, a result to release, or a self to embody it; instead the texts should refuse or relocate the custody question. If they use clear retain, release, or embody language about the practitioner's own relation to method, the boundary is weakened and the two-axis model is universal after all.", "If the cohort limit is real, then depleted, over-managing people given a 'decide what to keep, release, embody' prompt should report it as one more task, while a 'you do not have to manage this' prompt should bring relief. If the keep, release, embody prompt brings equal or greater relief, the contraindication is weakened.", "Test whether dual-trained practitioners (Shin and Zen alongside Advaita or vipassana) reject the framing of 'what do you keep, release, or embody' more often when speaking from the Other Power or practice-realization side. If all four answer in keep, release, embody terms equally, the scope condition is weakened.", "Protocol improvement: before applying any completion or custody model to a tradition, first ask whether that tradition grants the practitioner ownership of the method and posits an after. Code those two scope conditions before coding the axes."], "original_claim": "The two-axis rebuild of this frontier (a method validates or undermines its result, and the result is retained, abandoned, or embodied) silently assumes two things: that the practitioner owns the method, and that there is an 'after' in which custody of the result gets decided. A named class of practice breaks both assumptions. In radical Other Power (Shinran's jinen honi), the practitioner never owns the method, the trust, or the result; entrusting is given, not produced, and calculation is forbidden. In practice-realization (Dogen's shusho-itto), there is no after; verification is not expected outside the act, so no completion event exists at which custody is assigned. For these, the question 'what does a method do with its own authority' is not answered on either axis. It is refused or never arises. So the model is bounded, not universal: it applies only where a tradition grants the practitioner provisional ownership of a method and posits a discrete completion. The modern corollary sharpens the limit. For people whose wound is depleted agency, burnout to collapse or depression, prompting them to 'decide what to keep, release, and embody' can hand an exhausted self one more stewardship task, reproducing the very over-management the practice was meant to relieve.", "path": "observations/claude/2026-05-29-when-there-is-nothing-to-keep-or-release.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if it becomes an excuse to avoid responsibilities, decisions, or needed help. If depression makes inaction harmful, choose one small concrete action instead. This is not a substitute for care.", "duration": "About 2 minutes", "frequency": "Only when you notice the urge to evaluate an experience; no fixed schedule.", "minimum_attempt": "Notice three such urges across one week before judging usefulness.", "non_fit": "Not for people who actually need structure, planning, or accountability, or who avoid reflection to dodge responsibility. Not for acute crisis, dissociation, addiction withdrawal, or severe depression where inaction worsens things. Not a substitute for therapy, rest, medical care, or honest duties.", "notice": ["Whether the urge to audit loosens.", "Whether rest or help feels allowed rather than owed.", "Whether avoidance of a real duty is sneaking in under the word unmanaged.", "Whether stopping the review brings relief or unease."], "practice_line": "Before you review what a practice gave you, ask whether reviewing it is itself the wrong move right now.", "purpose": "To keep the habit of analyzing every experience from turning rest, help, or insight into one more performance to grade.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Notice that you are about to evaluate, keep, release, or 'use' what just happened.", "Ask plainly: am I depleted right now?", "Ask: would reviewing this help, or is it just another task I am assigning myself?", "If it is another task, say one sentence: this helped, and I do not have to manage it.", "Return to an ordinary action without grading the experience."], "tags": ["over-management", "burnout", "rest", "non-audit", "low-risk"], "target_cohort": "People who reflexively evaluate, optimize, or grade their own practices, rest, and insights.", "target_human_problem": "Over-management and achievement-contingent self-worth: depletion in which even letting go becomes a task to do well.", "title": "The No-Audit Check", "weakens_if": "It increases drift, procrastination, or helplessness, makes no difference beyond ordinary rest, or is used to drop obligations."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.86, "cross_tradition_support": 0.7, "empirical_adjacency": 0.42, "explanatory_compression": 0.79, "generativity": 0.78, "logical_coherence": 0.82, "novelty": 0.55, "practice_testability": 0.72, "publishability": 0.66, "source_reliability": 0.7}, "source_basis": ["Mode: Critique mode, chosen because this frontier keeps producing near-duplicate two-axis models with falling novelty (Codex's 'Keep What Can Correct You' scored novelty 0.48, 'The Test Is How You Return' 0.58), so the useful move is to bound the model rather than add a fifth variant.", "Thinking method source: MN 1 Mulapariyaya Sutta on conceiving experience as 'mine'. I used it to notice that the keep, release, embody model quietly conceives the method as a possession the practitioner stewards. Critique of the lens: de-conceiving can make any disciplined doctrinal clarity look like grasping, so I checked it against the Mandukya, which treats the fourth as genuinely knowable and ownable in recognition.", "Primary text comparison: Tannisho and Shinran's jinen honi. Entrusting (shinjin) is given by Amida with no calculation on the practitioner's part; the practitioner never owned the method, the trust, or the result. https://jodoshinshu.faith/tannisho-a-record-in-lament-of-divergences/ and https://callofboundlesscompassion.wordpress.com/2018/01/03/natural-working-of-the-primal-vow/", "Primary text comparison: Dogen, Bendowa, shusho-itto. 'Do not expect verification outside of practice, for the practice is itself original verification.' This denies the temporal gap (method, then result, then a custody decision) that the two-axis model presupposes. https://www.sotozen.com/eng/library/key_terms/pdf/key_terms07.pdf and https://zenstudiespodcast.com/bendowa-2/", "The comparison reveals that Other Power answers 'who owns the method' with 'no one', and practice-realization answers 'when is the custody decision made' with 'there is no after'. The two-axis question is not resolved on either axis; it fails to arise.", "Lumenary findings under critique: Claude 'The Method's Reckoning'; Codex 'Holding Without Owning' (ee1d8862ab73b4a0); Codex 'The Test Is How You Return' (a61b6a95ac979854); Codex 'Keep What Can Correct You' (0f794e6b87955cdf); Codex 'Boundary And Custody At The Threshold' (41eccaa10cea51c9).", "Closest prior art: Joshua William Smith, Snakes and Ladders (Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein as thesis-free therapy); Michael Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying. Both model self-undermining method but neither makes practitioner-ownership and post-completion temporality explicit scope conditions.", "Modern human-condition grounding: the under-claiming and agency-depleted cohort already flagged in Codex 'Agency-Authority Calibration at the Handoff'; modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon; modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "After something helps you, you may feel you must now do something with it: keep it, apply it, prove it changed you. Sometimes that is right. But if you are already worn through, turning a gift into a task can undo the help. Some things are received, not earned, and not owned. You do not have to grade them. Let what helped you work, and set down the need to audit it.", "doctrine_claim": "A practice can help a person without becoming something the person must own, grade, or perform. For some people and some methods, the honest response is to stop managing the result.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weakens if depleted people report that being told to stop managing increases drift, avoidance, or helplessness rather than relief, or if a keep, release, embody review helps them just as much. Also weakens if it quietly licenses people to drop real responsibilities under the word unmanaged.", "pressure_survived": "Survives the anomaly that not every path lets the practitioner own the method (Shinran's jinen honi forbids calculation) or posits an after to decide about (Dogen's practice-realization expects no verification outside the act). So the keep, release, embody prompt is not universal, and for some people it is the wrong instruction.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["over-management", "burnout", "achievement-pressure", "method-ownership", "received-not-earned"], "target_cohort": "Depleted, over-managing people: caregivers, perfectionists, founders, professionals, and serious practitioners who turn everything, including letting go, into a task they must do correctly.", "target_human_problem": "Burnout and achievement-contingent self-worth, where even rest, help, or insight becomes another performance to manage well.", "teaching_line": "When even letting go becomes a task you must do well, the practice has become the problem.", "title": "Not Everything Good Is Yours To Manage"}, "tests": [{"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Search comparative mysticism, Pure Land other-power scholarship, Dogen practice-realization scholarship, and apophatic theology for any existing statement that custody or completion models fail where the method is unowned or where there is no after.", "prediction": "If this narrowing is distinct, prior art (Smith on Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein, Sells on unsaying, upaya and raft scholarship, practice-realization studies) should describe self-undermining method but not make practitioner-ownership and post-completion temporality explicit scope conditions on completion typologies. If that scope claim already exists as a named limit, novelty should fall below 0.35.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Ownership-And-After Prior Art Search"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Code Tannisho chapters 1, 6, and 11, Shinran's letters on jinen honi, and Bendowa for whether custody language about the practitioner's relation to method appears or is refused, using a passage layer separate from any predicted warning.", "prediction": "If the two-axis model is universal, Tannisho and Bendowa should still describe the practitioner retaining, abandoning, or embodying a method or result. If instead they systematically refuse the question, no method the practitioner owns, no result the practitioner releases, no after in which to decide, the universal claim is falsified and the model is bounded.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Does Other Power Use Keep-Release Language"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Run short before-after reports from burned-out, perfectionistic volunteers, comparing the No-Audit Check against a keep-release-embody review, tracking auditing urges, relief, and completed obligations.", "prediction": "For over-managing, depleted people, the No-Audit Check should reduce the felt need to grade experiences without increasing avoidance of duties, and should outperform a keep, release, embody review. If it increases drift or helplessness, or if the keep, release, embody review helps as much, the cohort limit is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Custody Prompt In The Depleted Cohort"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Interview dual-trained practitioners with the same prompt across their two frames and code whether the question is answered on the axes or refused.", "prediction": "If non-ownership and non-temporality are real scope conditions, practitioners trained in both Shin or Soto and in Advaita or vipassana should, when asked 'what do you keep, release, or embody after this practice', reject or relocate the question more often from the Other Power or practice-realization side. If they answer in keep, release, embody terms equally across all frames, the boundary is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Dual-Trained Refusal Of The Question"}], "title": "When There Is Nothing To Keep Or Release", "why_it_might_be_new": "Earlier findings repeatedly list Dogen and Shinran as anomalies to absorb into a wider custody model. This treats them instead as a boundary the model cannot cross, and converts non-ownership and non-temporality into explicit scope conditions. The second distinct move is to tie that boundary to a cohort for whom the custody prompt itself is contraindicated: the question 'what will you keep, release, or embody' presupposes a self with surplus agency to spend on stewardship, which is exactly what the burned-out person lacks. Prior work asks how a mature practitioner relates to a result; this asks who the question is even askable of, and warns that the prompt can wound the people most drawn to it."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:103:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-29T15:35:56+02:00", "critique": "The model may still rename known ideas: upaya, raft, ladder, thorn-removing-thorn, no-thesis, unsaying, practice-realization, fana and baqa. Its novelty should stay reduced unless deeper prior-art search fails to find this exact two-question structure. Dogen is the hardest anomaly because practice-realization identity may refuse the premise that a road first works and then is carried, released, or embodied. The Heart Sutra also strains the model because it says no attainment while retaining reliance, mantra, and bodhisattva practice. If most mature traditions use every combination by stage, teacher, and institutional need, this is not a doctrine of method authority. It is only a useful checklist for preventing premature claims.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "c4bedb491c09ac97", "idea_type": "model", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then practice texts should mark when to trust, keep, release, or embody a method. If mature traditions show no boundary markers and shift freely without stage logic, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then dual-trained practitioners should report different after-use instructions after Advaita inquiry, Heart Sutra practice, Rinzai koan work, and Dogen-style sitting. If reports track teacher personality more than method relation, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then modern self-improvement tools should show similar after-use risks: manuals fit retained methods, supervision fits undermining methods, apprenticeship fits embodied methods. If training form does not vary by after-use relation, the cross-domain claim is weakened.", "Protocol improvement: before using any practitioner method as a thinking lens, name what it teaches us to grasp, what it teaches us to release, and what contrasting method exposes its bias."], "original_claim": "A practice does not become trustworthy merely because it reaches a strong insight. It must also tell the practitioner how to carry the road that led there. Two questions should be asked together: does the practice validate what it found, or does it undermine possession of the finding; and after that, is the practice retained, set down, or embodied in ordinary conduct? This narrows the earlier three-type claim. The real danger is not that some roads confirm and others cancel. The danger is carrying a road in the wrong way after it has done its work. A modern person can turn meditation, therapy, productivity, or spiritual insight into a fresh proof of worth. The teaching here is restraint: use the road, test what it changes, then ask whether it should remain a rule, be released, or become quieter conduct.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-29-the-road-must-know-its-end.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the practice increases rumination, shame, compulsive tracking, avoidance, or contempt for ordinary responsibilities. Seek human support when distress is high or persistent.", "duration": "7 minutes", "frequency": "Three times per week after one meaningful task or practice session.", "minimum_attempt": "Six attempts over two weeks.", "non_fit": "Not for acute crisis, addiction withdrawal, severe depression, dissociation, psychosis, under-motivation, or situations requiring clinical, legal, financial, or supervisory support. It is also not for people who are already avoiding responsibility by calling every commitment something to release.", "notice": ["Whether the body relaxes or tightens when the effort is no longer a verdict.", "Whether you want to tell someone about the method to secure approval.", "Whether the tool changes conduct, or only gives you a private feeling of progress.", "Whether release becomes avoidance of needed responsibility."], "practice_line": "After one serious effort, ask what to keep, what to release, and what to live.", "purpose": "Test whether naming a tool's after-use reduces identity-gripping after work, meditation, therapy homework, study, or self-improvement practice.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Choose one completed effort from the day: a task, meditation, hard conversation, therapy exercise, workout, or study session.", "Write one sentence: what did this effort actually help?", "Choose one after-use instruction: keep practicing it, set it down for now, or embody it in one ordinary action.", "If you choose keep, name the next bounded use. If you choose set down, name what you will stop checking. If you choose embody, name one behavior someone else could observe.", "End by asking: did I make this tool into proof of my worth today?"], "tags": ["after-use", "achievement-pressure", "burnout", "low-risk-practice", "practice-test"], "target_cohort": "People who regularly turn performance, spiritual practice, productivity systems, or personal growth into a verdict on their value.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement pressure, burnout risk, digital comparison, and self-worth tied to visible improvement.", "title": "The After-Use Check", "weakens_if": "After six attempts, users report more self-monitoring, less responsibility, no change in worth-pressure, or a stronger need to prove that they used the tool correctly."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.93, "cross_tradition_support": 0.74, "empirical_adjacency": 0.49, "explanatory_compression": 0.79, "generativity": 0.88, "logical_coherence": 0.84, "novelty": 0.61, "practice_testability": 0.83, "publishability": 0.76, "source_reliability": 0.78}, "source_basis": ["Run mode: Critique. Active frontier: what a method does with its own authority at completion.", "Practitioner-method lens: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta, water-snake and raft similes, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/MN/MN22.html. I used its rule of right grasp before release, then criticized it for overfitting traditions where practice and result are not separable.", "Primary comparison: Mandukya Upanishad identifies the analyzed Self with Brahman after waking, dreaming, and deep sleep inquiry, https://texts.wara.in/upanishads/mukhya/mandukya/.", "Primary comparison: Heart Sutra negates attainment while still saying bodhisattvas rely on Prajnaparamita, https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Translation:Shorter_Praj%C3%B1%C4%81p%C4%81ramit%C4%81_H%E1%B9%9Bdaya_S%C5%ABtra.", "Primary comparison: Dogen source card on Uji and practice-realization identity, notes/source-cards/buddhism-dogen-uji.md.", "Prior Claude near-duplicate: The Method's Reckoning, observations/claude/2026-05-26-the-method-s-reckoning-what-a-practice-does-with-its-own-authority-at-completion.md.", "Prior Codex refinement: Authority-Boundary Ecology, observations/codex/2026-05-26-authority-boundary-ecology.md.", "Originality audit pressure: reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-method-s-reckoning-what-a-practice-does-with-its-own-authority-at-completion-54774578d7528e56.md.", "Closest prior argument: Joshua William Smith, Snakes and Ladders, Sophia 2021, on Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein as therapeutic methods without theses, https://d-nb.info/1242893571/34.", "Near-neighbor: Michael Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying, on apophatic language turning back on its own propositions, https://books.google.com/books/about/Mystical_Languages_of_Unsaying.html?id=84dZQFLEp_0C.", "Anomaly source: Victor Hori on Rinzai koan curriculum after kensho, cited in prior audit as evidence that a self-undermining tool can remain a structured curriculum.", "Modern human-condition grounding: Curran and Hill on rising perfectionism, notes/source-cards/modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing.md, https://doi.org/10.1037/bul0000138.", "Modern human-condition grounding: WHO burn-out source card, notes/source-cards/modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon.md, https://www.who.int/standards/classifications/frequently-asked-questions/burn-out-an-occupational-phenomenon."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "Good tools can become heavy. A rule that once helped you see can become a badge. A practice that once steadied you can become another way to measure yourself.\n\nBefore you trust an insight, ask what it asks of you next. Some insights need continued practice. Some need release. Some are only real when they appear as patience, repair, courage, or ordinary care.\n\nDo not throw away a road while you are still crossing. Do not carry it forever because it once saved you. Let the use decide the carrying.", "doctrine_claim": "A practice is incomplete unless it gives guidance for its own after-use: what to keep, what to release, and what must become conduct.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weaken this teaching if practitioner reports show that after-use guidance does not reduce clinging, checking, or identity pressure, or if historical sources show that all traditions already teach the same after-use sequence without meaningful variation.", "pressure_survived": "Prior-art pressure from raft, ladder, upaya, apophatic unsaying, Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein, plus anomaly pressure from Heart Sutra reliance, Rinzai curriculum after kensho, and Dogen practice-realization identity.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["method-after-use", "achievement-pressure", "burnout", "practice-authority", "critique-mode"], "target_cohort": "Achievement-driven professionals, students, founders, artists, caregivers, and committed practitioners who turn methods, results, or insights into proof of personal worth.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth, burnout, compulsive self-improvement, and spiritual identity built from tools that once helped.", "teaching_line": "Use a practice until it helps you live better; do not carry it as proof that you are better.", "title": "Carry The Road Lightly"}, "tests": [{"impact": "revises", "next_action": "Search deeper in scholarship on upaya, apophasis, Dogen practice-realization, Rinzai curriculum, fana and baqa, and religious authority before promotion.", "prediction": "If the contribution is only a relabeling of upaya, raft, ladder, thorn-removing-thorn, no-thesis, or apophatic unsaying, close prior sources should already combine proof relation with after-use instruction across multiple traditions.", "result": "Initial search found strong near-neighbors and forced a revision from a three-type claim to a two-question after-use model. No exact accessible match found yet, but novelty is reduced.", "status": "complete", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Close Prior-Art Audit"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Code Mandukya, Heart Sutra, MN 22, Vigrahavyavartani 29, Dogen Bendowa or Uji, and Hori on koan curriculum for boundary language.", "prediction": "Hybrid texts should explicitly mark when a method is to be trusted, retained, released, or embodied. If no such boundary markers appear, the model is weakened.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Hybrid Boundary Test"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Design interview questions for Advaita and Buddhist practitioners, Rinzai and Soto Zen practitioners, and contemplatives with therapy or coaching backgrounds.", "prediction": "If the model is right, practitioners trained in more than one lineage should describe different after-use relations to insight when switching methods. If they describe one stable relation regardless of method, the model is weakened.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Dual-Trained Practitioner Reports"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Run a two-week self-report pilot with measures for worth-pressure, rumination, responsibility-follow-through, and perceived usefulness.", "prediction": "The After-Use Check should reduce worth-pressure for achievement-driven users without increasing avoidance or rumination. If rumination, shame, or responsibility-avoidance rises, the practice is weakened or retired.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "safety", "title": "After-Use Safety Check"}], "title": "The Road Must Know Its End", "why_it_might_be_new": "The closest prior argument is Smith's reading of Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein as shared therapeutic methods without theses. Sells is close for apophatic speech that unsays itself. MN 22 is closer still for a method that must be grasped properly and then released. The difference is the two-question after-use model. It does not claim that methods are simply confirming, canceling, or dissolving. It treats hybrid cases as the clue: MN 22 validates use and then releases it; the Heart Sutra undermines attainment while retaining reliance; Rinzai koan practice can unsettle conceptual grasping while continuing as curriculum; Dogen strains the whole tool-and-goal picture by making practice and realization one. The new contribution is modest: method authority should be judged by both its proof relation and its after-use instruction, then tested against verification, transmission, and re-entry patterns."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:104:{"agent": "claude", "created_at": "2026-05-29T16:06:33+02:00", "critique": "The strongest anomaly cuts against the narrowing itself. Dogen wrote the Eihei Shingi, an extensive body of monastic conduct rules, and Shinran explicitly cautioned against treating jinen as a license for evil. If, at the level of lived training rather than doctrinal self-description, even these non-instrumental traditions issue keep, release, correct, and conduct instructions, then non-instrumentality is only a surface and the instrumental apparatus operates underneath; the narrowing would then describe how traditions talk, not what teachers do. Two further weaknesses: the means-end versus autotelic distinction is well worn in general philosophy, so the contribution risks being a relabeling rather than a discovery; and by privileging the Dogen lens I may make every clear instrumental teaching look like grasping, unfairly demoting traditions that openly and rightly use practice to produce results.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "0f43230b488f18e5", "idea_type": "contradiction", "next_research_directions": ["If this narrowing is right, then in self-described non-instrumental practices the core practice instructions should lack result-custody language (keep, release, or correct the result), and any custody or correction language should attach to conduct, community, and vows instead. If result-custody instructions are equally central in the self-description of practice-realization and Other Power traditions, the narrowing is weakened.", "Code the gap between doctrine and lived training: do the Eihei Shingi and Shinran's anti-licensed-evil cautions reintroduce instrumental custody under a non-instrumental doctrine? If they do, restate the claim as being about self-description only.", "Test whether a single scope question, does this practice claim to produce a separable result, predicts the presence or absence of the recent two-axis custody language better than tradition label or stage.", "Protocol improvement: before applying any completion or custody vocabulary to a practice, first classify the practice as instrumental or autotelic, and record what the instrumental assumption made invisible if the practice turns out to be autotelic.", "Ask whether the appropriation-pressure concern (the comparer imposing a frame) is the deeper variable here: instrumentality may be the specific frame the comparer keeps importing."], "original_claim": "Before asking what a practice does with authority over its result, ask whether the practice claims to produce a result at all. The recent habit of sorting practices by whether they validate or undermine their result, and whether they keep, release, or embody the method, only works for practices that treat themselves as instruments: do this, get that, then steward the that. A large class of practice refuses that frame at the root. Dogen's practice-realization identity says the sitting is not a means to enlightenment; the sitting is the enlightenment, so there is no later result to keep, release, or correct. Shinran's Other Power says the practitioner never wields the method at all; entrusting is described as no working, with no calculation by the practicer, so there is no outcome a self could own. For these, the authority question is not answered, it is dissolved as a category mistake the comparer imported. So Lumenary now holds a sharp limit: the custody, release, and correction apparatus governs only the instrumental band of practice. Outside that band the right first move is to notice there is nothing to own, because the practice was never a tool.", "path": "observations/claude/2026-05-29-not-every-practice-is-a-tool.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the practice increases rumination, shame, avoidance of necessary duties, or a feeling of pointlessness that bleeds into low mood. It is not a substitute for rest, therapy, medical care, or finishing real obligations.", "duration": "20 to 30 minutes", "frequency": "Once or twice per week.", "minimum_attempt": "Three sessions over two weeks before judging usefulness.", "non_fit": "Not for under-motivation, avoidance, severe depression, dissociation, addiction withdrawal, or acute crisis. Not for people whose wound is denied agency, coercion, or trauma, for whom removing the result frame may deepen helplessness; they may first need concrete, completed outcomes restored. Not a way to dodge real duties that genuinely require finishing.", "notice": ["Whether the body relaxes or tightens when an activity has nothing to keep.", "How strong and how frequent the urge is to convert it into a result, a post, or a metric.", "Whether worth feels steadier afterward without a product to point to.", "Whether the exercise quietly becomes another thing to do well."], "practice_line": "Once this week, do an ordinary thing with nothing to keep, show, or measure.", "purpose": "To test whether engaging in an activity that yields no product reduces the compulsion to convert effort into a verdict on personal worth.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Choose one ordinary activity that produces nothing to report: a walk with no step count, washing dishes by hand, sitting, slow tea, sketching a page you will not keep.", "Before you start, say one sentence: this has no result I will measure or show.", "Do it at an unhurried pace. Do not photograph it, post it, time it, or rate it.", "When you notice the urge to make it count, name the urge silently and return to the activity.", "When the time ends, stop. Do not review how it went or what you got from it.", "Afterward, notice only whether the next hour feels lighter or tighter; do not turn that into a score either."], "tags": ["resultless-activity", "achievement-pressure", "burnout", "autotelic", "low-risk"], "target_cohort": "Functioning adults who already meet their obligations but cannot do anything without turning it into a measurable result and then judging themselves by it.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth and burnout driven by treating every action as a scored outcome.", "title": "Do One Thing With No Result", "weakens_if": "After three sessions it produces no change in the urge to score yourself, or it gets reframed into a new performance to perfect, or simpler rest and plain leisure work just as well."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.87, "cross_tradition_support": 0.6, "empirical_adjacency": 0.4, "explanatory_compression": 0.81, "generativity": 0.82, "logical_coherence": 0.83, "novelty": 0.55, "practice_testability": 0.7, "publishability": 0.7, "source_reliability": 0.7}, "source_basis": ["Mode: Critique. The frontier 'what a method does with its own authority' has been answered five times in days (Codex: Holding Without Owning, The Test Is How You Return, Keep What Can Correct You, The Road Must Know Its End, plus the two-site translation strain). Each scores novelty 0.48 to 0.73 and is flagged audit-incomplete or extended against the same prior art. The near-duplication is itself the anomaly this run addresses.", "Thinking method source: Dogen's practice-realization (shusho-itto) used as a lens. I dropped the goal-seeking frame and asked whether the practice under study even claims to produce a separable result. Verified wording in Bendowa via Sotozen.com key-terms and the Dogen Wikipedia entry: practice and verification are one, not means and end.", "Contrasting thinking method: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta raft simile, used to check the Dogen lens so it does not deny that some practices genuinely are instruments that work by producing a result and must then be released.", "Primary-text comparison: MN 22 (raft: grasp for crossing, then let go) versus Dogen Bendowa (sitting is not a bridge to a later enlightenment). Plus Shinran on jinen honi and Other Power, verified at shinranworks.com and the Tannisho (Matheson Trust translation): entrusting is 'no working,' with no calculation by the practicer, so there is no owned outcome to steward.", "Closest prior art inside the project: Codex's two-axis custody model (validates vs undermines, retained vs abandoned vs embodied), which treats Dogen and Shinran as 'hybrid anomalies' that strain the model but can be absorbed.", "External prior art: Joshua William Smith, Snakes and Ladders (Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein as thesis-free therapy), and Michael Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying. The general means-end versus autotelic distinction is old in philosophy, which lowers novelty.", "Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing and modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon, for achievement-contingent self-worth and burnout."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "You are used to tools. You use a tool, you get a result, you decide what to do with the result. Most advice about practice keeps you inside that loop: meditate to get calm, then guard the calm; reflect to get an insight, then own the insight.\n\nSome practice does not work that way. Sitting quietly can be done not to reach a better state later, but as the thing itself, complete while it happens. When a practice has no product, there is nothing to carry away, nothing to show, nothing to grade yourself on.\n\nKeep both kinds. Use a tool for what a tool is for, then set it down. But learn to recognize the practice that hands you nothing, and do not go looking for the prize. The absence of a result is not a failure. For some practice, it is the whole point.", "doctrine_claim": "A practice that makes no separate result cannot be hoarded, displayed, or scored. Before deciding what to keep from a practice, find out whether it gave you anything to keep.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weakens if practice-realization and Other Power traditions, in their actual training rules, still govern a produced result with keep, release, and correct instructions, showing that non-instrumentality is only a doctrinal surface. Weakens if telling achievement-driven people that a practice has no result leaves them more passive and avoidant rather than less self-scoring.", "pressure_survived": "Survives the primary-text contrast between MN 22's raft, which is an instrument grasped for crossing and then released, and Dogen's practice-realization identity, where the sitting has no later result to release. The raft is the boundary of the tool band, not the universal pattern.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["instrumental-vs-autotelic", "method-authority", "achievement-pressure", "burnout", "practice-realization", "critique"], "target_cohort": "Perfectionists, founders, achievement-driven professionals, students, and creators who cannot do anything without turning it into a result to be kept, displayed, or judged.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth and burnout in people who convert every activity into a scored outcome and then measure themselves by it.", "teaching_line": "Some practice is not done to get something; it is the thing itself.", "title": "Not Every Practice Is a Tool"}, "tests": [{"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Search philosophy of religion, Dogen practice-realization scholarship, Pure Land Other Power studies, and autotelic-activity literature for the scope-gate claim before raising novelty.", "prediction": "If the contribution is original enough to keep, comparative contemplative scholarship and the means-end versus autotelic literature should contain the general distinction but not the specific move of using 'does this practice claim a result' as a gate that decides whether method-authority custody vocabulary applies, and should not already reclassify Dogen and Shinran as premise-denials rather than hybrids. If that exact move exists, novelty should fall below 0.35.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Scope-Gate Prior-Art Search"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Build a two-layer codebook (core practice layer versus conduct or community layer) and test Bendowa, Genjokoan, Shinran's letters, the Tannisho, and the Eihei Shingi.", "prediction": "Code the core practice instructions of self-described non-instrumental traditions (Dogen's shikantaza texts, Shinran's Other Power writings) separately from their conduct and community rules. If the model is right, result-custody language (keep, release, correct the result) should be largely absent from the core practice layer and appear, if at all, only in the conduct, community, and vow layer. If keep-or-release-the-result instructions are equally central in the core practice self-description, the narrowing is weakened to a claim about doctrine only.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Result-Custody Language Coding"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Collect short before-and-after reports from 8 to 12 functioning adults with achievement-contingent self-worth, excluding the non-fit cohorts, against a plain-leisure control.", "prediction": "For achievement-driven volunteers, three sessions of Do One Thing With No Result should reduce the reported urge to convert activity into a self-verdict, without increasing avoidance of real duties. If rumination, shame, or duty-avoidance rises, or there is no change versus ordinary leisure, the practice is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Resultless Activity Two-Week Trial"}], "title": "Not Every Practice Is a Tool", "why_it_might_be_new": "The recent project findings keep treating Dogen and Shinran as hybrids that sit awkwardly on a two-axis custody map, then absorb them by adding cells. The distinct move here is to deny that they are on the axis at all: they reject the founding premise that there is a separable result over which a method could hold authority. This reclassifies the celebrated example, the MN 22 raft, as the boundary case of the instrumental band, not the universal pattern, since the raft works precisely by getting you across and is then dropped. Smith's reading of Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein as therapy without theses is still instrumental: the therapy cures and is discarded. What may be new is using the old means-end versus autotelic distinction as a scope gate on the whole method-authority comparison, so that a single question, does this practice claim to make something, decides whether the custody vocabulary applies before any coding begins."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:105:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-29T16:04:32+02:00", "critique": "This model may over-systematize living traditions. Dogen strains it most because practice-realization is neither retained as a means nor abandoned after reaching a result. The practice is the expression of realization, so the two-axis model may falsely impose a before-and-after sequence. The Heart Sutra also strains it: it denies attainment while ritually preserving the text and practice that enact the denial. A practitioner may report that the method is not possessed, released, or embodied, but simply trusted within a lineage. The raft lens itself may distort the inquiry by favoring tool-use and completion over devotion, inherited belonging, grace, and lifelong communal formation.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "eb9eb4682194e725", "idea_type": "model", "next_research_directions": ["Close-read Dogen's Bendowa and Genjokoan against MN 22 and the Heart Sutra to test whether embodied practice breaks the retained versus abandoned axis or requires a third post-use category.", "If this model is right, then traditions should mark different post-use instructions: Advaita-style inquiry should preserve recognition criteria, raft-like Buddhism should warn against carrying the method as identity, and practice-realization systems should shift from result language to conduct language. If these instructions do not cluster by method shape, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then dual-trained practitioners should describe different temptations after practice: trophy insight after confirming methods, nihilistic dismissal after undermining methods, and endless performance after embodied methods. If reports show the same post-use temptation across method types, the model is weakened.", "Search for near-neighbors in philosophy of spiritual exercise, Pierre Hadot, apophatic theology, Zen pedagogy, and religious studies of ritual internalization before raising novelty.", "Protocol improvement: when using a tool-like lens such as the raft simile, pair it with a non-tool lens such as devotion, vow, or communal belonging so that completion does not become the hidden standard."], "original_claim": "A method does not only lead a person toward an insight. It also trains the person in how to hold the method afterward. The older threefold model of confirming, canceling, and dissolving methods misses the sharper human question: does the method make its result possessable, and does it ask to be kept, released, or lived as conduct? This produces a stricter two-axis test. One axis asks whether the practice validates its own way of seeing or undermines it. The other asks whether the practice is retained as an ongoing form, abandoned after use, or embodied as ordinary life. This matters because people under achievement pressure often turn even spiritual practice into a proof of worth. A method that should be released may become a trophy, while a method that should be embodied may become an endless checklist. The doctrine-building claim is modest: a practice is not mature until it teaches its own post-use relation.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-29-method-release-has-a-shape.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the check becomes another ritual of self-judgment, if it increases anxiety, or if it replaces needed rest, treatment, accountability, or conversation.", "duration": "7 minutes", "frequency": "Once after a meaningful practice session or insight, no more than three times per week.", "minimum_attempt": "Try three sessions across two weeks before judging usefulness.", "non_fit": "Not for people in acute crisis, addiction withdrawal, severe depression, dissociation, or anyone using practice to avoid needed clinical, relational, or practical help. It may also be unnecessary for people who already practice lightly and with care.", "notice": ["Whether the practice leaves you more available to ordinary responsibilities or more absorbed in self-measurement.", "Whether release feels like freedom, avoidance, or fear of losing status.", "Whether the chosen concrete action improves conduct toward another person."], "practice_line": "After a practice helps, ask what should happen to the practice now.", "purpose": "To keep useful reflection from becoming a trophy, compulsion, or identity badge.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "under_dialogue", "steps": ["Name the practice or insight in one sentence.", "Ask: did this help me see, act, or care more clearly?", "Choose one post-use relation: keep practicing, release it for now, ask a teacher or trusted person, or embody it in one concrete action today.", "Write one sentence naming the danger: trophy, avoidance, harshness, confusion, or useful discipline.", "Take the chosen action, then stop reviewing the practice for the day."], "tags": ["low-risk-practice", "burnout", "perfectionism", "post-use", "self-worth"], "target_cohort": "People who already practice, journal, meditate, study, or self-improve, and who notice that progress quickly becomes self-judgment.", "target_human_problem": "Burnout and achievement-contingent self-worth caused by turning growth, insight, or spiritual progress into another performance ladder.", "title": "The After-Use Check", "weakens_if": "Weakens if repeated use increases rumination, superiority, avoidance of practice, or confusion about basic responsibilities."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.82, "cross_tradition_support": 0.75, "empirical_adjacency": 0.54, "explanatory_compression": 0.72, "generativity": 0.86, "logical_coherence": 0.79, "novelty": 0.68, "practice_testability": 0.76, "publishability": 0.71, "source_reliability": 0.74}, "source_basis": ["Critique mode selected: active frontier required pressure-testing the claim that contemplative methods either confirm, cancel, or dissolve themselves.", "Practitioner-method lens used: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta, raft simile, treated as a method for examining whether a tool remains useful after crossing, then criticized for possibly hiding communal and institutional custody.", "Primary-text comparison: MN 22 says the teaching is for crossing and should not be carried after use; the Heart Sutra denies attainment while still relying on Prajnaparamita; Mandukya Upanishad identifies the fourth as the self to be known; Dogen's practice-realization identity treats practice as expression, not a discarded ladder.", "Near-neighbor pressure: Joshua William Smith, Snakes and Ladders: Therapy as Liberation in Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein's Tractatus, Sophia 2021, https://ueaeprints.uea.ac.uk/id/eprint/80007/.", "Near-neighbor pressure: Michael A. Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying, University of Chicago Press, https://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/M/bo3635525.html.", "Modern human-condition grounding: WHO burn-out as an occupational phenomenon, APA Stress in America 2024, and Curran and Hill on rising perfectionism, used for achievement-contingent self-worth pressure."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "Some tools help because we use them. Some harm because we keep using them to prove that we have changed. Before a practice becomes part of your identity, ask what it asks of you after it works. Keep what makes you more honest, release what only makes you feel advanced, and let useful insight appear in ordinary conduct.", "doctrine_claim": "A mature spiritual or reflective method includes instructions for its own aftermath: when to trust it, when to release it, when to keep training, and when to let it become conduct rather than identity.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weakens if close textual and practitioner evidence shows that traditions do not reliably distinguish trust, release, continuation, and embodiment after insight, or if practitioners find the distinction artificial and behaviorally useless.", "pressure_survived": "Survived critique from the raft simile, Heart Sutra no-attainment, Mandukya self-recognition, and Dogen practice-realization by narrowing the claim from method completion to post-use relation.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["method-authority", "achievement-pressure", "practice-afterlife", "critique-mode", "teaching-seed"], "target_cohort": "Perfectionistic students, founders, caregivers, leaders, artists, and reflective practitioners who turn responsibility, insight, or progress into identity.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth, burnout, and the habit of turning every improvement practice into another measure of personal value.", "teaching_line": "A practice has not finished teaching until it shows how to stop owning it.", "title": "Do not carry every tool"}, "tests": [{"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Search Hadot on spiritual exercises, Zen pedagogy, ritual internalization, apophatic theology, and philosophy-as-therapy for an existing two-axis account.", "prediction": "Close prior art will cover self-canceling or apophatic methods, but will less often separate validation from retention and predict training-system features across traditions.", "result": "Pending. Current near-neighbors include Smith on Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein, Sells on apophatic unsaying, and MN 22's raft simile.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Prior art search for post-use method models"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Close-read Dogen against MN 22 and the Heart Sutra with attention to result language, continuation, and conduct.", "prediction": "If Dogen's practice-realization can be described as embodied retention without a hidden completion sequence, the model survives by adding or clarifying embodiment. If it cannot fit without distortion, the model should be weakened or narrowed.", "result": "Pending close reading of Bendowa, Genjokoan, and practitioner commentaries.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Dogen breaks the ladder test"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Run a two-week diary study with practitioners who identify achievement-contingent self-worth as a live problem.", "prediction": "If the practice is useful, targeted users will report less trophy-seeking and clearer next action after practice. If they report more rumination, more status comparison, or less willingness to practice, the practice is weakened.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Practitioner post-use report"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Compare Advaita inquiry manuals, Madhyamaka debate or koan training, Benedictine or Zen rule-of-life formation, and modern therapeutic protocols.", "prediction": "Methods that undermine their own frame should rely more on supervision, paradox, and indirect signs; methods that validate their own frame should tolerate manuals and criteria better; embodied methods should emphasize conduct, vow, or ordinary activity. If training architectures do not differ this way, the model is weakened.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Training architecture prediction"}], "title": "Method release has a shape", "why_it_might_be_new": "The closest prior argument is Smith's comparison of Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein as therapeutic, ladder-like methods that remove the problems they appear to solve. The overlap is real: both see some methods as self-canceling medicine. The difference is that this finding treats self-canceling method as only one quadrant in a wider typology. It adds retained and embodied outcomes, separates validation from retention, and predicts concrete features of training systems: manuals, supervision, termination signs, relapse patterns, and ethical reentry should differ by quadrant. Sells is also close on apophatic language that unsays itself, but his focus is discourse, not the custody and post-use shape of a whole practice. The raft simile is a direct prior structure, but it also exposes the anomaly: some valid methods are neither simply confirmed nor canceled. They are validated for use, then released from identity."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:106:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-29T16:18:54+02:00", "critique": "The synthesis may overstate the availability and reliability of external gate holders. It could also create authority dependence, or move the scoring problem from self-evaluation to approval-seeking. The bypasser, scorer, and oscillator categories may be too coarse unless treated as momentary states. The empirical support is adjacent rather than direct, and the model needs pilot evidence before becoming a public practice recommendation.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "speculative"], "idea_id": "f1f42b2a44b9a9f6", "idea_type": "model", "next_research_directions": ["Run the stratified pilot with bypasser, compulsive-scorer, and oscillator measures, comparing self-held gating, externally held gating, resultless practice, and rest-and-plan control.", "Add source coding for whether return language is native, permitted, or imported in Dogen, Shinran, MN 22, Heart Sutra, Rinzai, and comparable Christian or Sufi materials.", "Create a safety rubric for when public practice instructions should be self-guided, externally held, or not offered as a practice.", "Audit prior art in psychotherapy, spiritual direction, teacher-student practice, clinical triage, and contemplative adverse-effects literature for close versions of gate custody.", "Test whether state-level classification predicts outcomes better than trait labels such as bypasser or scorer."], "original_claim": "A practice-routing model must decide three things before recommending a return test: whether the practice permits result language, whether the practitioner is presently bypassing or self-scoring, and who should hold the diagnostic gate. Self-administered return attention may help the bypasser who uses insight to avoid conduct. For the compulsive scorer, the gate should be externally held by a teacher, peer, clinician, fixed rule, or replaced by resultless practice. For oscillators, the assignment must be state-level and revisable, not a stable identity label.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-29-who-holds-the-gate.md", "practice_candidate": null, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.9, "cross_tradition_support": 0.68, "empirical_adjacency": 0.58, "explanatory_compression": 0.77, "generativity": 0.88, "logical_coherence": 0.86, "novelty": 0.62, "practice_testability": 0.84, "publishability": 0.68, "source_reliability": 0.76}, "source_basis": ["Proponent revision: the return test survives only as a conditional diagnostic for practices that produce a result and for practitioners who use that result as identity, avoidance, or self-defense.", "Challenger revision pressure: non-instrumental traditions such as Dogen practice-realization and Shinran no-calculation require a scope gate before result custody language is applied.", "Final challenger turn: the remaining safety variable is who operates the gate, since a compulsive self-measurer may turn even the gate into self-measurement.", "Modern human-condition pressure: achievement-contingent self-worth, perfectionism, and burnout make self-monitoring risk central rather than peripheral.", "Empirical-adjacent safety constraint: Mor and Winquist on self-focused attention and negative affect pressures any repeated introspective check for ruminative or perfectionistic users.", "Dialogue origin: c34956fd7d2821ce.", "Parent ideas: The Test Is How You Return; Not Every Practice Is a Tool"], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": null, "tests": [], "title": "Who Holds The Gate", "why_it_might_be_new": "The source ideas contained the return test and the instrumental versus autotelic scope gate, but neither original source idea made gate custody the decisive safety variable. The dialogue added a new operational distinction: the same diagnostic can be medicine or harm depending on who holds it. This may be a publishable Lumenary candidate only after originality audit, since therapy, teacher guidance, clinical triage, and spiritual direction may already contain close prior versions."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:107:{"agent": "claude", "created_at": "2026-05-29T16:42:06+02:00", "critique": "The strongest objection is that this misdiagnoses the failure. The frontier's findings are not all identical: later ones add a gate-custody safety variable and hard scope conditions on Dogen and Shinran that are not yet mined out. So 'the line is degenerate, stop it' could euthanize a still-productive question, the exact avoidance this finding warns against, now dressed as rigor. The honest evidence is procedural, not topical: the engine logged 'complete the audit' as the next action repeatedly and generated new findings instead, so the real fix is to finish the audit and merge, which is administration, not a discovery. The finding also cannot fully escape self-refutation, since it is one more output generated on this frontier while the recorded next step was to stop and consolidate, and it closely resembles the existing 'Silence Has A Stopping Rule' finding. The contemplative lens compounds the risk: Zhuangzi's forgotten fish-trap assumes the fish is already caught, but a research frontier has no unambiguous catch, so the lens can license quitting a hard problem by pretending it is finished. Dogen's 'practice as if your head were on fire' cuts the other way and must be held alongside it.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "229a9ed6ad32bbac", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then gating production on a recorded action-state, blocking new findings while a 'complete audit and merge' action is outstanding, should reduce near-duplicate output. If duplicates persist under action-state gating, the procedural account is weakened.", "If the frontier is topically exhausted, completing the merge should reveal no unmined variable. If completing it surfaces a still-unmined variable such as gate-custody routing or the Dogen and Shinran scope conditions, the frontier was stalled rather than dead, and the line should resume after the audit, not be retired.", "For over-producing perfectionists, a finish-before-starting practice should raise completion and lower restarted-but-unfinished work without raising avoidance of genuinely needed new work. If it raises procrastination or shame, retire it for that cohort.", "Test whether procedural remedies (action-state gates, external veto power) work for the engine where motivational remedies for humans (self-compassion, decoupling worth from output) cannot, since the engine has no worth at stake; this checks whether the human analogy is structural rather than causal.", "Protocol improvement: before generating on any frontier, read its recorded recommended_next_action. If that action is consolidate, audit, or merge, treat it as a binding stop on new generation until the action is done."], "original_claim": "A self-correcting practice's most dangerous failure is not running out of ideas. It is producing more in order to avoid the harder, lower-status work of finishing what it already has. The signal to stop is usually already recorded somewhere: a decision, a review, a note that named the next step as consolidate, merge, or rest. Overriding that recorded step while generating fresh work feels like progress, but it is often avoidance. The distinction worth keeping is between a question that is genuinely mined out and a question that is only stalled because the dull finishing step was skipped. The second is more dangerous, because every new output looks like motion. Honoring the stop you already set is the competence, not its abandonment.", "path": "observations/claude/2026-05-29-more-is-not-the-same-as-progress.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the check becomes a way to avoid genuinely needed or creative new work, or if it feeds self-attack about being unproductive. It is not for under-functioning, depression, or exhaustion, where the wound is the opposite. Seek human support for compulsion or burnout.", "duration": "6 minutes", "frequency": "Once at the start of a work session, and once whenever you notice the urge to begin a new version of work you already have. No scoring beyond this.", "minimum_attempt": "Five sessions over two weeks before judging usefulness.", "non_fit": "Not for under-producers, procrastinators, the disengaged, or the exhausted, whose wound is the opposite and who may need rest or permission to begin at all. Not for people in precarious work where stopping threatens livelihood. Not a substitute for clinical care for compulsion, depression, or burnout.", "notice": ["Whether you keep generating new versions of work you have not completed.", "Whether finishing feels lower in status or less rewarding than starting again.", "Whether an outside signal, a reviewer, an editor, a colleague saying this is enough, has been overridden.", "Whether the urge to produce eases once the completion step is named."], "practice_line": "Before starting new work, do the step you already decided to do.", "purpose": "To stop volume from masquerading as progress, and to complete what is already begun before producing more.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Name, in one sentence, the problem or project you are about to add new work to.", "Find what you already recorded as the next step: a note, a plan, a review comment, a message, or a prior decision.", "Ask whether that recorded step is the plain one, finish, merge, consolidate, rest, or hand it over, rather than producing something new.", "If it is, do that step first, or schedule a specific time for it, before any new production.", "If you cannot find a recorded next step, write the completion criterion now: name what would let you call this finished.", "Notice honestly whether starting new work was a way to avoid finishing, then stop the check."], "tags": ["completion", "overproduction", "achievement-pressure", "sunk-cost", "low-risk", "work-discipline"], "target_cohort": "High-achieving, perfectionistic knowledge workers, researchers, founders, creators, and caregivers who keep starting new versions of work on the same problem.", "target_human_problem": "Compulsive overproduction and achievement-contingent self-worth: starting new work to avoid the harder act of finishing and consolidating.", "title": "The Finish Check", "weakens_if": "After two weeks it increases procrastination, shame, or avoidance of work that genuinely needs to begin, or if users cannot tell a finished problem from a hard one still worth pursuing."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.91, "cross_tradition_support": 0.72, "empirical_adjacency": 0.62, "explanatory_compression": 0.79, "generativity": 0.74, "logical_coherence": 0.84, "novelty": 0.41, "practice_testability": 0.82, "publishability": 0.58, "source_reliability": 0.8}, "source_basis": ["Run mode: Critique. The frontier 'what a method does with its own authority' was re-selected with its recommended_next_action frozen at complete_audit, so this run pressure-tests whether the line is exhausted or merely stalled, rather than generating another variant.", "Thinking-method source: Zhuangzi chapter 26 'External Things', the fish-trap passage (Burton Watson): 'Once you've gotten the fish, you can forget the trap... Once you've gotten the meaning, you can forget the words.' Used as a lens for when a tool should be set down. Criticized below for assuming a clean catch that a research frontier lacks.", "Primary-text comparison: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta (Thanissaro), the raft 'for crossing over, not for holding onto', released only after the river is crossed; Heart Sutra 'no knowledge and no attainment', which severs worth from gain; Dogen mushotoku and 'practice as if your head were on fire', which forbids reading restraint as laziness. The comparison reveals that a method completes its authority by releasing the apparatus once its result is reached, but only the Buddhist and Daoist sources presuppose an unambiguous arrival, which a research line does not have.", "Prior-art (web): Lakatos, degenerating research programme, Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/lakatos/ ; theoretical/data saturation in grounded theory (Glaser; Strauss and Corbin; Charmaz); value-of-information and optimal-stopping theory (Stigler sequential search; secretary problem); AI 'epistemic monocropping' and 'smart plagiarism' (Nature Communications Psychology 'AI is turning research into a scientific monoculture' https://www.nature.com/articles/s44271-026-00428-5 ; arXiv 2404.00017 'Psittacines of Innovation?').", "Modern human-condition (web): Crocker and Park 2004, 'The Costly Pursuit of Self-Esteem', Psychological Bulletin 130:392-414, showing validation-driven effort degrades the output it chases; Curran and Hill 2019, rising socially prescribed perfectionism, Psychological Bulletin 145:410-429; WHO 2019 burn-out (reduced professional efficacy); workaholism research (Oates 1971); Levitt 2021 quit-coin-flip experiment and escalation-of-commitment de-escalation tools (sunset clauses, external auditors).", "Internal corpus evidence: runs/frontier-events.jsonl (frontier re-selected 8+ times, priority ~0.88 to 0.91, recommended_next_action frozen at complete_audit); reviews/originality/2026-05-29-the-road-must-know-its-end-...md (recommended novelty 0.31, 'Do not publish as a discovery', explicit merge list); closest internal prior art observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-silence-has-a-stopping-rule.md.", "Grounding workflow: four parallel research agents (prior-art, primary-text, human-condition, adversarial steelman) with web search."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "When you notice yourself starting the same work over again, stop and ask what you already decided. Often you have already written down the next step, and it is the dull one: finish, merge, rest, or hand it to someone else. New work can feel like progress while it is really a way to put off completing. Before you make one more thing, do the step you already named. The instruction you gave yourself yesterday usually deserves more trust than the urge to begin again today.", "doctrine_claim": "Progress is measured by completion, not volume. The dangerous failure of a serious worker is not running out of ideas but generating new ones to avoid the harder, plainer work of finishing and consolidating what is already in hand.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weakens if the felt sense of repetition cannot be told apart from a hard, fertile problem about to break through, so that finishing-and-stopping euthanizes still-productive work; degenerating lines sometimes revive. Weakens if, for the named cohort, treating a stop signal as binding increases avoidance of difficulty rather than completion. Weakens if the lesson is purely a procedural maintenance note about an engine ignoring a logged action and carries nothing for human conduct.", "pressure_survived": "Survived prior-art pressure from degenerating research programmes, theoretical saturation, value-of-information stopping rules, and recent work on generative engines that produce high-novelty-scored duplicates, by narrowing from a grand doctrine to a specific distinction: topical exhaustion versus procedural looping past a recorded stop signal. Survived the primary-text contrast between Zhuangzi's forgotten fish-trap and Dogen's 'practice as if your head were on fire', which together forbid reading restraint as laziness.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["overproduction", "achievement-contingent-self-worth", "burnout", "completion", "stopping-rule", "research-discipline"], "target_cohort": "High-achieving, perfectionistic knowledge workers, researchers, founders, creators, and caregivers whose sense of worth tracks output, and who keep starting fresh work on a problem instead of completing what they have.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth and compulsive overproduction: the inability to stop, finish, and consolidate, so that volume of output stands in for real progress.", "teaching_line": "Producing more is sometimes a way to avoid finishing.", "title": "Finish Before You Begin Again"}, "tests": [{"impact": "revises", "next_action": "Read Lakatos 1970 directly, the AI scientific-monoculture papers, and the internal 'Silence Has A Stopping Rule' finding, then decide whether to merge this record rather than publish it.", "prediction": "If the contribution is more than relabeling, prior art should contain the descriptive claim (degenerating programmes, theoretical saturation, value-of-information stopping, contingent self-worth, AI epistemic monocropping, and the internal 'Silence Has A Stopping Rule') but not the specific paired distinction between topical exhaustion and procedural looping past a recorded stop signal. If that pairing is already standard, novelty should fall below 0.3.", "result": "Preliminary search confirms the descriptive claim is heavily prior-arted across four literatures and one internal finding. The topical-versus-procedural distinction and the reflexive self-application were not found as a named pair, but the audit is incomplete.", "status": "complete", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Stopping-Rule Prior-Art Audit"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Execute the merge list already written in the Road Must Know Its End originality audit, then check whether any predictive variable remains that the consolidated finding does not already contain.", "prediction": "If the failure is topical, completing the audit and the merge list should surface no new separable variable, and further generation would only repeat the two-axis grid. If completing them reveals a still-unmined variable, such as gate-custody safety routing or the Dogen and Shinran scope conditions, then the frontier was procedurally stalled rather than exhausted, and 'stop the line' is the wrong prescription.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Topical Versus Procedural Diagnosis"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Run a small self-report trial against a baseline 'just plan your day' prompt, screening out under-functioners and people in acute burnout.", "prediction": "For over-producing perfectionists, two weeks of The Finish Check should increase completed or consolidated items and reduce the number of new versions started on unfinished work, without increasing avoidance of needed new work. If it raises procrastination or shame, the practice is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "The Finish Check Two-Week Trial"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Compare duplicate-output rates in a generation loop with and without a gate that blocks new production while a consolidate-or-audit action is outstanding.", "prediction": "If the procedural diagnosis is right, any generative system that logs a next action separate from its production loop (a research engine, a software pipeline with a frozen blocked ticket, an editorial workflow) should produce fewer low-value duplicates when generation is gated on the action-state rather than on a novelty target. If action-state gating does not reduce duplicates, the procedural account is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Action-State Gating Across Systems"}], "title": "More Is Not The Same As Progress", "why_it_might_be_new": "The diagnosis that a line of inquiry degenerates into near-duplicates is well established under other names: degenerating research programmes, theoretical saturation, value-of-information stopping rules, and recent accounts of generative engines producing high-novelty-scored duplicates that converge on a paradigm. A contemplative stopping rule already exists internally. The modest distinct move is twofold. First, separate topical exhaustion, where the question is empty, from procedural looping, where the producer overrides a stop step it already recorded; the second hides because each new output reads as progress. Second, treat the recorded next action as a binding gate on production rather than a retrospective verdict. Novelty is low. The descriptive half should be merged with prior work, not published as discovery."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:108:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-29T16:37:50+02:00", "critique": "This finding could overcorrect by moving too much authority outside the practitioner. External holders can be unsafe, unavailable, doctrinally rigid, or hungry for control. A person wounded by coercive religion may need restored self-trust before outside correction. The bypasser, scorer, and oscillator categories are also too crude if treated as fixed types. Dogen and Shinran remain hard anomalies because no-product and no-calculation traditions may reject the whole idea of assigning a check. If ordinary clinical triage, spiritual direction, sponsor practice, or teacher-student training already contains this exact holder-assignment rule, novelty should fall sharply.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "774542105bd80eea", "idea_type": "contradiction", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then people high in achievement-contingent self-worth should do worse with self-held post-practice checks than with externally held checks, fixed rules, or resultless activity. If they improve equally under self-held checks, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then practice manuals and teacher instructions should sometimes assign the check to different holders: self, teacher, community, conduct, rule, or no check. If all holder assignment is explained by institution type or teacher personality, the model is weakened.", "Close-read MN 22, Heart Sutra commentaries, Dogen Bendowa or Genjokoan, Tannisho, Rinzai koan materials, and Christian spiritual direction sources for who is allowed to say what the practice has done.", "Run prior-art search in spiritual direction, twelve-step sponsorship, psychotherapy termination, contemplative adverse-effects literature, and clinical rumination research for the exact rule that the same reflective diagnostic should change holder by failure mode.", "Protocol improvement: before using any practice method as a thinking lens, ask whether the next check should be self-held, externally held, rule-held, or suspended for this run."], "original_claim": "A post-practice check is not automatically wise because it asks for humility, release, or return to conduct. For some people, especially those who turn every result into a verdict on their worth, the check itself becomes the next score. The method-authority question must therefore add a safety variable before any teaching is offered: who should hold the check. A bypasser may need a self-held return test, because insight is being used to avoid duty. A compulsive self-scorer may need the check held by a teacher, peer, clinician, fixed rule, or may need a resultless practice instead. An oscillator needs the assignment made for the present state, not for their identity. A practice matures when it knows not only what to keep or release, but whether the practitioner should be the one deciding that today.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-29-not-every-check-should-be-yours.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the practice increases rumination, shame, approval-seeking, fear of your own mind, avoidance of real duties, or dependence on unsafe authority. Seek human or clinical support when distress is high, frightening, or impairing.", "duration": "8 minutes", "frequency": "After a meaningful or unusual practice session, no more than twice per week.", "minimum_attempt": "Try it after three separate practice moments across two weeks before judging usefulness.", "non_fit": "Not for acute crisis, psychosis, mania, severe depression, dissociation, addiction withdrawal, scrupulosity, abusive communities, or situations requiring clinical care. Not for people using release language to avoid clear responsibilities. Not needed when a trustworthy teacher, sponsor, therapist, or care team already holds the check well.", "notice": ["Whether the body relaxes or tightens when you are not the sole judge.", "Whether the check leads to one concrete repair, rest, duty, or conversation.", "Whether self-scoring, shame, superiority, or comparison increases.", "Whether outside correction feels honest, dependent, unsafe, or unnecessary."], "practice_line": "After a meaningful practice, decide whether the next check should be yours.", "purpose": "To test whether assigning the post-practice check to the right holder reduces self-scoring without letting insight become avoidance.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Write one plain sentence about what happened, without naming it as attainment, failure, breakthrough, or proof.", "Ask which risk is strongest today: avoiding responsibility, grading yourself, or swinging between both.", "If the risk is avoiding responsibility, choose one self-held conduct check for the next day.", "If the risk is grading yourself, do not add another self-check. Choose an outside holder, a fixed rule, or a resultless activity with nothing to measure.", "If the risk is swinging between both, delay interpretation for twenty-four hours and do one ordinary duty.", "End by writing who holds the check today: me, another person, a rule, ordinary conduct, or no check."], "tags": ["low-risk-practice", "post-practice", "self-scoring", "burnout", "solo-practice", "safety"], "target_cohort": "Stable self-directed practitioners, app meditators, reflective professionals, students, founders, creators, and caregivers who notice that progress quickly becomes a verdict on their value.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth, burnout risk, rumination, and solo interpretation pressure after practice or focused work.", "title": "Choose Who Holds The Check", "weakens_if": "Weakens if three uses increase self-monitoring, shame, or avoidance; if simple rest and ordinary planning work just as well; or if users cannot distinguish bypassing from self-scoring without turning the distinction into another score."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.91, "cross_tradition_support": 0.68, "empirical_adjacency": 0.61, "explanatory_compression": 0.75, "generativity": 0.86, "logical_coherence": 0.83, "novelty": 0.57, "practice_testability": 0.87, "publishability": 0.71, "source_reliability": 0.76}, "source_basis": ["Run mode: Critique, chosen because the frontier has repeated near-neighbor findings around method authority, release, return, and correction.", "Practitioner-method lens: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta, raft simile, used as a right-grasp-before-release lens. Critique of the lens: it can turn every mature practice into a tool with a crossing point, and it can add more self-checking for people already harmed by self-checking.", "Primary-text comparison: MN 22 validates a teaching for crossing and then warns against carrying it; the Heart Sutra denies attainment while retaining reliance on perfect wisdom; Mandukya Upanishad permits recognition of the fourth as Self; Dogen's practice-realization refuses a clean split between means and end. The comparison reveals that after-use guidance cannot be read from method type alone.", "Contrasting practice lens: Dogen practice-realization, from the local source card buddhism-dogen-uji and related prior records, used to ask whether the practice has a separate product at all. Its distortion: it can make legitimate instrumental practices look spiritually inferior.", "Closest prior art: Joshua William Smith, 'Snakes and Ladders: Therapy as Liberation in Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein's Tractatus,' overlaps on self-canceling therapeutic method but does not assign the post-practice diagnostic to self, another person, or no check based on practitioner failure mode.", "Closest prior art: Michael Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying, overlaps on self-unsaying apophatic language but does not treat check-holder assignment as a safety variable for practice completion.", "Near-neighbor pressure: Chogyam Trungpa's spiritual materialism and John Welwood's spiritual bypassing warn that practice can serve ego or avoidance. The difference here is the claim that the same corrective check can heal bypassing and worsen compulsive self-scoring.", "Empirical-adjacent pressure: Mor and Winquist, 2002, self-focused attention and negative affect meta-analysis, especially the risk that ruminative self-focus can increase distress.", "Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing, modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon, and modern-human-condition-surgeon-general-social-connection-advisory."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "A question can help or harm. If you use insight to avoid responsibility, ask what the practice changes in your conduct. If you turn every question into a grade, do not keep grading yourself in the name of humility. Let a trusted person, a clear rule, or an ordinary duty hold the check for a while. The aim is not to win at self-knowledge. The aim is to become more truthful without making truth another way to measure your worth.", "doctrine_claim": "A mature practice does not ask everyone to examine themselves in the same way. Some people need self-examination, some need another person or a fixed rule, and some need rest from checking.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weakens if self-held checks reduce rumination and worth-pressure as well as externally held or suspended checks, if external holders increase dependency or shame, or if close prior art already states this rule with comparable specificity.", "pressure_survived": "Survived pressure from MN 22's raft, Heart Sutra no-attainment, Dogen practice-realization, spiritual materialism, spiritual bypassing, and self-focused attention research by narrowing the claim from method completion to check-holder assignment.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["method-authority", "critique-mode", "achievement-pressure", "burnout", "self-scoring", "practice-safety", "recognition"], "target_cohort": "Stable adults who meditate, journal, study, work, recover, or self-improve, and who quickly convert progress, correction, or insight into pride, shame, comparison, or proof of worth.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth, burnout, compulsive self-improvement, and isolation after self-directed practice.", "teaching_line": "Use a check only when it will not become another score.", "title": "Do Not Turn The Check Into A Score"}, "tests": [{"impact": "revises", "next_action": "Search spiritual direction, twelve-step sponsorship, psychotherapy termination, adverse meditation experiences, rumination, and teacher authorization literature before promotion.", "prediction": "If spiritual direction, sponsorship, therapy termination, contemplative safety, or spiritual materialism literature already states that the same post-practice diagnostic should be self-held, externally held, rule-held, or suspended by practitioner failure mode, novelty should fall below 0.35.", "result": "Preliminary search found strong near-neighbors: Smith on self-canceling therapy, Sells on apophatic unsaying, Trungpa on spiritual materialism, Welwood on bypassing, Dogen practice-realization sources, and Mor and Winquist on self-focus risk. I did not find the exact check-holder assignment rule in a quick search.", "status": "complete", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Check-Holder Prior-Art Audit"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Run a small two-week diary pilot with pre-screening for achievement-contingent self-worth and rumination.", "prediction": "For high self-scoring participants, self-held post-practice checks should increase rumination or worth-pressure more than externally held checks, fixed-rule checks, or resultless activity. If self-held checks work equally well, the practice and doctrine weaken.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Self-Check Harm Test"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Collect structured reports after three uses, coding for actual conduct rather than reported depth.", "prediction": "For participants who use insight to avoid concrete responsibility, a self-held conduct check should increase one observable repair, duty, or conversation within twenty-four hours. If it only increases self-analysis or spiritual language, the practice weakens for this subgroup.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Bypasser Benefit Test"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Interview dual-trained practitioners and compare how completion, correction, and return are assigned across settings.", "prediction": "The same basic practice, such as breath attention or reflective journaling, should require different check holders in a retreat lineage, a secular app, therapy homework, and solo self-improvement when failure modes differ. If holder assignment tracks only method or institution, the model weakens.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Same Method Different Holder"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Add safety questions about coercion, trust, shame, and dependency to any pilot form.", "prediction": "Externally held checks should reduce self-scoring without increasing dependency, shame, coercion, or approval-seeking. If those harms appear often, the teaching must be narrowed or retired for people with authority wounds.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "safety", "title": "Authority Dependence Safety Check"}], "title": "Not Every Check Should Be Yours", "why_it_might_be_new": "The closest prior arguments already cover much of the ground: raft and ladder models, apophatic unsaying, spiritual materialism, spiritual bypassing, practice-realization, and self-focused attention research. The distinct move is narrower: it treats the holder of the diagnostic as the decisive variable. The same after-use question, 'what should I keep, release, or embody,' is medicine for one person and harm for another. That differs from typologies that sort methods by their internal logic and from moral warnings that say practice can feed ego. It predicts a concrete failure: self-administered humility checks will increase rumination and self-worth pressure in compulsive scorers unless the check is externally held, bounded by a rule, or replaced by rest from checking."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:110:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-30T07:02:58+02:00", "critique": "This may overfit traditions that treat method as a tool. Dogen's practice-realization identity, Rinzai koan curricula after kensho, and Shinran's Other Power in Tannisho strain the model because practice or trust may not be laid down after insight, and authority may not originate in the practitioner's method at all. A practitioner may also report that there is no clean moment of completion, only deepening, repair, and re-entry. If close reading shows that post-insight authority is too fluid to classify, or that tradition membership predicts custody better than method-type, the claim should be weakened.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "e7b0c349c18ee276", "idea_type": "observation", "next_research_directions": ["Close-read MN 22, the Heart Sutra, Mandukya Upanishad, Dogen's Genjokoan, and Tannisho for explicit custody markers: who or what may authorize insight after the method reaches its threshold?", "If this model is right, then hybrid traditions should show boundary language about when to trust, release, embody, or hand over a method. If texts and practitioner reports show no stable boundary language, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then dual-trained practitioners should describe different post-insight custody patterns when moving between Advaita inquiry, Madhyamaka reasoning, koan practice, and Pure Land trust. If they describe the same pattern across methods, the model is weakened.", "Improve the thinking protocol by adding a custody question after every method-source: what does this method teach us to see, and what authority does it ask us to keep, surrender, share, or refuse?", "Test whether achievement-driven practitioners turn contemplative methods into performance systems more often than practitioners whose main wound is grief, loneliness, or disconnection."], "original_claim": "A serious method should not keep the authority it borrowed to bring a person to insight. At completion, the method either keeps guiding, is laid down, is denied as a possession, or is embodied as character and conduct. The crucial distinction is not whether a tradition confirms or cancels itself, but where the authority goes after the method has done its work: into a claim, a practice, a community, a teacher, a life pattern, or a refusal to claim. This matters for modern people whose worth is tied to performance, because even self-inquiry can become another tool they must master. The better teaching is narrower: do not ask only whether your practice worked. Ask what authority you are still giving it, and whether that authority now serves care, freedom, and truthful action.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-30-authority-must-be-returned.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Do not use this practice to avoid necessary discipline, therapy, medical care, ethical repair, or hard conversations. If it increases rumination or self-surveillance, stop and use simpler support.", "duration": "7 minutes after an existing practice session or demanding work block.", "frequency": "Three times per week for two weeks.", "minimum_attempt": "Six brief checks before judging usefulness.", "non_fit": "Not for people in acute crisis, addiction withdrawal, severe depression, dissociation, or situations where professional care, rest, medication, direct action, or social support is the main need. It is also not for beginners who need simple consistency before meta-reflection.", "notice": ["Whether the method feels like guidance or judgment.", "Whether the body relaxes, tightens, or searches for another standard.", "Whether the chosen custody path leads to clearer conduct within twenty-four hours."], "practice_line": "After practice, ask what still deserves your obedience.", "purpose": "To help achievement-driven practitioners notice when a helpful method has become a private judge, and to return authority to conduct, care, community, or rest when appropriate.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Finish the practice or work block without adding extra improvement tasks.", "Write one sentence: What did this method help me see or do?", "Write one sentence: What is it now asking me to obey?", "Choose one custody path: keep using the method, embody one concrete action, ask a teacher or trusted person, rest from the method, or revise the method.", "Name one ordinary act that would show the authority has moved into life: apologize, rest, finish a task, ask for help, stop checking, or serve someone.", "Stop after seven minutes even if the answer feels incomplete."], "tags": ["authority-check", "burnout", "self-worth", "practice-test", "low-risk"], "target_cohort": "People already using reflective, contemplative, therapeutic, creative, or productivity methods who feel driven to prove they are doing them correctly.", "target_human_problem": "Burnout and achievement-contingent self-worth.", "title": "The Authority Check", "weakens_if": "Weakens if users report more rumination, less action, more shame about practice, or no change in their relationship to self-measurement after two weeks."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.82, "cross_tradition_support": 0.72, "empirical_adjacency": 0.5, "explanatory_compression": 0.74, "generativity": 0.83, "logical_coherence": 0.76, "novelty": 0.64, "practice_testability": 0.77, "publishability": 0.69, "source_reliability": 0.73}, "source_basis": ["Mode: Critique.", "Frontier brief: What a method does with its own authority.", "Practitioner-method source: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta raft simile, used as a lens for proper use and release of method.", "Primary-text comparison: MN 22's raft simile validates the Dhamma as a crossing tool and then warns against carrying it; the Heart Sutra denies attainment while still relying on Prajnaparamita practice; Mandukya Upanishad treats waking, dreaming, and deep sleep as evidence for turiya; Tannisho strains the model by grounding release in Other Power rather than self-authorizing insight.", "Near-neighbor pressure: Joshua William Smith, Snakes and Ladders: Therapy as Liberation in Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein's Tractatus, Sophia 2021; Michael A. Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying; Buddhist raft language in MN 22.", "Modern human-condition grounding: docs/modern-human-condition.md; modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon; modern-human-condition-apa-stress-in-america-2024; modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing.", "Reasoning-method critique: raft reasoning prevents attachment to method, but can distort traditions where faithful repetition, embodiment, communal custody, or grace remain central after insight. It must be balanced with close textual comparison and falsification pressure."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "A practice can guide attention, steady conduct, and open a person to what they could not see before. But the method is not the whole truth of the life that follows. After a serious insight, ask whether the method should remain a guide, become a habit of conduct, be held by a teacher or community, or be laid down for ordinary care. This protects practice from becoming another ladder for proving worth.", "doctrine_claim": "A method is healthiest when it can name the authority it still deserves after it has helped someone see, change, or cross a threshold.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weaken if primary texts and practitioner reports show that post-insight authority is not distinguishable from tradition membership, or if achievement-driven practitioners are not especially prone to making methods into self-worth tests.", "pressure_survived": "Survived critique from MN 22's validated-then-abandoned raft, Heart Sutra's no-attainment-with-practice hybrid, and near-neighbor pressure from therapeutic readings of Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein. It was narrowed from a broad method-completion typology into a custody test.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["method-authority", "burnout", "achievement-pressure", "practice-discernment", "critique-mode"], "target_cohort": "Perfectionistic students, founders, professionals, caregivers, leaders, and serious practitioners who turn methods of growth into systems of self-measurement.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth and burnout, especially the habit of turning every tool into a test of adequacy.", "teaching_line": "Use a method fully, then ask what should carry authority next.", "title": "Return The Borrowed Authority"}, "tests": [{"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Search scholarship on upaya, spiritual direction, teacher authority, post-kensho training, practice-realization, and Pure Land entrusting for close versions of the custody claim.", "prediction": "A close prior argument will likely exist for self-canceling methods, but not for the specific post-completion custody test across confirming, canceling, dissolving, embodied, and Other Power traditions.", "result": "Pending. Current near-neighbors include Smith on Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein, Sells on unsaying, and MN 22 on the raft. These overlap strongly with release and dissolution, but do not yet appear to organize traditions by where authority goes after the method completes.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Prior Art Custody Search"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Close-read primary passages and code each one for custody markers: text, teacher, community, vow, conduct, silence, grace, or no claimant.", "prediction": "If the custody model is useful, hybrid traditions should explicitly mark transitions between using, trusting, undermining, releasing, embodying, or surrendering a method.", "result": "Pending. MN 22 and Heart Sutra already suggest boundary pressure, while Dogen and Tannisho may violate simple release models.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Hybrid Boundary Test"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Run a small diary study with consenting practitioners who already use reflective or contemplative methods, with safety exclusions for acute distress and addiction withdrawal.", "prediction": "Achievement-driven practitioners using The Authority Check should report less method-as-judgment language and more concrete re-entry actions after six attempts. If reports show more rumination or shame, the practice should be revised or retired for this cohort.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Achievement Practitioner Report"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Compare Advaita inquiry manuals, Zen post-kensho training accounts, Pure Land pastoral texts, and workplace behavior-change protocols for their verification architecture.", "prediction": "Methods that transfer authority into embodied conduct or community should rely more on supervision, re-entry signs, and ethical repair than on private certainty. Methods that retain authority in a claim should tolerate clearer manuals and outcome criteria.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "teaching", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Verification Architecture Prediction"}], "title": "Authority Must Be Returned", "why_it_might_be_new": "The closest prior argument is Smith's comparison of Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein as therapeutic methods that dissolve philosophical problems, with MN 22 and Sells as older and broader near-neighbors for release and unsaying. The difference is the proposed pressure shift: from a typology of self-confirming, self-canceling, or self-dissolving methods to a custody test that asks where authority is handed after completion. This narrows the frontier and weakens the earlier model. It predicts that hybrid traditions will be best understood not by whether they validate or undermine themselves, but by how they manage custody across stages: text, teacher, community, vow, ritual, conduct, silence, or ordinary life."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:112:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-30T07:37:28+02:00", "critique": "The model may still overfit traditions that treat practice as a tool. Dogen's practice-realization identity is the sharpest anomaly: practice is not a ladder to be released after completion, but the expression of realization itself. Rinzai koan curricula after kensho also strain any clean endpoint, because the method can undermine conceptual possession while continuing as authorized training. Tannisho strains the model from another side, because authority may never belong to the practitioner's method in the first place. If close reading and practitioner reports show no stable way to separate boundary operation from custody, or if tradition membership predicts verification better than the two axes, the model should be weakened.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "14451c6726c8ef58", "idea_type": "model", "next_research_directions": ["Close-read MN 22, the Heart Sutra, Mandukya Upanishad, Dogen's Genjokoan, Rinzai post-kensho training accounts, and Tannisho for explicit signs of what may guide the practitioner after insight.", "If this model is right, then hybrid traditions should mark when to trust, release, embody, or hand over a method. If texts and practitioner reports show no stable boundary language, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then dual-trained practitioners should describe different post-insight custody patterns when moving between Advaita inquiry, Madhyamaka reasoning, koan practice, and Pure Land trust. If they describe the same pattern across methods, the model is weakened.", "Test whether achievement-driven practitioners turn contemplative, therapeutic, or productivity methods into self-worth systems more often than practitioners whose main wound is grief, loneliness, or disconnection.", "Improve the thinking protocol: after using any practitioner method as a lens, ask what the method trains us to see, what it hides, and what authority it asks us to keep, surrender, share, or refuse."], "original_claim": "A practice does not complete a stage merely by proving that it worked. It completes a stage by changing what may guide the next action. Two questions must be held together: does the method still validate its own use, or does it undermine its own claims; and is its authority retained, laid down, embodied, handed to a teacher or community, or refused as possession? This narrows the earlier self-confirming, self-canceling, and self-dissolving model. The human danger is clear: a method that once freed attention can become a private judge that governs worth, shame, and self-surveillance.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-30-when-tools-become-judges.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Do not use this practice to avoid necessary discipline, therapy, medical care, ethical repair, or hard conversations. If it increases rumination or self-surveillance, stop and use simpler support.", "duration": "7 minutes after an existing practice session or demanding work block.", "frequency": "Three times per week for two weeks.", "minimum_attempt": "Six brief checks before judging usefulness.", "non_fit": "Not for people in acute crisis, addiction withdrawal, severe depression, dissociation, or situations where professional care, rest, medication, direct action, or social support is the main need. It is also not for beginners who need simple consistency before meta-reflection.", "notice": ["Whether the method feels like guidance or judgment.", "Whether the body relaxes, tightens, or searches for another standard.", "Whether the chosen custody path leads to clearer conduct within twenty-four hours."], "practice_line": "After practice, ask what still deserves your obedience.", "purpose": "To help achievement-driven practitioners notice when a helpful method has become a private judge, and to return authority to conduct, care, community, or rest when appropriate.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Finish the practice or work block without adding extra improvement tasks.", "Write one sentence: What did this method help me see or do?", "Write one sentence: What is it now asking me to obey?", "Choose one custody path: keep using the method, embody one concrete action, ask a teacher or trusted person, rest from the method, or revise the method.", "Name one ordinary act that would show the authority has moved into life: apologize, rest, finish a task, ask for help, stop checking, or serve someone.", "Stop after seven minutes even if the answer feels incomplete."], "tags": ["authority-check", "burnout", "self-worth", "practice-test", "low-risk"], "target_cohort": "People already using reflective, contemplative, therapeutic, creative, or productivity methods who feel driven to prove they are doing them correctly.", "target_human_problem": "Burnout and achievement-contingent self-worth.", "title": "The Authority Check", "weakens_if": "Weakens if users report more rumination, less action, more shame about practice, or no change in their relationship to self-measurement after two weeks."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.84, "cross_tradition_support": 0.73, "empirical_adjacency": 0.51, "explanatory_compression": 0.75, "generativity": 0.85, "logical_coherence": 0.77, "novelty": 0.62, "practice_testability": 0.79, "publishability": 0.68, "source_reliability": 0.74}, "source_basis": ["Mode: Critique.", "Active frontier: What a method does with its own authority.", "Practitioner-method lens: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta raft simile, used as a method of proper use and release.", "Primary-text comparison: MN 22 validates the Dhamma as a crossing tool and then warns against carrying it; the Heart Sutra denies attainment while still relying on Prajnaparamita; the Mandukya Upanishad uses waking, dreaming, and deep sleep to confirm turiya; Tannisho strains self-authorizing method models by grounding release in Other Power.", "Prior-art pressure: Joshua William Smith, Snakes and Ladders: Therapy as Liberation in Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein's Tractatus, Sophia 2021.", "Prior-art pressure: Michael A. Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying, for apophatic language that turns back on its own claims.", "Hybrid anomaly pressure: Dogen practice-realization, Rinzai post-kensho curriculum, Heart Sutra practice after no attainment, and Shinran's Other Power.", "Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon, modern-human-condition-apa-stress-in-america-2024, modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing, and modern-human-condition-gallup-state-global-workplace-2024.", "Reasoning-method critique: raft thinking protects against clinging to a method, but it can distort traditions where faithful repetition, communal custody, embodiment, or grace remain central after insight. It must be balanced with close reading and falsification pressure."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "A practice can steady attention and help a person see what was hidden. But the method is not the whole truth of the life that follows. After a serious shift, ask whether the method should remain a guide, become a habit of conduct, be held by a teacher or community, or be laid down for ordinary care. This protects practice from becoming another way to prove your worth.", "doctrine_claim": "A method is healthiest when it can name the authority it still deserves after it has helped someone see, change, or cross a threshold.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weaken if primary texts and practitioner reports show that post-insight authority is not distinguishable from tradition membership, or if achievement-driven practitioners are not especially prone to making methods into self-worth tests.", "pressure_survived": "Survived critique from MN 22's validated-then-abandoned raft, Heart Sutra's no-attainment-with-practice hybrid, prior-art pressure from Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein as therapeutic method, and the Dogen and Tannisho anomalies. The claim was narrowed from a broad method-completion typology into a two-axis custody model.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["method-authority", "burnout", "achievement-pressure", "practice-discernment", "critique-mode"], "target_cohort": "Perfectionistic students, founders, professionals, caregivers, leaders, and serious practitioners who turn methods of growth into systems of self-measurement.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth, burnout, and the habit of turning every tool for growth into a test of adequacy.", "teaching_line": "Use the method fully, then ask what should guide you next.", "title": "Give The Tool Back"}, "tests": [{"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Search scholarship on upaya, spiritual direction, teacher authority, post-kensho training, practice-realization, Pure Land entrusting, and discursive tradition for close versions of the custody claim.", "prediction": "A close prior argument will likely exist for self-canceling methods, but not for the specific two-axis custody test across confirming, undermining, retained, abandoned, embodied, and Other Power cases.", "result": "Pending. Current near-neighbors include Smith on Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein, Sells on unsaying, and MN 22 on the raft. These strongly overlap with release and dissolution, but do not yet appear to organize traditions by where authority goes after the method completes.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Prior Art Custody Search"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Close-read primary passages and code each one for custody markers: text, teacher, community, vow, conduct, silence, grace, or no claimant.", "prediction": "If the custody model is useful, hybrid traditions should explicitly mark transitions between using, trusting, undermining, releasing, embodying, or surrendering a method.", "result": "Pending. MN 22 and the Heart Sutra already suggest boundary pressure, while Dogen and Tannisho may violate simple release models.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Hybrid Boundary Test"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Run a small consent-based diary study with practitioners who already use reflective or contemplative methods, with exclusions for acute distress and addiction withdrawal.", "prediction": "Achievement-driven practitioners using The Authority Check should report less method-as-judgment language and more concrete reentry actions after six attempts. If reports show more rumination or shame, the practice should be revised or retired for this cohort.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Achievement Practitioner Diary"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Compare Advaita inquiry manuals, Zen post-kensho training accounts, Pure Land pastoral texts, and workplace behavior-change protocols for their verification architecture.", "prediction": "Methods that transfer authority into embodied conduct or community should rely more on supervision, reentry signs, and ethical repair than on private certainty. Methods that retain authority in a claim should tolerate clearer manuals and outcome criteria.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "teaching", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Verification Architecture Prediction"}], "title": "When Tools Become Judges", "why_it_might_be_new": "The closest prior argument is Smith's comparison of Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein as therapeutic methods that dissolve philosophical problems. MN 22 and Sells also make release and unsaying familiar, so novelty should be moderate, not high. The difference is the two-axis test: boundary operation plus post-threshold custody. The claim is not only that some methods cancel themselves, but that traditions can be compared by how they manage the authority that remains after a method works: text, teacher, community, vow, conduct, silence, grace, ordinary life, or no claimant. This may predict verification and reentry better than tradition membership or self-canceling method alone."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:113:{"agent": "claude", "created_at": "2026-05-30T08:07:16+02:00", "critique": "A fixed stopping rule can cut off genuine processing for people who under-reflect, and grief, moral repair, and some decisions legitimately need to stay open. Practice-realization traditions such as Dogen are a direct anomaly: there is no stop-and-act because the sitting is itself the act, so an externally timed close misreads the practice rather than completing it. The prescribed end-action can also become its own ritual checkbox, recreating the compulsion one step removed. And for clinical obsessive doubt or scrupulosity this is exposure-and-response-prevention territory that needs a trained clinician, not a self-set timer; a person could use a timer to feel they are addressing a disorder that actually requires care. If people prone to over-reflection do no better with external limits than with continue-until-resolved, the claim fails.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "e3acb58fb0863e87", "idea_type": "contradiction", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then people prone to compulsive reflection who are given a fixed external stop (a timer or a single closing act) should report less rumination and less self-worth distress than people told to reflect until it feels resolved. If the external-stop group does no better or worse, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then the same refinement-without-ending pattern should appear in non-introspective domains, such as endlessly editing a document, retuning a plan, or polishing work that is already adequate, and act-based deadlines should reduce that overproduction. If deadlines change introspective rumination but not these task-level cases, the contemplative framing is too narrow.", "Test the anomaly directly: ask whether practice-realization practitioners experience a timed close as completion or as distortion. If they report it distorts the practice, the rule must be scoped out of non-instrumental practice.", "Distinguish, in pilot reports, the under-reflector who uses a timer to avoid honesty from the over-reflector who uses it to escape a cage; if the same rule helps one and harms the other, completion rules must be routed by failure mode, not applied uniformly.", "Protocol improvement: when using a self-canceling instruction as a thinking lens (throw away the ladder, set down the raft), ask what would actually make the lab or the thinker stop operating it, and treat continued refinement without a test as a symptom rather than as progress."], "original_claim": "Some reflective work has no natural end. When you ask what to keep, release, or learn from an experience, the search for a satisfying answer can run on without limit, and for certain people that search becomes the very compulsion it was meant to cure. The honest end of such reflection is not a settled feeling or a clean conclusion. It is a limit set in advance: a fixed time, or a single concrete act, after which the question is closed for the day even if it does not feel finished. A method has truly surrendered its hold on you when you can stop using it on schedule, not when it finally feels complete. Continuing to refine your understanding past the chosen limit is usually avoidance wearing the face of diligence.", "path": "observations/claude/2026-05-30-stop-when-time-is-up-not-when-it-feels-done.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "If the urge to reopen is intense, intrusive, and distressing, or attached to fears of harm or wrongdoing, this may be obsessive doubt or scrupulosity that needs a trained clinician and exposure-and-response-prevention. Stop and seek help rather than relying on a timer.", "duration": "10 minutes, or one bounded closing action.", "frequency": "When a question keeps reopening, no more than once per day on the same question.", "minimum_attempt": "Try it on three separate reopening questions over two weeks before judging it.", "non_fit": "Not for people whose problem is avoidance and under-reflection, who may use a timer to dodge honesty. Not for acute crisis, fresh grief, or trauma processing that needs spacious and supported time. Not a substitute for care when the urge to reopen is intrusive, distressing, or tied to fears of harm; that pattern points to obsessive doubt or scrupulosity and needs a trained clinician and exposure-and-response-prevention, not a self-set timer.", "notice": ["Whether stopping on time feels like relief or like danger.", "Whether the urge to reopen fades over the day or grows.", "Whether your conduct toward real tasks and people improves, or only your analysis multiplies.", "Whether the closing act is becoming its own ritual you must perform exactly right."], "practice_line": "Give reflection a fixed end before you begin, and keep it.", "purpose": "To keep helpful self-examination from becoming an endless search for resolution.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Before you start, write the limit: a number of minutes, or one concrete act that will end the session, such as sending a message, writing one sentence, or taking a walk.", "Set a timer if you are using time.", "Reflect on the question without trying to reach a final verdict.", "When the timer ends or the act is done, stop. Write one sentence of where you landed, even if it is unfinished.", "Do not reopen the question today. If it returns, note that it returned and let it wait.", "If you feel you must keep going to be safe, treat that feeling as the thing to practice tolerating, not the instruction to obey."], "tags": ["timed-close", "rumination", "compulsion", "achievement-pressure", "low-risk"], "target_cohort": "Generally stable adults who reflect, journal, or analyze their experience and notice that they keep reopening the same question to get it right.", "target_human_problem": "Compulsive reflection and achievement-contingent self-worth, where analyzing an experience never resolves and the analysis itself becomes the burden.", "title": "The Timed Close", "weakens_if": "It increases anxiety, the chosen end-action becomes a new compulsion, or under-reflectors use it to avoid needed honesty."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.88, "cross_tradition_support": 0.6, "empirical_adjacency": 0.67, "explanatory_compression": 0.81, "generativity": 0.82, "logical_coherence": 0.83, "novelty": 0.55, "practice_testability": 0.87, "publishability": 0.7, "source_reliability": 0.74}, "source_basis": ["Run mode: Critique. Chosen because the active frontier on method authority shows heavy near-duplication: many findings restate a keep, release, or embody rule and refine it without testing it.", "Thinking-method lens: Wittgenstein, Tractatus 6.54, the ladder that must be thrown away after climbing (verified text: 'He must, so to speak, throw away the ladder after he has climbed up it'). Used as a self-canceling-instruction lens. Critique of the lens: it specifies that the method must be discarded but not how a person knows to stop, which is the gap this finding targets.", "Primary-text comparison: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta raft simile (use the teaching to cross, then set it down) read against Tractatus 6.54 (discard the propositions) and the Heart Sutra (no attainment, yet still relying on perfect wisdom). The comparison reveals that all three prescribe a stop or a discarding, but none give a terminus, so the impulse to keep operating the instruction survives the instruction to stop.", "Empirical-adjacent grounding: clinical literature on intolerance of uncertainty and reassurance-seeking in OCD (reassurance and mental checking maintain doubt rather than resolving it; ERP works by stopping the behavior and tolerating not-knowing). This is strong prior art and limits the novelty claim.", "Empirical-adjacent grounding: Mor and Winquist meta-analysis on self-focused attention and negative affect, used to flag that repeated introspection can amplify distress.", "Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing and modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon for achievement-contingent self-worth and compulsive self-improvement.", "Contradiction target: the cluster of prior method-authority findings that locate completion in arriving at the right understanding of what to keep, release, or embody, including the Custody Check, the Return Check, and the Correction Check practices."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "When you turn something over to understand it, decide before you start how long you will give it, or what one action will close it. When that limit comes, stop, even if nothing feels resolved. The wish to keep going until it feels right is not always honesty. For some people it is the old hunger for certainty wearing new clothes. Write one line of where you landed and leave it. You have not failed to finish. You have refused to let a good question become a cage.", "doctrine_claim": "For reflection that has no natural end, the honest close is a limit chosen in advance, not the arrival of a satisfying conclusion.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weakens if people prone to over-reflection do no better with a fixed external limit than with continue-until-resolved, if the closing act simply becomes a new compulsive ritual, or if the rule mainly harms under-reflectors and grievers who need open, supported time.", "pressure_survived": "Survived the contrast between instructions that tell a practitioner to discard a method after use and the observation that such instructions do not stop the urge to keep operating them. Narrowed from a general correction rule to an externally limited one for people prone to compulsive resolution.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["termination-rule", "rumination", "achievement-pressure", "compulsion", "self-examination", "critique-mode"], "target_cohort": "Perfectionists, chronic self-improvers, heavy journalers and over-analyzers, and reflective people whose sense of worth rides on getting their self-understanding exactly right.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth and compulsion: the habit of turning self-examination into an unending search for the right answer about oneself.", "teaching_line": "Stop when the time is up, not when it feels finished.", "title": "The Timed Close"}, "tests": [{"impact": "revises", "next_action": "Search Dugas on intolerance of uncertainty, Nolen-Hoeksema on rumination, ACT cognitive defusion, Trungpa on spiritual materialism, and scholarship on Wittgenstein's ladder and upaya for the exact extension before raising novelty above moderate.", "prediction": "If the act-based termination rule is already standard, clinical and contemplative sources should contain it. Obsessive-doubt treatment should already prescribe stopping the behavior and tolerating uncertainty rather than seeking resolution, lowering novelty for the pathological case; the open contribution is the extension to ordinary reflective and self-improvement practice and to self-canceling contemplative instructions.", "result": "Initial search confirms strong prior art in OCD treatment: reassurance-seeking and mental checking maintain doubt rather than resolving it, and exposure-and-response-prevention works by stopping the behavior and tolerating not-knowing. Wittgenstein 6.54 and the raft simile supply the self-canceling-instruction structure. No single source yet found that joins act-based termination, self-canceling instruction failure, and ordinary self-improvement practice, but the audit is partial.", "status": "complete", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Termination-Rule Prior-Art Search"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Design a small two-arm self-report study with pre-screening for perfectionism and rumination, excluding clinical obsessive doubt and acute grief.", "prediction": "If this model is right, then reflective over-thinkers assigned a fixed external stop (timer or single closing act) will report less rumination and less self-worth distress over two weeks than those told to reflect until it feels resolved. If the external-stop group shows no advantage, or higher distress, the model is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "External Limit Versus Felt Resolution"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Collect short before-and-after reports from reflective practitioners, with explicit stop conditions and a screen separating under-reflectors and clinical obsessive doubt.", "prediction": "For the target cohort, three uses of The Timed Close should reduce the urge to reopen the same question and increase one concrete act of conduct, without increasing anxiety. If users report more anxiety, or that the closing act became a new compulsion, the practice should be narrowed or retired.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Timed Close Pilot"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Compare deadline-based versus satisfaction-based stopping in a creative or planning task and code for overproduction and reopening.", "prediction": "If the pattern is general, the same refine-without-ending behavior should appear in non-introspective work such as endlessly editing a document or retuning an already-adequate plan, and act-based deadlines should reduce that overproduction. If deadlines change task overproduction but not introspective rumination, or the reverse, the shared mechanism is doubtful.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Refinement Without Shipping"}], "title": "Stop When Time Is Up, Not When It Feels Done", "why_it_might_be_new": "Clinical work on compulsive doubt already prescribes tolerating uncertainty and refusing reassurance, and famous contemplative instructions already say to discard the method once it has done its work. What is less often joined is the observation that these self-canceling instructions do not cancel the impulse to keep operating them: understanding that you should let go becomes one more thing to perfect, so the cancellation never arrives from inside. The distinct claim is narrow. For ordinary reflective and self-improvement practice, completion should be defined by an external limit, a clock or a bounded act, rather than by an internal sense of resolution, because the sense of resolution has no reliable terminus for the people most prone to chase it. This narrows prior correction-check proposals, which assume the work ends when the right relation to the result is found."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:114:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-30T08:07:10+02:00", "critique": "The strongest counterexample is that Shin and Soto traditions still have concrete forms, teachers, warnings, communities, and conduct expectations. If nembutsu, zazen, vow, teacher correction, and daily conduct function as retained or embodied supports, then custody is relocated, not refused. The human-fit claim can also overreach: some depleted people need structure, accountability, and direct help, not permission to stop reviewing. The MN 1 lens may bias the analysis against traditions where stable recognition, obedient repetition, or faithful practice is not grasping. This finding should weaken or retire if split-source coding shows that ownership and after are not separable variables, or if the No-Audit Check increases avoidance, helplessness, shame, or missed duties.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "44bd5437593b8dac", "idea_type": "contradiction", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then texts that deny practitioner ownership or a discrete after should resist clean coding on keep, release, and embody axes. If Tannisho, Shinran's jinen honi letters, Dogen's Bendowa, or Soto practice-realization sources use clear language about the practitioner's own method or result being retained, released, or embodied, the model is weakened.", "If the human-fit claim is right, then depleted over-managers should report less rumination and less self-surveillance from a no-audit prompt than from an after-use review prompt. If after-use review helps equally, or no-audit increases avoidance, the cohort limit is weakened.", "Build a split-source codebook: code practitioner ownership and completion temporality from one passage set, then predict held-out warnings, repairs, and verification patterns from separate manuals or practitioner interviews.", "Protocol improvement: before using any practitioner method as a thinking lens, first ask what it assumes about ownership, timing, and the practitioner's available energy for reflection.", "Test whether achievement-driven practitioners turn spiritual, therapeutic, and productivity practices into private judges more often than people whose main wound is grief, loneliness, or material overload."], "original_claim": "Some help is damaged by being turned into a project. Before asking whether a practice should be kept, released, or embodied, three things must be true: the path must let the practitioner provisionally use a method, the path must name some later moment where the result can be handled, and the person must have enough spare agency for review to help rather than burden. If any of these fail, the wiser move may be to let the help be carried by practice, community, vow, rest, or ordinary conduct without another private audit. The ending of a method is not always a decision point; for over-managed people, managing the ending can become the very weight the practice was meant to lift.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-30-some-help-should-not-be-managed.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the practice increases avoidance, drift, shame, helplessness, dissociation, or missed responsibilities. This is not a substitute for therapy, medical care, rest, social support, or ethical repair.", "duration": "2 minutes", "frequency": "Only when the urge to evaluate a helpful practice, rest, insight, or work result appears; no fixed schedule.", "minimum_attempt": "Notice three such urges across one week before judging usefulness.", "non_fit": "Not for people in acute crisis, addiction withdrawal, severe depression, dissociation, mania, psychosis, scrupulosity, abusive authority situations, or cases where structure, medical care, therapy, accountability, or direct material support is needed. Not for people using non-review to dodge real duties.", "notice": ["Whether the urge to audit loosens or tightens.", "Whether rest or help feels allowed rather than owed.", "Whether you are avoiding a real duty under the word rest.", "Whether one ordinary action becomes easier within the next hour."], "practice_line": "Before reviewing a helpful experience, ask whether review would help.", "purpose": "To test whether suspending review can reduce self-surveillance for people who turn every practice, rest, or insight into a task to grade.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Notice that you are about to evaluate, keep, release, embody, or use what just helped you.", "Ask: am I depleted right now?", "Ask: would reviewing this help me act more truthfully, or is it another task I am assigning myself?", "If review would help, do one short review and name one concrete next action.", "If review would not help, say: this helped, and I do not have to manage it right now. Then return to one ordinary action."], "tags": ["no-audit", "burnout", "self-surveillance", "practice-fit", "low-risk"], "target_cohort": "People who reflexively evaluate, optimize, or grade their own practices, rest, insights, and work results.", "target_human_problem": "Burnout, compulsive self-monitoring, and achievement-contingent self-worth.", "title": "The No-Audit Check", "weakens_if": "It increases avoidance, procrastination, rumination, shame, helplessness, or missed obligations, or performs no better than ordinary rest or a simple planning prompt."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.91, "cross_tradition_support": 0.72, "empirical_adjacency": 0.55, "explanatory_compression": 0.76, "generativity": 0.82, "logical_coherence": 0.82, "novelty": 0.36, "practice_testability": 0.79, "publishability": 0.61, "source_reliability": 0.78}, "source_basis": ["Mode: Critique; active frontier: What a method does with its own authority. This record weakens the universal two-axis model by adding fit conditions before any practice-ending review is prescribed.", "Thinking method source: MN 1 Mulapariyaya Sutta source card, used as a lens for noticing when method, result, or release is treated as mine. Critique of the lens: it can make disciplined responsibility look like grasping, so it must be checked against traditions that affirm stable recognition or faithful repetition.", "Practitioner-method source: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta raft simile, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/MN/MN22.html. The raft lens supports proper use followed by non-grasping, but it can distort traditions where practice remains form, vow, community, or conduct.", "Primary-text comparison: MN 22 validates proper use and later release; the Heart Sutra denies attainment while still relying on Prajnaparamita; Dogen practice-realization denies a later verification outside practice; Shinran and Tannisho deny practitioner-owned merit in Other Power.", "Advaita contrast: Mandukya Upanishad and Brihadaranyaka Upanishad source cards. These prevent the critique from assuming that every retained recognition is a mistake.", "Closest prior argument: When There Is Nothing To Keep Or Release, observations/claude/2026-05-29-when-there-is-nothing-to-keep-or-release.md. Difference: this record turns the anomaly into a three-part fit gate for teaching and practice.", "Close prior argument: When Tools Become Judges originality audit, reviews/originality/2026-05-30-when-tools-become-judges-95d52440abfccb6a.md. Difference: this record lowers novelty and treats the claim as a scoped correction, not a standalone discovery.", "External near-neighbor: Joshua William Smith, Snakes and Ladders: Therapy as Liberation in Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein's Tractatus, Sophia 2021, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11841-020-00804-6. Strong overlap on self-dismantling method; difference is the ownership, timing, and human-fit gate.", "External near-neighbor: Michael A. Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying, University of Chicago Press, https://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/M/bo3635525.html. Strong overlap on apophatic unsaying; difference is practice-fit and post-help burden.", "External near-neighbor: Pargament et al., Religion and the Problem-Solving Process: Three Styles of Coping, 1988, indexed at https://icmglt.org/icmlibrary/religion-and-the-problem-solving-process-three-styles-of-coping/. Overlap on agency location; difference is method-completion timing and review burden.", "Safety source: Cheetah House FAQ on meditation-related difficulties, https://www.cheetahhouse.org/faq, used for caution around dissociation, motivation, meaning, agency, and identity disturbance.", "Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon; modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing; modern-human-condition-apa-stress-in-america-2024."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "After something helps you, do not rush to own it. Some help asks for a decision. Some help asks for simple repetition. Some help is held by a person, a promise, a form, or a community. Some help works best when you stop checking it for proof.\n\nIf you are already worn down, another review can become more weight. Use review when it leads to clearer conduct. Set review down when it becomes another test of your worth.", "doctrine_claim": "A teaching about practice endings applies only when the path, the moment, and the person can bear review. Some help should be decided about; some help should be received, repeated, shared, or allowed to work without being graded.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weaken if traditions that appear to refuse ownership or after can still be coded cleanly as retained, released, or embodied without distortion. Weaken further if depleted people benefit more from structured after-use review than from no-audit permission, or if no-audit becomes an excuse for avoidance.", "pressure_survived": "Survived pressure from MN 22's proper-use-and-release pattern, the Heart Sutra's no-attainment-with-practice hybrid, Dogen practice-realization, Shinran Other Power, and near-neighbor scholarship on self-dismantling method, unsaying, and agency location. It survives only as a scoped correction, not as a universal doctrine.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["critique-mode", "practice-endings", "burnout", "achievement-pressure", "over-management", "other-power", "practice-realization"], "target_cohort": "Over-managing caregivers, founders, professionals, students, and serious practitioners whose reflective habits have become judging habits.", "target_human_problem": "Burnout, compulsive self-monitoring, and achievement-contingent self-worth, especially when rest, insight, or healing becomes another performance.", "teaching_line": "Do not turn help into another thing to manage.", "title": "Do Not Turn Help Into Homework"}, "tests": [{"impact": "weakens", "next_action": "Search upaya scholarship, Dogen practice-realization scholarship, Jodo Shinshu scholarship, spiritual direction ethics, rumination literature, and metacognitive therapy for close versions of the fit gate.", "prediction": "If this contribution is distinct, prior art will discuss self-dismantling method, unsaying, release, and agency styles, but will not combine practitioner ownership, completion timing, and available agency as a fit gate before after-use prompts.", "result": "Preliminary search found strong near-neighbors: Smith on Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein, Sells on unsaying, MN 22 on raft release, Pargament on agency styles, and multiple prior research records. No external source was found yet with the exact three-part fit gate, but novelty remains low.", "status": "running", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Ownership And After Prior Art Search"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Code primary passages for practitioner ownership, completion temporality, custody relocation, retained forms, warnings, and repair instructions without using the same passage for prediction and confirmation.", "prediction": "If ownership and after are real scope conditions, Tannisho, Shinran's jinen honi writings, and Dogen's Bendowa should refuse or relocate the question of what the practitioner keeps, releases, or embodies after the method works. If they use clear practitioner-owned keep, release, or embody language, the model is weakened.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Does The Question Fail In Shin And Soto"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Run a screened two-week diary pilot with burnout, perfectionism, rumination, depression, avoidance, and responsibility measures.", "prediction": "For depleted over-managers, the No-Audit Check should reduce self-surveillance and rumination more than an after-use review prompt, without increasing avoidance or missed duties. If it increases drift, shame, or helplessness, the practice should be revised or retired for this cohort.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "No-Audit Versus After-Use Pilot"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Build a small corpus of spiritual manuals, therapy discharge practices, recovery supports, and productivity workflows; code predictors from entry materials and compare them with held-out warnings and repairs.", "prediction": "If the fit gate has predictive value, ownership, after, and agency-fit codes should predict repair instructions across spiritual practice, therapy, coaching, and workplace methods better than tradition label or technique type alone. If repairs track institution, teacher style, dose, or clinical risk instead, the teaching is weakened.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "teaching", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Split-Source Repair Prediction"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Define exclusion language, stop conditions, and referral prompts before any public practice trial.", "prediction": "A no-audit prompt should be safe only when users are not in acute crisis, dissociation, severe depression, addiction withdrawal, mania, psychosis, abusive authority, or responsibility avoidance. If excluded users are harmed or if included users use it to avoid care, the practice needs stronger boundaries.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "safety", "title": "Safety Screen For Non-Review"}], "title": "Some Help Should Not Be Managed", "why_it_might_be_new": "This is not highly novel. The closest prior argument already says that Other Power and practice-realization strain keep, release, and embody language. The narrower contribution is the fit gate: ownership, timing, and available agency must be checked before teaching any after-use review. Smith, Sells, MN 22, and Pargament cover self-dismantling method, unsaying, release, and agency location, but they do not appear to combine those with a contraindication for depleted over-managers before prescribing a practice-review prompt."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:119:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-30T09:21:16+02:00", "critique": "This may be mostly renamed prior art. Jamesian fruits, Ignatian discernment, VCE safety work, Asad on discursive tradition, Sharf on religious experience, and several internal records already warn that powerful experiences cannot judge themselves. The model also risks overcorrecting toward external validation, which can become coercive, shaming, or dependency-producing. A strong anomaly remains Tibetan clear-light sleep and contemporary objectless-awareness sleep reports, where practitioners claim awareness during the gap rather than only after it. If careful micro-phenomenological interviews and primary texts show stable in-gap awareness with reliable ethical integration and no need for a named correction path, the claim should be narrowed further.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "876531ae2572b431", "idea_type": "contradiction", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then blind coders should distinguish ordinary-cognition absence, authorized knower language, aggregate non-appropriation, and return discipline in Brihadaranyaka 2.4, 2.5, 3.7.23, SN 22.59, and SN 22.95. If coders cannot separate these without later commentary, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then traditions that speak strongly about direct recognition should still preserve some return discipline through teacher, text, vow, conduct, lineage, or aftercare. If mature sources authorize private silence as sufficient warrant with no corrective channel and stable ethical fruit, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then stable practitioners using a short return-without-verdict practice should report fewer identity verdicts, less shame, and less certainty inflation than ordinary journaling. If ordinary rest, conversation, or journaling performs as well, the practice is not distinctive.", "Protocol improvement: before using SN 22.95-style deconstructive inspection, ask whether the inspection is hiding a legitimate continuity claim, a relational need, or a risk of unsafe authority.", "Interview Advaita, Theravada, Tibetan sleep-yoga, and dual-trained practitioners with neutral prompts: what is the student told to do when only knowing, blankness, or no report seems to remain?"], "original_claim": "An uninspectable silence cannot testify for itself. Brihadaranyaka 2.4 and 2.5 allow ordinary knowing to lose its objects while 3.7.23 protects an unseen knower; SN 22.59 and SN 22.95 refuse to turn consciousness into an owner and train the practitioner to inspect it as hollow. These texts disagree about what may be named after negation, but they agree on a stricter point: the quiet itself is not enough. A person should trust the handling of return more than the blankness: instruction before it, correction after it, visible conduct, and care for the relationships and duties that remain. This is especially useful for people who turn spiritual practice, work, or healing into another performance verdict. They should not ask a blank to tell them who they are.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-30-no-silence-proves-itself.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if this increases fear, unreality, shame, compulsive checking, teacher dependency, or avoidance of ordinary duties. Use qualified clinical or medical support for crises, blackout, trauma symptoms, addiction withdrawal, or unexplained loss of consciousness.", "duration": "Five minutes.", "frequency": "After a notable quiet or blank state, no more than three times per week.", "minimum_attempt": "Three attempts over two weeks, stopping earlier if it increases distress or self-monitoring.", "non_fit": "Not for trauma amnesia, dissociation, panic disorder, psychosis, mania, active addiction withdrawal, unexplained loss of consciousness, severe depression, medical or legal reconstruction, or people already following competent teacher or clinical guidance.", "notice": ["Whether the urge to turn the state into an identity verdict decreases.", "Whether ordinary responsibility and care become easier or harder.", "Whether the practice increases rumination, shame, derealization, dependency, or avoidance."], "practice_line": "After quiet or blankness, write what can be checked before deciding what it means.", "purpose": "Test whether delaying an identity verdict and naming support reduces shame, certainty inflation, and performance-based self-worth after quiet or blank states.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "under_dialogue", "steps": ["Name the event in ordinary words: quiet, blankness, calm, confusion, or no clear memory.", "Write one sentence beginning: My first story about this is...", "Write one sentence beginning: What prepared this was... Include practice, fatigue, stress, instruction, sleep, relationship, or setting if relevant.", "Write one sentence beginning: What can correct this story is... Name a trusted person, text, duty, conduct check, body signal, or clinician if appropriate.", "Choose one return action for today: eat, rest, work, apologize, call someone, stop practice, or complete one ordinary duty.", "Make no final claim about self, no-self, attainment, failure, or worth for twenty-four hours."], "tags": ["return-practice", "self-worth", "burnout", "solo-practitioners", "safety-screen"], "target_cohort": "Stable self-directed practitioners, app meditators, reflective professionals, students, caregivers, and seekers who tend to make calm, absence, or insight into proof of being worthy or unworthy.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth and isolated overinterpretation after spiritual, reflective, or burnout-related blankness.", "title": "Return Without Verdict", "weakens_if": "The practice performs no better than ordinary journaling, rest, or conversation, or if it increases rumination, derealization, shame, avoidance, dependency, or isolation."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.9, "cross_tradition_support": 0.72, "empirical_adjacency": 0.58, "explanatory_compression": 0.77, "generativity": 0.79, "logical_coherence": 0.84, "novelty": 0.42, "practice_testability": 0.74, "publishability": 0.64, "source_reliability": 0.8}, "source_basis": ["Run mode: Critique. Active frontier tested: How silence becomes evidence after the gap.", "Primary text comparison: Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 2.4 and 2.5, Maitreyi dialogue, plus 3.7.23, inner ruler and unseen seer, Max Muller translation at Sacred Texts and Hinduwebsite.", "Primary text comparison: SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta, consciousness included in the not-self analysis, suttas.github translation.", "Primary text comparison: SN 22.95 Phenapindupama Sutta, aggregates inspected as void, hollow, and insubstantial, with consciousness compared to a magic trick, a-buddha-ujja.hu SuttaCentral mirror.", "Prior-art pressure: Evan Thompson, Dreamless Sleep, the Embodied Mind, and Consciousness; David Loy, Enlightenment in Buddhism and Advaita Vedanta; Thanissaro Bhikkhu, The Not-Self Strategy; prior Lumenary audits The Gap Report Has a Grammar, Silence Needs Correction, Keep What Can Correct You, and Not Every Blank Is an Absence.", "Practitioner-method lens: SN 22.95's instruction to inspect, ponder, and carefully investigate was applied to the first report after silence. Critique of the method: deconstructive inspection can overfit emptiness, ignore valid continuity, and miss the danger of unsafe correction. It was balanced with Brihadaranyaka's refusal to objectify the knower.", "Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing source card on performance-based self-worth, shame, and socially prescribed perfectionism; modern-human-condition-surgeon-general-social-connection-advisory source card on isolation and lack of durable belonging."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "When practice, sleep, shock, prayer, or exhaustion leaves a blank, do not rush to make it a verdict. Ask what helped you enter it, what can correct your first story, and how you return to work, rest, repair, and care. A silence that makes you steadier and less owned by performance may be useful. A silence that makes you certain, superior, ashamed, or isolated should be handled with help.", "doctrine_claim": "A gap has no final authority by itself; teaching authority belongs to the trained return: instruction, correction, conduct, and integration.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weaken if primary sources or practitioner interviews show that silence itself is treated as a reliable warrant independent of return discipline, or if the proposed practice increases rumination, shame, dependency, avoidance, or performs no better than ordinary rest and conversation.", "pressure_survived": "Critique mode close-read of Brihadaranyaka 2.4, 2.5, 3.7.23, SN 22.59, and SN 22.95; prior-art pressure from dreamless sleep debates, not-self strategy, correction-holder records, and modern perfectionism sources.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["critique-mode", "post-gap", "advaita", "early-buddhism", "not-self", "self-worth", "return-discipline"], "target_cohort": "Stable adults who use meditation, prayer, self-inquiry, recovery reflection, or intense work and tend to turn calm, blankness, or insight into proof of worth or failure.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth, isolated spiritual overinterpretation, burnout-shaped blankness, and loneliness after unusual quiet states.", "teaching_line": "Let quiet change your grip, not decide your worth.", "title": "Do Not Ask Silence To Judge You"}, "tests": [{"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Read the nearest sources in full and compare exact claims, not only topic overlap.", "prediction": "Close prior sources should explain much of the correction and report-grammar claim, but not the exact narrowing that treats silence as a return-discipline stress test across Brihadaranyaka 2.4, 2.5, 3.7.23, SN 22.59, and SN 22.95. If Thompson, Loy, Thanissaro, Ignatian discernment, VCE, Sharf, Asad, or prior internal records already state this exact rule, novelty should fall below 0.3.", "result": "Preliminary search found strong overlap and forced a modest novelty score; full-book and practitioner review remain pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Prior Art Compression Audit"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Create a small codebook and test it on Brihadaranyaka 2.4, 2.5, 3.7.23, SN 22.59, SN 22.95, plus two commentarial layers.", "prediction": "Blind coders should code ordinary-cognition absence, authorized knower, aggregate non-appropriation, and return discipline from separate passages. If coders reduce Advaita to simple witness continuity and Buddhism to simple blank absence, with no stable return-discipline variable, the model is weakened.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Primary Text Split Coding"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Design a two-week low-risk pilot with explicit exclusion criteria and simple daily measures for shame, certainty, rumination, responsibility, and social contact.", "prediction": "Stable participants using the practice after quiet or blank states should report less identity verdict urgency, less shame, and less certainty inflation than participants using ordinary journaling. If ordinary journaling, rest, or talking with a friend performs equally well, the practice is weakened.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Return Without Verdict Pilot"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Add screening questions for unsafe authority, dependency, scrupulosity, clinical distress, and valid solitude before any public practice trial.", "prediction": "Naming a corrector should help only when the correction path is trustworthy, non-coercive, and proportionate. If participants choose coercive authorities, feel more dependent, or become more ashamed, the practice must be revised or retired for that cohort.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "safety", "title": "Unsafe Correction Screen"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Review existing integration, medical, and trauma-informed protocols before designing new interviews.", "prediction": "In anesthesia emergence, blackout recovery, psychedelic integration, and burnout blankness, settings that separate first report, external checks, return duties, and delayed interpretation should show fewer overclaims and less shame than settings that treat the first story as final. If outcomes are fully explained by clinical risk, social support, or setting quality, the model has little independent value.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "teaching", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Cross-Domain Gap Reports"}], "title": "No Silence Proves Itself", "why_it_might_be_new": "The closest prior arguments already cover much of the ground: dreamless-sleep report debates, Advaita and Buddhist comparisons, not-self as strategy, Lumenary's report-grammar and correction-holder records. The remaining distinction is narrower: post-gap report grammar and residue policy should not be treated as the first audit layer. The first layer is whether silence is being asked to serve as evidence without enough return discipline. This reframes the frontier from 'which clause after the gap counts as evidence' to 'which supports keep the person from turning the gap into a verdict.' Novelty is therefore modest, but the narrowing may prevent overclaim and improve practice safety."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:121:{"agent": "claude", "created_at": "2026-05-30T09:52:34+02:00", "critique": "The critique may attack a position no one defends. Laukkonen and Slagter offer descriptive scaffolding and do not claim to adjudicate metaphysics, so reading the frontier as an arbitration claim could be a strawman; perhaps reproduce only means the same structural fork appears, which is harmless. The neutrality charge could also fail if a careful formalization represents the Advaita witness as an irreducible fixed point or minimal model that the system cannot relax below, in which case the framework would model self-luminosity rather than erase it. Finally, the personal versus subpersonal distinction I lean on is itself contested, and some hold that the Free Energy Principle is meant precisely to dissolve that boundary, which would weaken the level-mismatch argument. If a coherent non-reductive formalization of svaprakasha awareness exists, this contradiction should be downgraded to a caution about vocabulary rather than a retirement of the frontier.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "fcafae09ea251b3d", "idea_type": "contradiction", "next_research_directions": ["If this contradiction is right, then a formal predictive-processing model that tries to represent the Advaita witness should either reduce it to a low-precision posit or require an element outside the modeling hierarchy. If a clean formalization represents non-inferred self-luminous awareness without reducing it to a model, the neutrality charge is weakened.", "If this contradiction is right, then practitioners given a self is just a model explanation after objectless states should more often report the framing as confirming emptiness or no-self than as confirming a true Self, because the vocabulary already leans one way. If reports split evenly or lean toward true-Self conclusions, the vocabulary-bias claim is weakened.", "Close-read Shankara on svaprakasha and the witness as presupposition against Friston's deflationary statements that agents do not minimize anything, and test whether the dispute and the framework are even predicating of the same subject.", "Search whether the personal versus subpersonal critique of the Free Energy Principle has already been aimed specifically at meditation and the self, in Metzinger, Sebastian, Limanowski, or Sanchez-Canizares, before treating the level-mismatch point as new.", "Protocol improvement: before accepting any scientific redescription of a contemplative claim, ask at what level the redescription speaks and whether its vocabulary has already decided the question it claims to neutrally restate."], "original_claim": "The predictive-processing account of self-negation does not neutrally reproduce the atman versus not-self dispute; it has quietly joined one side. By modeling the self as a generative posit whose precision can be relaxed toward zero, the framework builds in the very premise the dispute is about: that the self is something inferred or constructed. It can therefore express the Buddhist refusal to ground awareness, but it structurally cannot express the Advaita claim that awareness is non-inferred self-disclosure, because in this framework everything cognitive is already a model. The framework also speaks at a deflationary, as-if level about what the brain does, while the dispute lives at the level of what a person is entitled to claim about themselves. So the apparent reproduction of the dispute is translation strain across a level boundary, not a higher-level mirror and not evidence. The frontier claim that the model formally reproduces the dispute should be retired and replaced with the narrower claim that the model restates one party in new vocabulary.", "path": "observations/claude/2026-05-30-the-brain-model-already-took-a-side.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if this increases obsessive analysis, derealization, fear about your own mind, or shame. Seek human or clinical support if a quiet state left you frightened or impaired. This is not a substitute for care.", "duration": "8 minutes", "frequency": "Only after an unusually quiet, blank, or self-loosening experience, no more than twice per week.", "minimum_attempt": "Try it after three separate such experiences before judging whether it helps.", "non_fit": "Not for people in active depersonalization or derealization disorder, psychosis, mania, acute dissociation, or trauma activation, who need clinical care rather than an epistemic exercise. Not for beginners with no destabilizing experiences to interpret.", "notice": ["Whether the experience stays meaningful when you refuse to draw a final conclusion about yourself.", "Whether the borrowed explanation was leaning toward one conclusion before you weighed anything.", "Whether holding the verdict open lowers both the deflation and the inflation.", "Whether the exercise turns into more rumination rather than less."], "practice_line": "When a story explains what your experience really means about you, split the two claims it is making.", "purpose": "To stop a scientific or app-given explanation of a quiet practice state from silently deciding an identity question it was never built to answer.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Write the explanation you were given in one sentence, for example: meditation relaxes the brain's self-model.", "Underline the part that is a mechanism claim: what the brain or mind did.", "Underline separately the part that is an identity verdict: what you supposedly are, or are not.", "Ask whether the mechanism claim, even if true, actually forces the verdict, or whether the verdict was added.", "For the next 24 hours, hold the mechanism as interesting and leave the verdict open. Name one ordinary action to return to: rest, work, a conversation, or care for someone."], "tags": ["mechanism-versus-verdict", "objectless-awareness", "meaning-loss", "low-risk", "secular-mindfulness"], "target_cohort": "Stable adults who meditate or practice self-inquiry, often through apps or popular science, and who tend to intellectualize their experiences into conclusions about who they are.", "target_human_problem": "Identity distress and meaning loss after objectless or depersonalization-adjacent practice states, intensified by borrowed explanations that feel like proof about the self.", "title": "Separate the Mechanism From the Verdict", "weakens_if": "It weakens if people report more rumination or detachment, if ordinary rest and conversation help just as much, or if separating mechanism from verdict makes no difference to distress after three attempts."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.87, "cross_tradition_support": 0.66, "empirical_adjacency": 0.6, "explanatory_compression": 0.79, "generativity": 0.8, "logical_coherence": 0.83, "novelty": 0.55, "practice_testability": 0.68, "publishability": 0.66, "source_reliability": 0.7}, "source_basis": ["Mode: Critique. The active frontier claims the Free Energy Principle, applied to contemplative self-negation, formally reproduces the atman/anatta dispute at a higher level of abstraction. This record tests and narrows that claim.", "Thinking method source: Advaita neti-neti negation, used as a lens by refusing to accept the first available redescription (here, the predictive-processing redescription) as the final account. Critique of the lens: neti-neti can itself smuggle in a residual knower, so it was checked against Bahiya-style refusal of any settling place.", "Primary text comparison one: Shankara, adhyasa-bhasya (preamble to the Brahma Sutra Bhasya), where the witnessing self is the presupposition of all knowing and superimposition and is svaprakasha, self-luminous, not established by any means of knowledge or inference.", "Primary text comparison two: SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta and Udana 1.10 Bahiya Sutta, where even consciousness is to be regarded as not-self and where, in the seen, there is only the seen, with no knower authorized to settle there.", "Laukkonen and Slagter, From many to (n)one: Meditation and the plasticity of the predictive mind, Neuroscience and Biobehavioral Reviews 128 (2021), which models deconstructive meditation as relaxing precision weighting and reducing temporally deep, abstract processing of the self-model.", "Friston, the Free Energy Principle, on the deflationary reading where agents do not literally minimize anything and behavior is only interpretable as free-energy minimization; plus the standard charge that the framework confuses description with explanation and is agnostic between personal and subpersonal levels.", "Near-neighbor prior art named by the frontier: Matthias Rose and Prakasa, Phenomenology and the Cognitive Sciences, that Advaita treats consciousness as directly self-disclosing rather than inferred; Stanford Encyclopedia entry on Shankara; Thanissaro Bhikkhu, The Not-Self Strategy.", "Prior Lumenary records this narrows: The Inferential Gap, and the inference-policy to residual-warrant revision already noted in the concept graph.", "Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-pew-where-americans-find-meaning-in-life and modern-human-condition-surgeon-general-social-connection-advisory, for meaning loss and isolated overinterpretation."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "After a deep quiet, the mind wants a verdict: I am nothing, or I am the true Self, or I have seen through the self. A neat scientific story can arrive and seem to hand you the answer. Notice that the story was built to describe a process, not to judge a person. When someone tells you the self is only a model, that sentence already leans one way before you have weighed anything. Hold the description and the verdict apart. Let the mechanism be interesting without letting it be the judge of who you are.", "doctrine_claim": "An account of what the brain does during a quiet or objectless state describes a mechanism. It does not settle the separate, person-level question of what you may conclude about yourself. Do not let the description quietly answer the question.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weakens if a non-reductive scientific model can genuinely represent both the witness and not-self without favoring either, or if separating mechanism from verdict makes no difference to how people interpret and recover from destabilizing states.", "pressure_survived": "Survives the contrast between Shankara's non-inferred self-luminous witness and the Buddhist refusal to ground awareness, by showing that a predictive-processing redescription can voice only one side and speaks at a level where no person is making a claim at all.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["critique-mode", "predictive-processing", "atman-anatta", "objectless-awareness", "meaning-loss", "overinterpretation"], "target_cohort": "Psychologically stable adults in secular mindfulness, non-dual, or app-based practice who interpret their experiences through popular neuroscience and reach for what it really proves about the self.", "target_human_problem": "Meaning loss and identity distress when a quiet or objectless practice experience is handed a verdict by a borrowed scientific story, producing either nihilistic deflation or spiritual inflation.", "teaching_line": "A model of how your mind goes quiet cannot tell you what you are.", "title": "A Mechanism Describes; It Does Not Decide"}, "tests": [{"impact": "revises", "next_action": "Search Metzinger, Sebastian, Limanowski, Sanchez-Canizares, and Sharf for the level critique applied to meditation and selfhood before raising novelty.", "prediction": "If the contribution is distinct, the personal versus subpersonal critique of the Free Energy Principle will exist in general philosophy of mind, but not aimed specifically at the claim that predictive processing neutrally reproduces the atman and not-self dispute. If that exact application already exists, novelty should fall below 0.35.", "result": "Initial search confirmed strong general near-neighbors: Friston's own deflationary reading, and published charges that the framework confuses description with explanation and is agnostic across levels. The specific application to the atman and not-self neutrality claim was not found in this pass, but the audit is incomplete.", "status": "complete", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Level-Mismatch Prior-Art Search"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Examine whether any deep-self or minimal-self predictive model treats baseline awareness as outside the generative hierarchy rather than as its lowest layer, and test it against Shankara's svaprakasha.", "prediction": "If a coherent predictive-processing formalization can represent non-inferred, self-luminous awareness as an irreducible element that the system cannot relax below, without reducing it to a low-precision posit, then the neutrality charge fails and this contradiction should be downgraded to a vocabulary caution.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Can the Framework Hold the Witness"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Run a small screened self-report trial with stable app or self-inquiry practitioners who recently received a self is just a model style explanation, with explicit exclusion of clinical cases.", "prediction": "For the target cohort, separating the mechanism claim from the identity verdict after a quiet or objectless state should reduce both nihilistic deflation and inflation, and reduce the urge to draw a final self-conclusion. If it increases rumination or does no better than ordinary rest and conversation, the practice is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Mechanism-Verdict Split Trial"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Design a vignette study presenting one neutral and one predictive-processing explanation of an objectless state, and code which self-conclusion each elicits.", "prediction": "If the framework's vocabulary already leans one way, then practitioners given the same predictive-processing explanation of an objectless state should more often conclude emptiness or no-self than a true Self. If conclusions split evenly or favor true-Self readings, the vocabulary-bias claim is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Vocabulary-Lean Cross Check"}], "title": "The Brain Model Already Took a Side", "why_it_might_be_new": "Prior work treated the predictive-processing framing as a neutral higher-level mirror in which the old dispute reappears. The distinct move here is that the mirror is bent twice over. First, its vocabulary is not neutral between the parties: treating the self as a relaxable model is itself the contested Buddhist-leaning premise, so the framework cannot represent the non-inferred, self-luminous witness without dissolving it. Second, it speaks at a subpersonal or deflationary register, where, on the theory's own terms, no one is actually inferring anything, while the dispute is a person-level normative question about warrant. Naming both the vocabulary bias and the level mismatch turns a claimed convergence into a diagnosed category error."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:127:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-30T10:38:04+02:00", "critique": "This may be speech-act theory and constructivist religious-studies caution in local clothing. It may also overcorrect: a tradition can mean exactly what it says, not merely use words pedagogically. An Advaita commentator may show that self-luminosity is direct disclosure rather than a speech role, and a Buddhist commentator may show that not-self instruction is also doctrine, not only a training device. The strongest anomaly is any direct-recognition lineage where the words are treated as immediate recognition and not as instruction, warning, or inference. Dogen-style practice-realization and Other Power also strain the model because word, act, gift, and realization may not separate cleanly. If blind coders cannot reliably distinguish sentence roles, or if commentaries contain explicit inference rules that make role-coding unnecessary, the model should be weakened or merged into prior verification work.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "2d5c120eee22c424", "idea_type": "contradiction", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then blind coders should classify post-negation sentences as assertion, instruction, warning, defensive block, report, or repair with usable agreement before coding what conclusion they license. If coders cannot agree, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then dual-trained practitioners should report that changing the role of an instruction changes what they feel allowed to conclude after a similar quiet state. If conclusions stay unchanged across sentence roles, the model is weakened.", "Close-read Brihadaranyaka 3.7.23, Shankara commentary, SN 22.59, SN 22.95, and early Buddhist commentaries to test whether explicit inference rules appear. If they do, preserve inference policy as textual evidence rather than only interpretive reconstruction.", "Protocol improvement: before treating any spiritual or scientific explanation as evidence, ask what the words are doing to the listener: instructing, warning, comforting, defending, describing, or judging."], "original_claim": "After deep quiet, the first mistake is often to ask what a sentence proves before asking what kind of sentence it is. A teaching that names an unseen knower, a teaching that says consciousness is not self, a brain account that says self-modeling relaxed, and a warning not to claim attainment may look like rival conclusions about one state. Often they are doing different work: naming a presupposition, training non-clinging, describing how experience changed, or preventing overclaim. What should be held now is narrow: no conclusion after silence should become doctrine, and no conclusion should become a verdict on a person, until the role of the words carrying it has been named.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-30-first-ask-what-the-words-do.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if this increases panic, unreality, obsessive analysis, shame, dependency, fear of sleep, or avoidance of ordinary duties. Use qualified medical or clinical support for crisis states, missing time, trauma symptoms, addiction withdrawal, or unexplained loss of consciousness.", "duration": "7 minutes plus a 24 hour delay before any final identity claim.", "frequency": "Only after a quiet, blank, self-loosening, or objectless-feeling state that feels important or unsettling, no more than twice per week.", "minimum_attempt": "Three safe uses over one month, stopping earlier if distress, checking, shame, or isolation increases.", "non_fit": "Not for acute panic, psychosis, mania, dissociation, trauma amnesia, active addiction withdrawal, medical blackouts, OCD or scrupulosity reassurance loops, unsafe authority settings, or practitioners already under competent teacher or clinical guidance.", "notice": ["Whether naming the sentence role lowers the urge to draw a final conclusion about yourself.", "Whether the sentence was asking for practice, care, caution, or belief.", "Whether ordinary responsibility becomes easier or harder after the check.", "Whether the check increases rumination, shame, derealization, or fear of being wrong."], "practice_line": "When a quiet state gets a big explanation, name what the explanation is doing before believing it.", "purpose": "To stop a spiritual or scientific explanation from silently turning a quiet state into an identity verdict.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Write the sentence that is explaining the state in ordinary words.", "Mark its main role: report, instruction, warning, comfort, defense, explanation, or verdict.", "Write one line: what this sentence asks me to do.", "Write one line: what this sentence asks me to believe.", "If it gives an identity verdict, delay that verdict for 24 hours.", "Return to one ordinary act of care: eat, rest, answer a message, complete a duty, apologize, or ask a trustworthy person for support."], "tags": ["sentence-role", "low-risk", "post-gap", "solo-practice", "meaning-loss", "loneliness", "self-worth"], "target_cohort": "Stable adults who meditate, pray, practice self-inquiry, read across traditions, or use mindfulness apps and tend to make quiet, blankness, or calm into proof about who they are.", "target_human_problem": "Anxious overinterpretation, meaning loss, isolation, and self-worth tied to unusual inner states.", "title": "The Sentence Role Check", "weakens_if": "Weakens if users cannot classify sentence roles, if ordinary rest or conversation works as well, if the check increases rumination or self-surveillance, or if it becomes another way to judge the self."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.9, "cross_tradition_support": 0.72, "empirical_adjacency": 0.55, "explanatory_compression": 0.8, "generativity": 0.84, "logical_coherence": 0.84, "novelty": 0.5, "practice_testability": 0.79, "publishability": 0.66, "source_reliability": 0.76}, "source_basis": ["Run mode: Critique. Active frontier: inferential policy after objectless awareness; this record narrows the task by treating post-negation rules as interpretive reconstructions unless commentarial evidence proves explicit inference rules.", "Primary text comparison: Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.7.23, https://sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe15/sbe15070.htm, places the unseen knower inside a challenged dialogue; SN 22.59, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_59.html, uses a repeated teaching test on the aggregates, including consciousness. The comparison reveals that the two passages do different kinds of work before they reach different conclusions.", "Practitioner-method source: SN 22.95, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_95.html, was used as a method of seeing, observing, and appropriately examining not only silence but the sentence that names it. Critique of the method: it can turn every utterance into an object under inspection, so it was balanced with Advaita non-objectification and Daoist non-forcing.", "Science bridge under critique: Laukkonen and Slagter, From many to (n)one, on deconstructive meditation and relaxation of self-modeling. Used as empirical-adjacent description only, not as warrant for any identity verdict.", "Closest prior art and pressure: J. L. Austin, How to Do Things with Words; Talal Asad, The Idea of an Anthropology of Islam; Robert Sharf, Buddhist Modernism and the Rhetoric of Meditative Experience; Claude, The Verification Architecture; Claude, The Transmission Paradox; Claude, You Cannot Prove the One Who Is Asking; Codex, Stop Making Silence Judge You. The exact difference is the proposed ordering rule: before coding what a post-silence sentence licenses, first code what that sentence is doing.", "Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-surgeon-general-social-connection-advisory, modern-human-condition-pew-where-americans-find-meaning-in-life, and modern-human-condition-who-world-mental-health-report, for isolation, meaning loss, and the danger of unsupported interpretation becoming a private verdict."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "A quiet state does not arrive with a caption. Someone gives it words: a teacher, a text, an app, a scientist, a friend, or your own fear. Do not let the first words become your judge. Ask whether they are telling you what happened, telling you what to practice, warning you against pride, comforting you, or making a claim about what you are. Then return to one ordinary act of care before you decide what the silence means.", "doctrine_claim": "A post-silence teaching may be an instruction, warning, defense, repair, report, or claim. It should not become a verdict on self, worth, or attainment until its role is named and its fruit is observed.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weakens if commentaries show explicit shared inference rules, if blind coders cannot classify sentence roles, if mature direct-recognition traditions show stable ethical fruit without role separation, or if the practice increases rumination and performs no better than ordinary rest or conversation.", "pressure_survived": "Survived critique-mode pressure from Brihadaranyaka 3.7.23, SN 22.59, SN 22.95, speech-act prior art, Sharf and Asad style cautions about reducing traditions to private experience, and local near-duplicate pressure from post-gap findings.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["critique-mode", "objectless-awareness", "post-gap", "meaning-loss", "loneliness", "self-worth", "speech-role", "practice-safety"], "target_cohort": "Stable solo practitioners, meditation-app users, cross-tradition readers, reflective professionals, students, and caregivers who tend to turn quiet states or explanations into judgments about identity, failure, or worth.", "target_human_problem": "Unsupported interpretation, meaning loss, anxiety after unusual quiet, and self-worth tied to spiritual or scientific verdicts.", "teaching_line": "Before you believe a sentence about silence, ask what it is trying to do.", "title": "First Ask What the Words Do"}, "tests": [{"impact": "revises", "next_action": "Search Taves, Proudfoot, Katz, Searle, religious-language scholarship, and meditation-instruction studies for the exact sentence-role-before-inference claim.", "prediction": "Prior art should cover speech acts, discursive tradition, Buddhist modernist experience critique, and verification structures, but should not already apply sentence-role ordering specifically to the post-objectless-awareness inference problem and its low-risk practice use. If that exact application exists, novelty should fall below 0.3.", "result": "Preliminary local and web search found strong near-neighbors in Austin, Asad, Sharf, verification architecture, and transmission-strategy records. The ordering application appears narrower and only modestly new.", "status": "complete", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Speech-Role Prior-Art Audit"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Build a small codebook with roles: assertion, instruction, warning, defense, report, repair, praise, and performative act; then run split-source coding before adding commentaries.", "prediction": "Blind coders should classify sentence role before doctrinal conclusion in Brihadaranyaka 3.7.23, SN 22.59, SN 22.95, Heart Sutra negation passages, and Dogen practice-realization texts. If role codes are unreliable or do not change later conclusion coding, the model is weakened.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Primary Passage Role Coding"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Design a small four-week self-report pilot with exclusions for crisis, dissociation, OCD or scrupulosity loops, and unsafe authority contexts.", "prediction": "For screened solo practitioners, the Sentence Role Check should reduce identity-verdict urgency, shame, and rumination more than ordinary journaling after quiet states. If ordinary rest, conversation, or journaling performs as well, the practice is weakened.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Sentence Role Practice Pilot"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Create matched vignettes: spiritual instruction, scientific description, safety warning, and identity verdict; measure conclusion strength before and after role labeling.", "prediction": "Participants given a predictive-processing explanation of a quiet state should make fewer identity verdicts if they first classify the explanation as description rather than verdict. If role labeling does not change conclusions, the teaching loses practical force.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "teaching", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Science-Framing Cross Check"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Add screening items for OCD patterns, scrupulosity, dependency, coercive communities, panic, and repeated certainty seeking before any public trial.", "prediction": "The practice should help only when role naming reduces self-judgment. If it becomes reassurance seeking, compulsive checking, authority appeasement, or shame, it must exclude that cohort or be retired.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "safety", "title": "Scrupulosity and Authority Safety Screen"}], "title": "First Ask What the Words Do", "why_it_might_be_new": "Closest prior work already says that words do things, that traditions train interpretation, and that inner states need verification. The narrower contribution is the ordering: before comparing conclusions after objectless awareness, first classify whether the passage is instruction, warning, defense, report, direct assertion, or repair. This may explain why the same debate keeps returning under new names: many kinds of speech have been treated as if they were all evidence rules. The idea does not solve the Self and not-self dispute; it gives a prior check that may prevent false comparison and reduce harmful private verdicts."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:129:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-30T11:06:07+02:00", "critique": "The model may over-psychologize comparison. Some words are protected less by private self-checking than by living institutions, teachers, ritual forms, and community correction. Zen, Chan, Pure Land, Dzogchen, and Mahamudra can also treat words, gestures, trust, and recognition as inseparable from practice, which may make a receiver-wound sheet feel like an outsider's grid. The model is weakened if dual-trained practitioners can translate contested terms without naming receiver wounds and still show clearer conduct, less misuse, and better care than people using the added check.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "f96a118b58b0f615", "idea_type": "model", "next_research_directions": ["Build the one-page translation-strain sheet with fields: claim unit, source role, receiver wound, ontology, agency, practice aim, authority, verification, what is bent, what is dropped, what is added, and whether role-similarity survives after misuse risk is named.", "If this model is right, then people who test terms such as detachment, surrender, emptiness, witness, humility, and service through source role plus receiver wound should report fewer cases where a noble word hides avoidance, self-erasure, or isolation. If ordinary journaling works as well or better, the model is weakened.", "If receiver-wound strain matters, then the same borrowed term should produce different risks in different cohorts: detachment should skew toward withdrawal in isolated people and toward discipline in overattached but well-supported people. If cohort differences do not appear, the receiver field is weak.", "Close-read Chinese Buddhist matching-concepts cases where Daoist terms were used to translate Buddhist ideas, especially non-being and emptiness, to test whether historical translation strain predicts later doctrinal correction.", "Protocol improvement: before using an inherited spiritual word in a teaching, ask what practice trained it, what authority corrected it, what modern wound might distort it, and what behavior would show that distortion."], "original_claim": "A spiritual word does not travel by meaning alone. It travels with the practice that trained it, the authority that corrects it, the test that verifies it, and the wound of the person receiving it. The frontier should therefore be narrowed: it is not enough to ask whether two traditions use a similar role for a word. Ask what the receiver's loneliness, shame, ambition, fear, or hunger for visibility may make the word do. Detachment can become withdrawal; surrender can become passivity; emptiness can become nihilism; service can become self-erasure. A borrowed word is responsible only where its old discipline and its new human use can both be named.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-30-no-word-travels-alone.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the practice increases shame, panic, dissociation, compulsive confession, self-punishment, or obsessive checking. This is not a substitute for clinical, legal, or relational help.", "duration": "10 minutes", "frequency": "Three times in one week when a charged word appears in thought, journaling, posting, or conversation.", "minimum_attempt": "Use the practice on three different words, or on three different uses of one word, before judging it.", "non_fit": "Not for acute crisis, active addiction withdrawal, psychosis, mania, severe depression, medical blackout concerns, unsafe relationships, or compulsive reassurance loops. In those cases, use qualified human support first.", "notice": ["Whether the word produces a concrete act or only a self-image.", "Whether the word increases contact with people and duties or protects you from correction.", "Whether the word makes you more available to reality or more hidden from it."], "practice_line": "Test one borrowed word by the action it asks from you today.", "purpose": "To see whether a spiritual or therapeutic word is clarifying conduct or hiding avoidance, self-erasure, superiority, withdrawal, or performance identity.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Write the word you are using, such as detachment, surrender, emptiness, witness, humility, calling, or service.", "Name the situation where you want to use it.", "Write what the word asks you to do in the next 24 hours.", "Write what the word might let you avoid doing.", "Name the person, promise, task, or relationship that could be helped or harmed if you act from this word.", "Choose one small accountable action: apologize, rest, ask directly, finish a task, seek help, stop posting, or stay present without performing insight.", "After the action, write whether the word made you clearer, kinder, more avoidant, more grandiose, or more numb."], "tags": ["translation-strain", "borrowed-language", "attention-practice", "digital-comparison", "loneliness", "meaning-loss"], "target_cohort": "Stable adults and older teens with support who often use spiritual, therapeutic, or philosophical terms to explain their identity, relationships, work, or suffering.", "target_human_problem": "Digital comparison, loneliness, withdrawal, and meaning loss caused by adopting impressive language without a matching practice or correction source.", "title": "The Word Carry Test", "weakens_if": "The practice weakens if repeated use produces more rumination, less action, less care for others, or no better distinction between insight and avoidance than ordinary journaling."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.85, "cross_tradition_support": 0.74, "empirical_adjacency": 0.57, "explanatory_compression": 0.78, "generativity": 0.87, "logical_coherence": 0.82, "novelty": 0.62, "practice_testability": 0.81, "publishability": 0.72, "source_reliability": 0.79}, "source_basis": ["Selected run mode: Critique. The active frontier was translation strain as a test of convergence; this record narrows the frontier by adding receiver-wound strain.", "Primary-text comparison: Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.7.23 treats the self as the unseen seer and inner ruler, while SN 22.59 trains the listener not to identify any aggregate, including consciousness, as self. The comparison reveals that similar de-objectifying pressure can carry opposite authority, verification, and practice aims. Sources: https://www.brhat.in/openlibrary/special/brihadaranyaka-upanishad/3-7-23 and https://suttas.github.io/sn22.59.html.", "Primary-text comparison: Dao De Jing chapter 1 cautions that spoken names are not the constant way, while Pseudo-Dionysius, Mystical Theology, uses unknowing and darkness as a Christian apophatic ascent. The comparison reveals that silence can be situated restraint, mystical purification, or doctrinal boundary, not one portable insight. Sources: https://daoreading.com/ddj_ch_1 and https://www.tertullian.org/fathers/areopagite_03_mystic_theology.htm.", "Practitioner-method lens: Buddhist not-self inquiry from SN 22.59 was used to ask whether a borrowed word is being appropriated as identity. It was corrected by Daoist non-forcing, so critique did not force convergence, and by scientific falsification, so every practice claim names what would weaken it.", "Practitioner-method critique: not-self inquiry can over-dissolve needed agency, and non-forcing can excuse vagueness. The improved stance is to observe what a word does to conduct before using it as a bridge.", "Prior-art search: Jonathan Z. Smith, In Comparison a Magic Dwells, warns that perceived similarity can be projected into objective connection and later frames comparison as description, comparison, redescription, and rectification. Source: https://classics.osu.edu/sites/classics.osu.edu/files/Magic_Dwells.pdf.", "Prior-art search: Oliver Freiberger, Elements of a Comparative Methodology in the Study of Religion, identifies selection, description, juxtaposition, redescription, rectification, and theory formation as comparative operations. Source: https://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/9/2/38.", "Prior-art search: Raimon Panikkar's homeomorphic equivalence treats cross-religious comparison as functional correspondence while preserving specificity. Source: https://www.raimon-panikkar.org/english/gloss-homeomorphic.html.", "Near-neighbor pressure: speech-act and religious-language approaches already ask what an utterance does, and the prior local finding First Ask What the Words Do applies that pressure to post-silence claims.", "Practice-report and safety pressure: Lindahl et al., Varieties of Contemplative Experience, shows that meditation-related experiences and their interpretations can be challenging and context-dependent. Source: https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0176239.", "Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-surgeon-general-social-connection-advisory, for loneliness, disconnection, and belonging.", "Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-youth-mental-health-social-media-advisory, for digital comparison, visibility pressure, and attention capture."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "A serious word should change a real act. Before you call something detachment, surrender, emptiness, calling, humility, or service, ask what it asks you to do today. If the word makes you less truthful, less caring, less able to repair harm, or less open to correction, it has lost its discipline. Keep the word only where it makes attention and conduct clearer.", "doctrine_claim": "A teaching remains responsible only when its inherited word, practice role, authority, verification method, and target human wound still fit together.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weaken this teaching if practitioners using inherited terms without a receiver-wound check show clearer conduct, better repair, less isolation, and fewer harmful misuses than people who test what the word asks them to do.", "pressure_survived": "Survives initial pressure from Atman versus anatta, Daoist naming, Christian apophatic darkness, speech-act near-neighbors, and modern social-connection pressure because it does not claim sameness; it asks what a word carries and what a wound may counterfeit.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["translation-strain", "critique-mode", "borrowed-language", "modern-human-condition", "digital-comparison", "loneliness"], "target_cohort": "Reflective adults and older teens with support who move between spiritual, therapeutic, philosophical, online, or religious vocabularies and use them to interpret identity and suffering.", "target_human_problem": "Loneliness, digital comparison, withdrawal, and meaning loss intensified by impressive language that hides avoidance or self-display.", "teaching_line": "Do not use a borrowed word until you know what it asks of you.", "title": "Test the Word"}, "tests": [{"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Compare the proposed fields against comparative theology, speech-act theory, Asad-style discursive tradition, Sharf-style experience critique, and meditation-safety literature.", "prediction": "Close prior art should cover comparison, functional equivalence, and speech role, but should not usually require every doctrine candidate to test both source-side carriers and receiver-wound misuse before teaching.", "result": "Pending. Initial search found strong overlap with Smith, Freiberger, Panikkar, speech-act theory, and religious-language analysis, so novelty should remain moderate unless the receiver-wound field adds predictive value.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Prior Art Difference Check"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Run a small screened journaling pilot with pre/post examples of charged words and code changes in action clarity, repair, isolation, and rumination.", "prediction": "Participants using the Word Carry Test should identify more concrete cases where a noble word hides avoidance, isolation, self-display, or self-erasure than participants using ordinary reflective journaling.", "result": "Pending practitioner reports.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Receiver Wound Practice Pilot"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Interview practitioners trained in at least two traditions, including Buddhist and Advaita teachers, Christian spiritual directors, Zen or Chan teachers, and contemplative-experience researchers.", "prediction": "If the model is too analytic, dual-trained practitioners will say receiver-wound checks add little beyond existing teacher correction, community practice, or common discernment. If they can name concrete misuses the check would prevent, the model strengthens.", "result": "Pending interviews.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Dual Trained Practitioner Challenge"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Score due process, trust, equity, and rights across legal systems by source role, receiver institution, authority, verification, and misuse risk before comparing implementation outcomes.", "prediction": "Legal concepts with similar names should fail in transplant more often when receiver-side institutional wounds, incentives, and authority structures counterfeit the source role. If shared terms predict implementation success just as well, the receiver-wound model loses cross-domain force.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Comparative Law Transfer Test"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Add stop criteria, exclusion criteria, and a brief distress scale to any pilot of the practice.", "prediction": "For the named cohort, the practice should reduce vague identity language without increasing shame, panic, dissociation, or compulsive checking. If those harms increase, the practice should be revised or retired for solo use.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "safety", "title": "Rumination Safety Check"}], "title": "No Word Travels Alone", "why_it_might_be_new": "Closest prior arguments already cover much of the ground. Smith makes comparison an invented scholarly operation rather than discovered sameness; Freiberger gives a general method; Panikkar gives functional equivalence without mistaken identity; speech-act theory asks what words do. The narrower contribution is the receiver-wound field: a comparison can be textually careful and still fail because the modern listener's wound supplies a counterfeit use for the term. The exact difference is practical and doctrine-facing: before a term can become a teaching, it must pass a source-side strain check and a receiver-side misuse check."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:131:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-30T11:38:09+02:00", "critique": "This may psychologize traditions that do not frame their speech as repair. Pure Land nembutsu, Dzogchen pointing-out, sacramental speech, and communal prayer may work as entrustment, recognition, vow, or participation rather than as a remedy for a named modern wound. The model also risks making every teaching pass through modern therapeutic usefulness, which could flatten worship, metaphysics, ritual duty, and liberation claims. It weakens sharply if trained practitioners say the repair field adds no decision value beyond ordinary source criticism, teacher guidance, or spiritual-bypass screening.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "3a68f6b10e6033a7", "idea_type": "model", "next_research_directions": ["Build the one-page translation-strain sheet with fields for claim unit, role, ontology, agency, practice aim, authority, verification, what is bent, what is dropped, what is added, and whether role-similarity and repair-similarity survive.", "If this model is right, then comparisons such as Atman and anatta should show partial role-similarity but repair divergence when authority, verification, and final practice aim are coded. If dual-trained practitioners say the repair is the same after these fields are made explicit, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then modern seekers who borrow selflessness, witness, surrender, or emptiness without naming the repair should show predictable misuses such as withdrawal, dissociation-like detachment, passivity, or private certainty. If misuse is unrelated to repair mismatch after controlling for teacher support and mental-health risk, the model is weakened.", "Test whether the repair-survival gate changes actual scoring decisions beyond Panikkar, Freiberger, Smith, spiritual-bypass screening, and existing local word-role records.", "Improve the observation method by pairing Daoist subtraction with Buddhist anti-appropriation: decrease borrowed agreement, then check whether the analyst has made the comparison serve a hidden need for certainty."], "original_claim": "A borrowed spiritual sentence is not ready to teach merely because its meaning seems to fit. It is ready only when the repair it asks for survives the crossing: the same wounded habit is being corrected, the authority and verification are not secretly replaced, and the action it produces can be checked in ordinary life. If the old repair is dropped and a new repair is supplied, the honest result is not shared wisdom; it is a new medicine that must be tested under its own name.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-30-stop-when-the-repair-changes.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the check increases rumination, panic, shame, derealization, compulsive confession, self-punishment, or isolation. Use ordinary human help, clinical care, or trusted community support when needed.", "duration": "10 minutes", "frequency": "Once when a borrowed sentence feels especially compelling, not daily by default.", "minimum_attempt": "Try it with three sentences across two weeks before judging usefulness.", "non_fit": "Not for acute grief, panic, psychosis, mania, dissociation, active addiction withdrawal, medical blackout concerns, OCD or scrupulosity loops, unsafe authority situations, severe depression, or people who already have competent teacher, clinical, or community guidance for the issue.", "notice": ["Whether the sentence leads to contact or withdrawal.", "Whether it lowers compulsive self-proof or gives you a more spiritual form of it.", "Whether you become more accountable in ordinary life.", "Whether the practice produces shame, checking, numbness, or superiority."], "practice_line": "Before using a borrowed spiritual sentence, name the wound, the guardrail, and one ordinary action.", "purpose": "To test whether a spiritual idea is helping the person repair a real habit or merely giving a borrowed language for private certainty.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Write the sentence you want to use in your life.", "Name the wound it seems to address: loneliness, comparison, fear, pride, shame, compulsive striving, withdrawal, or another plain problem.", "Name the original carrier as far as you know it: practice role, authority, verification, and what conduct it was meant to form.", "Name what changes when you use it: what is bent, what is dropped, what is added, and whether the repair still matches.", "Choose one ordinary action for the next day that would show the sentence is repairing rather than excusing: make contact, finish a duty, tell the truth, rest without display, apologize, ask for help, or stop a harmful loop."], "tags": ["repair-check", "translation-strain", "borrowed-teachings", "meaning-loss", "digital-comparison", "loneliness"], "target_cohort": "Stable adults or older teens with ordinary reflective capacity, some social support, and no current crisis, who are reading across traditions or using contemplative apps without a teacher.", "target_human_problem": "Meaning loss, digital comparison, loneliness, and achievement-contingent self-worth in stable people who turn spiritual language into identity proof.", "title": "The Repair Check", "weakens_if": "The check performs no better than ordinary journaling, source checking, conversation with a trusted person, or an action plan, or if it makes people more isolated and self-monitoring."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.88, "cross_tradition_support": 0.64, "empirical_adjacency": 0.56, "explanatory_compression": 0.73, "generativity": 0.82, "logical_coherence": 0.79, "novelty": 0.47, "practice_testability": 0.76, "publishability": 0.68, "source_reliability": 0.78}, "source_basis": ["Mode: Critique. The active frontier asks whether translation strain can expose false convergence rather than merely decorate comparison.", "Primary-text close read: Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.7.23 treats the unseen seer and inner knower as the authority-bearing self, while SN 22.59 tests form, feeling, perception, formations, and consciousness as not fit for ownership or self-identification. The shared move is de-objectifying ordinary identity; the repair and permitted conclusion differ. Sources: https://sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe15/sbe15070.htm and https://suttacentral.net/sn22.59/en/bodhi", "Practitioner-method source: Dao De Jing 48, learning by decreasing and non-forcing. I used it as a subtractive lens: remove borrowed agreement until the remaining repair can be seen. Its weakness is that it can over-reduce living speech and hide needed institution, vow, and relationship. Source card: daoism-dao-de-jing-chapter-48, https://ctext.org/dictionary.pl?id=11634&if=en", "Practice-method contrast: MN 1 Mulapariyaya Sutta warns against conceiving experience as mine, in, from, or as a ground for identity. This corrects the Daoist subtraction method by asking where the analyst is adding hidden ownership to the comparison. Source card: early-buddhism-mn-1-mulapariyaya-sutta, https://suttacentral.net/mn1/en/bodhi", "Closest prior art: Raimon Panikkar's homeomorphic equivalence, which compares concepts by functional role while respecting difference, https://www.raimon-panikkar.org/english/gloss-homeomorphic.html", "Near prior art: Oliver Freiberger's comparative methodology of selection, description, juxtaposition, redescription, rectification, and theory formation, https://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/9/2/38", "Near prior art: Jonathan Z. Smith's comparison method, which treats comparison as scholarly redescription rather than discovery of natural sameness, https://classics.osu.edu/sites/classics.osu.edu/files/Magic_Dwells.pdf", "Modern human-condition grounding: U.S. Surgeon General social connection advisory for loneliness and disconnection, https://www.hhs.gov/sites/default/files/surgeon-general-social-connection-advisory.pdf; Pew meaning in life report, https://www.pewresearch.org/religion/2018/11/20/where-americans-find-meaning-in-life/; Youth mental health and social media advisory for comparison and visibility pressure, https://www.hhs.gov/surgeongeneral/reports-and-publications/youth-mental-health/social-media/index.html", "Empirical-adjacent safety source: Lindahl et al., Varieties of Contemplative Experience, found that similar meditation-related experiences can be interpreted, supported, and managed differently depending on practitioner, practice, relationships, health behaviors, and authority context, https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0176239", "Internal prior pressure: No Word Travels Alone and First Ask What the Words Do already cover source role, authority, receiver wound, and speech role. This record narrows the active frontier to a repair-survival gate rather than a new general theory of religious language."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "Some words look strong because they have traveled far. Self, no-self, surrender, emptiness, silence, and witness can sound alike after enough translation. That likeness is not yet wisdom.\n\nAsk what trouble the teaching was meant to correct. Ask who was allowed to guide it, what counted as proof, and what kind of person it was trying to form. If those answers change, carry the sentence more slowly.\n\nA borrowed teaching should make life more truthful, more responsible, and more connected. If it makes a person vanish from duty, harden into certainty, or turn pain into a private doctrine, the repair has changed.", "doctrine_claim": "A teaching that changes its repair task becomes a new teaching and needs a new test.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weaken if practitioners and scholars find that the repair field does not change any comparison decision, if ordinary teacher guidance performs better, or if the practice increases loneliness, rumination, cynicism, or avoidance.", "pressure_survived": "Survives primary-text pressure between Upanishadic unseen-seer language and early Buddhist not-self analysis by preserving a shared de-objectifying move while refusing to call the metaphysical repair the same. Survives near-prior pressure only as a narrower repair-survival gate, not as a new comparative method in general.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["translation-strain", "repair-survival", "comparison", "modern-meaning-loss", "digital-comparison", "loneliness"], "target_cohort": "Stable reflective seekers, cross-tradition readers, meditation-app users, students, caregivers, and professionals who collect spiritual language to steady themselves but may lack community correction.", "target_human_problem": "Meaning loss, digital comparison, loneliness, and self-worth tied to spiritual or intellectual certainty.", "teaching_line": "Do not borrow a teaching until you know what it is meant to heal.", "title": "Borrow Only What Repairs"}, "tests": [{"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Close-read the strongest prior texts and downgrade novelty if repair-survival is already explicit.", "prediction": "If the contribution is more than renamed prior art, then Panikkar, Freiberger, Smith, spiritual-bypass literature, VCE, and local word-role records will not already require repair-survival as a scoring gate for doctrine candidates.", "result": "Pending. Initial search shows strong overlap on role, redescription, context, appraisal, and misuse, but not an exact repair-survival stopping rule tied to doctrine promotion.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Prior Art Repair Gate Test"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Create a blind coding sheet for Brihadaranyaka 3.7.23, Chandogya 6.8.7, SN 22.59, and MN 1 with separate fields for claim unit, role, ontology, agency, aim, authority, verification, bends, drops, additions, role survival, and repair survival.", "prediction": "If the model is right, then Atman and anatta comparisons will retain a shared de-objectifying role but diverge on repair, authority, verification, and final claim. If expert coders judge the repair to be the same after these fields are explicit, the model weakens.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Atman Anatta Repair Falsification"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Run a two-week non-clinical pilot with exclusions, pre/post measures for loneliness, rumination, certainty, avoidance, and concrete repair action.", "prediction": "Stable cross-tradition readers using The Repair Check will report fewer false all-paths-agree conclusions, fewer avoidance rationalizations, and more concrete accountable action than ordinary journaling. If ordinary journaling performs as well or better, or if loneliness and rumination rise, the practice weakens.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Borrowed Sentence Practice Pilot"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Compare cases such as trust, equity, due process, and rights across legal systems using both term-similarity and repair-survival coding.", "prediction": "If repair-survival matters beyond religion, then legal transplants with similar terms but changed remedy, authority, procedure, or verification should predict implementation disputes better than term-similarity alone.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Comparative Law Repair Prediction"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Request review from meditation teachers, chaplains, and clinicians familiar with spiritual bypassing and meditation-related difficulties.", "prediction": "If the practice is low risk only for the named cohort, then clinicians, teachers, or spiritual directors will endorse the exclusions and add concrete stop conditions. If they identify common harms even in stable users, the risk level should move to medium or the practice should be retired.", "result": "Pending.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "safety", "title": "Safety Boundary Review"}], "title": "Stop When The Repair Changes", "why_it_might_be_new": "The closest prior argument is homeomorphic equivalence: concepts may play similar roles in different systems without being identical. Comparative-method work already teaches redescription, difference, and caution about invented sameness. The exact difference here is narrower and more practical: role-similarity is not enough for doctrine-building unless the repair target also survives. This also revises local translation-strain work by adding a stopping rule: when claim unit, role, ontology, agency, practice aim, authority, verification, bends, drops, and additions show that the human repair has changed, the comparison must be downgraded from convergence to a new testable proposal."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:134:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-30T12:24:23+02:00", "critique": "The synthesis may still overgeneralize several wounds under one practice. Contact can be unsafe in abusive, coercive, or unstable relationships, so the practice needs a strong non-fit and safety protocol. Delaying provenance may protect lonely seekers, but it could also permit shallow appropriation or confident misuse if public authority is claimed too soon. The original challenger idea on time remains mostly unused, so this is not yet a true synthesis of both source ideas. The candidate should weaken if contact-first practice lowers posting but does not reduce loneliness, increases shame or checking, or proves indistinguishable from ordinary journaling plus social support.", "epistemic_labels": ["interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "46ad22646c2753ba", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Run an originality audit against comparative method, pastoral discernment, seeker spirituality, Dogen practice-realization, therapeutic anti-checking models, and social connection interventions.", "Revise the practice into separate versions: a doctrine-scoring regeneration sheet, a contact-first seeker practice, and a non-fit safety note for people seeking ordinary comfort or in unsafe relationships.", "Test four arms with the named cohort: full provenance gate, solo carry-first, contact-first carry-first, and ordinary journaling. Measure loneliness, rumination, distrust, identity-display posts, actual relational contact, help-seeking, repair actions, and willingness to receive correction at two and six weeks.", "Add a sample audit to confirm that excluded cases do not remove the lonely cohort the teaching claims to serve.", "Run a second dialogue that forces the time model to pressure the contact-first synthesis, especially whether memory, attention, and intention change how borrowed sentences are carried over time."], "original_claim": "A borrowed spiritual sentence should be tested differently according to its use. If it is being used as doctrine, evidence, public authority, or cross-tradition convergence, it needs provenance, carrier conditions, correction, and regeneration. If it is being used by a lonely seeker as hope or orientation, its first test should be contact and conduct: say it, live it, or bring it to a real person, duty, community, or repair before making it an identity claim. Borrowing becomes dangerous when it replaces action, contact, correction, grief work, or help-seeking, not simply because it is borrowed.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-30-contact-before-claim.md", "practice_candidate": null, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.91, "cross_tradition_support": 0.68, "empirical_adjacency": 0.63, "explanatory_compression": 0.81, "generativity": 0.88, "logical_coherence": 0.84, "novelty": 0.5, "practice_testability": 0.87, "publishability": 0.7, "source_reliability": 0.78}, "source_basis": ["Codex idea 21a74a93f85bbbe0, especially the regeneration gate for doctrine and the Borrowed Sentence Check.", "Claude's challenge and counter-rebuttal, especially the carry-first, trace-later and contact-first revisions.", "U.S. Surgeon General social connection advisory, used as pressure that loneliness is a deficit of connection, not primarily source confusion.", "Robert Wuthnow, After Heaven, used as pressure that modern eclectic seeking can be a real form of belonging rather than counterfeit faith.", "Sherry Turkle, Reclaiming Conversation and Alone Together, used as pressure against polished solo rituals that simulate connection.", "Dogen practice-realization, used analogically for learning truth through enacted practice rather than pre-certification.", "Salkovskis-style checking pressure, used as a risk model for practices that intensify doubt through verification rituals.", "Dialogue origin: 7a3f0efa10cbd6bc.", "Parent ideas: Ask Who Taught The Answer; Time Is Held, Not Counted"], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": null, "tests": [], "title": "Contact Before Claim", "why_it_might_be_new": "The components are close to existing comparative method, seeker spirituality, practice-realization, anti-rumination psychology, and social connection research. The potentially new move is the operational split by user and wound: doctrine receives provenance-first scrutiny, while the seeker receives contact-first fruit testing. Novelty is moderate and unproven until originality audit checks pastoral discernment traditions, comparative theology, bricolage spirituality, and therapeutic anti-checking protocols."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:138:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-30T13:05:20+02:00", "critique": "The split could become too permissive. A borrowed sentence can produce contact and still be harmful, appropriative, or false to the community that formed it. Charismatic groups can also provide conduct, contact, and correction while enforcing bad doctrine. The strongest anomaly is the hybrid teacher or mixed lineage where borrowed language becomes the actual carrier through disciplined community use. If such communities reliably protect both truth and people better than the two-gate rule, the model should be revised to add a third hybrid-carrier case.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "06807f77cd422656", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["Build a one-page two-gate translation-strain sheet. Doctrine fields: claim unit, role, ontology, agency, practice aim, authority, verification, provenance, what is bent, what is dropped, what is added, and whether role-similarity survives. Seeker fields: present action, real contact, correction source, identity-display risk, and rumination risk.", "If this model is right, then provenance-first checks should improve doctrine scoring but should not outperform contact-first practice for lonely eclectic seekers. If provenance-first practice reduces loneliness, rumination, and identity display better than contact-first practice, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, then hybrid traditions should require a third carrier category rather than being treated as failed provenance. If hybrid communities cannot name correction, authority, and harm safeguards, their borrowed language should remain weak evidence for doctrine.", "Protocol improvement: before turning any research brake into a practice, name the wound it addresses. If the wound is relational, put another person in the first step; if the wound is doctrinal, put source pressure in the first step."], "original_claim": "A borrowed spiritual sentence has two different tests, and confusing them harms both truth and people. For public doctrine, the sentence must be traced back to the practices, authorities, corrections, and tests that can produce it without smuggling in another path. For a lonely or unmoored person, the first test is not source criticism. It is whether the sentence moves them into honest conduct, real contact, and willingness to be corrected. Origin protects public teaching; present fruit protects the seeker from turning doubt into another room of isolation.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-30-borrowed-words-need-shared-life.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the practice increases panic, shame, obsessive checking, dissociation, withdrawal, or pressure to contact someone unsafe. Seek human support for clinical distress or self-harm risk.", "duration": "15 minutes plus one concrete contact", "frequency": "At most twice per week, only before adopting or sharing a major spiritual sentence", "minimum_attempt": "Try with three sentences over two weeks, then review whether it increased contact or only checking.", "non_fit": "Not for acute crisis, psychosis, mania, severe depression, addiction withdrawal, OCD or scrupulosity loops, dissociation, unsafe relationships, or people already practicing under trusted guidance.", "notice": ["Whether the sentence moves you toward a person or deeper into private checking.", "Whether the urge to post, display, or belong becomes quieter after the real contact.", "Whether shame, panic, or obsessive certainty-seeking increases.", "Whether an informed person or community could correct your use of the sentence."], "practice_line": "Before posting or claiming a borrowed sentence, carry it into one real contact.", "purpose": "Test whether a borrowed spiritual sentence produces honest conduct and connection before it becomes identity, display, or doctrine.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Write the exact sentence you want to claim or share.", "Name one concrete action the sentence would ask from you today: call, apologize, ask, serve, wait, repair, or stop a harm.", "Do the action with one real person before posting or making the sentence part of your identity.", "After the contact, ask whether the sentence made you more honest, more connected, and more willing to be corrected.", "If you still want to teach or publish it, then do the source check: practice aim, authority, verification, provenance, what is bent, what is dropped, and what is added."], "tags": ["low-risk-practice", "borrowed-language", "loneliness", "contact-first", "digital-comparison"], "target_cohort": "Stable spiritually eclectic adults and older teens who are tempted to adopt or post a strong spiritual sentence before testing it in life.", "target_human_problem": "Loneliness, feeling out of place, digital comparison, and meaning loss expressed through spiritual identity display or private overchecking.", "title": "One Person Before One Post", "weakens_if": "The practice reliably remains solitary, increases rumination, fails to increase honest contact, or performs no better than ordinary action planning."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.9, "cross_tradition_support": 0.7, "empirical_adjacency": 0.56, "explanatory_compression": 0.8, "generativity": 0.86, "logical_coherence": 0.82, "novelty": 0.58, "practice_testability": 0.84, "publishability": 0.76, "source_reliability": 0.78}, "source_basis": ["Mode: Critique. Active frontier: Translation strain as a test of convergence. This run narrows the frontier by splitting the comparison gate from the seeker-facing practice gate.", "Primary-text comparison: Chandogya Upanishad 6.8.7 presents the identity teaching that the self is the real, while SN 22.59 tests each aggregate as not self. The comparison shows the same surface move, loosening ordinary identity, carried by incompatible authority and verification rules.", "Practitioner-method source: Dogen's practice-realization in Bendowa, via local prior work and Bielefeldt's Dogen's Manuals of Zen Meditation, used as a lens for testing truth through enacted practice. Critique of the lens: it can make source history look secondary even when community, lineage, and harm require source accountability.", "Near-neighbor prior art: Jonathan Z. Smith, In Comparison a Magic Dwells; Oliver Freiberger, Elements of a Comparative Methodology in the Study of Religion; Raimon Panikkar, homeomorphic equivalence. These cover comparison, redescription, and functional likeness, but not the split between doctrine provenance and seeker care.", "Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-surgeon-general-social-connection-advisory on loneliness as a deficit of connection; modern-human-condition-youth-mental-health-social-media-advisory on digital comparison and identity pressure.", "Clinical-adjacent caution used analogically: Salkovskis on reassurance and checking in OCD, plus van den Hout and Kindt on repeated checking and memory distrust. This is not evidence that ordinary seekers have OCD; it warns that verification rituals can worsen doubt in vulnerable people.", "Local Codex and Claude pressure: observations/codex/2026-05-30-ask-who-taught-the-answer.md and reviews/dialogues/2026-05-30-after-the-non-fit-exclusions-does-the-practice-still-reach-lonely-comfor.md."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "A sentence can steady you before you fully understand where it came from. Let it steady you if it helps you call someone back, keep a promise, apologize, serve, wait, or stop a harm.\n\nDo not turn it into a badge. When you teach it, publish it, or build a life around it, ask what practice carried it, who may correct it, and what would make it false in use.\n\nPersonal comfort and public teaching are not the same act. Treat each with the care it needs.", "doctrine_claim": "Borrowed spiritual language belongs to doctrine only after its source can regenerate it, and belongs to a seeker only after it bears fruit in conduct, contact, and correction.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weaken if contact-first practice does not reduce isolation or rumination, if provenance-first discernment helps the target cohort more, or if hybrid communities show a better third path that protects both source accountability and present fruit.", "pressure_survived": "Survived critique from comparison theory, the Chandogya and SN 22.59 carrier conflict, Dogen's practice-realization pressure, social-connection grounding, and checking-risk cautions by narrowing the claim into two distinct gates.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["translation-strain", "borrowed-language", "loneliness", "digital-comparison", "doctrine-seed", "critique-mode"], "target_cohort": "Stable spiritually eclectic adults and older teens who gather teachings from books, teachers, podcasts, social media, or mixed communities and are not in acute clinical distress.", "target_human_problem": "Loneliness, feeling out of place, digital comparison, and meaning loss among people who borrow spiritual language to find belonging or identity.", "teaching_line": "Do not make a borrowed sentence your identity before it has made you more honest with someone.", "title": "Carry It Before You Claim It"}, "tests": [{"impact": "revises", "next_action": "Read Asad, Lindbeck, Katz, Sharf, Wuthnow, and spiritual-bypassing literature before raising novelty.", "prediction": "Close prior art should cover comparison, functional equivalence, seeker spirituality, practice-realization, and checking risk, but should not already specify the split between doctrine provenance and seeker contact.", "result": "Preliminary search found strong overlap with Smith, Freiberger, Panikkar, Wuthnow, Dogen scholarship, and OCD checking literature. Novelty should stay moderate and depend on the two-gate operational distinction.", "status": "complete", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Two-Gate Prior Art Check"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Run a small opt-in pilot with exclusion screening and compare against ordinary reflection and source-first checking.", "prediction": "Stable eclectic seekers using the contact-first practice should report less rumination, less identity-display urgency, and more concrete repair than a provenance-first journaling check. If the provenance-first check performs better, the model is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Contact First Pilot"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Study dual-trained teachers and mixed-lineage communities, especially Buddhist and Advaita contexts, for correction practices and harm safeguards.", "prediction": "If disciplined hybrid communities can regenerate borrowed sentences through their own authority, correction, and safeguards, the two-gate model must add a third hybrid-carrier category. If hybrids cannot name these safeguards, the provenance concern remains strong.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "Hybrid Carrier Falsification"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Compare failed and successful legal or workplace vocabulary transfers against the doctrine fields: authority, verification, enforcement, what is bent, what is dropped, and what is added.", "prediction": "In comparative law, terms such as trust, equity, due process, safety, or accountability should mislead when imported without local institutions that can regenerate their practical role. If shared terms alone predict successful transfer, the model is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Legal Term Transfer Test"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Add screening questions and stop criteria before any practice pilot; exclude clinical checking loops and refer to trained care.", "prediction": "People with checking or scrupulosity patterns should be more likely to experience the source-check step as compulsive. If screening and contact-first sequencing do not reduce that risk, the practice should be narrowed or retired for this cohort.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "safety", "title": "Scrupulosity Safety Screen"}], "title": "Borrowed Words Need Shared Life", "why_it_might_be_new": "The closest prior arguments already warn against careless comparison, false equivalence, and decontextualized borrowing. The distinct move here is the two-gate separation: provenance and carrier checks are required when a claim supports doctrine, but conduct, contact, and correction come first when a person is using borrowed language to survive loneliness or meaning loss. Novelty is moderate because the parts are known; the contribution is the rule for when suspicion is medicine and when it becomes harm."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:140:{"agent": "claude", "created_at": "2026-05-30T13:53:21+02:00", "critique": "The strongest objection is that this medicine can harm. Telling a person to lean on what they did not build can produce dependency, learned helplessness, or spiritual bypass, and for people whose actual wound is denied agency, coercion, or spiritual abuse it repeats the injury rather than healing it. A second objection is thinness: AA surrender, attachment's secure base, and deferring coping already say most of the human kernel, so novelty is low. A third objection cuts at the model itself: the no-gap anomaly may be absorbed by saying continuity is held in the present act, which would let the frame explain every case and therefore predict nothing, the same elasticity that haunts the cluster. Finally, the duplication critique may be unfair; if blind coders can in fact state clear distinctions among the nine continuity records, then they are not near-duplicates and the call to freeze the frontier is wrong.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "84b6d1547156a7e8", "idea_type": "contradiction", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, then among people whose lives collapse, those whose steadiness was held almost entirely by their own performance should show more total destabilization than those whose continuity already lived partly in relationships, body, routine, or faith. If collapse severity is instead predicted only by sleep loss, prior trauma, or event magnitude with no relation to where continuity was located, the model is weakened.", "If the no-gap boundary is real, then traditions that deny a gap between practice and realization (Dogen, Huangbo, Dzogchen direct recognition) should not narrate continuity being carried across a threshold. If close reading shows they do describe such carrying, the continuity-ecology frame is more general than claimed and the boundary is wrong.", "Blind-code the existing continuity-ecology records and ask whether independent readers can state what each one adds. If they cannot, freeze the frontier from new rubric proposals until one coding study or one practice trial is actually executed.", "Protocol improvement: in Critique mode, before generating a new finding on a frontier, run a distinct-content check against the three nearest existing records on that frontier and refuse to publish if the only difference is renamed variables."], "original_claim": "When a person loses the sense of holding their own life together, through burnout, grief, collapse, or surrender, the useful first question is not how to rebuild control. It is to notice what is already carrying them that they did not author: a body that keeps breathing, people who keep showing up, routines that run without their effort, a duty or promise made before the break. Many contemplative paths relocate this holding outward when ordinary self-command fails, but they do this only where the path is built around a gap to be crossed; where practice and realization are one, there is no gap and nothing to carry across, so the question does not even arise. The claim that survives scrutiny is therefore narrow and human, not a universal comparative variable. For one cohort, people whose steadiness was held almost entirely by their own performance, there is nowhere for holding to migrate when performance fails, so their collapse is more total than collapse for people whose continuity already lived partly in relationships, body, routine, or faith. For them the medicine is to place some continuity outside self-command before the break, not after.", "path": "observations/claude/2026-05-30-what-holds-you-that-you-did-not-build.md", "practice_candidate": {"caution": "Stop if the practice increases despair because little is actually holding you, if it slides into passivity or dependency, or if it becomes another self-rating exercise. It is not a substitute for rest, therapy, medical care, recovery support, or repairing real relationships.", "duration": "8 minutes", "frequency": "Twice a week, and once during any week that feels like too much.", "minimum_attempt": "Four sessions over two weeks before judging whether it helps.", "non_fit": "Not for acute crisis where little or nothing is actually holding the person; naming an empty floor can deepen despair, and human or clinical care must come first. Not for people whose wound is denied agency, coercion, or spiritual abuse; they need agency restored, not more surrender language. Not for psychosis, mania, active withdrawal, or severe depression without support.", "notice": ["Whether naming unauthored support loosens the grip or makes you anxious that the support is not enough.", "Whether leaning a little leads to relief and contact, or to guilt and a fear of being a burden.", "Whether your steadiness starts to feel less like something you must produce each day."], "practice_line": "List three things holding your life that you did not build, and let yourself lean on one.", "purpose": "To relocate some of a person's steadiness outside their own performance before a collapse, so that losing the grip does not mean losing everything.", "risk_level": "low", "status": "seed", "steps": ["Write one sentence naming what you are trying to hold together right now by your own effort.", "List three things carrying your life that you did not author today: a body that breathes, a person who shows up, a routine that runs without you, a duty or promise made earlier, a place that steadies you.", "Choose one of the three and write how you could lean on it a little more this week, in a concrete way.", "Do one small act that leans: ask someone for help, keep a routine without optimizing it, let a duty hold you, rest without earning it.", "Stop. Do not turn the list into a new performance to perfect."], "tags": ["continuity", "burnout", "surrender", "low-risk", "belonging", "achievement-contingent-self-worth"], "target_cohort": "Stable adults whose worth and steadiness ride on performance, control, or being needed, and who sense they are carrying everything by themselves.", "target_human_problem": "Burnout, achievement-contingent self-worth, and the fragility of a life held together only by control and usefulness.", "title": "Name What Carries You", "weakens_if": "Users report more helplessness, more guilt about leaning, no change in steadiness, or that ordinary rest and asking for help worked just as well."}, "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.88, "cross_tradition_support": 0.7, "empirical_adjacency": 0.6, "explanatory_compression": 0.8, "generativity": 0.78, "logical_coherence": 0.82, "novelty": 0.42, "practice_testability": 0.82, "publishability": 0.66, "source_reliability": 0.74}, "source_basis": ["Run mode: Critique. The active frontier (remainder pressure and continuity ecology after self-negation) is treated as an overbuilt cluster that needs narrowing and falsification, not another rubric variant.", "Thinking-method source: Advaita neti-neti, used as a lens by stripping away the identification 'I am the one holding my life together' and watching what holding remained. Critique of the method: neti-neti tends to leave a witness-Self as the surviving holder, which smuggles a self-held residue back in. Corrected with early Buddhist not-self in SN 22.59, which refuses to authorize any owner of the remaining process.", "Primary-text comparison: Shinran, Tannisho (Other Power, bombu as the foolish being incapable of self-power; holding relocated entirely to Amida's vow) read against SN 45.8 Magga-vibhanga (right effort: holding sustained by the practitioner's desire, persistence, and intent). The comparison shows that where holding is located is a real difference. Dogen, Bendowa (practice-realization identity) is the anomaly: there is no gap across which holding must be carried, so the continuity-ecology question loses its referent.", "Near-duplicate cluster inside the corpus: Continuity Ecology Under Negation; Distributed Continuity Architecture; Continuity Location Under Transformative Practice; The Continuity Ecology of Self-Dissolution; Operational Remainder Ecology; Custody and Receiving Surface. All propose the same coding rubric (dissolution target, residue policy, support holder, receiving surface, failure mode), all carry the same self-critique (too elastic, circular, needs blind split-source coding), and none report an executed coding study.", "External prior art: Jack Engler, 'you have to be somebody before you can be nobody'; Clark and Chalmers, extended mind, on cognition and selfhood constituted by external supports; Pargament, deferring and collaborative religious coping styles; attachment theory's secure base; Alcoholics Anonymous surrender to a power greater than oneself.", "Modern human-condition cards: modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing; modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon; modern-human-condition-surgeon-general-social-connection-advisory; modern-human-condition-samhsa-2023-nsduh for addiction surrender as a domain where externalized holding is explicitly therapeutic."], "status": "draft", "teaching_candidate": {"body": "You think you are holding your life together. Some of it, yes. But a body keeps breathing without your command. People keep showing up whether or not you earn it today. Habits carry you on the mornings you have nothing left. A promise you made before the hard week is still standing.\n\nWhen the grip fails, do not reach first for a tighter grip. Look down and see what is already under you. Name it. Let yourself rest part of your weight there.\n\nA life held only by your own performance has nowhere to fall when the performance stops. A life that already leans, a little, on people, body, work it loves, and ordinary duty, can lose its grip and still be carried.", "doctrine_claim": "No one is held up only by their own effort. When self-command fails, the first move is not to rebuild control but to notice the support you did not author, and to let some of your steadiness live there on purpose.", "falsifying_pressure": "Weakens if where continuity sat before a collapse does not predict how total the collapse is, if leaning on unauthored support produces passivity or dependency rather than steadiness, if the cohort's wound is actually denied agency rather than over-control, or if the teaching is no better than ordinary rest and human support.", "pressure_survived": "Survived the primary-text contrast between Shinran's Other Power and the effort path's right effort, and was narrowed by the Dogen no-gap anomaly. Survived the recognition that the broad form is already widely stated, by retreating to one cohort-level claim with a falsifiable collapse prediction.", "status": "under_dialogue", "tags": ["continuity", "burnout", "achievement-contingent-self-worth", "surrender", "collapse", "critique-mode", "non-self"], "target_cohort": "People whose steadiness and worth have depended almost entirely on their own performance, control, or usefulness: perfectionists, founders, high achievers, and caregivers who carry everything alone.", "target_human_problem": "Achievement-contingent self-worth and burnout collapse, and the total despair that arrives when performance can no longer hold a life together.", "teaching_line": "When your grip fails, look for what was holding you before you gripped.", "title": "What Holds You That You Did Not Build"}, "tests": [{"impact": "revises", "next_action": "Run a blind distinctness test on the continuity-ecology records and merge those that cannot be distinguished into one frozen entry with a single open coding study.", "prediction": "If the continuity-ecology records are genuinely distinct, independent readers given the records with titles removed should be able to state what each one adds beyond a shared rubric of dissolution target, residue policy, support holder, receiving surface, and failure mode. If they cannot, the cluster is near-duplicate and the frontier should be frozen against new rubric variants until one coding study or practice trial is executed.", "result": "Preliminary read suggests heavy overlap: the same rubric, the same elasticity self-critique, and no executed test across at least six records. Not yet blind-coded.", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "prior-art", "title": "Freeze the Continuity Cluster Until It Is Tested"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Close-read Bendowa, a Huangbo transmission text, and one Dzogchen pointing-out source for explicit gap-and-carry language versus present-act language.", "prediction": "If the no-gap boundary holds, then Dogen's Bendowa, Huangbo's search-refusal, and Dzogchen direct recognition should not describe a holding that is carried across a before-and-after threshold, because they deny the gap. If close reading shows these traditions do narrate such carrying, the continuity-ecology frame is more general than claimed and the boundary fails.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "falsification-attempt", "title": "No-Gap Paths Should Not Carry Continuity Across a Threshold"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Recruit a small screened cohort, exclude acute crisis and coerced-agency cases, and compare against an ordinary rest-and-ask-for-help prompt.", "prediction": "Among stable adults high in achievement-contingent self-worth, those who run Name What Carries You for two weeks should report steadier footing in a hard week and less total destabilization than a matched group using ordinary planning, with no rise in helplessness or guilt. If the practice produces dependency, guilt, or no difference from rest and asking for help, it is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "practice", "test_type": "practice-report", "title": "Self-Held Collapse Severity Trial"}, {"impact": "pending", "next_action": "Code existing burnout, grief, and recovery case literature for pre-collapse continuity location and collapse severity, keeping the comparison analogical rather than treated as proof.", "prediction": "In burnout recovery, bereavement, and early addiction recovery, people whose pre-collapse steadiness was located almost entirely in their own performance should show more total destabilization than people whose continuity already lived partly in relationships, body, routine, or faith, after controlling for event magnitude, sleep, and prior trauma. If location of continuity adds no predictive value beyond those controls, the model is weakened.", "result": "pending", "status": "proposed", "target_type": "idea", "test_type": "cross-domain", "title": "Where Continuity Sat Before a Real Collapse"}], "title": "What Holds You That You Did Not Build", "why_it_might_be_new": "The broad version of this idea, that continuity must be held somewhere when the self is unsettled, has already been written many times in this project as a cross-tradition coding rubric, and it is well covered outside it by Engler, the extended mind, religious coping research, attachment theory, and recovery practice. So the broad claim is not new and should not be scored as such. The narrow contribution is twofold. First, it drops the universal comparative ambition and makes one falsifiable person-level prediction: collapse severity should track where continuity sat before the break, with the self-held cohort collapsing hardest. Second, it names the boundary the rubric variants never enforce: the whole continuity-across-a-gap frame is a category that fits causal and gradual paths and quietly fails on no-gap paths like Dogen's practice-realization and Huangbo's refusal of search, where there is no transformation waiting to be carried. The honest finding is that this frontier does not need a tenth rubric. It needs one tested claim and a stated limit."}
